C- Incorrect- covers the urogenital triangle 

D- Incorrect found in males and females

E- Correct!

Question: What's the definition of non-competitive inhibition and what effect does this inhibition have on Km and Vmax?
OptionA: They only bind to an allosteric site. They decrease Vmax whilst having no effect on Km.
OptionB: They bind either to free enzymes or the the enzyme-substrate complex typically at an allosteric site. They decrease Vmax whilst having no effect on Km.
OptionC: They bind either to free enzymes or the the enzyme-substrate complex typically at an allosteric site. They increase Vmax whilst having no effect on Km.
OptionD: They only bind to an allosteric site. They decrease Vmax whilst also decreasing Km.
Explanation:
B is correct! B gives the perfect definition of non-competitive inhibition.

Vmax decreases due to the maximum rate of reaction has decreased as all enzyme active sites are saturated with substrates. There is no change in Km due to no change in substrate concentration would affect the Km to reach Vmax at 1/2.

Question: What is the approximate normal arterial blood gas range for PaCO2 what does an increase in partial pressure of carbon dioxide indicate?
Explanation:
ABG is important as a diagnostic test to see if respiratory rate meets metabolic demand. An arterial blood gas (ABG) test measures the acidity (pH) and the levels of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood from an artery. This test is used to check how well your lungs are able to move oxygen into the blood and remove carbon dioxide from the blood.

 

The normal range for PaCO2 is 35-45 mmHg and an increase is said to be respiratory acidosis.

if bicarbonate conc decreases excessively this is considered metabolic acidosis. 

Rememe right : Metabloic refers to kidneys and respiratory refers to lungs, Acidosis is do with loss, Bicarbonate is to do with kidney and CO2 in lungs.

 

The normal range for PaO2 is 83-98 mmHg or >79 mmHg.

These values may differ in various textbooks and websites.

Question: During breast feeding a neuro - endocrine reflex takes place , which of the following pathways best  describes this ?
OptionA: Feeding > activates the hypothalamus > cell bodies produce prolactin  > travel down nerve fibers > posterior pituitary >circulation
OptionB: Feeding > activates the hypothalamus > cell bodies produce oxytocin > travel down blood vessels  > posterior pituitary >circulation
OptionC: Feeding > activates the hypothalamus > cell bodies produce oxytocin > travel down nerve fibers > anterior pituitary >circulation
OptionD: Feeding > activates the hypothalamus > cell bodies produce oxytocin > travel down nerve fibers > posterior pituitary >circulation
OptionE: Feeding > activates the hypothalamus > cell bodies produce oxytocin > travel down nerve fibers > posterior pituitary > anterior pituitary
Explanation:
D- well done , this is the correct pathway 

A- Prolactin is the hormones that enables milk to be produced and is released by the anterior pituitary ( FLAT PeG)

B- Would be correct but since oxytocin is released by the posterior pituitary gland it will travel down nerves not blood vessels

C - Remember that oxytocin is released by the posterior pituitary  

E- From the posterior pituitary gland, oxytocin will then travel into the circulation ( and then the receptors on the myoepithelial cells of the breast )

Question: Growth hormone, which is released by the anterior pituitary gland, effects the muscle in various ways to bring about growth .Which of these effects on the muscle below is false ?
Explanation: C - well done that is correct . Increased lipolysis is an effect that growth hormone has on adipose tissues and not on the muscles .

Question: Mrs Smith is the mother of a newborn baby who has been diagnosed with Prader-Willi syndrome. This condition can lead to many complex problems including obesity. This weight gain is related to excess levels of which digestive hormone?
Explanation:
Leptin - incorrect. Leptin is an anorexigenic hormone which INHIBITS hunger.

Ghrelin - correct. Ghrelin is also known as the 'hunger hormone' which acts on the hypothalamus to increase hunger, increasing gastric acid secretion and stomach motility to prepare for food. Excess levels of ghrelin can be found in patients with Prader-Willi syndrome.

CCK - incorrect. CCK causes the pancreas to release digestive enzymes and the gall bladder to contract and secrete bile. It furthermore acts as a hunger suppressant decreasing gastric emptying

PYY - incorrect. PYY reduces appetite, inhibits motility and slows gastric emptying allows more efficient digestion + absorption

Gastrin - incorrect. Gastrin stimulates the parietal cells to secrete HCl and the chief cells to secrete pepsinogens.

Question: The complement system is a part of the immune system that is responsible for helping effector cells by marking  and attacking pathogens. Which antibody/antibodies activate the complement system in the adaptive response?
Explanation:
IgM and IgE - incorrect. IgM does activate the complement system however IgE does not. IgE is responsible for allergic reactions and protects against parasitic worms (helminths).

IgA - incorrect. IgA is responsible for protection against pathogens by neutralisation of pathogen by binding to the active site.

IgM and IgG - Correct. IgM and IgG are both responsible for complement activation.IgG is able to cross the placenta and IgM is in the plasma only and is also responsible for the early stages of immunity.

IgD - incorrect. IgD activates basophils and mast cells.

IgG - incorrect. IgG does activate the complement system but is not the only antibody to do this. IgG also has a role in opsonisation, neutralisation and ADCC (antibody dependent cellular cytotoxicity) - interaction with NK cells.

Question: Step 10 of glycolysis is a regulatory step, involving the enzyme pyruvate kinase. Pyruvate kinase catalyses the formation of pyruvate and reduced NAD from phosphenolpyruvate and NAD+. What up regulates and down regulates pyruvate kinase?
OptionA:
Up regulated by ATP and alanine 

Down regulated by Fructose-6-phosphate
OptionB:
Up regulated by Fructose-6-phosphate 
Down regulated by ATP and alanine
OptionC:
Up regulated by fructose-1,6-bisphosphate 
Down regulated by ATP and alanine
OptionD:
Up regulated by Alanine
Down regulated by ATP and fructose-1,6-bisphosphate
OptionE:
Up regulated by ATP and alanine
Down regulated by Fructose-1,6-bisphosphate
Explanation:
C is Correct! Pyruvate kinase is up regulated by fructose-1,6-bisphosphate and down regulated by ATP and alanine, both allosterically 

A- Incorrect

B- Down regulation is correct but up regulation is incorrect as it is fructose-1,6-bisphosphate rather than fructose-6-phosphate 

C- Correct!

D- Incorrect- should be the other way round and ATP added as a down regulator 

E- Incorrect- should be the other way round

Question: You're a GP and a patient presents to you with shoulder discomfort. You ask them to reach their arms out and press against the wall in front of them. You notice that they appear to have a winged scapular. This condition is a result of muscle paralysis. What muscles may be paralysed and what nerves supply these muscles?
OptionA:
Serratus anterior- long thoracic nerve 

Deltoid - axillary nerve 

Teres minor- axillary nerve
OptionB:
Serratus Anterior- long thoracic nerve 

Trapezius- spinal accessory nerve CN XI 

Rhomboid major and minor- dorsal scapular nerve
OptionC:
Trapezius - spinal accessory nerve CN XI 

Deltoid - axillary nerve 

Teres major - lower subscapular nerve
OptionD:
Rhomboid major and minor - dorsal scapular nerve 

Deltoid - axillary nerve 

Teres major - lower subscapular nerve
OptionE:
Serratus anterior - long thoracic nerve 

Teres major - lower sub scapular nerve 

Rhomboid major and minor - dorsal scapular nerve
Explanation:
B is Correct! A patient with a winged scapular is likely to have paralysis of serratus anterior which is innervated by CN XI. However, there may also be paralysis to 3 other muscles which are trapezius and rhomboid major and minor. Trapezius has motor innervation by the spinal accessory nerve CN XI and the rhomboids are innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve.

In the absence of nerve damage, this condition may arise from chronic poor posture leading to scapular dyskinesis.

Question: During your lectures you find yourself falling asleep and that your eyes start drooping. You keep blinking multiple times to stay awake. Which of the following drugs would not trigger a blink response and what is its mechanism of action?
OptionA: Tropicamide is a mAcHR (muscuranic AcH receptor) antagonist which causes paralysis of ciliary muscle as well as pupil constrictor muscles. Blinking doesn’t occur because muscles are paralysed.
OptionB: Phenylephrine acts directly on adrenoreceptors in the eye causing pupil to dilate (by innervation of iris dilator muscles). Blinking doesn’t occur as dilated eyes remain open.
OptionC: Pilocarpine is mAcHR agonist which causes vasodilation as well as constriction of ocular muscles due to release of nitric oxide. Blinking doesn’t occur because the muscles are constricted and their movement is limited.
OptionD: Tetracaine works by blocking voltage gated Na+ channels involved in conduction of nerve impulses and giving a temporary numbing effect. Blinking doesn’t occur as the eye doesn’t register pain etc.
OptionE: Fluorescein is a drug with glows green under blue light and causes thickening of the cornea. As a result blinking doesn’t occur because the eye can’t close over the thick cornea.
Explanation:
Tetracaine (Option C) is the right answer. Tetracaine is used as a local anasthetic as it causes numbness (nerve impulses aren’t carried and pain etc isn’t felt). It is useful in cataract surgery and when treating painful cornea trauma.

Thinking in terms of muscles, blinking is controlled by orbicularis oculi (innervated by facial nerve (C7))- in closing the eyelid. The levator (C3) and frontalis (C7) muscles are the antagonists to it - to open the eyelid again.

 

Phenylephrine is a drug used topically. It act similarly to noradrenaline on the adrenoreceptors of the eye. Causes pupil dilation and scleral whitening (due to vasoconstriction of scleral vessels).

 

Tropicamide is used to see the retina as the paralysed ciliary muscles don’t contract and the pupils remain dilated.

 

Pilocarpine is useful in reducing Intra ocular pressure as it opens the canal of Schlemm. Bloodshot eyes are seen with this drug due to its vasodilatory effects caused by nitric oxide release. This disappears fast and eyes become white again due to shirt half life of Nitric oxide.

 

Fluorescein is a dye that shines green under blue light and is useful in seeing corneal abrasions. It is used in angiography.

 

The sentences about blinking in the other answer options are made up except for tetracaine. :)

Question: The muscles of mastication are associated with movements of the jaw. What are the four main muscles of mastication?
OptionB: Masseter, temporalis, anterior belly of digastric, myelohyoid
OptionD: Temporalis, medial pterygoid, lateral pterygoid, anterior belly of digastric
OptionE: masseter, medial pterygoid, anterior belly of digastric, myelohyoid
Explanation:
Procerus is a nasal muscle therefore not involved in mastication

Nasalis is a nasal muscle also.

While myelohyoid and the anterior belly of digastric muscle can be involved in mastication they are accessory muscles, not the main muscles involved in mastication.

C - correct answer. The MAIN four muscles involved in mastication are: Masseter, temporals, medial pterygoid and lateral pterygoid
Tags: PCS 3, Musculoskeletal System, Head and neck

Question: General sensation (touch, temp, pain) to the anterior 2/3 of the tongue, the palate and mouth is supplied by which nerve?
Explanation:
A - ophthalmic division of trigeminal nerve provides sensory innervation to skin, mucous membranes and sinuses of the upper face and scalp

B - IX glossopharyngeal nerve provides sensory innervation and taste to the posterior 1/3 of the tongue, external ear and middle ear cavity.

C - Maxillary division of trigeminal nerve provides sensory innervation to cheeks, lower eye lip, nasal mucosa, upper lip, upper teeth and palate

D - Correct answer - Mandibular division of trigeminal nerve, provides sensory innervation to anterior 2/3 of tongue, skin over mandible and lower teeth. It also provides motor innervation to the muscles of mastication

E - XII hypoglossal nerve provides motor innervation to the intrinsic and extrinsic tongue muscles
Tags: Head and neck, nerves, Cranial Nerves

Question:
There are three main phases of the uterine cycle: menstrual phase, proliferative phase and secretory phase. 

What are the main events of the proliferative phase?
OptionA: Corpus luteum secretes progesterone and oestrogen preparing the endometrium for implantation and uterine glands secrete uterine milk which is high in protein and glycogen
OptionB:
thickening of the endometrium due to decreased oestrogen from follicles

Spiral arteries develop but are inactive

Uterine glands develop but are inactive
OptionC:
Thickening of the endometrium due to increased oestrogen from follicles

Spiral arteries develop and are active allowing a good blood supply to the uterus

Uterine glands develop but are inactive
OptionD:
No fertilisation has occurred so the corpus lute degenerates and therefore progesterone levels drop

Spiral arteries break down and bleeding occurs

Uterine lining disintegrates
OptionE:
Thickening of the endometrium due to increased oestrogen from follicles

Spiral arteries develop but are inactive

Uterine glands develop but are inactive
Explanation:
In the proliferative phase, spiral arteries develop but they do not become active until the secretory phase. This rules out C as the correct answer

 

In the proliferative phase, uterine glands develop but also do not become active until the secretory phase. This rules out A which is describing the secretory phase

 

D - This is describing the menstrual phase

 

 The thickening of the endometrium is due to increased oestrogen, therefore B cannot be the correct answer.

 

E is the correct answer.

Question: Which of the following is not a function of progesterone?
OptionA: Stimulates uterine lining to prepare for implantation and gestation
OptionC: Increases blood flow to endometrium by stimulating spiral arteries and increases uterine secretions
OptionD: Contributes to breast development in anticipation of lactation
OptionE: reduces contractility of the muscles of the uterus
Explanation: LH is the hormone responsible for stimulating ovulation, therefore B is not a function of progesterone.

Question: Miss Jones is a 16yo female who has been brought into the emergency department having a severe panic attack. She is hyperventilating and when asked communicates that she has tingling in her hands. What has happened to her acid-base status and how do her symptoms explain this?
OptionA:
Respiratory alkalosis due to fast excretion of CO2

Tingling is due to hypocalcemia.
OptionB:
Respiratory acidosis due to fast excretion of CO2

Tingling is due to hypocalemia
OptionC:
Respiratory alkalosis due to fast excretion of CO2

Tingling is due to hypercalcemia
OptionD:
Respiratory acidosis due to fast excretion of CO2

Tingling is due to hyperkalemia
OptionE:
Respiratory acidosis due to fast excretion of CO2

Tingling is due to hypokalemia
Explanation:
This patient is experiencing respiratory alkalosis due to fast excretion of CO2, this causes a decrease in CO2 levels and CO2 partial pressure. This increases the pH of the blood. 

In order to try and compensate you would need to lower the pH of the blood. 

In this case this is done by H+ from albumin binding to calcium which in turn reduces the free Ca2+ available in the serum available for muscle contraction - causing the tingling.

Therefore, this patient is suffering from hypocalcaemia. 

 

For these reasons A can be the only correct answer

 

*Neuromuscular irritability is the hallmark of acute hypocalcemia*

Question: Mr John, is a 55yo man who has been found in respiratory arrest (he has stopped breathing). This would cause respiratory acidosis as there is a build up of CO2 which would decrease the pH of blood. Which organ would try to compensate this and have the fastest impact?
OptionA:
Kidneys compensate by reabsorbing more HCO3 from the tubular fluid, increasing HCO3 levels in the blood

increased urinary excretion of hydrogen ions
OptionB: Kidneys compensate by secreting H+ into the blood
OptionC: Kidneys compensate by excreting HCO3, decreasing HCO3 levels in the blood
OptionD: The lungs will compensate if a breathing tube is placed or the patient is put on a ventilator decreasing CO2 levels
OptionE: The lungs compensate by the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide
Explanation:
This is an emergency situation where an immediate response is needed otherwise the patient will die. 

Therefore the only correct answer is D, if ventilation can be restored this will usually lead to a rapid fall in PaCO2 and correction of acidosis.

 

A - This is also a correct answer as the kidneys do compensate be reabsorbing more HCO3 into the blood, however this is a slow mechanism that takes a few days to be effective.

 

E - This is what happens in normal breathing and as the patient is in respiratory arrest this is evidently not possible.

Question: What is the cremaster reflex and which nerve innervates the muscles involved?
OptionA: When the superior medial calf is stroked, knee rises rapidly due to contraction of quadriceps. This reflex was found by M.Cremaster and the muscles are innervated by the genitofemoral nerves of lumbar plexus (L1 and L2).
OptionB: When the superior medial knee is stroked, hair on the thigh stands erect. Occurs due to stimulation of hair follicles in Cremaster glands and is innervated by external femoral nerves.
OptionC: When the superior medial thigh is stroked, testes rises rapidly. Occurs due to contraction of the Cremaster muscle and is innervated by testicular nerve of lumbar plexus.
OptionD: When the superior medial calf is stroked, knee rises rapidly due to contraction of the quadriceps. This is called Cremaster reflex as M.K.Cremaster found this reflex and is innervated by the femoral nerve (L2).
OptionE: When the superior medial thigh region is stroked in males, the testes rises rapidly. This occurs due to the Cremaster muscle contracting. The muscle is innervated by the genito femoral nerves of the lumbar plexus (L1 and L2).
Explanation: The reflex is useful in lowering and raising testes in order to control its temperature. The female equivalent is called the Geigel reflex. Absence of this reflex may suggest nerve damage to the L1 and L2 which are the genitofemoral nerves.
Tags: PCS 3, Pelvis, innervation, muscles, Male reproductive system

Question: A 21 year old women has entered the GP. She explained that she has noticed a lump in her vagina that has become progressively worse in pain. She says there's pain when walking, sitting and when participating in sexual intercourse. On examination, you notice there is a lump on the vaginal lips (labia). There is also some signs of puss and inflamed tissue. When asking about past surgeries/ childbirth, she says no to both. What is the condition?
Explanation:
A is correct! 

Bartholin's cyst occurs when a flap of skin grows over this Bartholin's gland, fluid can back up into the gland and form a cyst, This cyst is usually painless. But, in this women the cyst has becomes infected, due to presence of puss and pain. 

B i incorrect due to no extra information given about abdominal pain, bladder dysfunction nor urinary incontinence. 

C is incorrect as there is no other information/symptoms given, that would suggest a tumour of the vagina. 

D is incorrect. Vaginal cysts usually occur during childbirth/ surgery, and in the text, the patient tells the GP she hasn't had a surgery to the vagina nor gave birth to a child.

Question: A 56-year-old ma walk into the GP. He explained he was experiencing frequent urination and nocturia. He further explained he was experiencing difficulty starting urination and inability to completely empty the bladder. You ask his family history, he tells you that his father has had prostate problems. What is his condition?
Explanation:
B is correct!

Benig prostate enlargement (prostatic hypertrophy). When the prostate becomes enlarged, it puts pressure on the bladder and urethra and causes the symptoms indicated in the stem. This is the correct answer due to it usually occurs in older men where balance of hormones in the body changes as age increases and causes prostate gland to grow. Risk factors as given in this stem is that the patient has a blood relative, a father that has previously had prostate problems. Indicating, B is the correct answer. 

A is incorrect  due to needing more tests e.g. urine tests to cancel out prostate cancer.

C is incorrect due to prostatitis is very painful and distressing, unlike the description the male patient told you. Also, it usually occurs between the ages of 30 to 50. 

D is incorrect due to urinary hesitancy being associated with a result from another effect. For example, a nerve damage, infections and certain medications. 

E is incorrect as UTI can become a complication of most urinary prroblems  , as therefore, isn't specific enough.

Question: During the contraction of skeletal muscle what causes myosin to detach from actin ?

Question: What are the two cranial nerves that arise from the cerebrum?

Trigeminal, Abducens, Facial nerve, Vestibulocochlear nerves arise from the pons. Glossopharyngeal, vagus, spinal accessory and hypoglossal nerves arise from the medulla oblangata.

Question: The right optic nerve tract and the left optic nerve tract contain nerve fibres which are carrying information from different parts of the eye. Which of these options correctly describes the nerve fibres in the right and left optic tracts?
OptionA:
Right- fibres from right temporal/lateral retina and right nasal/medial retina 

Left- fibres from left temporal/lateral retina and left nasal/medial retina
OptionB:
Right- fibres from left temporal/lateral retina and right nasal/medial retina
Left- fibres from right temporal/lateral retina and left nasal/medial retina
OptionC:
Right- fibres from the right temporal/lateral retina and left nasal/medial retina
Left- fibres from the left temporal/lateral retina and right nasal/medial retina
OptionD:
Right-fibres from left temporal/lateral retina and left nasal/medial retina 
Left- fibres from right temporal/lateral retina and right nasal/medial retina
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

The optic nerve partial cross over forms the optic chiasm in the middle cranial fossa. The fibres from the medial/nasal half of the retina cross over to the contralateral optic tract. Whereas, the fibres from the temporal/lateral part of the retina remain ipsilateral and do not cross over at the optic chiasm. 

This means the right optic tract contains fibres from the right temporal/lateral retina and left nasal/medial retina. The left optic tract contains fibres from the left temporal/lateral retina and right nasal/medial retina. 

Therefore, C is the correct answer!

Question: The anterior cranial fossa consists of which bones?

The anterior cranial fossa is made up of the frontal, sphenoid and ethmoid bones.

Question: Which of the following are correct regarding indirect inguinal hernias?

OptionE: Caused due to weakness of the cojoint tendon.

Direct inguinal hernias lie medial to inferior epigsastric artery, occurs typically in elder men, seen as abdominal hernias. They occur through the Hesselbach triangle.

 

Indirect inguinal hernias lie lateral to inferior epigastric artery, can occur irrespective of age, seen as scrotal hernias. Occurs due to processus vaginalis not closing off. Most common type of hernia.

 

hernias can also occur in females!

impedance matching – ensures the fluid in the ear is properly distributed. The tympanic membrane has a large surface area, but the force generated by sound vibrations in air is weak. The ossicles

Question: Match the correct function to cranial nerve (XII) - The Hypoglossal nerve

Explanation:

C) This is the correct answer! The hypoglossal nerves general function is speech, chewing and swallowing.

D) This would be the vestibulocochlear nerve (VIII)

E) This would be the facial never (VII)

Question: Which two options are most likely to increase blood pressure?
OptionA: Increased contractilty of the heart, decrease in preload
OptionD: Increased contractility of heart, narrowing of blood vessels
Explanation:
Drugs that reduce HBP - ACE inhibitors, Calcium ion channel blockers, Antidiuretics, ARBs. Different drugs are given to different people depending on race, age and which range their BP lies in. For eg in the NHS website it states that,

— if you're under 55 years of age – you'll usually be offered an ACE inhibitor or an angiotensin-2 receptor blocker (ARB)

— if you're aged 55 or older, or you're any age and of African or Caribbean origin – you'll usually be offered a calcium channel blocker

 

BP increases due to increased contractility of the heart, reduced radius of vessels and increase in preload. This is because their is more pressure and force applied on the walls of the heart and more volumes of blood are forced through vessels. 

 

Other factors like smoking, increased bpdy weight and too much salt in your diet for example contribute to increasing blood pressure. For further information, the NHS website is extremely helpful. https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/high-blood-pressure-hypertension/

Question: Dr Shiby Stephens knocks out Tyson Fury to become the undisputed world champion. Unfortunately however she sustained a boxers fracture during the fight. What bone has been fractured?

Question: What type of epithelia is found in your bladder?
Explanation: D is correct

Question: Those not doing medicine may make slightly inappropriate guesses as to what a "power stroke" is. However you know that it is instead the...
OptionA: pivoting of the myosin heads that move the actin molecule towards the M line.
OptionB: pivoting of the myosin heads that move the actin molecule towards the Z line.
OptionC: pivoting of the myosin heads that move the actin molecule away from the M line.
OptionD: pivoting of the myosin heads that move the actin molecule away from the Z line.
OptionE: "I prefer not to speak. If I speak, I am in big trouble" - Jose Mourinho 2014
Explanation: A is correct. During muscle contraction ADP and a phosphate dissociate from the myosin head causing the head to pivot. This cause the "power stroke"

Question: A female presents with what she describes as a broken 'cheekbone'. What is the true name for this bone?
Explanation: The zygomatic bone is the correct term for the cheekbone. This bone is described as diamond shaped and is lateral to the orbit.

Question: Which paranasal sinuses drain into the middle meatus?
Explanation: B is correct as the frontal, maxillary and ethmoid drain into the middle meatus. The location of this opening is marked by the semilunar hiatus, a crescent-shaped groove on the lateral walls of the nasal cavity

Question: Which nerve innervates the posterior third of the tongue?
Explanation: The glossopharyngeal nerve innervates the posterior third of the tongue as well as the oropharynx.

Question: Match the correct clinical significance to the classification of bone.
OptionA:
Flat bones- bones develop around tendons
short bones- allows attachment of muscles and protection of organs
Sesamoid- gives strength but limited movement
OptionB:
Flat bones- gives strength but limited movement
short bones- allows attachment of muscles and protection of organs

OptionC:

short bones- bones develop around tendons
Sesamoid- gives strength but limited movement

short bones- gives strength but limited movement

short bones- gives strength but limited movement

Question: A child presents with pain in the elbow after their father has been swinging them around in the air by holding onto the Childs hands. You diagnose them with Nursemaids elbow (a.k.a milkmaid elbow). What has occurred to cause this pain?
OptionA: The ligament of the elbow has slipped into the joint.
Explanation:
A is correct. In children 0-4 years the ligaments are very soft and elastic so it is common for the ligament to slip into the joint causing discomfort. The ligaments become tighter and after the age of 5 is it very uncommon for this to occur.

 

B is unlikely to occur from the fathers actions and would not come under the nursemaid diagnosis.

C could occur as the elbow is the most common dislocation in children, however the diagnosis is specific to the ligament.

D is unlikely to occur and does not follow the diagnosis

E would occur is any blood vessels are torn but this does not follow the diagnosis

Question: A 42 year old male patient presents to his GP having recently lost his sense of smell. From the GPS understanding of cranial nerves, what cranial nerve is most likely to have been affected and what is the name of that cranial nerve.
Explanation:
CN VII – facial nerve (incorrect the facial nerve supplies motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression 
CN IX – glossopharyngeal nerve (incorrect the glossopharyngeal nerve supplies the  sensory innervation of the oropharynx 
CN I – olfactory nerve (correct the olfactory nerve supplies special sensory innervation for the sense of smell) 

CN II – optic nerve (incorrect the optic nerve supplies special sensory innervation for the sense of sight)
Tags: Head and neck, PCS 3, Cranial Nerves

Question: A 6 month old baby presents to A&E having recently fallen over and has suffered  blunt force trauma to the back of the head. Understanding the anatomy of an infants skull what should the consultant be concerned about.
OptionA: Damage to the anterior fontanel, the area where the frontal bone will eventually fuse with the two temporal bones
OptionB: Damage to the anterior fontanel, the area where the occipital bone will eventually fuse with the two temporal bones
OptionC: Damage to the posterior fontanel, area where the occipital bones will eventually fuse with the two temporal bones
OptionD: Damage to the posterior fontanel, the area where the frontal bone and the two temporal bones will eventually fuse.
Explanation:
- Damage to the anterior fontanel the area where the frontal bone fuses with the two temporal bones (incorrect) 


- Damage to the posterior fontanel area where the occipital bones fuse with the two temporal bones (correct)


- Damage to the anterior fontanel the area where the occipital bone and the two temporal bone fuses (incorrect)


- Damage to the posterior fontanel the area where the frontal bone and the two temporal bones fuse (incorrect)

 

 

An injury to the head is of concern in a young child as the bones skull has not fully fused together. This means that the brain is vulnerable to damage in these particular areas (posterior fontanel and anterior fontanel)
The correct answer is the posterior fontanel as the blunt force trauma has occurred at the back of the head so its of a bigger concern than the anterior fontanel 
The posterior fontanel concerns the occipital bone and the 2 temporal bones
The anterior fontanel concerns the temporal bone and the 2 temporal bones

Question: Which organelle oxidises molecules within a cell and produces H2O2?
Explanation:
A= incorrect as lysosomes are involved in autophagy and phagocytosis.

B= Correct these contain oxidative enzymes and produce hydrogen peroxide.

C= incorrect as mitochondria are involved in ATP production for energy.

D= incorrect as endosomes are involved in endocytosis.

Question: A 25 year old male cricketer presents to A&E having had a ball strike him in the head specifically at the  the temple at  significant speed. What is the name of the specific area of the skull that is vulnerable to fracture and what are the consequences of such a fracture
OptionA: The pterion – epidural hematoma rupture of the middle meningeal artery
OptionB: The pterion – subdural hematoma rupture of the middle meningeal artery
OptionC: The temporal bone – subdural hematoma rupture of the superior meningeal artery
OptionD: The zygomatic bone – epidural hematoma rupture of the superior meningeal artery
Explanation:
The pterion – epidural hematoma rupture of the middle meningeal artery (correct)
The zygomatic bone – epidural hematoma rupture of the superior meningeal artery (incorrect)
The pterion – subdural hematoma rupture of the middle meningeal artery (incorrect)
The temporal bone – subdural hematoma rupture of the superior meningeal artery (incorrect)

 

 

The pterion region of the skull is the weakest point of the skull because of 2 main reasons, 

1 - It is structurally weak due to the union between many bones 

2- The bone in this area is very thin 

This makes this area prone to fracture.

As the Pterion lies over the middle meningeal artery as the bone becomes fractured damage to this vessel may occur leading to a epidural hematoma.

An epidural hematoma is where bleeding occurs between the dura mater and the skull 

 

A subdural hematoma occurs when there is a damage to the blood vessels within the dura causing a collection of blood between the dura matter and the brain, and is not what is found in this situation

Question: A patient presents with tingling in the pinky finger and medial half of the ring finger. What nerve may be damaged to cause this?
Explanation: This should be an easy question! The median nerve innervates the thumb, index, middle and lateral half of the ring finger. The ulnar nerve innervated the pinky finger and other half of the ring finger. The radial nerve innervates the back of the hand.

Question: Identify the correct labels for A to E.
Explanation:
C is correct!

A - Lunate
B - Triquetrum
C - Pisiform
D - Hamate

Question:
A 16-year-old male visits his GP after his mother noticed that one of his eyes was not moving in unison with the other. Upon examination, the GP observed the patient's right pupil was in the characteristic 'down and out' position and there was ptosis of the right eyelid. 

Using your knowledge of cranial nerves, which nerve has a lesion resulting in these symptoms?
Explanation:
E is the correct answer!

Lesion of the oculomotor nerve (CN III) results in a characteristic "down and out" pupil due to unopposed action of the superior oblique and lateral rectus muscles. Ptosis occurs as motor innervation of the levator palpebrae superiosis muscle is lost and so cannot elevate the superior eyelid. 

 

A - the trochlear nerve innervates the superior oblique muscle. A lesion here would result in the patient complaining of diplopia (double vision) and the potential development of a head tilt away from the site of the lesion.

B - the optic nerve does not innervate the extraocular muscles.

C - the abducens nerve innervates the lateral rectus. A lesion of here would result in the affected eye being abducted by the resting tone of the medial rectus.

D - the trigeminal nerve does not innervate the extraocular muscles.
Tags: Head and neck, PCS 3, Cranial Nerves, anatomy

Question: Where does a hiatal hernia occur?
Explanation:
D is the correct answer!

A hiatus hernia occurs when part of the stomach protrudes into the chest through the oesophageal hiatus of the diaphragm. There are 2 types: sliding hiatus hernia and rolling hiatus hernia.

Question: There are 4 auscultation sites. Identify the correct sites and the valves that correspond to each.
OptionA:
Left 2nd intercostal space- Pulmonary

Right 3rd intercostal space- Aortic

Left 5th intercostal space- Tricuspid 

Left 5th intercostal space in the mid-clavicular line- Mitral
OptionB:
Left 2nd intercostal space- Pulmonary

Right 2nd intercostal space- Aortic 

Left 5th intercostal space in mid-clavicular line- Mitral

Right 5th intercostal space- Tricuspid
OptionC:
Left 2nd intercostal space- Aortic
Right 2nd intercostal space- Pulmonary
Left 5th intercostal space- Tricuspid
Left 5th intercostal space in mid-clavicular line- Mitral
OptionD:
Left 2nd intercostal space- Pulmonary

Right 2nd intercostal space- Aortic

Left 5th intercostal space- Tricuspid 

Left 5th intercostal space in mid-clavicular line- Mitral
OptionE:
Left 2nd intercostal space- Pulmonary
Right 3rd intercostal space- Aortic
Left 5th intercostal space- Mitral
Left 5th intercostal space in the mid-clavicular line- Tricuspid
Explanation:

The 4 Auscultatory sites are:

Question: Which of these exteroceptors in the skin sense shear stress?
Explanation:
D- Ruffini's endings is the correct answer!

A- Naked endings sense pain and temperature. 

B- Pacinian corpuscule sense vibrations

C- Merkel's endings sense sustained pressure to recognise texture and shape.

Question:
Neurotransmitters are vital chemicals for communication between neurones and span a variety of responsibilities.

 

Which major class of these chemicals are considered responsible for things like consciousness, attention, cognition and emotion?
Explanation:
- Amino acid neurotransmitters have general functions involving excitatory and inhibitory mechanisms - Include Glutamate, GABA, Glycine etc.

 

- Monoamines (biogenic) neurotransmitters are responsible for consciousness, attention, cognition, emotion and more. Include Serotonin, Histamine, Dopamine, Epinephrine (adrenaline), Norepinephrine (noradrenaline)

 

- Catecholamines are a sub-group within Monoamines, while they would have similar actions to monoamines, catecholamines are not the major class of these neurotransmitters. Dopamine, Epinephrine (adrenaline) and Norepinephrine (noradrenaline) are all Catecholamines

 

- Peptide neurotransmitters such as opioids have roles generally to do with pain e.g. Endorphins

Question: Within the brainstem, there are certain neurones which appear dark. What are these neurones and how might they appear in a person who has Parkinson's disease?
OptionA:
Adrenergic Neurons 

Lighter than in a person without Parkinson's
OptionB:
Dopaminergic Neurons 

Lighter than in a person without Parkinson's disease
OptionC:
Adrenergic Neurons 

Darker than in a person without Parkinson's
OptionD:
Dopaminergic Neurons

Darker than in a person without Parkinson's disease
Explanation:
Correct answer is B!

Dopaminergic neurones are found in the substantia nigra of the basal ganglia which is part of the basal ganglia. Their function is to produce dopamine and as a bi-product, melanin is produced. In a person with Parkinson's, these neurones die and therefore, no dopamine or melanin is produced in this area, causing the region to appear lighter.

Here is a link to a short video explaining Parkinson's disease: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7upHDhAmkqU

Question:
FSH is an important reproductive hormone produced and secreted from gonadotrophs in the anterior pituitary.

Correctly identify the primary functions of FSH.
OptionA:
Development of follicle by decreasing the number of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte
Stimulates aromatase to convert Androstenedione to oestrogen
Maintains the corpus luteum and endometrium
OptionB:
Growth and development of follicle by increasing the number of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte
Stimulates aromatase to convert Androstenedione to oestrogen
Maintains the endometrium
OptionC:
Growth and development of follicle by increasing the number of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte
Stimulates release of progesterone

Maintains the endometrium
OptionD:
Growth and development of follicle by increasing the number of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte
Inhibits aromatase from converting Androstenedione to oestrogen
Maintains the corpus luteum
OptionE:
Growth and development of follicle by increasing the number of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte 

Stimulates aromatase to convert Androstenedione to oestrogen 

Maintains the corpus luteum
Explanation:
E is correct!

The primary roles of FSH are:

  • Stimulates the growth and development of the follicle by increasing the number of granolas cells

Question: The piriformis muscle forms part of the posterior pelvic wall. Piriformis leaves the lesser pelvis via a feature of the pelvic bone. What is the name of this feature?
Explanation:
A is correct! 

Piriformis leaves the lesser pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen and goes attaches to the femur bone. Piriformis muscle also acts as a bed for the sacral plexus network

Question: What types of joints are the sacroiliac and pubic symphysis joints in the pelvis?
Explanation:
Correct answer is B!

The sacroiliac joint is a synovial joint formed by the sacrum and the ilium bones of the pelvis. 

The pubic symphysis is a cartilaginous joint between the 2 pubic rami. 

To remember this:

S for sacroiliac, S for synovial 

PCS is like PSC: pubic symphysis cartilaginous

Question: The Anterior pituitary gland secretes 6 different hormones most of which are tropic hormones, what are the 6 hormones that the anterior pituitary gland secretes?
OptionA: Growth Hormone, Adrenaline, Adrenocorticotropic hormone, Thyroid stimulating hormone, follicle stimulating hormone and luteinising hormone.
OptionB: Adrenocorticotropic hormone, Thyroid stimulating hormone, Prolactin, luteinising hormone, Follicle stimulating hormone and growth hormone.
OptionC: Oestrogen, Growth hormone, thyroid stimulating hormone, progesterone, follicle stimulating hormone and testosterone.
OptionD: MSH, Growth hormone, prolactin, thyroid stimulating hormone, adrenaline and progesterone
OptionE: GnRH, somatostatin, growth hormone, MSH, thyroid stimulating hormone and adrenaline
Explanation: Growth hormone, prolactin, adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH), Follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinising hormone (LH) are the 6 hormones- several of these hormones are tropic hormones which means that they regulate the secretions of other endocrine organs for example ACTH stimulates the adrenal cortex to go on and secrete its hormones such as adrenaline.

Question: Angiotensin converting enzyme is released from the lungs. What is the function of this enzyme?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C! 

This process is part of the renin-angiotensin system.

When fluid volume and blood pressure are low, renin is released from the kidney. Renin acts on angiotensinogen, which is released from the liver, and converts it to angiotensin I. ACE is then released from the lungs to convert angiotensin I into angiotensin II. Angiotensin II acts directly on blood vessels, causing vasoconstriction. Or, angiotensin II stimulates adrenal glands to release aldosterone which increases salt and water absorption in the kidneys. These actions increase the fluid volume and blood pressure.

Question: Which of these veins do not join to the coronary sinus but drain deoxygenated blood directly into the right atrium?
Explanation:
A) Incorrect! Winds from the anterior aspect of the heart to meet the coronary sinus.

B) Correct! Can be seen going directly into the right atrium.

C) Incorrect! Meets the coronary sinus from the apex of the heart.

D) Incorrect! Meets the coronary sinus posteriorly.

E) Incorrect! Winds from the anterior aspect of the heart to meet the coronary sinus like A).

Question: You have an upcoming tutorial and have done minimal pre reading. You start to stress that Dr Jeff Allen will pick on you. At 9 am you log onto zoom and see Dr Allen flashing his wholesome smile. You know he’s definitely going to pick on you. Your stomach feels funny, as if there’s butterflies in it and your palms start to sweat. What’s going on in this situation and what is the physiology behind this?
OptionA:
You're anticipating stress.

If the situation is perceived as stressful, the hypothalamus is activated.

Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) is released from the hypothalamus. 

ACTH binds to receptors on the adrenal cortex.

This stimulates the release of cortisol, a steroid hormone into the bloodstream.

Cortisol causes blood vessels surrounding the stomach and intesintes to constrict and muscles to contract. Sweat glands are also stimulated.
OptionB:
You’re starting to develop a fever.

The anticipation of stress caues your hypothalmus to be activated.

This simulates release of histamines.

As a result, your body temperature rises to combat this and sweating begins in an effort to cool the body again.

Due to this change, stoimach acidity increases and this causes a funny feeling in your stomach.
OptionC:
You’re having a bad reaction to food.

This is because the anticipated stress is causing your parasympathetic nervus system to stimulate the production of gastrin indirectly.

As a result, the acidity in your stomach rises, making your stomach feel fluttery.

Because your body’s pH has changed, you start sweating to lower it.
OptionD:
You’re anticipating stress.
If a situation is percieved as stressful, hypothalamus is activated.
Corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) is secreted by the hypothalamus.
CRH binding to specific receptors on the anterior pituitary gland causes production of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH).
ACTH is released and travels to the adrenal glands, where it binds to specific receptors on the adrenal cortex.
The binding of ACTH to the receptors on the adrenal cortex stimulates the release of cortisol into the bloodstream.

Cortisol causes blood vessels surrounding stomach and intestines to constrict and muscles to contract. Cortisol also stimulates your sweat glands.
OptionE:
You‘re anticipating stress.

When stress is perceived, the hypothalamus is activated. As a result, CRH is released from the hypothalamus. 

CRH binds to receptors in the adrenal glands and those stimulates the release of cortisol.

Cortisol stimulates the release of ACTH from the anterior pituitary.

Cortisol causes intestines to contract and blood flow to the GI tract to decrease. Body temperaure also rises and this causes sweating to cool the body down.
Explanation:
Stress is perceived and this activates the hypothalamus. CRH is released from the hypothalamus. ACTH is then released from the anterior pituitary gland. Cortisol is released from the adrenal cortex. 

Cortisol causes constriction of the blood vessels surrounding your stomach and intestines and the digestive muscles contract. It's that drop in blood flow that makes you feel like winged insects are fluttering around in your stomach.

cortisol is also said to increase body temp resulting in sweating. The sweat due to stress is different as it has a pungent odour. This is because apocrine sweat glands (armpit and groin) are activated due to stress. All occurs due to the HPA (hypothalamic pituitary adrenal) axis.

 

Excess sweating is a condition called hyperhydrosis.

Question: Which of the following is false regarding the musculoskeletal system?
OptionA: Acts as a framework for the body.
OptionD: Acts as a reservoir for storage of iron.
OptionE: Involved in the regulation of mineral homeostasi.
Explanation:
D is false - iron is stored as ferritin in the liver and in RBC (haem in Haemoglobin). To cross the plasma membrane Fe3+ is converted to Fe2+ using an enzyme ferric reductase. This is seen in enterocytes.

 

Calcium and phosphate are the 2 main components of Hydroxyapatite - the bone mineral that strengthens the mechanical resistance of the bone matrix. Phosphate also plays a role in the maturation of osteocytes.

Question: Which extraocular muscle‘s main action is intorsion and what is its innervation?
OptionA: Inferior oblique muscle - innervated by oculomotor nerve
OptionB: Inferior rectus muscle - innervated by oculomotor nerve
OptionC: Superior rectus muscle - innervated by oculomotor nerve
OptionD: Superior oblique muscle - innervated by oculomotor nerve
OptionE: Superior oblique muscle - innervated by trochlear nerve
Explanation:
Mnemonic to help - SOI IOX (superior oblique intorsion and inferior oblique eXtorsion)

to remember the nerves - LARSOT - Lateral rectus -> Abducens , Superior oblique -> trochlear 

 

Remember that only one muscle is responsible for upper eyelid moevement -> Levator palpabrae superiori. Innervated by oculomotor nerve. Superior tarsal muscle assists and it‘s innervated by Sympathetic fibres from the superior cervical ganglion.

In the lower eyelid is mostly controlled by orbicularis oculi muscle.

 

the remaining 6 extraocular muscles we have learned have actions in moving the eyeball. Some muscles have a main action eg lateral rectus for abduction. but these muscles also assist other muscles in the total movement of the eyeball.
Tags: anatomy, Eyes, Head and neck, PCS 3, innervation

Question: A young man aged 32 has recently been diagnosed by his consultant with a pituitary tumour after having continuous sight issues . From your understanding of the lesions within the optic pathway what area within the optic pathway is affected and what specifically would you expect in the patients visual field.
OptionA: damage / compression of the optic chiasm - loss of vision on the lateral sides of his left and right eye
OptionB: damage / compression of the optic chiasm - loss of vision on the medial side of the left eye
OptionC: damage / compression of the optic nerve - loss of vision on the medial sides of his left and right eye
OptionD: damage / compression of the retina - loss off vision on in both eyes
OptionE: damage / compression of the retina - loss of vision on the lateral side of his left eye
Explanation:
Pituitary tumours compress the optic chiasm and cause bitemporal hemianopia (loss of peripheral vision in both eyes). This is as the optic chiasm is the area where fibres from both eyes cross. 

 

Left eye

The information that comes from the left side of the world crosses to move towards the right side of the brain. so damage to the fibres that cross will be damaged and therefor images from the left side of the world will be lost.

 

Right eye

The information that comes from the right side of the world and crosses towards  the left side of the brain so damage to the fibres that cross will be damaged and therefor image from the right side of the world will be lost.

Question: What are oxytocin receptors in the uterus are activated by?
OptionC: Equal high levels of oestrogen and progesterone
OptionD: Equal low levels of oestrogen and progesterone
Explanation:
B is correct!

When there are high levels of oestrogen relative to progesterone, oxytocin receptors in the uterus are activated. Oxytocin stimulates the uterine muscles to contract during labour.

Question: In females, what does the term 'Bridge over troubled water' refer to?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

The uterine artery lies over the ureter, not the urethra! This is clinically important as during a hysterectomy, removing the uterus and uterine artery means the ureter is at risk of being damaged.

Question: Which option describes the correct movement of ions during phase 2 of a cardiac action potential?
OptionA:
Influx of Calcium ions via L type calcium channels 

Efflux of potassium ions via delayed potassium channels
OptionB:
Influx of Calcium ions via L type calcium channels
Efflux of sodium ions via delayed sodium channels
OptionC:
Influx of sodium ions via sodium channels
Efflux of potassium ions via delayed potassium channels
OptionD:
Influx of potassium ions via delayed potassium channels
Efflux of calcium ions via L type calcium channels
OptionE:
Influx of sodium and calcium ions via sodium channels and L type calcium channels 

Efflux of potassium ions via delayed potassium channels
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Calcium ions move into cells via L type calcium channels whereas, potassium moves out of cells via delayed potassium channels. The movement of these 2 ions 'balance' each other out and can be seen as almost a plateau on a cardiac action potential graph.

Question: What is the equation for the bicarbonate buffer system?
Explanation:
A - INCORRECT. This only the partial equation to the complete buffer equation.

B - INCORRECT. H2CO3- is the wrong symbol for bicarbonate.

C - INCORRECT. CO2 does not react with H2 but to H2O and carbonic acid is not an enzyme.

 

D - CORRECT!

The full equation for the bicarbonate buffer system is CO2 + H2O ⇌ H2CO3 ⇌ HCO3- + H+. As H2CO3 is usually in very small quantities, the equation is normally summarised as CO2 + H2O ⇌ HCO3- + H+.

 

 

E - INCORRECT. This is the equation for photosynthesis. We are not studying plant physiology (thank the Lord).

Question:
The spine is formed by vertebrae from five regions; the cervical (cervix = "neck"), thoracic, lumbar, sacral and coccygeal / caudal vertebrae. 

(Although, the sacral and coccygeal vertebrae fuse in adulthood).

 

This question will be very straight forward, so try answering the following question before reading the options.

How many are there of each class of vertebrae?
Explanation:
The vertebrae are as follows...

C 1-7

T 1-12

L 1-5

S 1-5

C 1-3, 1-4 or 1-5 (There can be 3 to 5 Coccygeal vertebrae, most people have 4 which fuse in adulthood. 

 

You could google "Numbers and Types of vertebrae" for various diagrams

Question:
The spinal cord begins at the bottom of the brain stem, from the medulla oblongata, and ends in the lower back, as it tapers to form a cone called the conus medullaris.

 

At which, or between which vertebral level(s) does the spinal cord end?
OptionC: Between the 5th (final) Sacral vertebra and the 1st Coccygeal vertebra
Explanation:
The spinal cord tapers and ends at the level between the first and second lumbar vertebrae in an average adult. The most distal bulbous part of the spinal cord is called the Conus Medullaris, and its tapering end continues as the filum terminale, before forming the Cauda Equina.

 

 

This is why we perform Lumbar punctures for spinal taps and not Sacral or Thoracic punctures for example.

Just bellow where the spinal cord tapers and ends is a collection of nerves called the Cauda Equina (Horse Tail) due to their appearance.

There is spinal fluid here that can be extracted without damaging the spinal cord. A needle can safely be inserted between L3 and L4.

 

 

Useful info on Medscape at https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1148690-overview#:~:text=The%20spinal%20cord%20tapers%20and,continues%20as%20the%20filum%20terminale

Question: What is the correct difference between an agonist and an antagonist in terms of their affinity for the receptor and intrinsic activity?
OptionA:
Agonist- has an affinity for the receptor, however, has no intrinsic activity.

Antagonist- has affinity for receptor and has intrinsic activity
OptionB:
Agonist- has affinity for receptor and has intrinsic activity

Antagonist- has affinity for receptor but no intrinsic activity
OptionC:
Agonist- doesn't have affinity for receptor but has intrinsic activity

Antagonist- doesn't have affinity for receptor but has intrinsic activity
OptionD:
Agonist- doesn't have affinity for receptor and doesn't have intrinsic activity

Antagonist- has affinity for receptor but doesn't have intrinsic activity
OptionE:
Agonist- has affinity for receptor and has intrinsic activity
Antagonist- has affinity for receptor but and has intrinsic activity
Explanation:
Agonist- binds to the receptor and interacts to produce an effect. The agonist has affinity for receptor and intrinsic activity
Antagonist- binds to the receptor but does not produce an effect. The antagonist prevents access of neurotransmitters to the receptor. It Has affinity for receptor but NO intrinsic activity

Question: What's the difference between saturated and unsaturated fatty acids?
OptionA:
saturated fatty acids do contain a carbon to carbon double bond, carbons are linked to a minimum number of hydrogen atoms.

Whilst unsaturated fatty acids don't contain a carbon to carbon double bond, creating a straight chain.
OptionB:
saturated fatty acids do contain a carbon to carbon double bond, carbons are linked to minimum number of carbon atoms.

Whilst unsaturated fatty acids don't contain a carbon to carbon double bond, creating a kink in the chain.
OptionC:
saturated fatty acids don't contain a carbon to carbon double bond, carbons are linked to a maximum number of hydrogen atoms.

Whilst unsaturated fatty acids do contain a carbon to carbon double bond, creating a kink in the chain.
OptionD:
saturated fatty acids don't contain a carbon to carbon double bond, hydrogens are linked to a maximum number of carbon atoms.

Whilst unsaturated fatty acids do contain a carbon to carbon double bond, creating a kink chain.
Explanation:
C is correct!

 

Saturated and Unsaturated fatty acids are different due to the presence of a carbon to carbon double bond, that creates a kink (unsaturated) or a straight chain (saturated).

 

Therefore;

Saturated= no C=C, all C atoms linked to a maximum possible number of H atoms, creating a straight chain

Unsaturated= C=C present, straight chain of fatty acid may kink

 

(remember; unsaturated fatty acids contain 2 types; 

1. cis; where H atoms attached to C=C are on the SAME SIDE

2. trans; where H atoms attached to C=C are on DIFFERENT SIDES

Question: What does amphibolic mean?
OptionB: pathway that includes anabolic and catabolic processes
OptionD: pathway that doesn't include anabolic and catabolic processes
Explanation:
B is correct!

 

Anabolic pathways are those that require energy to synthesize larger molecules. Catabolic pathways are those that generate energy by breaking down larger molecules.

 

An example of a amphibolic pathway is Kreb's cycle. In the Kreb's cycle;

1. Catabolism of carbs + fatty acids
2. Synthesis of anabolic precursors for amino acids synthesis (oxaloacetate)

Question: The microtubules are used to move vesicles around inside the cell. What are their motor proteins called?
Explanation:
Spindle fibres are made from tubulin proteins.

Actin and myosin are involved in muscle contraction.

Question: Following  an injury a  patient comes to A and E  presenting with neck and shoulder pain and more specifically a dull ache along  the medial border of the scapula. The nerve innervation to 2 extrinsic muscles that attach here has been damaged  .What is the nerve ?
Explanation:
E is correct , well done ! - Remember the clue here is that the Levator scapulae and the rhomboids are extrinsic muscles that both attach to the medial border of the scapula and are both innervated by the Dorsal scapula nerve .Extrinsic meaning – originate from the torso, and attach to the bones of the shoulder (clavicle, scapula or humerus).

 

A - The accessory nerve innervates the trapezius muscle which is extrinsic but attachment spans over the Acromion process, clavicle and scapula

 

B - the axillary nerve is responsible for innervating the Teres Minor and the deltoid muscle  which  are both Intrinsic muscles (Intrinsic – originate from the scapula and/or clavicle, and attach to the humerus.)  So they do not attach to the scapula 

 

C - the Suprascapular nerve innervates the Supraspinatus and infraspinatus  Intrinsic rotator cuff muscles , so they do not attach to the scapula .

 

E-  the Thoracodorsal nerve innervates the Latissimus Dorsi . Though this is an extrinsic muscle It attaches to the Intertubercular groove so it cannot be this .

Question: A patient presents in your GP surgery with fibromyalgia, a condition which causes them chronic pain. You notice that they have a heightened pain response to light touch. What is this symptom clinically known as?

B - incorrect as this is a decreased sensitivity to painful stimuli

Question: A 71-year-old male patient has been brought into the local A&E department, after sustaining a gunshot wound, the bullet skimmed the lateral part of the left humerus. The patient is also complaining of numbness in the posterior forearm and is showing an inability to extend the wrist and fingers (wrist drop)- the doctor believes that these symptoms are directly related to the gunshot wound. Using your knowledge of the upper limb, what was injured when the patient was shot? (if the patient was facing forward like you're facing the screen of the computer, they were shot by someone from the direction of 7 o clock- gunman has bad aim)
OptionA: The patient has damaged the extensor carpi radialis longus and the extensor digitorum.
OptionB: Radial nerve palsy as a result of the damage to the radial nerve via the humerus.
OptionC: (High) median nerve palsy as a result of damage to the median nerve via the humerus.
OptionD: Torn triceps brachii tendon of the lateral head.
OptionE: The patient has damaged the axillary nerve on the left side.
Explanation: It is B because the gunshot wound is sustained on the lateral side of the arm (in the anatomical position), the radial nerve runs along the lateral side of the humerus in the radial groove. An injury like the bullet skimming the lateral part of the humerus could damage the radial nerve. Damage to the radial nerve leads to the extrinsic extensor function of the hand and wrist being lost- resulting in the inability to extend the fingers and wrist (the symptoms the patient presented with). This results in the condition known as radial nerve palsy. The radial nerve is essential in innervating the extensor muscles of the forearm and the triceps brachii. This time though the symptoms for a torn tricep tendon wouldn't match with this patients profile.

Question: What is the important molecule that both up-regulates glycolysis and down-regulates gluconeogenesis?
During fasting ketones are produced in the liver due to glucose shortages. Choose the most appropriate explanation as to why this is necessary.
OptionA: Due to lack of acetyl CoA for Krebs cycle due to down-regulation of the link reaction.
OptionB: To be used to produce glucose in gluconeogensis
OptionC: Due to oxaloacetate being used for gluconeogensis, breaking the Krebs cycle and leading to acetyl coA build up
OptionD: Due to acetyl coA being used in gluconegoensis, inhibiting the Krebs cycle
Explanation:
C is the correct awnser! 

During fasting the liver uses up its glycogen stores and thus converts everything into glucose via gluconegoensis. Oxaloactete is required for gluconeogensis causing the Krebs cycle to be broken due to its loss. However, acetyl coA is still being produced through fatty acids breakdown and therefore leads to acetyl coA build up. Consequently the excess acetyl coA is converted to ketones in the liver, this allows for fatty acids to continue being broken down and ketones can also cross the blood brain barrier so are used for the TCA cycle in the brain.

Question: High density lipoproteins (HDL) are one of the five major groups of lipoproteins. What is the function of HDL's in lipid transport?
OptionA: Takes excess cholesterol from the rest of the body to the liver to be reused/recyled
OptionB: Transport dietary TAG's from the intestine to other tissues
OptionC: Transport newly formed fats from liver to other tissues
OptionD: Used as an enzyme in the cholesterol synthesis
OptionE: Breaks down cholesterol into bile salts for excretion
Explanation:
A is the correct answer!

B is the function of chylomicrons 

C is the function of VLDL's and LDL's

D and E are incorrect as HDL's are used in  cholesterol transport rather than the reactions required to synthesis/breakdown cholesterol.

Question: You are carrying out a fundoscopy examination . During the procedure the patient complains telling you they are not able to focus on close distant objects . You tell them that is because  you have administered which drug ?
Explanation:
C - This is correct , well done . This drug acts as an  antagonist. It will bind and block cholinergic receptors , inhibiting Parasympathetic pathways. We know that the ciliary muscle  has parasympathetic innervation , if this innervation is inhibited , the muscle is paralyzed and wont be able to contract . Hence , the patient wont be able to focus on close distant objects . 

 

A - Phenylephrine acts as an agonist in the sympathetic pathway. it will bind to adrenergic receptors mimicking noradrenaline. This will result in pupil dilation and constriction of blood vessels . 

 

B - Pilocarpine is an  agonist  in the parasympathetic pathway. This means that it will bind to cholinergic receptors and mimic acetylcholine. This will result in Pupil constriction and dilation of blood vessels  , giving a blood shot appearance. 

 

D - Tetracaine is an anesthetic . It works by blocking Voltage gated sodium channels so that no action potential can be generated. As a result the no sensory impulses are sent , which  will  relieve pain in the eye. 

 

E - Fluorescein is a fluorescent dye that glows green under blue light.

Question: Narrow angle glaucoma is a serious type of glaucoma that occurs suddenly. This condition occurs when fluid builds up behind the iris. This buildup of fluid causes a sudden, dangerous increase in intraocular pressure. Intraocular pressure can be lowered by stimulation of parasympathetic nerve fibres acting on the pupil constrictor muscles, causing constriction of the pupil and consequently opening of the Canal of Schlemm to allow excess fluid to drain. What drug could be administered to cause this?
Explanation:
D is the correct awnser!

  • Phenylephrine stimulates sympathetic nerve fibres acting on the pupil dilator causing pupil dilation as well as whitening of the sclera through vasoconstriction.
  • Tropicamide is a muscarinic receptor antagonist (blocker) acting on the parasympathetic system, it causes paralysis of both cilary muscles and constricter muscles causing pupil dilation and inability to focus on close distant objects. 
  • Tetracaine is a local anaesthetic that blocks voltage-gates Na+ channels in sensory nerve axons, causing temporary numbing of pain and pressure so it inhibits the corneal reflex. 
  • Fluorescein is a fluorescent dye that can be used to diagnose corneal abrasions and foreign bodies

Question: You are assessing the movements of a patient's eyes. As you move your finger from left to right, you notice that the left eye is following your finger fine but the right eye does not fully abduct when you move your finger to the left. Which nerve is most likely to be damaged and what muscle does this relate to?
Explanation:
Answer: 

B: Abducens Nerve (CN VI) - Lateral Rectus Muscle

The lateral rectus muscle is the main muscle responsible for abducting the eye. If the eye is not abducting fully, this is most likely the muscle that has had its nerve damaged. The nerve that supplies lateral rectus is the abducens nerve (CN IV).

 

 

A: Abducens nerve does not supply the inferior oblique.

C: Trochlear nerve does not supply the inferior oblique.

D: If the oculomotor nerve had been damaged, the right eye would be seen to only be able to abduct as the superior, medial and inferior rectus would be affected by this damage.

E: Oculomotor nerve does not supply the lateral rectus.

 

Image link: https://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=i&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.slideserve.com%2Fklaus%2Flab-activity-19-20&psig=AOvVaw2OxNQUKvyF_CsDROF_5VwW&ust=1608764981741000&source=images&cd=vfe&ved=0CAIQjRxqFwoTCLiW8t7a4u0CFQAAAAAdAAAAABAJ

Explanation:
A is the correct answer! 

Cells involved include

Natural killer cells
Eosinophils
Basophils
Mast cells

 

Complement are involved in the innate immune system but are proteins not cells.

Question: Which complement proteins are pro inflammatory peptides?
Explanation:
B is correct!

 

C3a, C4a and C5a are pro inflammatory peptides that induce the release of inflammatory mediators from mast cells. They bind to mast cells and basophils to cause degranulation. Histamine and serotonin released increase vascular permeability. Also promote the synthesis of pro inflammatory cytokines. 

The complement system forms part of the innate immune system and complement components are usually made in the liver. The complement system supports other parts of the immune system by opsonising pathogens and triggering inflammation

Question: Steroid hormones such as testosterone and oestrogen are different in many ways to peptide hormone such as ADH and Growth Hormone. Which of the following is not true regarding steroid hormones?
OptionE: Mechanism of action is binding DNA/modifying transcription

Question: In glycolysis, glucokinase catalyses the phosphorylation of glucose forming glucose-6-phosphate. What is this enzyme inhibited by?
Explanation:
Glucokinase is basically the liver version of hexokinase.

Hexokinase is involved in the first step of glycolysis and is inhibited by Glucose-6-phosphate both allosterically and competitively.

Glucokinase is not inhibited, which is important because it acts as a glucose sensor. It has as a lower affinity to glucose, so will only catalyse the reaction with high blood glucose level. This is useful as Glucose 6-phosphate is what is used to make glycogen.

Question: A way of combating obesity would be to use 2,4DHP sliming drug. But it has been banned as it has toxic effects on kidneys. Also causing nausea, vomiting, liver failure, overheating, irregular heart rate and death. How does 2,4DHP make someone lose weight?
OptionA: It is lipid soluble so can easily enter adipocytes' cell membranes and bind to an intracellular receptor, initiating a cascade that would eventually lead to lipolysis
OptionB: It opens the thermogenin channel which is a mitochondrial proton channel allowing protons to flow from the intermembrane space back into the matrix without having to go through ATP synthase
OptionC: It gradually inhibits the electron transport chain by acting as a proton ionophore, that is, it binds protons on one side of a membrane, and being fat-soluble it drifts to the opposite side where it loses the protons.
OptionD: It uncouples the electron transport chain from ATP synthesis which allows rapid oxidation of Krebs substrates, promoting the mobilisation of carbohydrates and fats
OptionE: It effectively accepts and donates proton, so uncouples electron transport chain
Explanation:
A) Incorrect

B) That's how neonates uncouple the ETC chain to generate non-shivering heat in order to keep warm

C) Is correct but doesn't specifically answer the "weight loss" part of the question

D) Specifically answers the question

E) Is correct but D is more specific and actually answers the question

Question: Fintrol is used as a fish poison that contains Antimycin A which inhibits the electron transport chain. How does that work?
OptionA: It is an allosteric inhibitor of of cytochrome c reductase (complex III). It binds to the Qi site inhibiting the oxidation of ubiquinone (CoQ) so it can't deliver its electrons causing disruption of the ETC chain
OptionB: It blocks NADH dehydrogenase (complex I) in the respiratory chain, blocking the flow of electrons from NADH to CoQ (ubiquinone). Therefore no ATP can be formed from NADH
OptionC: It is a competitive inhibitor that disrupts the electron transport chain by binding to the enzyme cytochrome c oxidase (complex IV) so it cannot transport any electrons to oxygen. The cell is unable to produce ATP aerobically
OptionD: It gradually inhibits electron transport chain by acting as a proton ionophore, that is, it binds protons on one side of a membrane, and being fat-soluble it drifts to the opposite side where it loses the protons so they don't pass through ATP synthase
Explanation:
A) correct!

B) this is the action of Amytal

C) this is the action of Cyanide

D) this is actually how 2,4DNP uncouples the ETC chain leading to weight loss (and also death)

E) honestly same

Question:
A young man has come into the hospital with a new unknown respiratory infection the inmate immune response is kicked into action.

What cells are involved and where are these cells found?
OptionA:
blood = basophils, eosinophils, natural killers, and mast cells

OptionC:

Question: You are a junior doctor working in A&E. A patient presents with chest pain and shortness of breath. Upon listening to his chest with a stethoscope, you hear a systolic ejection murmur which you deduce is indicative of a faulty cardiac valve. You place your stethoscope on the right second intercostal space. Which valve requires repair?
Explanation:
The aortic valve is located in the right 2nd intercostal space. 

 

Systolic ejection murmur's (SEMs) most commonly present as aortic stenosis (narrowing of the aortic valve).

 

Aortic stenosis restricts the blood flow from the left ventricle to the aorta resulting in shortness of breath.

 

The muscle of the left ventricle is working harder to eject blood through the narrowed aortic valve and therefore has a higher oxygen demand.

 

The muscle's oxygen demand is in excess of the oxygen delivered in the blood resulting in chest pain (angina).
Tags: Blood vessels, PCS 3, Heart, Cardiology, Thorax

Question: The mnemonic to remember the causes of cardio-respiratory arrest consist of 4Hs and 4Ts. What are the 4Hs?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. Causes of cardio-respiratory arrest include;

 

Hypoxia: deficiency in the amount of oxygen reaching the tissues


Hypovolemia: abnormal depletion in the volume of blood, more specifically blood plasma


Hypo/hyperthermia: the condition of having an abnormally (typically dangerously) high or low body temperature


Hypo/hyperkalaemia: a potassium level in your blood that is higher or lower than normal

Question: After numerous investigations ,you have diagnosed a 50 year old, multiple sclerosis patient with brown-sequard syndrome . The lumbar lesion is on the right hand side of their spinal cord . What symptoms is the patient most likely to experience ?
OptionA:
Loss of Discriminative touch , Conscious proprioception and vibration Contralaterally 

Loss of Simple touch , pain and temperature Ipsilaterally
OptionB:
Loss of Discriminative touch , Conscious proprioception and vibration on the left hand side of the body

Loss of Simple touch , pain and temperature contralaterally
OptionC:
Loss of Discriminative touch , Conscious proprioception and vibration Ipsilaterally 

Loss of Simple touch , pain and temperature on the left hand side of the body
OptionD:
Loss of Discriminative touch , Conscious proprioception and vibration Ipsilaterally

Loss of Simple touch , pain and temperature on both sides of the body
OptionE:
Loss of Discriminative touch , Conscious proprioception and vibration on both sides of the body 

Loss of Simple touch , pain and temperature on the left hand side of the body
Explanation:
Well done C is the correct answer ! 

- The dorsal column pathway is responsible for Discriminative touch , Conscious proprioception and vibration. It will synapse with the sensory interneuron at the medulla region ( where it will cross sides ).Hence any effects from damage to this pathway will take place on the Same side as the lumbar lesion.

- The Spinothalamic pathway is responsible for Simple touch , pain and temperature. It will synapse with the sensory interneuron at the spinal cord region (where it will cross sides ). Hence any effects from damage to this pathway will take place on the opposite side of the lumbar lesion.

- Remember in this case : 

-Right hand side = ipsilateral = on the same side as the lumbar lesion

-left hand side = contralateral = on the opposite side of the lumbar lesion 

- The last power point slide from the sensory nervous system lecture should be helpful to visualize this
