Question: A fracture through the roof of the maxillary sinus might result in sensory loss to the:
Explanation:
The upper incisor and canine teeth receive sensory innervation from the anterior superior alveolar nerve, which runs along the floor of the orbit. As the roof of the maxillary sinus abuts the floor of the orbit, a fracture here might result in a lesion in the anterior superior alveolar nerve.

The upper molar teeth receive sensory innervation from the posterior superior alveolar nerve, which does not run along the floor of the orbit and would therefore not be affected by a fracture through the roof of the maxillary sinus.

Question: Which type of joint is this?
Explanation:
D is correct

 

Fibrous joint - Permits little to no movement (synarthrosis) due to dense fibrous connective tissue holding the bones together

(e.g. sutures between flat bones in the skull)

Primary cartilaginous joint - Permits slight movement (amphiarthrosis) and contains a layer of hyaline cartilage between the bones (e.g. sternocostal joint)

Secondary cartilaginous joint - Contains an extra layer of fibrocartilage between the hyaline layers (e.g. intervertebral disk joint)

Synovial joint - Permits complete movement (diarthrosis) and ends of bones are covered in a layer of hyaline cartilage in a joint cavity filled with synovial fluid  (e.g. elbow joint)

Question: What type of leukocyte is referred to as the machismo cell of the innate immune system and is described commonly as 'live hard, die young' cells and exist naturally in the blood even before an infection?
Explanation: Neutrophils exist naturally in the blood in large numbers and carry out the phagocytosis at the site of infection. It is not macrophages as they exist in the peripheral tissues awaiting the presence of pathogens which they detect through PRR's. It is not the natural killer cells as even though they are found in the blood, neutrophils are most abundant in the blood NK cells are not. NK cells are involved in the direct lysis of virally infected cells, whereas the neutrophils carry out phagocytosis at the site of infection (non-specific).

Question: What is the path of the pudenal nerve in the pelvis?
OptionA: Crosses the sacrospinous ligament; exits greater sciatic foramen; re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen
OptionB: Exits lesser sciatic foramen; crosses the ischial spine; re-enters the perineum through the greater sciatic foramen
OptionC: Exits greater sciatic foramen; crosses the sacrospinous ligament; re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen
OptionD: Exits greater sciatic foramen; crosses the ischial spine; re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen
OptionE: Exits greater sciatic foramen; crosses the sacrospinous ligament; re-enters the perineum through the obturator foramen
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

 

The pudenal nerve arises from the ventral rami of nerve roots S2, S3 and S4, before descending between the piriformis and ischiococcygeus muscles. From here it exits greater sciatic foramen, crosses the sacrospinous ligament, and re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen. Upon re-entry, it passes through the pudenal canal with the internal pudenal artery and vein, before branching into the inferior rectal nerve, then the perineal nerve, before continuing as the dorsal nerve of the penis or clitoris. 

 

The pudenal nerve innervates the anal sphincters and the urethral sphincter and provides cutaneous sensory innervation to the perineum, the penis, the scrotum, the labia majora, and the clitoris.

Question: One common symptom of COVID-19 is loss of taste and smell. Which cranial nerve is most likely being affected by the virus?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

 

The Olfactory nerve is responsible for the special sense of smell, with many receptors found in the lining of the nasal cavity responding to molecules in the air and relaying this information to the olfactory bulb, and then forebrain for processing via the olfactory tract.

 

The sense of taste is highly influenced by the taste of smell, so when the ability to smell is lost, many will also lose their sense of taste. This is why it is more likely to be the Olfactory nerve that is affected, rather than the Facial nerve which provides sense of taste to the anterior 2/3rd of the tongue, or the Glossopharyngeal nerve which provides taste to the posterior 1/3rd.

 

The Ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve is responsible from sensory innervation of the upper face, including the mucous membranes and sinuses.

 

The Hypoglossal nerve is responsible for motor innervation of the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue.

 

Extra Info:

The suspected mechanism by which COVID causes loss of smell is via damage to the supporting cells of the olfactory receptors. The receptors of the olfactory nerve are supported by glial cells known as Olfactory Ensheathing Cells (OECs) which myelinate the receptors and help maintain their health and function. These OEC's have been found to have a surface protein ACE-2 which can be targeted by the COVID-19 virus, allowing them to be damaged. Damage to these OEC's result in poor functioning of the olfactory receptors themselves, causing a loss in the ability to smell, and consequently taste.

 

Fortunately, these cells do regenerate fairly quickly so the sense of smell will usually return a few weeks or months following the infection.

Question: Which of these types of cartilage is the strongest?
Explanation:
Fibrocartilage is the strongest type of cartilage due to the dense layers of collagen (oriented in the same direction) which alternate with layers of hyaline cartilage.

Elastic cartilage contains chondrocytes that are found in a thread-like network of elastic fibres and provides strength and elasticity.

Question:
Lipoproteins exist in the phospholipid monolayer and are recognised by other receptors and enzymes. When you eat dietary fat it is packaged in large lipoproteins called ___1___.

These large lipoproteins go into circulation and deposit fat into tissues that need it. In the endothelium of these tissues there is an enzyme called ___2___ which recognises the lipoproteins and digests ___3___.

Explanation:
The correct answer is D 

 

Lipoproteins exist in the phospholipid monolayer and are recognised by other receptors and enzymes. When you eat dietary fat it is packaged in large lipoproteins called chylomicrons. These large lipoproteins go into circulation and deposit fat into tissues that need it. In the endothelium of these tissues there is an enzyme called LPL (lipoprotein lipase) which recognises the lipoproteins and digests TAG. Chylomicrons get smaller and become chylomicron remnants which are taken up by the liver and recycled. 

 

Extra background information: Excess carbohydrates is converted to fat by fatty acid synthesis. It is packaged in the liver into a slightly smaller version of lipoproteins called very low density lipoproteins (VLDL). The VLDL is exported and transported around the body and blood protein lipase takes fat out of them which makes them smaller. They become low density lipoproteins (LDL) which are taken up and recycled.

 

HDL recycles cholesterol from non liver tissues back to the liver.]

 

lipoproteins can be characterised as they have different protein components in their membrane.

Question:
Protein buffers are effective at resisting changes in pH when placed in an acidic or alkaline environment. Identify the correct option below that explains what happens when a protein buffers is placed in an alkaline environment. 

 

Shown below is the general structure of an amino acid. This may help in identifying the correct answer.
OptionA:
1. Amino acid - acts as a base 

 

2. Amino acid - absorbs H+ 

 

3. Therefore, increasing pH of environment
OptionB:
1. Amino acid - acts as a acid

 

2. Amino acid - releases H+

 

3. Therefore, decreasing pH of environment
OptionC:
1. Amino acid - acts as a base 

 

2. Amino acid - absorbs H+

 

3. Therefore, decreasing pH of environment
OptionD:
1. Amino acid - acts as a acid 

 

2. Amino acid - absorbs H+

 

3. Therefore, decreasing pH of environment
OptionE:
1. Amino acid - acts as a base 

 

2. Amino acid - releases H+

 

3. Therefore, increasing pH of environment
Explanation:
(A) Incorrect - Increasing pH of environment defeats the point of a buffer system as the environment is already alkaline. However, this would be the correct process if the environment was acidic.

 

(B) Correct - Amino acid acts as a acid, releasing H+ and therefore decreasing the pH of environment. This resists the change in pH posed by the alkaline environment.

 

(C) Incorrect - Absorbing H+ will increase the pH of environment, not decrease it.

 

(D) Incorrect - Acids release H+, not absorb them.

 

(E) Incorrect - Bases absorbs H+, not release them.

Question: A large gall stone leaves the gall bladder, passing through a series of ducts which results in it entering the duodenum and after a bit of a journey... being excreted as faeces. Which of the following would be the route of this gall stone from the gall bladder to the duodenum?
OptionA:
Cystic duct (origin) + Left hepatic duct-> Common bile duct

Pancreatic duct + Common bile duct-> Hepatopancreatic ampulla (of vatar)

 

The bile stone then enters the 2nd part of the duodenum which is controlled by the hepatopancreatic sphincter
OptionB:
Cystic duct (origin) + Common hepatic duct-> Pancreatic duct

Pancreatic duct + Common bile duct-> Hepatopancreatic ampulla (of vatar)

 

The bile stone then enters the 2nd part of the duodenum which is controlled by the hepatopancreatic sphincter
OptionC:
Cystic duct (origin) + Common hepatic duct-> Common bile duct

Pancreatic duct + Common bile duct-> Major duodenal papilla

 

The bile stone then enters the 2nd part of the duodenum which is controlled by the hepatopancreatic sphincter
OptionD:
Cystic duct (origin) + Common hepatic duct-> Common bile duct

Pancreatic duct + Common bile duct-> Hepatopancreatic ampulla (of vatar)

 

The bile stone then enters the 2nd part of the duodenum which is controlled by the hepatopancreatic sphincter
OptionE:
Cystic duct (origin) + Common hepatic duct-> Common bile duct

Pancreatic duct + Common bile duct-> Hepatopancreatic ampulla (of vatar)

 

The bile stone then enters the 1st part of the duodenum which is controlled by the hepatopancreatic sphincter
Explanation:
D is the correct answer!

 

I've provided an explanation for why the others are wrong below...

 

A- Incorrect as the left and right hepatic ducts form the common hepatic duct which then goes onto bind with the cystic duct to form the bile duct etc.

B- Incorrect as Cystic duct (origin) + Common hepatic duct-> Common bile duct, which in turn binds to the pancreatic duct

C- Incorrect as the main pancreatic duct and bile duct form the hepatopancreatic ampulla (of vatar), not the major duodenal papilla. The major duodenal papilla is a projection from the hepatopancreatic sphincter which is important for it's secretion of enzymes for digestion.

D- Correct!

E- Incorrect as the bile stone would enter the second part of the duodenum not the first. The hepatopancreatic ampulla of vatar and hepatopancreatic sphincter are located on the second part of the duodenum. The major duodenal papilla, a projection from the hepatopancreatic sphincter inside the lumen of the duodenum, marks the transition from the foregut to the midgut. 

 

I purposefully tried to make this one a bit confusing, hope the explanation helps though!

 

Also note that the- Hepatopancreatic sphincter/ sphincter of oddi are the same thing and are interchangeable.

Question: Atropine is a competitive (1)___________ of (2)____________ receptors. Therefore a side effect of this drug is a (3)____________ in heart rate
Explanation:
Atropine is a competitive (1) antagonist of (2) muscarinic receptors. Therefore a side effect of this drug is a (3) increase in heart rate

 

Explanation:

  • Muscarinic receptors are part of the parasympathetic nervous system
  • At rest, the heart is under parasympathetic control due to intrinsic heart rate being approximately 100 bpm (depends on age)
  • As atropine is an antagonist, it withdraws this parasympathetic control of the heart
  • Therefore, heart rate increases

Question:
Our immunity can be divided into that which is Innate and that which is Adaptive, each comprising of different cell types, with different functions.

 

Which cell type "bridges the gap" between the two types of immune response? Have a think about how it does this.
Explanation:
Dendritic Cells bridge the gap between the innate and adaptive immune response. 

 

They are very similar to macrophages in that they are capable of Phagocytosis, Antigen presentation, PAMP recognition and Cytokine release. The fundamental difference is that dendritic cells are also motile, meaning they can migrate to the draining lymph nodes in order to deliver components of pathogens (antigen presentation) to activate the B and T cells of the adaptive immune response.

Question: In the GI tract, an organ lying within a body cavity has a specific name for its outer membrane (membrane is farthest from the inner core or lumen of the organ). What is it?
Explanation:
Well done, the answer is B!

Serosa - The outer lining of organs and body cavities of the abdomen and chest, including the stomach. Serosa covers the organs that freely move inside a cavity. Also called serous membrane. 

Adventitia - the outermost covering of an organ, especially of a blood vessel. adventitia covers the organs that should be bound with the surrounding structures for support

 

Generally, if it is a part of the digestive tract that is free to move, it is covered by serosa, and if it is relatively rigidly fixed, it is covered by adventitia

 

mucosa is a membrane that lines various cavities in the body and covers the surface of internal organs. It consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells overlying a layer of loose connective tissue

 

The pleura includes two thin layers of tissue that protect and cushion the lungs. The inner layer (visceral pleura) wraps around the lungs and is stuck so tightly to the lungs that it cannot be peeled off. The outer layer (parietal pleura) lines the inside of the chest wall.

 

The mesentery is an organ that attaches the intestines to the posterior abdominal wall in humans and is formed by the double fold of peritoneum. It helps in storing fat and allowing blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves to supply the intestines, among other functions. Also known as omentum or stomach folds.

Question: The mesentery and lining of the peritoneal cavity, like the outermost layer of the digestive tract, consist of a specific membrane. What is it?
Explanation:
D is correct, great work!

 

a structure with a serosa = a structure that is lined by visceral peritoneum
a structure with an adventitia = a structure that is NOT lined by visceral peritoneum, (but instead is surrounded by connective tissue fixed to it)

 

I refered to https://anatomytool.org/content/serosa-and-adventitia for this explanation.

 

 

remember serosa is a serous membrane and covers a closed bodily cavity.

serosa is a smooth membrane, composed of a simple squamous epithelium and a sparse layer of loose connective tissue, covering the external surface of an organ such as the stomach and small intestine.

Serosa is a component of living organisms that is the tissue of serous membranes. There are four different forms of serosa: the pericardium of the heart, the tunica vaginalis of the testes, the pleura of the lungs and the peritoneum of the abdominal cavity.

 

Adventitia is serving to hold the organ in place and bind it to adjacent tissues and organs.

 

Serosa is different from adventitia because serosa is for lubrication where as adventitia is to bind structures together.

 

The exterior layer of the gastrointestinal tract is the adventitia where the tract goes through the body wall, but it is the serosa where the tract goes through body cavities. 

 

Mucosa and submucosa are within the abdomen layers.

Question:
the following description describes a theory of stress what is the theory 

 

- took individual perceptions and interpretations of events into acount when they looked as sress
- started by looking at stress in relation to the demands placed on an individual and wheter they felt they had the rescourses at their disposal to meet those demands
- if you feel that you have the resources to meet the demands placed upon you then that is going to mediate the degree of stresses to a large degree
- The interpretation of the stressful event is more important than the event itself
- Takes anticipatory anxiety into account
OptionA: cognitive appraisal theory by Lazarus and Folkman
Explanation:
A is the correct answer 

 

 

selye: general adaptation to stress 3 distinct phases 

- non specific response dictating that the body responds to stress with the same pattern of phsyiological responding regardless of the type of stressor
- befor the onset of a stress we are in a medium of homeostasis which is the normal level of resistance the stressor occurs you then move into the alarm stage
- alarm stage is where you are initially combatted with a stressor and you are processing how to respond once you have decided you are mobilised into action leading us to the resistance stage
- resistance stage is where you have ongoing exposure to the stresses and once you have decided how to respond to the stressor you stick with that decision eg continouse running away from the lion. At a certain point in this stage the parasympathetic nervouse system kicks in and compensates
- leading to exauhstion wehre we see the physiologial depletion of resources
- this response remains the same no matter what

 

 

flight or flight response by cannon

- organism perceives a threat the body sypathetic nervous system is awakened this results in the body being alert/awakened
- it involes the sympathetic nervous system and the endocrine system
- the result of awakening the sympathetic nervous sytem is that it mobilises three responses 1 attatch the threat 2 flee from the threat and 3 freeze in the sight of a threat
- it has an adaptive role as it allows for a swift response to a threatening stimuli via activation of the sympathetic andrenal medullary system and the Hypothalamic pituitary adrenal axis. and once these have been activated that is what we perseve as stress.
- can be harmfull for example when there is unnessasary activation or chronic actviation of the hypothalamic pituitary adrenal axis due to the inhibition of the negative feedback loops (dysregulation) this can be harmfull to both the physical and the psychological.

Question: Autoimmune gastritis (chronic inflammation of the stomach lining) can cause deficiency of which vitamin?
Explanation: The correct answer is vitamin B12 - chronic inflammation of the stomach reduces the secretion of intrinsic factor. Vitamin B12 has to attach to intrinsic factor in order to be absorbed in the intestines, and therefore a lack of intrinsic factor means there is a reduction in the amount of B12 absorbed. B12 deficiency causes pernicious anaemia

Question: Which of these is not a muscarinic agonist?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D!

Atropine is a muscarinic receptor antagonist.

Muscarinic receptor antagonists causes smooth muscle relaxation in the lungs, GI tract and bladder, dilation of the pupil and drying of exocrine secretions. They can be used to treat Bradycardia and asystole by inhibiting the parasympathetic nervous system and preventing Ach action from the vagus nerve. This increases heart rate 

All the others are muscarinic receptor agonists. These cause smooth muscle contraction in the lungs, GI tract and bladder, decrease heart rate, construct the pupil and increase exocrine secretions.

Question: Cholinergic syndrome occurs when someone has an adverse reaction to cholinergic drugs. Which of the following is not a symptom of cholinergic syndrome?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D!

Adverse reactions to cholinergic drugs cause the following symptoms:

Diarrhoea 

Urination

Miosis- pupil constriction 
Bradycardia

Emesis- vomiting 
Lethargy 

Lacrimation

Salivation

Spells Dumbells

Mydriasis is pupil dilation. This would be an adverse affect of anticholinergic drugs. To remember which way round miosis and mydriasis are:

Miosis is a smaller word so the pupil gets smaller

Mydriasis is a longer/wider word so the pupil gets wider

Question: Which of the following does not up regulate pyruvate dehydrogenase (enzyme of link reaction)?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D!

Pyruvate dehydrogenase catalyses the formation of acetyl CoA from Pyruvate. This step is irreversible and requires tight regulation. 

The enzyme is up regulated by: NAD+, Pyruvate, AMP and Calcium ions (important in muscle)

The enzyme is down regulated by: Acetyl CoA, NADH and ATP. These work by allosteric inhibition

ATP down regulates the enzyme as it signals there is less need for ATP production.

Question:
You are treating a 56 year old patient in hospital who has come to you with chest pain, acid reflex and trouble swallowing. After an examination and some tests you decide that this patient is suffering with a hiatal hernia, when the upper part of the stomach bulges through the oesophageal opening of the diaphragm. You are concerned this may lead to damage to the contents of this hiatus. 
What are the structures pass through this opening in the diaphragm?
OptionA: The inferior vena cava and the terminal branches of the right phrenic nerve.
OptionB: The oesophagus, the right vagus nerve and the oesophageal branches of the left gastric artery and vein.
OptionC: The oesophagus, the right and left vagus nerves and the oesophageal branches of the left gastric artery and vein.
OptionD: The aorta, thoracic duct and azygous vein.
OptionE: The oesophagus, the right and left vagus nerve, and the oesophageal branches of the right gastric artery and vein.
Explanation:
There are 3 openings in the diaphragm, the caval hiatus, oesophageal hiatus and the aortic hiatus. 

A - These are the contents of the caval hiatus, one of the other openings in the diaphragm. 

B - The oesophageal hiatus contains both the left and right vagus nerves, not just the right. 

C - These are the correct contents of the oesophageal hiatus!

D - These are the contents of the aortic hiatus, one of the other openings in the diaphragm. 

E - The oesophageal hiatus contains the oesophageal branches of the left gastric artery/ vein, not the right. The right gastric artery branches from the hepatic artery in the abdomen. 

The cause of hiatal hernias is largely unknown, but you are more likely to develop one if over the age of 50, obese, or have a job involving heavy lifting or straining. Small hiatal hernias do not not normally cause symptoms, but larger hernias may need to be treated surgically or managed with antacid medication.

Question:
Nina Roberts is 68 year old patient and has been recently diagnosed with Bell's palsy (swelling of the facial nerve, CNVII). This diagnosis was made following noticeable temporary weakness (ptosis, dropping of the mouth) and lack of movement affecting the left side of her face. She has been prescribed steroids to treat this.

 

Mrs Roberts later complains that she cannot taste her Christmas dinner and is fearful that she has contracted Covid-19 despite her best efforts to shield during the recent pandemic. Which of the following options is a more plausible explanation as to her loss of taste?
OptionA: Damage to the lingual branch of the glossopharyngeal nerve, CNIX
OptionB: There is damage to the vagus nerve (CNX)
OptionD: The Chorda tympani nerve (a branch of the facial nerve, CNVII) has become damaged
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

 

A - Incorrect. The glossopharyngeal nerve provides taste sensation to the posterior 1/3rd of the tongue via the lingual branch. There could be damage to the glossopharyngeal nerve but given her diagnosis it is more likely to be the facial nerve that has also affected her taste.

 

B - Incorrect. The vagus nerve, CNX, provides motor innervation to the palatoglossus muscle of the tongue

 

C - Incorrect. The hypoglossal nerve, CNXII, provides motor innervation to all muscles of the tongue with exception to the palatoglossus muscle

 

D - Correct. The patient has a Bell's palsy which is a result of damage to the facial nerve (mentioned in the question stem). The sensory fibers of the facial nerve, called the chorda tympani nerve, respond to taste input from the taste buds of the tongue.

 

E - Incorrect. The Abducens nerve, CNVI innervates the lateral rectus eye muscle
Tags: PCS 3, Head and neck, Cranial Nerves

Question: What are the 5 most important Rh blood groups?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer!

 

The Rh blood system consists of 49 defined blood group antigens, with C, c, D, E, and e being the most important groups (there is no 'd' antigen).

Rh(D) presence is usually described with a + suffix after the ABO blood type. Its absence is described with a - suffix after the ABO blood type (e.g. A+, A-, AB+, AB- etc.).

So terms like the Rh factor, Rh negative, and Rh positive refer to the Rh(D) only.

Question:
You are working in a GP surgery and speak to a father who is concerned about his 3 year old daughter. He says that she gets very out of breath just going up the stairs, is often tired and sleepy and sometimes says that her chest "feels funny". You agree to listen to her heart and think that you can hear a heart murmur. After further tests you explain to the father that you suspect that his daughter has a small hole in her heart due to the failure of an embryonic structure between the two atria to close. 
What is the name of this embryonic structure?
Explanation:
A - Fossa ovalis is the feature on the wall of the inside of the right atrium of the heart which is left as a remnant of the closing of the foramen ovale. The fossa ovalis is present in a normally developed, healthy heart. 

B - The ductus arteriosus is the blood vessel in the developing foetus that connects the trunk of the pulmonary artery to the proximal descending aorta. It allows most of the blood from the right ventricle to bypass the non-functioning lungs. It is closes around the time of birth, and becomes the ligamentum arteriosum.  

C - The left umbilical vein is present during foetal development and carries oxygenated blood from the placenta to the growing foetus. 

D - The foramen ovale is a small hole located in the septum of foetal hearts between the left and right atria. It allows passage of blood between the two atria (bypassing the ventricles) as there of no need for blood to be sent to the non-functioning lungs. It is one of two two foetal cardiac shunts, the other being the ductus arteriosus. The foramen ovale closes up around birth, leaving the fossa ovale which can be seen on the interior wall of the right atrium. 

E - The left auricle (names because of its ear shape) is a flap of muscle on the wall of the left atrium that is involved in pumping blood within the heart. 

 

A hole in the heart, or Atrial Septal Defect is a congenital condition that often happens due to the failure of the embryonic structure - the foramen ovale - to close during early infancy. The condition can often be mild with no symptoms or complications, however if the ASD is severe it can cause damage to the lungs and overworking of the right side of the heart. 

In this case, the child is experiencing substantial symptoms, and so you may want to refer them to a cardiac specialist who may suggest surgical intervention to repair the hole.

Question: What do ossicles do to the vibrations from the tympanic membrane?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

There are 3 ossicles- malleus, incus and stapes. These are the smallest bones in the body and transmit force from the tympanic membrane to the Organ of Corti. As the vibration is passed across, the ossicles increase the force of the vibrations from the tympanic membrane and decrease the amplitude. This means they turn low force, high amplitude vibrations into high force, low amplitude vibrations.

Question: Which vitamin below would show night blindness if it was deficient?
Explanation:
A is correct!

 

Vitamin A/ retinol, plays a role in transforming nerve impulses into images in the retina. The retina is a light-sensitive area in the back of your eye.

To see the full spectrum of light, your eye needs to produce certain pigments for your retina to work properly. Vitamin A deficiency stops the production of these pigments, leading to night blindness.

 

(an easy way to remember is Retinol=Retina)

Question: There are five classes of antibodies in the human body. Which antibody class is the only one that can cross the placenta?
Explanation:
D is correct!

 

IgA is formed from two light chains and two alpha heavy chains and is the most common immunoglobulin in secretions such as saliva and bile. IgA can also be a dimer. Its main function is antibody dependent neutralisation.

 

IgD is formed from two light chains and two delta heavy chains. It is a cell surface receptor that is expressed when B-cells leave the bone marrow and migrate to the secondary lymphoid tissues, being co-expressed with IgM.

 

IgE is formed of two light chains and two epsilon heavy chains. It binds to Fc receptors on basophils and mast cells to facilitate the inflammatory response to antigen, and is especially important in combatting helminths.

 

IgG consists of two light chains and two gamma heavy chains and is the most abundant immunoglobulin in the plasma. They are small enough to cross the placental membrane and so provide the foetus with antibodies at birth. There are four different isotypes with IgG1 and IgG4 being particularly effective in activating complement. Their main function is antibody dependent neutralisation, antibody dependent phagocytosis, and complement activation. Antibody dependent phagocytosis and complement activation are important in bacterial infections. Antibody dependent cellular cytotoxicity also occurs in virally infected cells.

 

IgM consists of two light chains and two μ heavy chains and is the first antibody to be produced during development and during the primary immune response. Its pentamer in the blood is also very effective at activating complement. Its main function is complement activation.

Question: A trisomy on chromosome 13 occurs in approximately 1/9500 births. What is the name of this condition?
Explanation: This is just a case of learning the different chromosomal abnormalities. A trisomy on chromosome 13 is known as Patau syndrome and there are few survivors beyond 1 year.

Explanation: they combine at L5 to become the inferior Vena cava

Question: Sarah has a family history of bleeding disorders, you are concerned that she may also have a bleeding disorder so order a test which measures the integrity of the intrinsic pathway in the classical model of haemostasis. What is the name of this test?
Explanation:
A - CORRECT!

B - INR (international normalised ratio) is a standardised version of PT and is usually used to monitor anticoagulant therapy involving warfarin

C - prothrombin time is a measure of the integrity of the extrinsic pathway

D - This is a test done on someone to assess platelet function, includes making a patient bleed and timing how long it takes to stop

Question: A Patient has been rushed to hospital after sustaining a head injury from going over the handlebars of their bike. What type of haemorrhage is shown on the MRI scan?
What is true for fatty acid activation?
OptionA:
Fatty acids are activated after oxidation

The enzyme is this reaction is acyl coA synthesase

ATP is required
OptionB:
Fatty acids are activated before oxidation

The enzyme is this reaction is acyl coA synthesase

AMP is required
OptionC:
Fatty acids are activated after oxidation

The enzyme is this reaction is acyl coA reductase

AMP is required
OptionD:
Fatty acids are activated before oxidation

The enzyme is this reaction is acyl coA synthesase

ATP is required
OptionE:
Fatty acids are activated after oxidation

The enzyme is this reaction is acyl coA reductase

ATP is required
Explanation:
D is the correct answer.

Fatty acid activation happens beforevoxidation. The enzyme involved is acyl coA synthesase. ATP is converted to AMP. The reaction is reversible but made irreversible by hydrolysis of inorganic phosphate. A high energy bond is formed from this. 

 

Fatty acid activation is regulated by substrate. The more substrate available the more fatty acid activation.

Question: A teratoma is a growth of diseased (1)_____________stem cells. It can contain numerous types of tissue such as (2)___________________________________
Explanation:
Correct answer is E. A teratoma is a growth of diseased pluripotent stem cells.

 

It can contain, hair, teeth, muscle and bone

Question: Mrs Jones comes into A and E, after sustaining a severe bleed. She is losing a lot of blood and so her osmolarity increases, stimulating the release of ADH. ADH acts on the collecting duct of the nephron and stimulates up-regulation of which Aquaporin on the apical membrane of the collecting duct?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer! ADH stimulates the up-regulation of AQP2 on the apical membrane to up-regulate H2O reabsorption. 

AQP3 and AQP4 are located on the basal membrane of the collecting duct. 

AQP1 is located in the descending limb in the loop of Henle.

Question: Fructose is transported from across the apical membrane using GLUT2 and which other transporter?
Explanation:
GLUT5 is the correct answer!

GLUT1 - this is responsible for the basal rate of glucose uptake and is found in all tissues. 

GLUT2 - this is inserted into the apical membrane when glucose concentration is high. It triggers the release of insulin. It is also used to transport fructose across the apical and basolateral membrane. 

GLUT3 - this is responsible for basal rate of glucose uptake and is found in all tissues. 

GLUT4 - this responds to insulin in order to take up glucose, it is found in adipose tissue and muscle. 

GLUT5 - this is the transporter used for fructose transport across the apical membrane. It is found in the small intestine.

Question: Which muscle compresses and supports abdominal viscera, and flexes and rotates the trunk to the contralateral side?
Explanation:
Correct answer is A!

The external oblique muscle compresses and supports abdominal viscera and rotates the trunk to the contralateral side.

The Internal oblique muscle compresses and supports abdominal viscera, and rotates trunk to ipsilateral side.

Transversus abdominis  compresses and supports abdominal viscera

To remember this: Internal oblique starts with an I and rotates to the Ipsilateral Side

Question: Ron John is a 53 year old male who gets rushed into hospital saying he is having breathing problems, is very breathless and that his chest feels ‘tight’. On examination you find that his neck is visibly red and bruised. When you question him on this, he says his friend accidentally hit him with a log on the back of the neck. Why is Ron John struggling to breathe?
OptionA: Vertebrae C3-C5 are located at the neck under his bruising. The vagus nerve arises from c3-c5, and the vagus nerve innervates the diaphragm, therefore, his diaphragm isn’t playing it’s role during inspiration and expiration so Ron John is struggling to breathe.
OptionB: Vertebrae C3-C5 are located at the neck under his bruising. The phrenic nerve arises from c3-c5, and the phrenic nerve innervates the diaphragm, therefore, his diaphragm isn’t playing it’s role during inspiration and expiration so Ron John is struggling to breathe.
OptionC: Vertebrae C1-C5 are located at the neck under his bruising. The vagus nerve arises from c1-c5, and the vagus nerve innervates the diaphragm, therefore, his diaphragm isn’t playing it’s role during inspiration and expiration so Ron John is struggling to breathe.
OptionD: Vertebrae C2-C4 are located at the neck. The azygous nerve arises from c3-c5, and the branches into the vagus nerve which innervates the diaphragm, therefore, his diaphragm isn’t playing it’s role during inspiration and expiration so Ron John is struggling to breathe.
OptionE: Vertebrae C3-C5 are located at the neck. The phrenic nerve arises from c3-c5, and branches into the vagus nerve which innervates the diaphragm, therefore, his diaphragm isn’t playing it’s role during inspiration and expiration so Ron John is struggling to breathe.
Explanation:
A. Incorrect. The vagus nerve originates from the medulla in the brainstem and doesn’t innervate the diaphragm. It innervates the pharynx and larynx. 

 

B. Correct! Phrenic nerve innervates the diaphragm and arises from C3-C5

 

C. Incorrect. The vagus nerve originates from the medulla in the brainstem and doesn’t innervate the diaphragm. It innervates the pharynx and larynx.

 

D. Incorrect. No such thing as the azygous nerve. 

 

E. Incorrect. The phrenic nerve doesn’t branch into the vagus nerve.

Question: What action might be impaired by damage to the indicated structure?
OptionA: Extension of the arm at the elbow
OptionC: Flexion of the arm at the elbow
OptionD: Abduction of the arm up to 15 degrees
Explanation:
The correct answer is E!

 

The indicated structure is the surgical neck of the humerus. A fracture here would likely damage the axillary nerve which innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles. The actions of these muscles would consequently be impaired.

 

The primary function of teres minor is external (lateral) rotation of the shoulder, along with infraspinatus. It also assists with arm adduction and extension of the shoulder. The combined function of the rotator cuff muscles is stabilisation of the shoulder.

 

The primary function of the deltoid is arm abduction above 15 degrees, and medial rotation of the arm at the glenohumeral joint. It does also assists in extension of the arm, but is not the primary muscle to do so.

 

A: Triceps brachii is responsible for extension of the arm at the elbow, which is innervated by the radial nerve,

B: Levator scapulae and trapezius are responsible for elevation of the scapula, which are innervated by the dorsal scapula and spinal accessory nerve respectively

C: Biceps brachii, coracobrachialis, and brachialis are responsible for flexion of the arm and are all innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve

D: Supraspinatus' main action is abduction of the arm up to 15 degrees, and is innervated by the suprascapular nerve.

Question: Which of the following most accurately describes a pain control mechanism in the spinal cord?
OptionA: Neurones containing opiate-like peptides in the dorsal horn block the release of substance P and suppress activity in the spinothalamic interneurones which relieves pain.
OptionB: Opitate-like peptides that are present naturally in the ventral horn relieve pain by supressing activity in spinothalamic interneurones.
OptionC: Axons of serotonin-containing neurones in the brainstem descend to the dorsal horn and block the release of substance P.
OptionD: Peptides such as endorphins are present naturally in the dorsal horn and produce an analgesic effect by stimulating the release of substance P and increasing activity in spinothalamic interneurones.
OptionE: Neurones containing natural opiate-like peptides in the dorsal horn relieve pain by acting on inhibitory GABAergic neurones to block pain pathways.
Explanation:
The most complete answer is: Neurones that contain natural opiate-like peptides are present naturally in the dorsal horn. These endorphins and enkephalins produce an analgesic (pain relieving) effect by blocking the release of substance P & suppressing activity in spinothalamic interneurones.

This is how the placebo effect can operate - if a patient feels like they are being cared for this can reduce their pain through the release of endorphins.

 

C & E refer to another method of pain control where serotonin-containing neurones descend to the dorsal horn and act on inhibitory GABAergic neurones to block the pain pathways.

Question: In the metabolism of glucose, what are the correct numbers of products of the TCA cycle produce per molecule of glucose?
Explanation: 3 NADH, 2 CO2, 1 ATP and 1 FADH2 are produced for every cycle. The cycle occurs twice as each glucose molecule forms 2 pyruvate molecules and therefore 2 acetyl CoA molecules, so these values are doubled.

Question: On a sarcomere, there are A, I and H bands. What happens to the length of the A band during muscle contraction?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

The A band stays the same length during muscle contraction, it is the I and H bands that get shorter, reducing the length of the sarcomere.

The A band corresponds to the full length of the myosin filament which does not change length. The I band is the region where actin and myosin are non-overlapping at rest, but as the overlap increases during contraction, the length of the I band shortens.

Question: Which fibres are responsible for the first, sharp, well-localised pain?
Explanation:
Correct answer is A!

A-delta fibres are thinly myelinated axons that respond to an intense, mechanical stimulus. They rapidly transmit the signal between 5-30m/s and are responsible for the first, sharp, well-localised pain that is experienced. 

C fibres are unmyelinated and respond to mechanical stimuli, high temperatures and irritant chemicals. The conduction speed of C fibres is much slower, between 0.5-2m/s. They have larger receptor fields and the sensation felt is slow, second, poorly localised pain

A-beta fibres respond to mild mechanical stimuli, such as touch, and do not transmit pain signals

Question: Which type of chromosome has the centromere slightly off centre and contains one arm longer than the other?
Explanation:
C is correct ! 

Examples of submetacentric chromosomes are chromosome 1, 4-12, 17, 18, X.

 

A is when the centromere is very close to one side of the chromosome, due to this, the short arm is lost (even though this has little affect on the function of the chromosome )

 

B is when the centromere it at the centre/ near the centre. The short and long arms are similar in length here.

 

D are not seen in healthy humans, since they are unstable and arise by misdivision / breakage near the centromere and are usually eliminated within a few cell divisions. But for completion, the centromere is located at one end of the chromosome, and the short arm would barely be visible .

 

E is a made up chromosome type.

Question:
Fill in the gaps to complete the passage of the extrahepatic biliary system and pancreatic ducts: 

 

The common hepatic duct from the liver joins the ___________ from the gall bladder to form the bile duct. This duct which runs behind the proximal duodenum then joins with the ___________________ to form the hepatopancreatic ampulla (of Vatar). This ampulla then enters the ____ part of the duodenum via the major duodenal papilla, guarded by the ________________________.
OptionA: cystic duct, main pancreatic duct, 1st, hepatopancreatic sphincter (of Oddi).
OptionB: minor bile duct, cystic duct, 2nd, hepatopancreatic sphincter (of Oddi).
OptionC: cystic duct, main pancreatic duct, 2nd, hepatopancreatic sphincter (of Oddi).
OptionD: cystic duct, main pancreatic duct, 2nd, hepatopancreatic sphincter (of pupillae).
OptionE: cystic duct, main pancreatic duct, 3rd, hepatopancreatic sphincter (of Oddi).
Explanation:
A - The hepatopancreatic ampulla enters the 2nd part of the duodenum, not the 1st. 

B - The common bile duct is formed by the joining of the common hepatic duct from the liver and the cystic duct from the gall bladder. The bile duct then joins with the main pancreatic duct, which comes from the pancreas. 

C - Correct!

D - The major duodenal papilla, where the hepatopancreatic ampulla enters the duodenum is guarded by the hepatopancreatic sphincter, which is also know an the sphincter of Oddi. The sphincter of pupillae is found in the eye. 

E - The hepatopancreatic ampulla enters the 2nd part of the duodenum, not the 3rd. 

 

The information from this question has come from the abdomen 5+6 lecture and page 307 in the 6th edition of Moore's Anatomy.

Question: What is the function of ligase in DNA replication?
OptionA: Create Okazaki fragments in the leading strand
OptionB: Join Okazaki fragments in the lagging strand
OptionC: Join Okazaki fragments in the leading strand
OptionD: Create Okazaki fragments in the lagging strand
Explanation:
The function of ligase is to join Okazaki fragments in the lagging strand. During DNA replication, Okazaki fragments are only present in the lagging strand and not the leading strand. Ligase joins these fragments by catalyzing the formation of a phosphodiester bond between adjacent nucleotides.

Ligase does not create Okazaki fragments in the leading or lagging strand.

just to note that 

ligases classification number is 6 

 

On - oxidoreductases 

the - transferases 

Himalayas - hydrolayses

lyfe - lyasases 

is - isomerases  

lightened - ligases

Question: Which statement correctly describes the parasympathetic supply to the sinoatrial node in the heart that, once increased, results in a decreased heart rate?
Explanation:
The parasympathetic supply to the sinoatrial node is provided by acetylcholine acting upon M2 muscarinic receptors and dominates over sympathetic activity at rest. An increase in the parasympathetic supply to the heart's sinoatrial node results in a decreased heart rate.

The sympathetic supply to the sinoatrial node is provided by noradrenaline acting upon B1 adrenoreceptors. An increase in the sympathetic supply to the heart's sinoatrial node (coupled with a reduction in the dominant parasympathetic supply) results in an increased heart rate.

Question: Which part of the ECG represents ventricular diastole?
Explanation:
Ventricular diastole (relaxation) follows repolarization of the ventricles and is represented by the T wave of the ECG. It lasts approximately 1 430ms.

 

QRS  complex represents ventricular depolarisation / systole

 

PR interval represents the time between the onset of atrial depolarization and the onset of ventricular depolarization. 


P wave represents atrial depolarisation

Question: Which of the following effects of growth hormone leads to an increase in height during adolescence?
OptionB: Increasing muscle mass by inducing skeletal myocyte hypertrophy
OptionC: Increasing blood glucose levels by stimulating gluconeogenesis by the liver
Explanation:
Stimulating bone formation by osteoblasts is the mechanism by which growth hormone leads to an increase in height during adolescence.

This explains why an excess of growth hormone before bones stop growing vertically, i.e. before the closure of the epiphyseal growth plates, causes gigantism.

Although all of the other options are effects of growth hormone, none of them account for the increase in height during adolescence. In fact, inducing somatostatin release from the hypothalamus is a negative feedback mechanism of growth hormone that limits its own secretion because somatostatin inhibits growth hormone release from the anterior pituitary gland.

 

osteoclasts breaks down bone tissue
Tags: Tissues within the body, PCS 1, Bones, PCS 3, Hormones

Question: During which of the following stages of life is the mean level of circulating growth hormone highest?
Explanation:
Mean circulating levels of growth hormone are highest in adolescence.

This accounts for the pubertal growth spurt as well as growth failure during adolescence in those with growth hormone deficiency. It also explains why synthetic growth hormone can be given to children with growth hormone deficiency to induce pubertal growth.

Circulating growth hormone levels during the other options given are lower than in adolescence.

Question: What type of receptor does phenylephrine bind to?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D!

Phenylephrine is an adrenergic agonist and binds to alpha 1 receptors which are G alpha Q receptors. Binding to this receptor initiates the intracellular cascade involving phospholipase C.
Phenylephrine can be used to examine the eye. It does this by acting like noradrenaline and causing pupil dilation and vasoconstriction. This allows the eye to be examined more easily.

Question: What examples below is a sex chromosome aneuploidy abnormality?
Explanation:
D is correct!

Turner syndrome (45, X) is a female-genetic disorder, where a person has only one X chromosome, rather than the normal XX. It's a monosomy aneuploidy abnormality. 

 

A is incorrect, due to triploidy being a polylpoidy abnormality. Meaning, a presence of extra set(s) of chromosomes. This abnormality is lethal, and often a cause of miscarriage.

 

B, C and E are all trisomy aneuploidy abnormalities.

B contains 3 copies of chromosome 16 rather than two. It is the most common trisomy leading to miscarriage and the second most common chromosomal cause of it.

 

C is Edwards syndrome. It contains 3 copies of chromosome number 18 instead of 2. This affects the way the baby grows and develops. Having 3 copies of chromosome 18 usually happens by chance, because of a change in the sperm or egg before a baby is conceived.

 

E is Downs syndrome. Genetic disorder caused by presence of all/ part of 3 copies of chromosome 21.

Question: Haemophilia is a group of disorders defined by a tendency of uncontrolled bleeding. Whether one has haemophilia A, B, or C is determined by which coagulation factor is deficient/dysfunctional. With this being said, which haemophilia would deficiency/dysfunction of coagulation factor XI result in?
Explanation:
The answer is C!

 

Haemophilia A is due to deficiency/dysfunction of coagulation factor VIII.

 

Haemophilia B is due to deficiency/dysfunction of coagulation factor IX.

 

Haemophilia C is due to deficiency/dysfunction of coagulation factor XI.

 

Due to the deficiency/dysfunction of coagulation factors, the activity of IXa.VIIIa complex is compromised and fibrin formation is either inefficient to form a soft clot or doesn't occur at all.

Question: Which of these is not a factor controlling Ion channel gating?

Ion channel gating= fluctuation between open and closed state

Question: Which of these describes Antiporters?
OptionA:
Couple the movement of two or more ion/molecules across the membrane

OptionB: Transport a single molecule across the membrane
OptionC: Couples movement of two or molecules across the membrane in different directions

Question: Which order correctly describes the sliding filament theory of contraction?
OptionA:
1. Ca2+ ,released from sarcoplasmic reticulum, binds to troponin, causing an allosteric change to tropomyosin, exposing the myosin binding site on actin.
2. The myosin head binds to the myosin binding site on the actin molecule, forming the cross bridges
3. ADP and Pi dissociate from the myosin as it pivots (power stroke) pulling the actin filament towards the M-line, starting the contraction of the sarcomere
4. ATP is supplied to the myosin head and the cross bridges detach.
5. ATP is hydrolysed to form ADP + Pi, and the energy released "recocks" or reactivates the myosin, resetting the position of the head
Step two repeats. This cycle will repeat until the Ca2+ is removed from the sarcomere, which then causes the tropomyosin to reset, covering the myosin binding site on the Actin filament, stopping the contraction. This motion is reset by the action of the antagonistic muscle group

5. ADP and Pi dissociate from the myosin as it pivots (power stroke) pulling the actin filament towards the M-line, starting the contraction of the sarcomere
Step two repeats. This cycle will repeat until the Ca2+ is removed from the sarcomere, which then causes the tropomyosin to reset, covering the actin binding site on the myosin filament, stopping the contraction. This motion is reset by the action of the antagonistic muscle group
Explanation:
Sliding filament theory of contraction

1. Ca2+ ,released from sarcoplasmic reticulum, binds to troponin, causing an allosteric change to tropomyosin, exposing the myosin binding site on actin.
2. The myosin head binds to the myosin binding site on the actin molecule, forming the cross bridges
3. ADP and Pi dissociate from the myosin as it pivots (power stroke) pulling the actin filament towards the M-line, starting the contraction of the sarcomere
4. ATP is supplied to the myosin head and the cross bridges detach.
5. ATP is hydrolysed to form ADP + Pi, and the energy released "recocks" or reactivates the myosin, resetting the position of the head
Step two repeats. This cycle will repeat until the Ca2+ is removed from the sarcomere, which then causes the tropomyosin to reset, covering the myosin binding site on the Actin filament, stopping the contraction. This motion is reset by the action of the antagonistic muscle group

Question:
You are working in the paediatric unit of a hospital and speaking to the parent of a child with a suspected "horseshoe kidney". This is a congenital condition where the inferior poles of the kidneys fuse to give a "U" shape, which happens in around 1 in 600 foetuses and rarely results in symptoms in the child once born. This U shaped kidney usually lies at the level of the L3-L5 vertebra because the root of the inferior mesenteric artery prevents normal relocation of the kidneys. 

What are the normal positions of these organs and why are they asymmetrical?
OptionA:
Both kidneys lie at level T12-L3.
The right kidney is positioned slightly higher than the left due to the position of the liver.
OptionB:
Both kidneys lie at level T12-L3.
The left kidney is positioned slightly higher than the right kidney due to the position of the stomach.
OptionC:
Both kidneys lie at level T12-L2.
The right kidney is positioned slightly higher than the left due to the position of the liver.
OptionD:
Both kidneys lie at level T12-L2.
The left kidney is positioned slightly higher than the right due to the position of the stomach.
OptionE:
Both kidneys lie at level T12-L3. 
The left kidney is positioned slightly higher than the right due to the position of the liver.
Explanation:
Answer E is correct. 

Normally, both kidneys lie at level T12-L3.
The left kidney is positioned slightly higher than the right kidney because the liver is so large that to fit around it, the kidney is at a slightly lower position in the body. 
Remember the kidneys are retroperitoneal (only their anterior surface is covered by the peritoneum) and so they are more vulnerable (this is the reason "kidney punches" are illegal in boxing).

Question: Which of these do not occur at the vertebral level L1?
OptionA: Right suprarenal vein drains into the IVC
OptionB: Right gonadal vein drains into the IVC
OptionC: Right Suprarenal vein drains into the IVC
OptionD: The superior mesenteric artery branches from the abdominal aorta
OptionE: Left renal vein drains into the IVC
Explanation:
B is the correct answer!

 

The right gonadal vein drains into the IVC at the L2 vertebral level. The rest of the answers do occur at the L1 level. 

 

At this level, the left gonadal, and suprarenal veins drain into the left renal vein. Some sources also say that the portal vein is formed at this level (by the joining of the splenic vein and the superior mesenteric vein), though others suggest it is at L2. Please let me know if you're certain about which it is.

Question:
PCS 3 Higher Learning Outcome: Outline the nervous pathways that control special sensation.

 

Jenny has been listening to Lofi beats during her revision. When her music is on a reasonable volume, she perceives it as very loud. This condition is called hyperacusis. This condition occurs when the stapedius muscle is paralysed due to its nerve being damaged. The Stapedius is the smallest muscle in the body and controls vibrations going to the Stapes.
Which of the following nerves is damaged in hyperacusis?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A: Facial.
Great work whether you got it right or wrong!
This question was by no means trying to catch you out, but rather to stretch you guys into using what you know to tackle the momentarily unknown. The question is heavily applied containing new terminology, but hopefully you were able to get it right. If not, then hopefully I can help teach you something. :)

 

What we should know
Firstly, the Stapes is one of 3 ossicle (bones of the middle ear: malleus, incus and stapes).
Facial nerve and Vestibulocochlear nerve run through the internal auditory canal in the petrous part of the temporal bone in the posterior cranial fossa.

 

Linking nerves to functions
So since this question is to do with the ear/sound, you can eliminate all the other options that aren’t Facial and Vestibulocochlear. Just like that you’ve got a fifty-fifty chance. Yay!

The Vestibulocochlear nerve is responsible for balance (vestibular branch of the nerve) and hearing (cochlear branch of the nerve).
The Cochlear nerve innervates the hair cells of the organ of Corti in the spirals of the cochlea. (TIP: Cochlear nerve to do with the Cochlea (spiral bit in the ear).)

 

Deduction
However, this question is asking about which nerve innervates a muscle that is attached to the Stapes. Not about anything to do with the Cochlea.
Therefore, by the powers of deduction, you are left with the Facial nerve, which is the correct answer.

 

Addition information
This question was adapted from Geeky medic who provided the following question and explanation:
Which of the following cranial nerves supplies stapedius?
Answer: Facial Nerve
Explanation: “Stapedius is a small muscle that inserts on the neck of the stapes and reduces the oscillatory range. As with many muscles in the head and neck, it is innervated by the facial nerve. When the facial nerve is damaged, the stapedius may become paralysed, increasing the oscillatory range and causing hyperacusis.”

https://geekyquiz.com
I hope all of that is clear and you enjoyed learning something new. Have a great day!
Tags: Ear, Nervous System, Neurons, PCS 3, Head and neck

Question: Which of the following drugs can be used to treat glaucoma?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

Pilocarpine is an Ach agonist. It binds to M3 receptors on the iris and causes circular muscles to contract, constricting the pupil. The Canal of Schlemm is opened and fluid is drained, decreasing the intraocular pressure. This prevents glaucoma which involves cupping of the optic disc and can lead to blindness if untreated.

Question: Which complement proteins cause degranulation of basophils and stimulate mast cells to release histamines and serotonin?
Explanation:
Correct answer is E!

C3a, C4a and C5a cause degranulation of basophils and stimulate histamine and serotonin release from mast cells. These cause the inflammatory effects of the complement system.

Question: Which of the following is not a social determinant of health?
Explanation:
E is the correct answer!

 

Social determinants of health are the non-medical factors that influence health outcomes. They are the conditions in which people are born, grow, work, live and age, and the wider set of forces and systems shaping the conditions of daily life. (Source: WHO).

 

Mental health is an individual's mental wellbeing, which can be influenced by social determinants.

Question: What type of neurone are most sensory neurones?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer! Most sensory neurones are pseudounipolar. This is a type of neurone which has 1 extension from its cell body, the axon, which has split into 2 branches.

A few sensory neurones are bipolar neurones.

Most relay neurones are multipolar neurones.

Tripolar neurones is not a classification of neurones.

Question: Which of the following is not considered part of the telencephalon?
Explanation: the correct answer is D as the thalamus and the hypothalamus make up the diencephalon not the telencephalon.

Question: What is the correct description of the 4 heart sounds?
OptionA:
1st = comes from the flow of blood into ventricles with atrial systole
2nd = "lub" when the AV values close 
3rd = "dub" when the semilunar valves close (loudest)
4th = comes from the ventricular walls during rapid filling of the ventricles in early diastole
OptionB:
1st =comes from the flow of blood into ventricles with atrial systole 
2nd = "lub" when the AV values close

3rd = comes from the ventricular walls during rapid filling of the ventricles in early diastole
4th = "dub" when the semilunar valves close (loudest)
OptionC:
1st = "lub" when the AV values close 
2nd = when the semilunar valves close
3rd = comes from the ventricular walls during rapid filling of the ventricles in early diastole
4th = "dub" comes from the flow of blood into ventricles with atrial systole (loudest)
OptionD:
1st = "lub" when the AV values close 
2nd = comes from the ventricular walls during rapid filling of the ventricles in early diastole
3rd =  "dub" when the semilunar valves close (loudest)
4th = comes from the flow of blood into ventricles with atrial systole
OptionE:
1st = "lub" when the AV values close (loudest)
2nd = "dub" when the semilunar valves close 
3rd =  comes from the ventricular walls during rapid filling of the ventricles in early diastole
4th = comes from the flow of blood into ventricles with atrial systole
Explanation:
The cycle is started from ventricular systole:

1st = "lub" sound heard when the AV values close - these vibrations are the loudest and the longest
2nd = "dub" sound heard when the semilunar valves close - these produce higher frequency vibrations
3rd = sound comes from blood hitting the ventricular walls during rapid filling of the ventricles in early diastole
4th = the sound of the flow of blood into the ventricles with atrial systole

Question: Which of the following cranial blood vessels does NOT drain into the cavernous sinus?
Explanation: The internal jugular vein couldn't possibly drain into the cavernous sinus as the cavernous sinus drains into the superior and inferior petrosal veins and then into the internal jugular veins.

Question: Which nerve does NOT pass through the superior orbital fissure?

Two rather short fellas walk into A&E with their "friend", an incredibly skinny and old thing. He seems to have a form of delirium as he doesn't stop babbling on about his precious. However the problem is that his starvation has caused acute symptoms of dizziness, pale skin and rapid heart beat, which the doctor suspects to be caused by iron deficiency anaemia (meaning his iron stores are depleted).

 

In what form is iron stored in the liver?
Explanation:
The Correct answer is C - Ferritin :)

 

A) Iron-sulphide centres are actually part of the electron transport chain (oxidative phosphorylation) and reside in the respiratory complexes to allow the transfer of electrons to pump H+ ions into the inter-membrane space of the mitochondria.

 

B) About 70% if the iron in the body is stored in haemoglobin, however this is in the blood as haemoglobin is in red blood cells, but the question asked for iron storage in the liver.

 

C) The correct answer! Ferritin is predominantly found in liver tissue and acts as a storage of iron. It is a protein that binds iron and holds it. Ferritin is ubiquitous and can be found throughout the body in small amounts, however the liver acts as the main site for its storage. A ferritin test will actually test the level of serum ferritin, however the concentration in the blood stream reflects the amount if iron stored in the body.

 

D) Albumin is a globular protein which is produced by the liver. It is mainly found as serum albumin (in the blood) and isn't associated with binding iron and storing it, however it has a multitude of uses like retaining fluid in the bloodstream by keeping the osmolality high so fluid doesn't leak out of the blood.

 

E) Ferrous fumarate is actually a medicine that is used to treat and prevent iron deficiency anaemia.

Question: Taste cells respond to the presence of which ion(s)?
Explanation: Taste cells respond to the presence of sodium and hydrogen ions - there are detected by ion channels on the surface of the cell.

Question:
You are in clinic and are asked to examine a patient to see if they have tonsillitus. When you look at the patient's mouth you see the following:

Explanation:
A = palatoglossal arch formed from the palatoglossus muscle

B = palatopharyngeal arch formed from the palatopharyngeus muscle

Both are supplied by the vagus nerve - cranial nerve 10

Question: What is pancuronium bromide?
Explanation:
Correct answer is B!

Pancuronium bromide binds to nicotinic receptors at neuromuscular junctions, preventing the binding of acetylcholine. This pleads to muscle paralysis and clinically, is used in surgery.

Important to note: Acetycholine is the only neurotransmitter at neuromuscular junctions

Question: What type of GPCR subunit are alpha 1 receptors associated with?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

Alpha 1 receptors are found in smooth muscle and are GPCR, specifically associated with G alpha Q subunits. When stimulated, they activate the phospholipase C pathway which leads to smooth muscle contraction.

Question: The papillae on the tongue are classified based on their appearance. Which of these is not a type of papillae on the tongue?
Explanation:
There are three types of papilla, based on their appearance: vallate, foliate, and fungiform.

The surface of the tongue, along with the rest of the oral cavity, is lined by a stratified squamous epithelium. In the surface of the tongue are raised bumps, called papilla, that contain the taste buds.

 

An article on https://courses.lumenlearning.com/austincc-ap1/chapter/special-senses-taste-gustation/ explains taste and has some quiz questions as well.
