Question: Which drug can cause overdose related hepatotoxicity?
Explanation:
Paracetamol - can cause overdose related hepatotoxicity (treat with n-acetyl cysteine). Contraindicated if in liver failure or if acute alcohol intoxication

Ibuprofen - can cause renal impairment. Contraindicated if gastric ulceration or history of renal impairment

Codeine - can cause constipation, dizziness, drowsiness, dependence. Contraindicated if in acute respiratory depression or coma

Prednisolone - can cause (chronic) Cushing's syndrome and immune suppression. Contraindicated if acute infection

Question: The walls of the heart are composed of thee layers of tissue including the pericardium (which is made up of three layers of connective tissue). Select the answer which best fits the arrangement of all the tissue layers of the heart.
OptionA:
Outer layer = pericardium. >innermost layer of pericardium = visceral pericardium or epicardium > pericardial cavity > 2nd layer = parietal pericardium > outer layer = fibrous pericardium
Middle layer = endocardium
Inner layer = myocardium
OptionB:
Outer layer = pericardium. >innermost layer of pericardium = visceral pericardium or epicardium > pericardial cavity > 2nd layer = parietal pericardium > outer layer = fibrous pericardium
Middle layer = myocardium
Inner layer = endocardium
OptionC:
Outer layer = pericardium. >innermost layer = parietal pericardium > pericardial cavity > 2nd layer = visceral pericardium or epicardium > outer layer = fibrous pericardium
Middle layer = myocardium
Inner layer = endocardium
OptionD:
Outer layer = pericardium. >innermost layer = visceral pericardium or epicardium > 2nd layer = parietal pericardium > pericardial cavity > outer layer = fibrous pericardium
Middle layer = myocardium
Inner layer = endocardium
OptionE:
Outer layer = pericardium. >innermost layer of pericardium = fibrous pericardium > pericardial cavity > 2nd layer = parietal pericardium > outer layer = visceral pericardium or epicardium
Middle layer = myocardium
Inner layer = endocardium
Explanation:
• The outer layer is the pericardium, which covers the heart and juxtacardiac layers of the great vessels.
  • The innermost layer, the visceral pericardium or epicardium that adheres to the heart, and the second layer, the parietal pericardium that adheres to and lines the internal surface of the fibrous pericardium, is made up of a serous membrane that folds back on itself where the great vessels emerge. The space between (which does not exist at points of reflection) the two serous pericardial membranes is the pericardial cavity/sac containing pericardial fluid within fibrous pericardium. The fluid separates the heart and its surroundings allowing cardiac motion and shape change. Volume of the pericardial cavity: 20-60 ml (average 15-30 ml) of serous plasma ultrafiltrate. Composition of the visceral layer: layer of ciliated mesothelial cells on a thin subserosal layer of connective tissue. 
  • The outer layer is the fibrous pericardium. Composed of connective tissue. Sac completely surrounds the heart but is not attached. 
  • Functions of the pericardium: 1) intrathoracic cardiac stability / anchors the heart in the mediastinum 2) reduces friction between the heart & the mediastinal structures 3) limiting cardiac distension & chamber dilation > prevents hypertrophy 4) uniform cardiac distribution of pericardial cavity hydrostatic pressure 5) barrier to spread of infection from adjacent organs 6) develops negative pericardial pressure during ventricle systole > facilitates filling of the atria 6) forms a system that applies automatic hydrostatic forces that compensate against alterations in gravitational or inertial forces
  • The middle layer is the myocardium formed of cardiac muscle and connective tissue. Function: contractile part of the heart.
  • The inner layer is the endocardium, which is continuous with the vascular endothelium (the inner lining of the blood vessels) and covers the heart valves. Composition = thin layer of connective tissue and endothelium.

Question: How does oestrogen effect osteoclasts and osteoblasts?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Oestrogen:

Inhibits the formation of osteoclasts 

Inhibits RANKL release by osteoblasts 

In post menopausal women, oestrogen levels are reduced. This means osteoclast formation is not inhibited as much and more osteoclasts form. RANKL release by osteoblasts is also less inhibited and more RANKL is released. Increased osteoclasts and RANKL increases bone resorption, leading to a greater risk of osteoporosis in post menopausal women

Question: Select the answer that best fits the innervation of the pericardium.
OptionA: The left and right phrenic nerves mainly transmit pain from the parietal layer of the serous pericardium AND visceral afferent fibres travelling via sympathetic nerves (arising from the cervical, upper thoracic & stellate ganglia) to the aortic and cardiac plexuses transmit pain from the visceral layer of serous pericardium.
OptionB: The left and right phrenic nerves mainly transmit pain from the visceral layer of serous pericardium AND visceral afferent fibres travelling via sympathetic nerves (arising from the cervical, upper thoracic & stellate ganglia) to the aortic and cardiac plexuses transmit pain from the parietal layer of the serous pericardium.
OptionC: The left and right vagal nerves mainly transmit pain from the parietal layer of the serous pericardium AND visceral afferent fibres travelling via sympathetic nerves (arising from the cervical, upper thoracic & stellate ganglia) to the aortic and cardiac plexuses transmit pain from the visceral layer of serous pericardium.
Explanation:
Innervation of the pericardium:

  • Left and right phrenic nerves mainly transmit pain from the parietal layer of the serous pericardium
  • Visceral afferent fibres travelling via sympathetic nerves (which from the cervical, upper thoracic & stellate ganglia) to the aortic and cardiac plexuses transmit pain from the visceral layer of serous pericardium
  • Vagal fibres (from the oesophageal plexus and left recurrent laryngeal nerve) also innervate the pericardium

Character of the pain from the pericardium:

  • Somatic
  • Typically sharp and severe
  • Substernal; but sometimes radiates to the superior border of the trapezius
  • Lying in the supine or left lateral position exacerbates the pain and leaning forwards relieves it

Question: Cardiac tamponade is the external compression of the heart, usually caused by pericardial effusion. Select the answer which includes the three classical diagnostic features or signs of cardiac tamponade, together known as Beck's triad.
OptionB:
1) Small quiet heart

2) Falling atrial pressure

3) Rising jugular venous pressure
OptionC:
1) Falling jugular venous pressure

2) Hypertension

3) Resonant heart sounds
OptionD:
1) Dilated neck veins

2) Cardiac arrest

3) A gradual increase in pericardial fluid volume
Explanation:
Explanation of cardiac tamponade: compression of the right atrium resulting from external compression of the heart which reduces venous return and thereby reduces cardiac output.

 

The three elements of Beck's triad, with explanations, are:

1) A small quiet heart > heart sounds will be muffled. Cause: fluid within the pericardial cavity.

2) Rising jugular venous pressure > neck veins may be dilated. Cause: impaired cardiac venous return.

3) Falling atrial pressure or hypotension. Cause: decreased stroke volume.

 

Symptoms may include: chest tightness, dyspnoea, cardiogenic shock, cardiac arrest, cardiac failure.

 

Emergency treatment: 1) relieve the tamponade by drainage of the fluid (percutaneous pericardial aspiration or pericardiocentesis); 2) Surgery in some cases may be required to address the underlying cause (via a subxiphoid incision or a left anterior thoracotomy)

 

Note that, in addition to infection resulting in pericardial effusion, cardiac tamponade can be secondary to: trauma; proximal extension of a dissecting aortic aneurysm; cardiac surgery; central venous catheter insertion

 

Role of echocardiography in cardiac tamponade: 1) as a diagnostic tool 2) to guide pericardiocentesis

 

Note that cardiac tamponade is more likely to be caused by a rapid increase in fluid volume (rather than a gradual increase in pericardial fluid). The implication of this is that the volume of fluid within the pericardial cavity may not be proportional to physiological circulatory impairment.

Question: Pericardiocentesis is the aspiration of fluid from the pericardial cavity. The image shows a sagittal section in the midplane of a cadaver. The broken line shows the direction of a pericardiocentesis needle. Indicate which approach to pericardiocentesis has been used in this case.
Explanation:
Indications for pericardiocentesis:

  1. aspiration of fluid in acute cardiac tamponade (compression of the heart by fluid or blood in the pericardial cavity) >> relieves pressure in the pericardial cavity & improves cardiac output while, for example, a thoracotomy is arranged
  2. relief of symptomatic pericardial effusion
  3. Diagnosis of neoplastic effusions
  4. Diagnosis of purulent pericarditis
  5. Introduction of cytotoxic agents into the pericardial cavity

Pericardiocentesis may be ineffective if there is substantial haemorrhage due to haemostasis and clot formation. Thoracotomy and opening of the pericardial cavity indicated.

 

Approach in the figure: the classic subxiphoid approach. Used in emergent situation. Insert needle into the angle between the xiphisternum (xiphoid process) and left costal margin at 30°-45° to the anatomical transverse plane - i.e. directed towards the left mid-clavicle (30°) or left shoulder (45°). Pros: needle enters fibrous pericardium where it is in direct contact with diaphragm >less risk of injury to pleura. Complications: pneumothorax, liver laceration or puncture; right atrial or ventricular laceration; irritation to diaphragm and phrenic nerve. 

 

Other approaches:

  1. Parasternal approach under ultrasound guidance. Preferred approach, especially for elective procedures.  Insertion: Fifth intercostal space at the left parasternal border no more than 1 cm lateral, cephalad to the inferior rib and perpendicular to the patient’s chest - directed posteriorly. Pros: Avoids injury to diaphragm and phrenic nerve; cardiac notch of left lung leaves pericardium exposed. Complications: pneumothorax, right ventricular laceration; internal thoracic vessels lie close to sternal approach. 
  2. Apical. Insertion: Fifth, sixth, or seventh left intercostal space approximately 6 cm from the parasternal border, cephalad to the inferior rib. 1 cm outside apex beat. Directed towards patient's right shoulder. Pros: smaller sized vessels near apex; left ventricle has a thicker wall which can seal off if punctured; fluid will accumulate around the apex if patient in left lateral position; pericardium is superficial; pleura usually absent over cardiac apex. Complications: pneumothorax, right or left ventricular laceration.
  3. Abdominal

Question: Select the answer which correctly describes the borders of the heart
OptionA:
Upper border = formed by the IVC
Inferior border = mainly formed by right ventricle
Right border = formed by right atrium
Left border = formed by left ventricle
OptionB:
Upper border = formed by the atria
Inferior border = mainly formed by right ventricle
Right border = formed by right atrium
Left border = formed by left atrium
OptionC:
Upper border = formed by the left atrium

Inferior border = mainly formed by right ventricle
Right border = formed by right atrium
Left border = formed by left ventricle
OptionD:
Upper border = formed by the atria
Inferior border = mainly formed by the apex
Right border = formed by right atrium
Left border = formed by left ventricle
OptionE:
Upper border = formed by the atria
Inferior border = mainly formed by right ventricle
Right border = formed by right atrium
Left border = formed by left ventricle
Explanation:
Upper / superior border = slightly oblique and formed by the atria. Also SVC, ascending aorta and pulmonary trunk

Question: The heart consists of two atria and two ventricles. It is obliquely positioned in the thorax. The heart has a base and an apex. Pick the description that best fits the orientation of the heart.
OptionA:
The base faces: anteriorly and to the right
The apex faces: posteriorly and to the left
Right atrium: positioned to the right; anterior and inferior to the left atrium; partly anterior to the left ventricle
Right ventricle: forms most of the anterior aspect of the ventricle mass
Left atrium: forms most of the posterior aspect of the heart
Left ventricle: forms the posterolateral, lateral and anterolateral surface of the heart and its apex
OptionB:
The base faces: posteriorly and to the right
The apex faces: anteriorly and to the left
Right atrium: positioned to the right; anterior and superior to the left atrium; partly anterior to the left ventricle
Right ventricle: forms most of the anterior aspect of the ventricle mass
Left atrium: forms most of the posterior aspect of the heart
Left ventricle: forms the posterolateral, lateral and anterolateral surface of the heart and its apex
OptionC:
The base faces: posteriorly and to the right

The apex faces: anteriorly and to the left

Right atrium: positioned to the right; anterior and inferior to the left atrium; partly anterior to the left ventricle

Right ventricle: forms most of the anterior aspect of the ventricle mass

Left atrium: forms most of the posterior aspect of the heart

Left ventricle: forms the posterolateral, lateral and anterolateral surface of the heart and its apex
OptionD:
The base faces: posteriorly and to the right
The apex faces: anteriorly and to the left
Right atrium: positioned to the right; posterior and inferior to the left atrium; partly anterior to the left ventricle
Right ventricle: forms most of the anterior aspect of the ventricle mass
Left atrium: forms most of the posterior aspect of the heart
Left ventricle: forms the posterolateral, lateral and anterolateral surface of the heart and its apex
OptionE:
The base faces: posteriorly and to the right
The apex faces: anteriorly and to the left
Right atrium: positioned to the right; anterior and inferior to the left atrium; partly anterior to the left ventricle
Right ventricle: forms most of the posterior aspect of the ventricle mass
Left atrium: forms most of the anterior aspect of the heart
Left ventricle: forms the posterolateral, lateral and anterolateral surface of the heart and its apex
Explanation:
The heart is positioned obliquely in the thorax - like a deformed pyramid. The base faces posteriorly and to the right, and the apex faces anteriorly and to the left. A posterolateral projection of a line from the apex to the centre of the base will emerge near the right scapular line.

 

Long axis of the heart: from right shoulder towards the left hypochondrium.

 

In the mediastinum, one-third of the heart is to the right of the median plane, and two-thirds to the left.

 

Each ventricle is the left of and anterior to its ventricle.

 

Right atrium: to the right; anterior and inferior to the left atrium; partly anterior to the left ventricle.
Right ventricle: forms most of the anterior aspect of the ventricle mass (i.e. forms the mid-anterior surface of the heart and the right ventricle lies anterior to the left ventricle). Inferior end lies to the right of the left ventricle. Upper extremity (supporting pulmonary valve) lies to the left of the left ventricle & superior to level of aortic valve.

Left atrium: forms most of the posterior aspect of the heart.
Left ventricle: forms the posterolateral, lateral and anterolateral surface of the heart and its apex. Prominent inferiorly. Runs along the left border to reach the cardiac apex.

 

Right heart = forms the largest part of the anterior surface.

Outflow tract of the right heat (pulmonary trunk) ascends until terminates on left side of the left ventricle's outflow tract (aorta). Inlet to right ventricle (tricuspid valve) is widely separated from its outlet (pulmonary valve).

 

Left heart = mostly posterior (but a left-sided strip of the left border that includes the cardiac apex is anterior in position). Largely obscured by right heart when viewed anteriorly. 

Mitral valve (inlet to left ventricle) is close to aortic valve (outlet to left ventricle). Planes of these orifices more co-planar than right

Cavity of left ventricle = narrow, conical. Tip is within the cardiac apex.

 

Surfaces of the heart:

Posterior surface / base = directed upward, backward and to the right. Formed mainly by left atrium, also by right atrium

Apex = directed downward, forward and to the left. Formed by left ventricle

Sternocostal / anterior = directed forward, upward and to the left. Formed mainly by right ventricle inferiorly and superiorly by the atria.

Diaphragmatic / inferior = mostly right ventricle, portion of left ventricle. Directed downward, slightly backwards. Rests upon central tendon of the diaphragm.

Right pulmonary = formed by right atrium superiorly and right ventricle inferiorly 

Left pulmonary = formed mainly by left ventricle, a little superiorly by the left atrium

 

Borders of the heart:

Upper / superior border = slightly oblique and formed by the atria. Also SVC, ascending aorta and pulmonary trunk

Inferior border (acute margin or border) = nearly horizontal; mainly formed by right ventricle and small part of left ventricle at the apex

Right border = more or less vertical; formed by right atrium. Also IVC and SVC. 

Left border (obtuse margin or border) = formed by left ventricle. Oblique and curved. Also left auricle, pulmonary trunk and arch of aorta. 

 

The atrial and ventricular septal structures are virtually in line anteriorly

Planes of the mitral and tricuspid valves - near vertical

Question: Where is the apex beat normally found?
OptionA: In the fifth left intercostal space 5 cm lateral to the midline
OptionB: Under the fifth rib 5 cm medial to the mid-clavicular line
OptionC: In the fifth left intercostal space in the mid-clavicular line.
OptionD: In the sixth left intercostal space lateral to the mid-clavicular line.
Explanation:
The cardiac apex

  • The apex of the conical left ventricle is directed anteroinferiorly and to the left
  • The cardiac apex overlapped by the left lung and its covering pleurae.
  • The apex is located most commonly behind the fifth left rib, fifth left intercostal space or the sixth left rib, near or a little medial to the mid-clavicular line
  • (The mid-clavicular line is located 8–9 cm lateral to the midline)

The apex beat

  • Is the most inferior and lateral position at which the cardiac impulse can be palpated
  • In males, the apex beat is normally found inferior and medial to the nipple

Inferolateral displacement of the apex beat usually indicates:

  • Left ventricular dilation due to ischaemic heart disease
  • Dilated cardiomyopathy
  • Volume overloaded left ventricle due to aortic or mitral regurgitation

Character of the apex beat (but note that echocardiography makes this of limited clinical relevance):

  • Tapping apex beat = mitral stenosis. Tapping represents a palpable first heart sound.
  • Dynamic or thrusting apex beat = consistent with a volume loaded left ventricle due to severe aortic or mitral regurgitation
  • Heaving apex beat = left ventricular hypertrophy due to e.g. hypertension or aortic stenosis

Question: The heart consists of a fused pair of muscular pumps. Do the two pumps circulate blood in parallel or in series?
OptionA: The muscular pumps circulate blood in series through systemic and pulmonary circulations
OptionB: The muscular pumps circulate blood in parallel through systemic and pulmonary circulations
OptionC: The muscular pumps circulate blood in series through one systemic circulation
Explanation:
• The heart is a fused pair of valve-containing muscular pumps
  • The pumps circulate bloodin seriesthrough systemic (left heart) and pulmonary (right heart) circulations
  • Although the pumps are physiologically separate, the fibromuscular framework and conduction tissues of the pumps are structurally interwoven  
  • The two atria receive venous blood. They are weakly contractile reservoirs for final filling of the two ventricles
  • The two ventricles provide the powerful expulsive contraction that forces blood into the main arterial trunks

Question: Which class(es) of antibiotics are indicated for a broad spectrum of infections?
Explanation:
Aminoglycosides - gram negative infections

Beta-lactams - gram positive infections

Sulfonamides - toxoplasma infections 

Quinolones - Broad spectrum

Tetracyclines - Broad spectrum 

Glycopeptides - gram positive 

Macrolides - infections caused by e.g. toxoplasma, mycoplasma, haemophilus, legionella

Question: Which classes of antibiotics exert a bacteriostatic effect?
Explanation:
Aminoglycosides - Bactericidal - block the initiation of bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 30s ribosomal subunit

Beta-lactams - Bactericidal - inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis. Binds to penicillin binding proteins preventing cross linking of peptides in cell wall. 

Sulfonamides - Bacteriostatic - inhibit bacterial dihyropterate synthetase which makes folate (DNA synthesis) limiting bacterial growth

Quinolones - Bactericidal - prevent bacterial DNA replication. Inhibits DNA topoisomerase. 

Tetracyclines - Bacteriostatic - outcompetes tRNA for "A" binding site of bacterial 50s ribosome

Glycopeptides - Bactericidal - blocks synthesis of peptidoglycans required for cell wall integrity. Alters membrane permeability and RNA synthesis. 

Macrolides - Bactericidal and Bacteriostatic - inhibits translocation events in bacterial protein synthesis by binding to 50s subunit or ribosome.

Question: Gentamicin is an example of which class of antibiotics?
Explanation:
Correct answer is B!

Gentamicin is an example of an aminoglycoside used to treat gram negative infections caused by bacteria such as Campylobacter and pseudomonas. Aminoglycosides prevent initiation of bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 30S subunit of the ribosome. Bactericidal mechanisms are more extensive and can include increasing bacterial cell wall permeability.

Question: What is the resting membrane potential (Em) of a ventricular myocyte?
Explanation:
• The resting membrane potential  (Em) of a ventricular myocyte is -90 mV (Answer B)
  • The electrical potential across a cell membrane can be measured by measuring the electrical potential inside the cell relative to the outside of the cell by a microelectrode in the cell. By convention, the outside of the cell is 0 mV (Answer A)

What determines the resting membrane potential?

  • Concentrations of positively and negatively charged ions across the cell membrane. Especially the concentrations of Na+, K+ and Ca2+.
  • The relative permeability of the cell membrane to these ions
  • The ionic pumps that transport ions across the cell membrane

Other wrong answers:

Answer C: -96 mV is the equilibrium potential (EK) for K+ (or the Nernst potential)

Answer D: +52 mV is the equilibrium potential (ENa) for Na+ (or the Nernst potential)

Answer E: +6 mV is the net electrochemical driving force for K+ in the ventricular myocyte (subtract the Ek from the Em)

Question: Choose the answer which best fits the concentrations of K+, Na+ and Ca2+ inside and outside a cardiac myocyte at a resting membrane potential of -90 mV
OptionA:
K+ inside = 4 mM

K+ outside = 150 mM

 

Na+ = 145 mM

Na+ = 20 mM

 

Ca++ = 2.5 mM

Ca++ =  0.0001 mM
OptionB:
K+ inside = 150 mM
K+ outside = 4 mM

 

Na+ = 145  mM
Na+ = 20 mM

 

Ca++ = 0.0001 mM
Ca++ = 2.5 mM
OptionC:
K+ inside = 150 mM
K+ outside = 4 mM

 

Na+ = 20 mM
Na+ = 145 mM

 

Ca++ = 2.5 mM
Ca++ = 0.0001 mM
OptionD:
K+ inside = 150 mM
K+ outside = 4 mM

 

Na+ = 20 mM
Na+ = 145 mM

 

Ca++ = 0.0001 mM
Ca++ = 2.5 mM
Explanation:
• The concentrations of Na+, K+ and Ca++ inside and outside the cell are the most important ion concentrations that determine the membrane potential across the cell membrane. Chloride ions contribute much less to the resting membrane potential. 
  • K+ is the most important in determining the membrane potential
  • In the myocyte, the concentration of K+ is high inside and low outside the cell. A chemical gradient/concentration difference exists for K+ to diffuse out of the cell
  • For Na+ and Ca++, the concentration is low inside and high outside the cell: the chemical gradient for Na+ and Ca++ favours an inward diffusion

What determines the concentration differences across the cell membrane for ions?

  • The activity of energy-dependent ionic pumps
  • The presence of impermeable, negatively charged proteins within the cell that affect the passive distribution of cations and anions

Answer D is the correct answer

False answers:

A = states that the concentration of K+ is low inside the cell and high outside, and the concentrations of Na+ and Ca++ are high inside the cell and low outside: the opposite is the case

B = the concentrations of Na+ are wrong. [Na+] is not high inside the cell and low outside

C = the concentrations of Ca++ are wrong. [Ca++] is not high inside the cell and low outside

Question:
The K+ concentration is 150 mM inside and 4 mM outside a resting cardiac myocyte. 

 

If the outside K+ concentration is increased from 4 to 10 nM, what would be the effect on the equilibrium potential for K+?
OptionA: The equilibrium potential would stay the same
OptionB: The equilibrium potential would become less negative
OptionC: The equilibrium potential would become more negative
Explanation:
Consider how the concentration gradients of ions across a cell membrane affect membrane potential. 

  • K+ has a higher concentration inside the cell than outside - the chemical gradient favours an outward diffusion of K+
  • As K+ leaves the cell, negatively charged proteins will be left behind
  • A separation of charge is created
  • A potential difference across the membrane is created - negative inside the cell relative to the outside
  • The equilibrium potential or Nernst potential for K+ is the membrane potential that is necessary to oppose the outward movement of K+ down its concentration gradient, i.e. the potential difference across the membrane required to maintain the concentration gradient across the membrane

The Nernst potential for K+ at 37 degrees celsius is Ek = -61 log [K+]I / [K+]O = -96 mV where the potassium concentration inside is 150 mM and the potassium concentration outside is 4 mM

The Nernst potential for K+ at 37 degrees celsius is Ek = -61 log [K+]I / [K+]O = -71.7 mV where the potassium concentration inside is 150 mM and the potassium concentration outside is 10 mM

 

Answer B is the correct answer

  • Increasing the outside K+ concentration from 4 to 10 mM reduces the chemical gradient for diffusion out of the cell
  • The membrane potential required to maintain the electrochemical equilibrium would be less negative

Question:
The resting membrane potential (Em) for a ventricular myocyte is -90 mV

The equilibrium potential for K+ (Ek) is -96 mV

 

What is the net electrochemical force acting on potassium?
Explanation:
Answer B is correct.

The net electrochemical driving force is the Em (-90mV) minus the Ek (-96 mV) = +6 mV

 

K+ slowly leaks outward from the cell because:

  • the resting cell has a finite permeability to K+
  • a small net outward driving force is acting on K+

Question:
The equilibrium potential for Na+ (ENa) is +52 mV. This is calculated using the Nernst equation. The sodium concentration inside the cell is 20 mM and outside 145 mM.

 

If the resting membrane potential (Em) of a ventricular myocyte is -90 mV, what is the net electrochemical force acting on Na+? And, at rest, would therefore a large or small amount of Na+ leak into the cell?
OptionA:
Net electrochemical force acting on sodium = +142 mV

 

AND

 

Only a small amount of Na+ would leak into the cell
OptionB:
Net electrochemical force acting on sodium = -142 mV

 

AND

 

A large amount of Na+ would leak into the cell
OptionC:
Net electrochemical force acting on sodium = -142 mV

 

AND

 

Only a small amount of Na+ would leak into the cell
OptionD:
Net electrochemical force acting on sodium = +142 mV

 

AND

 

A large amount of Na+ would leak into the cell
Explanation:
This question requires a two-part answer.

 

Firstly, work out the net electrochemical force acting on sodium.

This has two components. First, the sodium concentration gradient is driving sodium into the cell (the sodium concentration inside the cell is much lower than outside). The question tells us that the equilibrium potential according to the Nernst relationship is +52 mV - i.e. the electrical force necessary to counterbalance the chemical gradient is +52 mV. 

Second, the question tells us that the interior of the resting cell is very negative (-90 mV) - this is an electrical force that is pulling Na into the cell.

To derive the net electrochemical force, subtract the ENa from the Em: -90 mV - +52 mV = -142 mV

Therefore there is a large electrochemical force that is driving sodium into the cell

 

However, Em is determined not only by the concentrations of ions across the cell membrane - the relative permeability of the cell membrane to the ions also contributes to the Em. 

At rest, the permeability of Na+ is so low that only a small amount of Na+ leaks into the cell. Therefore Answer C is the correct answer

 

The same applies to Ca++. Since the ECa = +134 mV, the net electrochemical force acting on Ca++ is very large (-224 mV). But there is low membrane permeability to Ca++ at rest.
Tags: Cardiac, Cardiac Cycle, Cell membrane potentials

What is the action of this muscle?
OptionA: Inversion of the foot at the subtalar and transverse tarsal joints
OptionB: Assist with flexion of the digits at the interphalangeal and metatarsophalangeal joints
OptionC: Plantar flexion of the foot at the talocrural (ankle) joint
OptionD: Assist with adduction of the digits at the metatarsophalangeal joints
Explanation:
The quadratus plantae muscle is involved in assisting flexion of the 2nd, 3rd, 4th and little toes.

It does this by pulling on the tendons of the flexor digitorum longus muscle (seen attached to quadratus plantae in the image).

 

Quadratus plantae therefore flexes the proximal and middle phalanges at the proximal and distal interphalangeal joints and the proximal phalanges at the metatarsophalangeal joints.

Question: In the resting ventricular myocyte, the resting membrane potential (Em) is most near the equilibrium potential for which ion?
Explanation:
The Em in a resting ventricular myocyte is near the Ek, and distant form ENa and ECa. So answer A is correct. 

 

Why?

  • The membrane is much more permeable to K+ in the resting state than to Na+ or Ca2+
  • Na+ and Ca2+ thus makes a minor concentration to Em
  • Em reflects both the concentration gradients of individual ions (thus the equilibrium potentials) and the relative permeability of the membrane to the relevant ions

Medial thigh = obturator nerve

Question:
In the following equation, what does g' represent?

 

Em = g'K+ (Ek) + g'Na+ (ENa) + g'Ca2+ (ECa)
OptionB: The sum of the individual equilibrium potentials for the ions
OptionC: The membrane conductance for an ion relative to the sum of all ion conductances
Explanation:
The expression in the question relates membrane potential (Em) to the relative conductances of all ions (g') and their equilibrium potentials (E).

 

The relative conductance for an ion (Answer C) is the correct answer

 

For example, the relative conductance for K+ is:

 

(g'K+) = gK+ / (gK+ + gNa+ + gCa2+)

 

What is ion conductance?

  • An increase in membrane permeability for an ion results in an increase in electrical conductance for that ion
  • Ion conductance (g) is the ion current / net voltage (net electrochemical force) acting on the ion
  • Membrane permeability for an ion determines the movement of an ion (an electrical current) being driven by a net electrochemical force

What is the role of ionic conductances in determining EM?

  • Changes in EM are primarily determined by changes in ionic conductances
  • This is because in a cardiac cell the individual ion concentration gravies change only slightly - even when depolarisation causes Na+ to enter and K+ to leave the cell
  • The EM (-90 mV) is near the equilibrium potential for K+ (-96 mV) since the relative conductance for K+ is high in the resting cell
  • Na+ and Ca++ ions contribute little to the resting membrane potential since the relative conductance for Na+ and Ca++ is low in the resting cell
  • During an action potential, g'Na+ increase and g'K+ decrease. The membrane potential becomes more positive (depolarized) since the sodium equilibrium potential has more influence on the overall membrane potential. A large increase in g'Ca+, particularly when g'K+ is low, will also result in the membrane potential becoming more positive - depolarisation

(Note that in reality ion concentrations [equilibrium potentials] and ion conductances are not separate variables: the conductance of some ion channels are influenced by the concentration of the ion or by changes in membrane potential)

Explanation:

Note: the medial compartment muscles also have other roles, such as internal rotation and stabilizing the pelvis

Question: Which sarcolemmal pump or exchanger maintains the transmembrane ionic gradient for K+?
Explanation:
Answer C is correct. Answers D is a red herring and does not exist. Answers A and B is not relevant for the maintenance of the K+ ionic gradient.

  • Membrane potential depends on the maintenance of ionic concentration gradients across the membrane
  • Extracellular and intracellular concentrations of ions will change since Na+ and Ca2+ enter the cell down their electrochemical gradient (especially during action potentials), while K+ leaves the cell

Maintenance of the Na+ and K+ concentration gradients

  • the Na+/K+-ATPase pump maintains Na+ & K+ concentration gradients
  • If the pump fails, Na+ will accumulate within the cell; intracellular K+ will fall. The resting membrane potential (EM) will become less negative/more depolarised since Ek (the equilibrium potential of K+) will become less negative. Remember that if the outside K+ concentration increase, the chemical gradient for diffusion out of the cell reduces, and the membrane potential required to maintain the electrochemical equilibrium would be less negative according to the Nernst relationship. Em is determined by the relative conductances of all ions & their equilibrium potentials.
  • Since the pump system is energy dependent, the pump will fail under hypoxic conditions when ATP is lost. Or, cardiac glycosides such as digoxin inhibit the activity of the pump
  • The pump is electrogenic (produces a change in the electrical potential for a cell) since three Na+ is pumped in for every 2 K+ pumped out. It therefore creates a negative potential within the cell (up to -10 mV) since more positive charges are pumped out. Therefore, inhibition of the pump causes depolarisation in two ways: 1) failure to maintain the ionic gradients 2) loss of a electrogenic component of the membrane potential

Maintenance of the Ca2+ concentration gradient:

  • Ca2+ leaks into the resting cell and enters the cell during action potentials
  • An ATP-dependent Ca2+ pump pumps Ca2+ out of the cell. Creates a small negative electrogenic potential
  • The Na+/Ca++ exchanger (3:1) transports Na+ & Ca2++ in opposite directions. In resting cells, the negative EM causes three sodium ions (enters) to be exchanged for each calcium ion (leaves). This would create a small electrogenic potential. In depolarised cells, the exchanger operates in the opposite direction
  • Note that changes in the intracellular Na+ concentration influences the operation of the exchanger. This is exploited by digoxin: digoxin decreases the activity of the Na+/K+-ATPase pump > causing an increase in Na+ concentration > the gradient for Na+ movement into the cell through the Na+/Ca++ exchanger is reduced > less Ca2+ leaves the cell > increased intracellular Ca2+ increases the force of myocyte contraction
Tags: Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials, Electrical activity of the heart

Question: There are fast and slow sodium channels in cardiac cells. Select the characteristic that best fits the fast Na+ (INa) channel.
OptionA: A channel that contributes to phase 4 pacemaker current in SA and AV nodal cells
OptionB: A voltage-gated channel associated with phase 0 of myocytes
Explanation:
This question is on ion channels selective for sodium. 

 

The fast Na+ (INa) channel is voltage-gated. Characteristic: phase 0 of myocytes. Answer B. 

 

The slow Na+ (If) channel is voltage-gated and receptor-gated. Characteristic: contributes to phase 4 pacemaker current in SA and AV nodal cells. (Answer A). 

 

Answer C refers to the calcium-activated potassium channel (IK,Ca). Characteristic: activated by high cytosolic calcium and accelerates repolarization.
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials

Question:
There are 6 important potassium channels in cardiac cells: inward rectifier, transient outward, delayed rectifier, ATP-sensitive, acetylcholine activated, and calcium activated.

 

Select the answer which best describes the inward rectifier K+ channel.
OptionC: Maintains negative potential in phase 4 and closes with depolarisation
Explanation:
Inward rectifier (IK1):

  • Answer C
  • Maintains negative potential in phase 4 and closes with depolarisation
  • Voltage-gated

Delayed rectifier (IKr):

  • Answer A
  • Phase 3 repolarisation
  • Voltage gated

Transient outward (Ito):

  • Answer E
  • Voltage gated
  • Contributes to phase 1 in myocytes

ATP-sensitive (IK, ATP):

  • Does not feature in the answers
  • Receptor-gated
  • Inhibited by ATP
  • Opens when ATP decreases during cellular hypoxia

Acetylcholine activated (IK, ACh):

  • Answer D
  • Receptor-gated
  • Activated by acetylcholine and adenosine
  • Gi-protein coupled
  • Slows SA nodal firing

Calcium activated (IK, Ca)

  • Answer B
  • Receptor-gated
  • Activated by high cytosolic calcium
  • Accelerates repolarization
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials

Question:
An action potential is the sudden depolarisation of the membrane potential and its repolarization back to its resting state.

 

The answers below state the duration of action potentials in different human cells. Select the answer which best fits the duration of an action potential in a skeletal muscle cell.
OptionA: The action potential duration is about 1 to 2 ms
OptionB: The action potential duration is approximately 2 to 5 ms

Answer B = in skeletal muscle cells, the action potential lasts approximately 2-5 ms

Question:
By convention, the action potential of non pacemaker cardiac cells (found in atrial and ventricular myocytes and Purkinje fibres) is divided into five numbered phases.

 

Pick the answer that best describes phase 4.
OptionA: This phase represents the true resting membrane potential
OptionE: This phase represents the plateau of the repolarisation
Explanation:
Answer A is the correct answer. Note that the five phases are numbered from 0 to 4.

 

Changes in Na+, Ca2+ and K+ conductances primarily determine the action potential in non pacemaker cells

 

Phase 4 = true resting membrane potential

  • Near the equilibrium potential for K+ because gK+ through inward rectifying voltage-gated potassium channels is high relative to gNa+ and gCa2+ in resting cells

Phase 0 = rapid depolarisation

  • An action potential is conducted by an adjacent cell
  • The cell is rapidly depolarised form -90 mV to a threshold voltage of about -70 mV
  • Α transient increase in conductance of voltage-gated, fast Na+-channels initiates a rapid depolarisation
  • At the same time, gK+ falls
  • The conductance changes move the membrane potential away form the potassium equilibrium and closer to the sodium equilibrium potential

Phase 1 = initial depolarisation

  • Caused by the opening of transient outward potassium channels (Ito) and inactivation of Na+ channels

Phase 2 = plateau

  • Repolarization is delayed by the large increase in slow inward gCa2+
  • Inward calcium movement is through long-lasting (L-type) calcium channels. They open when membrane potential depolarises to about -40 mv. They are the major calcium channels in cardiac & vascular smooth muscle. As voltage-operated channels, they are opened by member depolarisation and remain open for a relatively long duration. Blocked by L-type calcium channel blockers (Verpamil, diltiazem)

Phase 3 = repolarisation

  • Occurs when gK+ increases through delayed rectifier potassium channels and gCa2+ decreases
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials

Question: The absolute or effective refractory period is when the cardiac cell is refractory/unexcitable to the initiation of new action potentials. During which phases does the effective refractory period occur?
Explanation:
The effective/absolute refractory period covers phases 0, 1, 2 and part of phase 3

  • The h-gates (inactivation gates) are closed
  • Stimulation of the cell would not produce new, propagated action potentials

The ERP is a protective mechanism:

  • Limits the frequency of action potentials in the heart - and therefore contractions - so that the heart can adequately fill and eject
  • Prevents sustained, tetanic contractions

End of the ERP - relative refractory period:

  • Suprathreshold depolarisation stimuli are required to elicit action potentials
  • Generated action potentials have a decreased phase 0 slope and lower amplitude - because not all sodium channels have recovered to the resting state
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials

Question: Which muscle originates from the anterior superior iliac spine and attaches to the superior, medial surface of the tibia?
Explanation:
Sartorius - Originates from anterior superior iliac spine and attaches to superior, medial surface of tibia.

 

Gracilis - Originates from the inferior rami of the pubis and the body of the pubis. Attaches to the medial surface of the tibia between the tendons of sartorius (anteriorly) and semitendinosus (posteriorly).

 

Rectus femoris - Originates from anterior inferior iliac spine and the area of the ilium immediately superior to the acetabulum. Attaches to patella via quadriceps femoris tendon.

 

Semitendinosus - Originates from the ischial tuberosity of the pelvis and attaches to medial surface of tibia. 

 

Semimembranosus - Originates from the ischial tuberosity (more superiorly than semitendinosus and biceps femoris). Attaches to medial tibial condyle

 

Biceps femoris - Long head originates from ischial tuberosity of pelvis. Short head originates from linea aspera on posterior surface of femur. Together, the heads form a tendon which inserts into the head of the fibula.

 

Gastrocnemius - Lateral head originates from the lateral femoral condyle and medial head from the medial femoral condyle. Fibres converge and form a single muscle belly. The muscle belly combines with soleus to form the calcaneal tendon which inserts onto the calcaneus.

Question: What is the origin of osteoclasts, osteoblasts and osteocytes?
OptionA: hematopoietic stem cell, mesenchymal stem cell, mesenchymal stem cell
OptionB: mesenchymal stem cell, mesenchymal stem cell, sentinel cells
OptionC: sentinel cells, hematopoietic stem cell, mesenchymal stem cell
Explanation:
A is correct!

 

osteoclasts originate from hematopoietic stem cells, osteoclastogenesis= (hematopoietic stem cell -> monocyte -> macrophage-> pre-osteoclast -> osteoclast fusion-> activated osteoclast)

osteoblasts and osteocytes originate from mesenchymal stem cells, osteoblastogenesis= (mesenchymal stem cells + bone morphogenetic protein BMP -> osteoprogenitor-> pre- osteoblast -> mature osteoblast -> osteocyte or a lining cell)

 

sentinal cells refer to cells in the body's first line of defense, which embed themselves in tissues such as skin. Sentinel cells can refer to specific antigen-presenting cells e.g. Macrophages (types of dendritic cells= Kupffer cells - in the liver and Langerhans cells - in the skin and mucosa)

Question: In which stage does chondrogenesis begin to occur in bone healing?
Explanation:
B is correct !

 

bone healing occur in 4 phases;

1. haemotoma formation; occurs straight after breakage- blood clot forms around the breaking and the injury results in secretion of pro-inflammatory cytokines e.g. TNF-alpha, BMPs and interleukins to create an inflammation (swelling). phagocytes clean the bone fragments and kill any germs.

 

2. fibrocartilaginous formation; granulation tissue begins to develop to re-join fracture after release of VEGF cytokine for angiogenesis to occur. mesenchymal stem cells are recruited and are differentiated into various cells. chondrogenesis begins to occur, where a soft callus from collagen is created around a fracture by chondroblasts. 

 

3. bony callus formation; hard callus formed from the soft callus which minerals are added to make it hard. newly formed blood vessels continue to proliferate, allowing further migration of mesenchymal stem cells. 

 

4. bone remodelling; centre of callus replaced by compact bone while callus edges become replaced by lamellar bone. continued migration of osteoblasts and osteoclasts, the hard callus undergoes repeated remodelling - termed 'coupled remodelling' to create a balance of resorption by osteoclasts and new bone formation by osteoblasts.

Question:
Pacemakers cells generate regular, spontaneous action potentials. They are sometimes also known as slow response action potentials. By convention, the sinoatrial nodal pacemaker action potential is divided into three phases. 

 

Which phase best fits this description: 'Repolarisation of the cell toward the equilibrium potential for K+'
Explanation:
Answer D/Phase 3 is correct. The three phases are Phase 4, Phase 0 and Phase 3. So, answers B and C are red herrings.

 

Action potentials in SA nodal cells are primarily the result of changes in gCa2+ and gK+ conductances

 

Phase 0 - the upstroke of the action potential. Primarily due to an increase in calcium conductance through L-type Ca2+ channels accompanied by a fall in potassium conductance

  • Depolarisation in phase 0 is primarily due to increased gCa2+ through L-type calcium channels. Voltage-operated: they open when the membrane is depolarised to a threshold voltage of about -40 mV
  • The slope of phase 0 - the rate of depolarisation - is much shallower since movement of Ca2+ through the L-type calcium channels is less rapid than fast sodium channels (in fast response nonpacemaker action potentials the depolarising current of the action potential is carried primarily by fast Na+ currents)
  • The membrane potential moves towards the calcium equilibrium potential
  • A transient decrease in gK+ occurs - contributing to depolarisation. See: Em = g'K (-96mV) + g'Ca(+134 mV)

Phase 3 - the period of repolarisation. An increase in potassium conductance and a decrease in calcium conductance

  • Voltage-operated, delayed rectifier potassium channels open with depolarisation
  • Increased gK+ repolarises the cell toward the equilibrium potential for K+ (Answer D)
  • Inactivation of the slow inward Ca2+ channels that opened during phase 0. gCa2+ decreases, which contributes to the repolarisation
  • Phase of repolarisation is self-limited and ends when the membrane potential reaches about -65 mV since with repolarisation the potassium channels begin to close

Phase 4 - the period of spontaneous depolarisation that leads to subsequent generation of a new action potential. Spontaneous depolarisation in which inward movement of Na+ contributes and decreased potassium conductance and increased calcium conductance

  • Early in phase 4 gK+ is still decreasing - contributes to depolarisation
  • In the repolarised state, a pacemaker current (If)/funny current occurs. The current is a depolarising one which involves the slow inward movement of Na+
  • In the second half, there is a small increase in gCa2+ through T-type calcium channels. T-type calcium channels are: transient; open briefly at very negative voltages (-50 mV); are not blocked by the classical L-type calcium channel blockers (e.g., verapamil, diltiazem)
  • As the depolarisation begins to reach threshold, the L-type calcium channels begin to open - a further increase in gCa2+ is caused until threshold is reached and phase O is initiated
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials

Question:
Cells within the sinoatrial node constitute the primary pacemaker site within the heart.

 

Other pacemakers cells are within the AV and and ventricular conduction system.

 

What mechanism overrides the intrinsic pacemaker activity of the secondary pacemakers?
Explanation:
Answer B is correct - the mechanism is overdrive suppression

Answers D and E are false since it is the Na+/K+-ATPase pump that is involved in the overdrive suppression mechanism

Answer A is false since the mechanism involves hyper polarisation of the secondary pacemakers

Answer C is false since cessation of the mechanism causes an ectopic focus

  • Firing rates of the secondary pacemakers are driven by the higher rate of the SA node
  • Secondary pacemakers are hyperpolarised when driven at a rate above its intrinsic rate
  • Hyperpolarisation is caused by the increased action potential frequency which stimulates the electrogenic Na+/K+-ATPase pump due to enhanced entry of sodium per unit time into these cells

Overdrive suppression ceases when:

  • the SA node becomes depressed
  • when action potentials from the SA node fail to reach secondary pacemakers

Cessation of the mechanism permits a secondary site to take over as the heart's pacemaker - the new pacemaker outside the SA node is called an ectopic focus
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials

Explanation:

Question:
There are three important ways pacemaker action potentials differ from cardiac nonpacemaker action potentials.

 

Choose the answer which best describes the pacemaker action potential.
OptionA:
1) No true resting potential
2) Slow rate of depolarisation
3) Depolarising current driven primarily by inward Ca2+ currents from T-type calcium channels
OptionB:
1) No true resting potential
2) Slow rate of depolarisation
3) Depolarising current driven primarily by inward Ca2+ currents from L-type calcium channels
OptionC:
1) True resting potential

2) Rapid rate of depolarisation

3) Depolarising current driven primarily by inward Na+ currents from Fast Na+ channels
OptionD:
1) True resting potential
2) Rapid rate of depolarisation
3) Depolarising current driven primarily by inward Na+ currents from Slow Na+ channels
Explanation:
Answer B is correct. 

  • The pacemaker action potentials are sometimes called slow response action potentials because the rate of depolarisation is slow compared to fast response non pacemaker cells
  • There is no true resting potential in pacemaker action potentials (unlike in fast response nonpacemaker cells): regular, spontaneous action potentials are generated instead
  • The depolarising current of the action potential is driven primarily by relatively slow, inward Ca2+ currents (through L-type calcium channels) instead of by fast Na+ currents - unlike most other cells that exhibit action potentials
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cell membrane potentials
