Question: Hypertension can be defined as persistent blood pressure greater than or equal to 140/90mmHg. There are many antihypertensive drugs including one called Losartan. What type of antihypertensive drug is Losartan?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

Losartan binds to angiotensin II receptors, blocking angiotensin II. This reduces vasoconstriction of blood vessels and reduces aldosterone release. Aldosterone increases water and salt reabsorption and K+ excretion. Reduced aldosterone and reduced vasoconstriction decrease blood pressure. 
A- ACE inhibitors prevent conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II by binding to ACE. An example of this is Ramipril

C- Calcium channel blockers block L type calcium ion channels, slowing depolarisation. This causes less forceful contractions and reduced heart rate. An example is Diltiazem 

D- Beta blockers bind to beta-1-adrenoreceptors which noradrenaline usually binds to. Noradrenaline activates adenylate cyclase and increases cAMP which activates protein kinase A, increasing contraction. Blocking this cascade reduces heart rate and decreases blood pressure. An example is Bisoprolol 

E- Thiazide like diuretics- examples include Furosemide, Spironolactone and bendrofluorethiazide. These all act on the kidney tubules effecting solute and water reabsorption.

Question: Which bones form the ankle joint?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E! 
The ankle joint is formed by the tibia, fibula and talus. Calcaneus is not part of the ankle joint. The medial malleolus of the tibia and the lateral malleolus of the fibula articulate with talus.

Question: How does bilateral renal artery stenosis effect blood pressure?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Bilateral renal artery stenosis is a narrowing of the renal arteries which reduces blood flow into the kidney and hypovolaemia is detected. This triggers renin secretion. Renin converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I. Angiotensin I is converted to angiotensin II by ACE. Aldosterone is released increases salt and water reabsorption. This increases blood pressure and is a cause of hypertension.

Question:
All cardiomyocytes are excitable. The cells of the sinoatrial node generate the most rapid rhythm, and function as the cardiac pacemaker. 

 

Select the answer which describes the location of the SA node.
OptionA: Located within the anterior wall of the right atrium
OptionB: Located within the atrial part of the muscular atrioventricular septum
OptionC: Subendocardially situated in the right atrium on the interatrial septum, above the attachment of the septal cusp of the tricuspid valve, to the left of the opening of the coronary sinus
OptionD: Subepicardially situated in the wall of the right atrium, just below the superior vena cava, at the top of the sulcus terminalis
Explanation:
Answer D is correct

 

Precise location of the sinoatrial node:

  • Located in the right atrium at the junction between the embryonic sinus venosus (venous) part and the primitive (proper) atrial part
  • Extends on the right from the crest of the right auricle. Courses posteroinferiorly into the upper part of the sulcus terminalis
  • Cigar-shaped structure, 8-25 mm long
  • Small mass of histologically distinctive myocardial cells
  • 10% of hearts extends in a horseshoe fashion across the crest of the auricle
  • Nodal tissue does not occupy the full thickness of the right atrial wall from epicardium to endocardium - it is a wedge of specialized subepicardial tissue within the sulcus terminalis
  • The excitation emanating from the sinuatrial node spreads to the atrial musculature and to the atrioventricular node through ordinary working atrial myocardium - there are no specialized internodal and interatrial conduction pathways

Location of the atrioventricular node: described by answers B or C
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Heart

Question: What is the rate of intrinsic automaticity that the SA node displays?
Explanation:
This is a question on the regulation of SA nodal pacemaker activity

 

Answer B is correct. SA node displays intrinsic automaticity at a rate of 100-110 depolarisations per minute.

 

But heart rate varies between 50-60 beats/min to over 200 beats/min. 

 

Changes in rate are primarily controlled by autonomic nerves acting on the SA node.
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Regulation of SA node

Question: At low resting heart rates, are vagal influences dominant over sympathetic influences? Or are sympathetic influences dominant over vagal influences? Or neither?
OptionA: At low resting heart rates, vagal influences are dominant over sympathetic influences
OptionB: At low resting heart rates, sympathetic influences are dominant over vagal influences
OptionC: At low resting heart rates, neither vagal influences or sympathetic influences are dominant
Explanation:
This is a question on the regulation of SA nodal pacemaker activity.

 

Answer A is correct: at low resting heart rates, vagal influences are dominant over sympathetic influences

  • Called vagal tone
  • SA nodal firing rate is increased by the autonomic nerves through 1) decreasing vagal tone 2) reciprocally increasing sympathetic activity on the SA node
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Regulation of SA node

Question: What is positive chronotropy?
OptionC: Increase in the strength of muscular contraction
OptionD: Reduction in the strength of muscular contraction
Explanation:
Answer B is correct. Increase in heart rate = positive chronotropic response

 

Answer A: reduction in heart rate = negative chronotropic response.

 

Answers C and D refer to cardiac inotropy or contractility.
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Regulation of SA node

Question: Which of the following muscles is not found in the posterior compartment of the leg?
Explanation:
B is correct - Fibularis brevis (and fibularis longus) are found within the lateral compartment of the leg exclusively. The other four muscles + soleus are situated within the posterior leg.

 

 

Link to Teach Me Anatomy: Muscles of the Lower Limb here

Question:
Autonomic influences can alter the rate of SA nodal pacemaker firing activity through three mechanisms:

 

1) Changing the slope of phase 4

2) Altering the threshold voltage for triggering phase 0

3) Altering the degree of hyperpolarization at the end of phase 3

 

These mechanisms work by increasing or decreasing the time to reach threshold. 

 

What autonomic influence increases the slope of phase 4 and lowers the threshold for the action potential?
OptionB: Release of acetylcholine at the SA node
Explanation:
Answer C is correct: sympathetic stimulation increases the firing rate (positive chronotropy) by increasing the slope of phase 4 and lowering the threshold for the action potential. (All the other answers, some of which are not even autonomic influences, would decrease the SA node firing rate). 

 

How?

  • Sympathetic adrenergic [releasing adrenalin (epinephrine) or similar substances] nerves release norepinephrine
  • Norepinephrine binds to β1-adrenoreceptors coupled to a stimulatory G-protein (Gs-protein)
  • This activates adenylyl cyclase and increases cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP)
  • If (pacemaker or funny current) is increased and L-type calcium channels open earlier
  • The combined effect increase the rate of depolarisation
  • Note that repolarization is also accelerated, which shortens over cycle length and may increase maximal hyperpolarization
Tags: Autonomic Nervous System, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Regulation of SA node

Question:
Autonomic influences can alter the rate of SA nodal pacemaker firing activity through three mechanisms:

  1. Changing the slope of phase 4
  2. Altering the threshold voltage for triggering phase 0
  3. Altering the degree of hyperpolarization at the end of phase 3

These mechanisms work by increasing or decreasing the time to reach threshold.

 

What autonomic influence acts through mechanism 1 by inhibiting funny currents?
OptionE: Release of norepinephrine by sympathetic adrenergic nerves
Explanation:
Answer A is correct: Vagal/parasympathetic stimulation. A decrease or increase in If would refer to mechanism 1 - changing the slope of phase 4. Inhibition of funny currents would decrease the slope of phase 4 - hence part of the negative chronotropic response from increasing vagal tone. 

 

Vagal stimulation decreases the slope of phase 4 (by inhibiting funny currents), hyperpolarizes the cell and increases the threshold voltage required to trigger phase 0. The pacemaker potential would take longer the reach threshold - therefore the pacemaker frequency is decreased & heart rate is slowed (negative chronotropy). Also the rate of repolarisation is reduced - contributing to increasing overall cycle length.  

 

How?

  • Vagal stimulation releases acetylcholine at the SA node
  • Acetylcholine binds to muscarinic receptors (M2)
  • Via the inhibitory G-protein (Gi-protein) cAMP is decreased
  • Moreover, acetylcholine activates KACh channels that hyperpolarizes the cell through increasing gK
Tags: Autonomic Nervous System, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Regulation of SA node

Question:
In addition to autonomic influences, nonneural mechanisms alter pacemaker activity.

 

Select the answer that decreases the SA node firing rate AND refers to the serum concentration of an ion.
Explanation:
Answer E is the correct answer. Changes in the SA nodal firing rate can be caused by changes in the serum concentration of ions. Hyperkalaemia induces bradycardia or may stop SA nodal firing. 

 

Factors that increase the SA firing rate:

  1. Symphatetic stimulation
  2. Muscarinic receptor antagonist
  3. β-adrenoreceptor agonists
  4. Circulating catecholamines (epinephrine or norepinephrine) cause tachycardia - similar mechanism to sympathetic stimulation
  5. Hypokalemia - causes tachycardia by increasing the rate of phase 4 depolarisation by decrease potassium conductance
  6. Hyperthyroidism - induces tachycardia
  7. Hyperthermia, fever

Factors that decrease the SA node firing rate:

 

  1. Vagal/parasympathetic stimulation 
  2. Muscarinic receptor agonists
  3. β-blockers
  4. Ischemia/hypoxia - depolarises the membrane potential. Causes bradycardia/abolition of pacemaker activity
  5. Hyperkalemia - induces bradycardia, may abolish pacemaker activity
  6. Sodium and calcium channel blockers. The latter induce bradycardia by inhibiting the L-type calcium channels - the slow inward Ca2+ currents during phase 4 and phase 0 are reduced
  7. Hypothermia
  8. Digoxin - induces bradycardia by increasing parasympathetic activity. Inhibits the sarcolemmal Na+/K+-ATPase - leads to depolarisation.
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Regulation of SA node

Question:
Action potentials are propagated through cardiac cells at different conduction velocities.

 

The answers below state the conduction velocities of different regions of the heart.

 

Select the conduction velocity for the AV node.
Explanation:
Answer B is correct.

 

Action potentials are generated by the SA node; & then cell-to-cell conduction spreads the action potentials throughout the atria

  • Depolarisation of the myocyte causes positive charges to accumulate just inside the sarcolemma
  • Ionic currents flow through low-resistance gap junctions at the intercalated discs
  • An action potential is elicited when the ionic currents are sufficient to depolarise the cell to its threshold potential
  • The action potential is propagated

Conduction velocities of different regions:

 

Atrial muscle = 0.5 m/sec

  • Some evidence of internodal tracts (e.g. Bachmann bundle) - specialised myocytes that act as atrial conducting pathways - but conduction in the atria is primarily through myocytes
  • Excitation-contraction coupling is initiated as the action potentials depolarise the atrial muscle

AV node = 0.05 m/sec

  • Located in the inferior-posterior region of the interatrial septum
  • The only normal pathway for action potentials to enter the ventricles since nonconducting connective tissue separates atria & ventricles
  • 1/10th of the atrial/ventricular myocyte velocity
  • Delay in conduction: 1) permits sufficient time for atrial depolarisation, contraction, & emptying of atrial blood prior to ventricular depolarisation and contraction 2) The frequency of impulses travelling through the AV node are limited - i.e. the preventing the negative consequences of atrial flutter and fibrillation on the ventricle

Bundle of His = 2 m/sec

  • At the base of the ventricle, where action potentials leave the AV node

Left & Right Bundle branches = 2 m/sec

  • The bundle branches allow the interventricular septum.
  • Action potentials are conducted at high velocity

Purkinje fibres = 4 m/sec

  • Formed from the division of the bundle branches
  • Action potentials are conducted at the highest velocity

Ventricular muscle = 0.5 m/sec

  • The final pathway for cell-to-cell conduction within the ventricles
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Heart, Cardiology

Question: How does autonomic activity decrease conduction velocity within the heart?
OptionA: Cellular hypoxia that decreases the availability of fast sodium channels
OptionD: Increased action of acetylcholine on M2 receptors via vagal nerves
Explanation:
Answer D is correct

 

This is a question on the regulation of conduction velocity. 

 

Intrinsic factors:

  • The electrical resistance between the cells
  • The nature of the action potential - especially the initial rate of depolarisation
  • Increased the number of activated fast sodium channels (responsible for the rapid upstroke velocity of nonpacemaker action potentials) increases the rate of depolarisation & hence the speed at which an adjoining cell depolarises
  • Decreased conduction velocity will occur from conductions that decrease the 1) availability of fast sodium channels (e.g. depolarisation caused by cellular hypoxia); 2) decrease the rate of phase 0; 3) decrease the magnitude of phase O
  • Slow inward calcium channels primarily determine phase O of the AV nodal action potential - so alterations in gCa will affect rate of depolarisation and hence rate of conductance between AV nodal cells

Extrinsic factors:

  • Increase in sympathetic firing or increased circulating catecholamines increases conduction velocity (via norepinephrine binding to β1-adrenoreceptors)
  • Activation of parasympathetic/vagal nerves decreases conduction velocity (via action of acetylcholine on M2 receptors). The AV node has a high degree of vagal innervation
  • Antiarrhythmic drugs that block fast sodium channels decrease nonnodal conduction velocity (upstroke velocity of phase 0 would be decreased since phase 0 of myocyte action potentials is generated by activation of fast sodium channels and the maximal degree of depolarisation would be decreased)
  • Digoxin activates vagal influences on the conduction system (esp AV node)
  • β-adrenoreceptor agonists increase conduction velocity; β-adrenoreceptor antagonists decrease conduction velocity
Tags: Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: Does the ECG measure absolute voltages or changes from a baseline voltage?
Explanation:
The ECG measures voltages changes from a baseline or isoelectric voltage.

 

Vertical calibration of the ECG = 1mV / cm

Paper recording peed = 25 mm/s
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: On the scalar electrocardiogram, what does the brief period after the P wave represent?
OptionC: Passage of impulse through the AV node
Explanation:
The brief isoelectric/zero voltage period after the P wave:

  • represents the time in which the atrial cells are depolarised and the impulse is travelling within the AV node. Conduction velocity is greatly reduced in the AV node.

The PR interval (more precisely, the P-Q interval):

  • Period of time from the onset of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex
  • Measure of the time from the onset of atrial depolarisation/activation to the onset of ventricular depolarisation/activation
  • Much of this time involves the passage of the impulse through the AV conduction system
  • Normally ranges from 0.12 to 0.20 seconds

If the duration of the PR interval is prolonged (>0.2 seconds):

  • There is a conduction defect (usually within the AV node)
  • Pathological mechanisms can be inflammatory, circulatory, pharmacological or nervous
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: What does the first wave of the ECG represent?
Explanation:
The first wave of the ECG is the P wave

  • It represents the wave of depolarisation that spreads from the SA node throughout the atria 

The normal duration of the P wave is:

  • 0.08-0.10 seconds
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: Select the answer which describes what the QRS complex represents AND states its normal duration (in seconds)
Explanation:
The QRS complex represents ventricular depolarisation

  • Ventricular depolarisation is rapid
  • The normal duration is 0.06-0.10 seconds


If the QRS complex is abnormally prolonged (>0.1 seconds):

  • Conduction is impaired within the ventricles
  • Causes of impairment: 1) defects in the normal conduction pathways (e.g. block of the left or right bundle branch) or aberrant conduction 3) ectopic foci (an ectopic ventricular pacemaker) drives ventricular depolarisation [impulses are then usually conducted over slower pathways > time for depolarisation is increased]
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: Select the answer that describes the ECG component that is particularly important in the diagnosis of ventricular ischemia.
OptionA: The wave that represents phase 3 of the ventricular action potential
OptionD: The component that represents the atrial depolarisation plus AV nodal delay
Explanation:
The ST segment is the isoelectric period following the QRS

  • During this period the ventricles are depolarised
  • Thus there is negligible potential difference in the ventricle - the segment will lie on the isoelectric line
  • Corresponds to the plateau phase of the ventricular action potential

In ventricular ischemia, the ST segment can become depressed or elevated


Why?

  • Nonuniform membrane potentials in ventricular cells will cause deviation from the isoelectric line indicating ischemic damage of the myocardium
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question:
The QRS complex represents ventricular depolarisation. The T wave represents ventricular repolarisation. 

 

In most leads, does the T wave deflect in the same direction from the isoelectric line as the major component of the QRS complex?
OptionA: In most leads, T waves are biphasic
OptionB: No, in most leads, the T wave does not follow the direction of the main QRS deflection
OptionC: Yes, in most leads, the T wave and major component of the QRS complex deviate in the same direction from the isoelectric line
Explanation:
• The T wave represents ventricular repolarisation (the return of the stimulated muscle to the resting state) or phase 3 of the action potential. Ventricular repolarisation also produces the U wave (represents the last remnants of the ventricular repolarisation)
  • Repolarization/phase 3 is caused by the closing of Ca2+ channels and the opening of K+ channels
  • The normal T wave is always negative in lead aVR but positive in lead II. Left-sided chest leads such as V4 to V6 normally always show a positive T wave
  • The T wave has a longer duration than the QRS complex: conduction of repolarisation does not utilise the high-velocity bundle branch and purkinje system

In most leads, the T wave follows the direction of the main QRS deflection (both being generally a positive deflection). This indicates that repolarisation proceeds in a direction counter to the depolarisation process.

 

 

Why?

  • Double negative: repolarization waves (negative signal) moving away from a positive recording electrode produces a positive voltage
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: What component of the ECG corresponds to the action potential duration and varies inversely with the heart rate?
Explanation:
• The QT interval represents the length of depolarisation and repolarisation and roughly corresponds to the action potential duration
  • Normal duration is between 0.20 to 0.40 seconds but its duration varies inversely with the heart rate: i.e. as the HR increases & the RR interval shortens, the QT interval normally shortens and vice versa. Why? 1) Direct effects of HR on action potential duration 2) neuroautonomic factors 
  • Represents the period of 'electrical systole' of the ventricles
  • Prolonged QT intervals can be diagnostic for susceptibility to certain types of arrhythmias
  • Note that the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the QRS to the end of the T wave

What is the corrected QT interval (QTc)?

  • Permits assessment of QT interval independent of HR
  • Divide the QT interval by the square root of the RR interval (that is, the interval between ventricular depolarisations)
  • (Note there are other formulas that have been proposed for calculating a rate-corrected QT interval)
  • QTc intervals are normally < 0.44 seconds
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology

Question: Select the answer that corresponds to sinus tachycardia
Explanation:
Answer A = sinus tachycardia

Answer B = sinus bradycardia

Answer C = normal sinus rhythm

 

Sinus rhythm:

  • Sinus rhythm is when the SA node is controlling the cardiac rhythm
  • There will be a consistent one-to-one correspondence between P waves and the QRS complex. Atrial depolarisation triggers ventricular depolarisation
  • Normal sinus rhythm ranges from 60 to 100 beats/min

Sinus bradycardia

  • Sinus rate of <60 beats/min
  • In many individuals will be a normal resting heart rate
  • Can result from depressed SA nodal function

Sinus tachycardia

  • Sinus rate of 100 to 180 beats/min
  • Abnormal at rest (normal when exercising/excited)
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiology, Cardiac rhythms

Question: What is the arrhythmia where the ventricular rate (as determined by the frequency of QRS complexes) can be less half of the atrial rate (as determined by the frequency of P waves)?
Explanation:
Atrial flutter is correct

 

  • Atrial rate is very high (250-350 beats/min)
  • Not all impulses are conducted through AV node
  • Ventricular rate is there much less than the atrial rate
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiac rhythms, Cardiology

Question: Name the dysrhythmia where no P waves are discernible
Explanation:
Answer B is correct = atrial fibrillation

  • Atrial depolarisations are not triggered by the SA node but depolarisations currents arise from other sites
  • No discernable P waves
  • F waves represent continuous irregular fluctuations of potential
  • The atria are unable to contribute to ventricular filling and do not contract and relax sequentially - atrial activity is continuous, uncoordinated, rippling
  • The ventricular rate is irregular since the pattern of AV conduction is irregular. No constant interval between QRS complexes. Irregular volume and rhythm of pulse since the strength of the ventricular contraction depends on the interval between beats
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiac rhythms, Cardiology

Question: How do local anaesthetics, such as Lignocaine, work?
OptionB: Upregulate the opening of Potassium channels to initiate repolarisation
OptionC: Increase the diameter of axons to lower the threshold
OptionD: Block Sodium channels and raise the threshold
OptionE: Decrease the diameter of an axon to lower the threshold
Explanation: D is correct- Raising the threshold means that a greater stimulus is required to instigate the opening of all the Sodium channels and cause the firing of an Action Potential. Local Anaesthetics can also work by blocking the Sodium channels opening, preventing the membrane potential from reaching the threshold and therefore blocking an AP from firing- no pain would therefore be felt following administering medication.

Question: Which of the following antibiotics is contraindicated in elderly people?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B, gentamicin. I like to remember this as "G" for geriatrics.

 

The reason for contraindication is reduced kidney function in elderly patients as the kidneys are one of the main methods of excretion of antibiotics. 

 

See antibiotic lecture for further details.

Question: Select the type of AV block where the consistent one-to-one correspondence remains between the P wave and QRS complexes
Explanation:
Answer A is correct

 

AV block is caused by depressed impulse conduction

 

First-degree AV block:

  • Conduction through AV block is delayed
  • Delayed impulse is able to excite the ventricles
  • Consistent one-to-one correspondence remains between the P wave and QRS complexes
  • PR interval >0.2 seconds (the time between the onset of atrial depolarisation and the onset of ventricular depolarisation)

Second-degree AV block

  • AV node does not conduct every impulse so not every atrial depolarisation will be followed by a ventricular depolarisation 
  • Two or three P waves may precede each QRS complex

Third-degree AV block

  • The AV node does not conduct atrial depolarisations
  • Secondary, latent pacemakers ensure the ventricles undergo depolarisation
  • Complete dissociation of P waves and QRS complexes
  • Ventricular bradycardia since the SA node has an higher intrinsic firing rate than the secondary, latent pacemakers
  • If the ectopic foci is within the ventricles the QRS complex will have abnormal shape & be wider (due to lack of use of normal conduction pathways)
Tags: ECG, Electrical activity of the heart, Cardiac, Cardiac rhythms, Cardiology

Question: What does PCSK9 do?
OptionA: Binds to LDL receptors on the liver and blocks LDL from binding
OptionB: Binds to LDL receptors on the liver triggering the uptake and digestion of them
OptionC: Binds to HDL and prevents it from collecting LDL and recycling it back to the liver
OptionD: Inhibits lipoprotein lipase preventing fatty acids and glycerol being extracted from chylomicrons
OptionE: Activates LDL receptors, promoting uptake of excess LDL
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

PCSK9 binds to LDL receptors on the liver and triggers the uptake of them by endocytosis. Lysosomes then digest the PCSK9 and the LDL receptor, decreasing the number of receptors expressed on the liver. This reduces LDL uptake and increases cholesterol in the blood. PCSK9 inhibitors prevent this occurring and are an effective treatment to reduce blood cholesterol.

Question: Which phase of a ventricular myocyte action potential is the ST segment on an ECG equivalent to?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D! 

During phase 2, there is no change in net membrane potential due to an efflux of K+ ions and a slow influx of Ca2+ ions causing a balance in charge, creating the plateau seen in phase 2 and the flat, isoelectric line seen as the ST segment. Eventually, the slow Ca2+ influx is exceeded by the K+ efflux, leading to the repolarisation phase which is phase 3.

Question: In ATP, what is the name of the bonds that attach the β and γ phosphoryl groups?
Explanation:
Adenosine triphosphate is an energy-coupling agent (not a fuel) & is produced by fuel oxidation & hydrolysed to drive a wide range of metabolic processes

  • Adenosine consists of a purine base (adenine) [a purine is a nitrogen-containing compound with a two-ring molecular structure] & a five-carbon sugar (ribose)
  • A phosphoester bond binds the initial phosphate group (α) to the sugar
  • Anhydride linkages (bonds that form between two phosphate groups) attach the two phosphate groups (β & γ)
  • Anhydride bonds a 'high-energy', unstable bonds; readily release the attached phosphate in a reaction coupled with another reaction
  • The terminal phosphate (Pi) is transferred by hydrolysis from ATP to another compound
  • Adenosine diphosphate (ADP) is left & energy released
  • Kinases catalyse phosphorylation reactions using ATP

Question: What is the term for the molecules involved in metabolism that transfer other groups between molecules?
Explanation:
Coenzymes are involved in metabolism and transfer other groups (e.g. two hydrogen groups or acyl groups) between molecules

 

NAD (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide) is involved in the transfer of two hydrogen groups from the oxidised form NAD+ to its reduced form NADH + H+

NADP (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate) is involved in the transfer of two hydrogen groups from the oxidised form NADP+ to its reduced form NADPH + H+

FAD (flavin adenine dinucleotide) is involved in the transfer of two hydrogen groups from the oxidised form FAD to its reduced form FADH2

 

 

CoA (coenzyme A) transfers acyl groups [CH3(CH2)nCO] from the oxidised form CoA to its reduced form acetyl-CoA

Question: Pantothenic acid is the parent molecule of which coenzyme that is derived from the B group of vitamins?
Explanation:
These coenzymes derive from the B group of vitamins

 

Parent molecules of the coenzymes featuring in the answers are:


NAD & NADP = the B vitamin, nicotinic acid / niacin. Nicotinic acid is a derivative of pyridine & interchangeable with its amide (nicotinamide). Nicotinamide is a component of the coenzymes NAD and NADP (its phosphate). Required in the diet; can by synthesised form the essential amino acid tryptophan. Deficiency causes pellagra: a nutritional disease common in maize-eating communities; symptoms: scaly dermatitis on exposed surfaces, diarrhoea, and depression. Good sources: meat, yeast extracts, pulses. RNI = 6.6 mg niacin equivalent/1000 kcal

 

 

FAD = riboflavin / vitamin B2. Water-soluble vitamin; present in most foods. Component of the flavin nucleotide coenzymes. Deficiency rare. 

 

CoA = the B vitamin, pantothenic acid. Constituent of coenzyme A. Important role in the transfer of acetyl groups in the body. Present in most foods.

Question: Which of the following statements regarding the femoral triangle is incorrect?
OptionA: Pectus femoris forms the lateral border of the triangle
OptionB: The femoral vein is the most medial blood vessel within the triangle
OptionC: The floor of the triangle is comprised of pectineus and iliopsoas
OptionD: The adductor canal continues from the apex of the femoral triangle
OptionE: Adductor longus forms the medial border of the femoral triangle
Explanation: A is correct, as sartorius forms the lateral border of the femoral triangle.

Question: Which layer of the epidermis is only present in areas of thick skin?
Explanation:
B is correct - the stratum lucidum is 2-3 additional layers of dead, keratinised cells found only in areas of thickened skin.

 

(+ note that stratum functionalis is found within the endometrium and is not a skin layer)

Question:
I am a layer of cells within the epidermis, its great to be here!

 

My cells' main role is to produce keratin to secure cells together. I am 8-10 cells thick.

 

 

Which epidermal layer am I?
Explanation:
D is correct

 

Stratum spinosum = keratinocytes

 

 

 

See University of Leeds Histology Guide

Question: Examine the diagram, which gland is which!?
Explanation:
C is correct

 

Summary:

Gland A = eccrine, sweat gland. Its a tubular gland within the hypodermis/ dermis that secretes directly onto skin.

Gland B = sebaceous, sebum gland. Its a spherical gland associated with a hair follicle

Gland C = likely to be apocrine gland. Its a non-branching and coiled gland which empties into a hair follicle - but higher up than a sebaceous gland.

Question: Why aren’t the auscultation sites directly over the position of the valves?
OptionA: Because the stethoscope listens to the flow of blood through the valves and placing directly on the valve would not allow for this
OptionB: Because if they were placed directly over the valve then the sound would be too quiet
OptionC: Because the exact positions of the valve are too difficult to access on a patient
OptionD: They are placed over the positions of the valves and this question is wrong
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

The stethoscope is placed on these auscultation sites as blood flows through the valves towards the stethoscope allowing us to hear the flow of the blood. 
The valve auscultation sites are:

Aortic- right 2nd intercostal space, parasternal 

Pulmonary- left 2nd intercostal space, parasternal 

Tricuspid- left 4/5th intercostal space, parastermnal 

Mitral- left 5th intercostal space in mid clavicular line, this is the apex beat

Question: Which of the following is not a vasodilator substance for coronary blood vessels?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

It is High H+ concentration that is a vasodilator substance 

A- hypoxia/low oxygen levels leads to a decrease in the production of ATP. ATP normally closes K+ATP channels and therefore, less ATP prevents the closure. This leads to the hyperpolarisation of the cell and prevents the opening of L type Ca2+ voltage gated channels. This reduces Ca2+ influx and decreases VSMC contraction, resulting in vasodilation

B- high carbon dioxide and high H+ blocks Ca2+ channels, reducing influx and causing vasodilation

D- High K+ causes opening of Kv outward rectifier channels causing hyperpolarisation. Less Ca2+ enters the cell resulting in VSMC relaxation 

E- High adenosine activates endothelial K+ ATP channels which leads to NO release which binds to a GPCR. This up regulates guanyl cyclase and increases cGMP production. cGMP switches on myosin light chain phosphatase and reduces VSMC contraction

There is a table with all of this which can be found in the cardiac physiology plenary slides on LC

Question: Which chamber of the heart would you find the infundibulum (also known as the conus arteriosus)?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

The infundibulum or the conus arteriosus is found in the right ventricle of the heart just before the pulmonary valve. It is a narrower portion of the right ventricle which opens into the pulmonary artery.

Question: The figure shows the general layout of fuel metabolism. The key has been removed. Select the answer which correctly describes processes 1, 2, 3, and 4.
Explanation:
Answer E is correct

 

Here are the ten processes listed in the key:

 

1 = glycogenolysis
2 = glycogenesis

 

3 = glycolysis
4 = gluconeogenesis

5 = pentose phosphate pathway

 

6 = fatty acid synthesis

7 = fatty acid oxidation

 

8 = tricarboxylic acid cycle 

 

9 = lipolysis

10 = triacylglycerol synthesis (esterification)

Question: From the answers below, select the molecule that is the common end-product of the metabolism of carbohydrates, fatty acids & amino acids
Explanation:
Acetyl residues/Acetyl-CoA (Answer D) is the common end-product of the catabolism of carbohydrates, fatty acids and amino acids.

 

The acetyl residues are further oxidised in a common pathway: the tricarboxylic acid cycle / citric acid cycle / Krebs cycle. The cycle begins when any of the three major metabolic precursors (pyruvate from carbohydrates, fatty acids from fats and amino acids from proteins) produce acetyl-CoA.

 

This provides free energy for the synthesis of ATP by the electron transfer chain (oxidative phosphorylation)

Question:
The molecule acetyl-CoA is present within the mitochondrion and in the cytosol. 

 

It has uses within the TCA cycle and in fatty acid synthesis.

 

Select the answer which correctly links the metabolic process to the intracellular location of acetyl-CoA.
OptionC:
TCA = mitochondrion & cytosol
Fatty acid synthesis = cytosol & mitochondrion
Explanation:
Answer B is correct.

 

  • All the enzymes involved in the TCA cycle lie within the mitochondrion
  • The TCA cycle is the metabolic engine in the mitochondria. Acetyl-CoA is oxidised to produce CO2 and reduced nucleotides
  • Acetyl-CoA cannot cross the inner mitochondrial membrane 
  • Therefore its use within the cycle is separated from its use in the cytosol (where it is involved in fatty acid synthesis)

Question:
The TCA cycle begins when major metabolic precursors produce acetyl-CoA.

 

Pyruvate from carbohydrates is actively transported by a carrier protein into the inner mitochondrial space or matrix. There it is decarboxylated to acetyl-CoA through the action of which enzyme?
Explanation:
Answer B is correct. 

  • Pyruvate dehydrogenase carboxylates pyruvate in the inner mitochondrial space to acetyl-CoA

Answer A refers pyruvate carboxylase. Pyruvate can be converted into oxaloacetate (note: also synthesised within the cycle) through the action of this enzyme - the reaction occurs in the liver in fasting. Pyruvate is then able to be channeled into glucose production rather than oxidation for energy by the liver.

 

Answers C and D refer to other enzymes used in the cycle.

Question: How are fatty acids able to be used in the TCA cycle?
Explanation:
Answer is correct. The process is fatty acid oxidation.

 

Fatty acids are broken down into two carbon fragments by β-oxidation at the beta carbon in the fatty acid chain. One FADH2 and one NADH molecule are produced.

 

The oxidised fatty acids attach to CoA. Transported through the mitochondrial membrane through special channels.

Question: What type of amino acids can only be metabolised into acetyl-CoA and derivatives?
Explanation:
Answer B is correct.

 

Glucogenic amino acids can be metabolised into pyruvate or other TCA cycle intermediates; and can be converted into glucose.

 

But ketogenic amino acids can only be metabolised into acetyl-CoA or derivates such as acetoacetate or acetoacetyl-CoA (ketone bodies). They cannot be converted into glucose. Note they do not necessarily produce ketone bodies.

Question:
Acetyl-CoA primes the start of the TCA cycle by combining with X molecule to form citrate (through the action of the enzyme citrate synthase). CoA is released. 

 

What is X?
Explanation:
Answer A is correct.

 

Acetyl CoA combines with oxaloacetate. Citrate is formed. CoA is released. The enzyme is citrate synthase (is the first enzyme used in the cycle).

Question:
Citrate from the combination of acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate is formed in the first reaction of the TCA cycle. Citrate is transformed into other molecules and then oxaloacetate is eventual regenerated.

 

How many enzyme reactions are there in the cycle?
Explanation: The cycle is a series of eight enzyme reactions that transform citrate.

Question: Early in the TCA cycle there are two oxidative decarboxylation reactions reducing what?
Explanation: NAD+ is reduced to form NADH in two oxidative decarboxylation reactions. CO2 is released. The second reaction forms succinyl-CoA, which has a high-energy thioester bond.

Question:
During the TCA cycle, molecule X is formed, which has a high-energy thioester bond. The hydrolysis of this bond conserves the energy by forming GTP (from GDP and Pi).

 

Name this molecule.
Explanation:
Answer C is correct. 

 

The reduction of NAD+ to form NADH leads to the formation of succinyl-CoA. The hydrolysis of its thioester bond forms one GTP molecule.

Question: In the TCA cycle, what is oxidised to from oxaloacetate, enabling the reduction of NAD+ to form NADH?
Explanation: Answer C is correct. In the final enzyme reaction in the cycle, malate is oxidised to oxaloacetate.

Question: Which of the following is false about atria auricles?
OptionC: They increase capacity when cardiac output increases
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Atria auricles/appendages are extensions of the atria that enable an increased capacity when cardiac output increases. Each atria has 1- left auricle and right auricle, not 2.

Question:
Intermediates in the TCA cycle may be used as substrates in other pathways.

 

Select the answer which correctly describes the use of the intermediates citrate, succinyl-CoA, and oxaloacetate.
OptionA:
Citrate = converted into aspartate

Succinyl-CoA = synthesis of haem

Oxaloacetate = fatty acid synthesis
OptionB:
Citrate =fatty acid synthesis
Succinyl-CoA = converted into aspartate
Oxaloacetate = synthesis of haem
OptionC:
Citrate = fatty acid synthesis
Succinyl-CoA = synthesis of haem
Oxaloacetate = converted into aspartate
Explanation:
Citrate = fatty acid synthesis

  • Only in the liver if there is plentiful glucose supply - i.e. the concentration of citrate will determine whether it will be oxidised in the cycle or converted into fat synthesis

Succinyl-CoA = synthesis of haem

Oxaloacetate = converted into aspartate. Various uses:

  • manufacture of amino acids and nucleic acids
  • supply of one of the amino acids incorporated into urea (in the urea cycle)
  • synthesis of glucose by the liver in fasting (gluconeogenesis)

Question: A patient comes to you with a painful eye. Upon examination they have flame haemorrhages, cotton wool spots and papilloedema. What has this patient presented with symptoms of?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

These are all symptoms of hypertensive retinopathy caused by untreated hypertension. The high pressure results in microvascular damage to vessels in the eye, causing blood to leak and flame haemorrhages/red patches to appear. The high pressure can also cause the optic disc to bulge outwards and papilloedema reflects the high intracranial pressures. This is a serious condition where the patient should be admitted to hospital and their blood pressure managed. This is from the hypertension treatments lightbulb on LC.

Question:
There are many important vitamins in our diet, the largest group being the B vitamins.

 

Which member of this group is necessary for the production of neurotransmitters Serotonin, Dopamine and Noradrenaline?
Explanation:
Vitamin B6 - Pyridoxine  is responsible for the formation of Serotonin, Dopamine and Noradrenaline

It is a coenzyme in amino acid, glucose and lipid metabolism and forms some Decarboxylases. Pyridoxine also helps make red blood cells 

 

 

For clarity: Riboflavin = B2, Niacin = B3, Pantothenic acid = B5, Pyridoxine = B6, Biotin = B7

Question:
There are many important vitamins in our diet, the largest group being the B vitamins.

 

Which member of this group is a precursor for Coenzyme A?
Explanation:
Answer D is correct

 

B5 - Pantothenic acid is a precursor to Coenzyme A and is widespread in foods. 

 

 

For clarity: Thiamine = B1, Riboflavin = B2, Niacin = B3, Pantothenic acid = B5, Pyridoxine = B6

Question: The dermis is split into the papillary layer layer and the reticular layer. The papillary layer is where the dermal papillae are located and is approximately 20% of the dermis. The reticular layer is made up of a type of connective tissue. What connective tissue is it composed of?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

The reticular layer is composed of dense irregular connective tissue which is different from the papillary layer which is composed of loose connective tissue. The reticular layer provides the skin with strength and elasticity

Question: A patient comes in with sustained hypertension and you conduct some investigations. These find the patient has bilateral renal artery stenosis. What type of hypertension is this?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

Secondary hypertension is caused by an underlying, pathological cause, an example being bilateral renal artery stenosis. This disease causes hypovolaemia detection by the kidneys and triggers the renin angiotensin system. Renin is released which converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I and ACE from the lungs converts angiotensin I to angiotensin II. Angiotensin II causes aldosterone release and vasoconstriction. Aldosterone increases water and salt reabsorption in the kidney. These increase blood pressure and result in hypertension.

 

Primary hypertension is often idiopathic and can have a familial link. This accounts for 95% of cases and risk can be reduced by modifying lifestyle factors.

Question: What nerve innervates the superficial posterior compartment of the leg?
What nerve innervates the anterior compartment of the leg?
What nerve innervates the posterior compartment of the thigh?
What nerves innervates semitendinosus muscle?

Which areas of the heart does this artery supply?

OptionD: Right atrium, SA and AV nodes and the posterior part of the interventricular septum (IVS).
OptionE: Right atrium, right ventricle and the interventricular septum (IVS).

The right coronary artery supplies the right ventricle, the SA and AV nodes and the posterior part of the IVS. (D)

Question: Troponin T is a cardiac biochemistry marker measured in clinical practice. Elevated troponin levels would be seen in patients who had which of the following?
Explanation: The correct answer is C!

Question: Diltiazem is an example of what type of medication?
Explanation:
Diltiazem is a calcium channel blocker

 

These work by lowering the amount of calcium ions entering cardiac cells and blood vessel walls. This prevents the heart from contracting as strongly.

Question:
Doris is an 87 year old lady who has come into surgery with suspected angina pectoris. You take her blood pressure which shows to be 130/85.

 

Using this data, calculate her mean arterial pressure.
Explanation:
This is a mean question, I didn't put the equation in because you never know what will come up in the exam!

 

(1/3 x systolic pressure) + (2/3 x diastolic pressure)

Question:
Damien is a 50 year old male patient who presents at the clinic with symptoms of heart failure. Through a series of tests you find the following data:

 

Left ventricle

End diastolic volume (EDV) = 110 mL

Residual volume (RV) = 70 mL

 

Use this data to work out the ejection fraction of the left ventricle
Explanation:
A bit of a mean question as I didn't give much data - in order to work out the ejection fraction we must first work out the stroke volume:

 

Stroke volume (SV) = EDV - RV

 

In this case, SV = 40 mL

 

 

Ejection fraction = SV/EDV x 100

 

(40/110) x 100 = 36.4%

 

A normal ejection fraction would be around 60%.

Question: which regions are supplied by the left anterior descending artery in the heart?
OptionB: left and right ventricles, anterior 2/3 of interventricular septum
Explanation:
B is correct!

 

the left anterior descending artery (LAD) arises from the left coronary artery. 

 

https://teachmeanatomy.info/thorax/organs/heart/heart-vasculature/  contains a nice table summarising where each coronary artery supplies blood to.

Question: Which factor decreases the afterload of the left ventricle?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Afterload is the resistance the left ventricle must overcome to circulate blood. 
It is increased in:

  • Hypertension- LV needs to work harder to pump blood into aorta 
  • Vasoconstriction- increased vascular resistance 
  • Aortic valve stenosis- narrowing of aortic valve causing LV to have to work harder to pump blood into aorta

Mitral valve regurgitation decreases the afterload as the blood in the ventricle has 2 exits- the aortic valve into the aorta and the mitral valve back into the atria. This website has some helpful explanations and diagrams https://www.cvphysiology.com/Heart%20Disease/HD009c

Question: The image shown is a histological slide of a uterus with 3 layers labeled (A, B & C). Label the 3 layers.
Explanation:
D is the correct answer!

 

This is just something that you have to learn unfortunately. To learn these names, think of their prefixes. Endometrium where endo is latin for inside or within. This layer is the internal layer of the uterus. You can also learn the position of the para/perimetrium by its prefix, peri which means around or perimeter.

Question: Nicorandil is an angina treatment which works in 2 ways. Which 2 ways does it work?
OptionA:
Stimulates guanyl cyclase which increases cGMP. cGMP causes smooth muscle relaxation

Inhibits the Na+/K+ inward funny current, slowing sino-atrial node phase 4, reducing automacity and impulse frequency
OptionB:
Inhibits the Na+/K+ inward funny current, slowing sino-atrial node phase 4, reducing automacity and impulse frequency
Blocks Ca2+ ion entry by binding to L type voltage gated ion channels
OptionC:
Blocks Ca2+ ion entry by binding to L type voltage gated ion channels

Stimulates guanyl cyclase which increases cGMP. cGMP causes smooth muscle relaxation
OptionD:
Stimulates guanyl cyclase which increases cGMP. cGMP causes smooth muscle relaxation
Activates K+ effluxer causing hyperpolarisation and preventing Ca2+ Voltage gated channels from opening
OptionE:
Activates K+ effluxer causing hyperpolarisation and preventing Ca2+ Voltage gated channels from opening

Blocks Ca2+ ion entry by binding to L type voltage gated ion channels
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Nicorandil:

  • Stimulates guanyl cyclase which increases cGMP. cGMP causes smooth muscle relaxation
  • Activates K+ effluxer causing hyperpolarisation and preventing Ca2+ Voltage gated channels from opening, reducing contraction of the myocardium and reducing myocardial oxygen demand 

Ivabradine:

  • Inhibits the Na+/K+ inward funny current, slowing sino-atrial node phase 4, reducing automacity and impulse frequency

These are alternative treatments to Angina.

Question:
Mrs Dankworth has been admitted to A&E with chest pains. You take a history and find the following:

  • She is a 40 year old female
  • BMI shows she is obese
  • Non-localised crushing chest pain, not radiating anywhere, random occurrence at rest
  • Family history of hypercholesterolaemia, you observe corneal arcus around her iris

You decide to do some tests:

 

ECG - ST depression

Cardiac markers - negative for troponins

Blood pressure - 180/95

 

What is the most likely diagnosis for Mrs Dankworth?
Explanation:
The most likely diagnosis would be unstable angina.

 

In unstable angina, you would expect the following:

- Chest pain at rest

- No cardiac troponins present

- ST depression on ECG

 

Blood pressure was given as this is a risk factor for acute coronary syndrome

 

Unstable angina and NSTEMI can be confused because NSTEMIs can also cause ST-depression

However in an NSTEMI you would observe the presence of cardiac troponins

 

A STEMI would present with ST elevation and troponins in the blood

Question: What is the PO2 of moist inspired air?
Explanation:
Answer A = 47 mm Hg is the water vapour pressure of moist inspired gas (which is fully saturated with water vapour), at body temperature

Answer B = is correct. 149 mm Hg is the PO2 of moist inspired air

Answer C = 40 mm Hg is the alveolar PCo2

Answer D = 760 mm Hg is the barometric pressure at sea level

Answer E = 100 mm Hg is the alveoli PO2

 

PO2 of moist inspired air:

  • PO2 falls during the transport from air to the alveoli and then to the tissues
  • The PO2 of air is 20.93% of total dry gas pressure
  • The PO2 of inspired air is (20.93/100) x (760-47) = 149 mm Hg

PO2 of alveolar gas:

  • PO2 falls by one-third, to 100 mm Hg, in the alveoli

The alveolar PO2 is determined by:

  • the rate of removal of O2 by the pulmonary capillary blood (i.e. tissue metabolic demands or O2 consumption)
  • the rate of replenishment of O2 by alveolar ventilation. The rate of alveolar ventilation primarily determines the alveolar PO2 since under resting conditions the rate of removal of O2 is stable
  • The tissue PO2 varies but can be 1 mm Hg. Pulmonary gas exchange determines tissue PO2

Question:
Mrs Jones, a female 56 year old patient presents at your GP surgery. She recently underwent surgery in which an intramuscular buttock injection was required. She explains that since her operation, her "hip hasn't been right".

 

You ask her to stand on each leg in turn. When she stands on her right leg, nothing abnormal is observed. However, when she stands on her left leg, her pelvis drops on the contralateral side. 

 

What is the most likely explanation for this presentation?
Explanation:
Mrs Jones has damaged her Superior Gluteal nerve. This nerve provides innervation to the muscles Gluteus medius and minimus, which provide stability to the pelvis by contracting when the opposite leg is raised. If the Superior Gluteal nerve is damaged, both muscles will be paralysed. When the patient is asked to stand on one leg, pelvic drop is observed on the leg that is raised. This is called the Trendelenburg sign.

 

There are several ways the Superior Gluteal nerve can be damaged. For example, dislocation of the hip joint, hip fractures and intramuscular buttock injections.

Question:
Mr Taylor has been rushed to A&E by paramedics after waking up in the middle of the night with severe chest pain.

 

You are the FY1 doctor on duty working the night shift and must see to this patient. You take a history and find the following:

  • Severe crushing chest pain
  • Pain gets worse when lying down and is relieved by leaning forward
  • Cough
  • Recently discharged from hospital following a gastrointestinal viral infection

After ordering some tests you find the following information:

 

ECG - ST-elevation of all leads (diffuse ST-elevation)

Cardiac troponins - normal

 

It is clear more tests are required, however after you discover this information, what is the likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
It would most likely be pericarditis.

 

One of the main factors here is that the chest pain is relieved by leaning forward - this is because it reduces pressure on the pericardium

Pericarditis often shows as ST elevation on all leads of the ECG.

 

Differentiating between a STEMI and pericarditis would be down to the number of leads of ST-elevation and the fact there are no cardiac troponins present for pericarditis.

 

Pericarditis can be caused by many things:

- Bacterial or viral infection

- Systematic illness

- Dressler syndrome

 

For viral pericarditis it is normally related to a gastrointestinal infection.

Question:
Hypoxaemia is the abnormally low PO2 in arterial blood.

 

Common causes of hypoxaemia include hypoventilation, diffusion limitation, shunt, and ventilation-perfusion inequality. These four common causes are described in the answers.

 

Of these, select the most common cause of hypoxaemia.
OptionA: Mismatched ventilation and blood flow in regions of the lung
OptionB: Depression of PO2 caused by incomplete diffusion at the blood-gas barrier
OptionC: Blood which enters the arterial system without passage through ventilated areas of the lung
Explanation: Ventilation-perfusion inequality (Answer A) is a more common cause of hypoxaemia than hypoventilation (D), diffusion limitation (B) and shunt (C)

Question: You are a year 3 medical student on a placement in the emergency department. A young patient presents with an abrasion on their forearm. They are interested in medicine so ask you what the healing process of the abrasion will be. You respond by telling them which 4 step wound healing process?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C 

1. Haemostasis- platelets form a soft clot to initially stop the bleeding and produce a temporary barrier to prevent the open wound from being infected.
2. Inflammation- PAMPs (pathogen associated molecular patterns) and DAMPs (damage associated molecular patterns) recognised by the dendritic cells and macrophages. Robust inflammatory response to remove necrotic threat and set the stage for wound healing. If pathogens are present this can lead to an adaptive immune response (T and B cells). Wound healing can only continue once wound is sterile. 
3. Proliferation wound is rebuilt with new granulation tissue (mix of collagen and other ECM). Split into 2 stages

A: Granulation - fibroblasts move to the wound and produce collagen and elastin in the wound site, forming connective skin tissue to replace damaged tissue.

B: Revascularisation - A new network of blood vessels develop (stimulated by vascular endothelial growth factor VEGF) to deliver oxygen and nutrients required by the fibroblasts. 
4. Remodelling - Newly formed collagen is rearranged and converted from type III to type I. This type of collagen strengthens the wound, dermis contract by 40-80%, pulling the wound edges together and closing the wound.
Tags: Wound healing, Wounds, Blunt Force Trauma, CBL, Case 1

Question: A woman presents to the A&E department with SOB, chest pain and a low blood pressure. After running some tests the doctor diagnoses a pulmonary embolism. The doctor is concerned as the patient is on warfarin (taken as an anticoagulant) due to previous issues with blood clots. On further conversation the doctor asks the patient if they have stopped taking their medication to which they say they still take it. The patient later reveals that they have altered their diet recently to try and lead a healthier lifestyle. They indicate that they now have 3 spinach, kale and apple smoothies per day and try to have sprouts or broccoli with as many meals as possible. What is it about these foods that could have caused a pulmonary embolus even with the patient on warfarin?
OptionA: They are high vitamin C and iron which boosts the absorption of iron increasing the RBC concentration in the blood
OptionB: They are high in vitamin K and prothrombin is a vitamin K-dependent protein
OptionC: They are high in vitamin C which can contraindicate the warfarin medication
OptionD: Being high in Vitamin K means that they increase prothrombin production and can cause further coagulation of the blood as it helps with conversion of clotting factors to their mature form.
Explanation: Prothrombin is a vitamin K-dependent protein, even though the patient is on warfarin they have rapidly and SUDDENLY increased the consumption of vitamin K leading to a rapid increase in prothrombin production causing unintended consequential clotting of the blood hence the pulmonary embolus. The doctor would need to prescribe an alternative anti-coagulant that has no food-drug interactions.

Question:
The presence of too many osteoclasts in comparison to osteoblasts leads to osteoporosis. 

What are the stages of osteoclastgenesis?
OptionA: Mesenchymal stem cell > monocyte > macrophage > osteoclast precursor > osteoclast
OptionB: Hematopoietic stem cell > monocyte > osteoblast > osteoclast precursor > osteoclast
OptionC: Hematopoietic stem cell > monocyte > macrophage > osteoclast precursor > osteoclast
OptionD: Mesenchymal stem cell > monocyte > osteoblast > osteoclast precursor > osteoclast
OptionE: Hematopoietic stem cell > macrophage > monocyte > osteoclast precursor > osteoclast
Explanation:
C is correct 

 

M-CSF triggers a Hematopoietic stem cell to differentiate into a monocyte. M-CSF then further triggers the formation of a macrophage from the monocyte. Many macrophages gather together and RANK ligand combines them hence osteoclasts are multinucleate. RANK L is expressed by osteoblasts. M-CSF and RANKL trigger the formation of an osteoclast precursor from the macrophages. M-CSF and RANKL fuses several osteoclast precursors together to finally form a multinucleate osteoclast.
Tags: bone healing, Bones, CBL, Case 1, Case One

Question: In the TCA cycle, what enzyme catalyses the oxidation of X molecule to fumarate, enabling the reduction of FAD to FADH2?
Explanation:
The enzyme succinate dehydrogenase is involved in the oxidation of succinate to fumarate. The reduction of flavin adenine dinucleotide to FADH2 is enabled.

 

Note by contributor: answer D originally specified flavoprotein, which is in fact a subunit of the SDH enzyme complex (see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Succinate_dehydrogenase), and has been changed in response to feedback - thanks!

Question:
Hypoventilation is the reduced ventilation of the lungs due to reduced breathing-rate and tidal volume. 

 

Hypoventilation is a cause of hypoxaemia and also affects the PCO2.

 

Using the alveolar ventilation equation, describe the effect on PCO2 (once a steady state has been established) if the alveolar ventilation is halved.
Explanation:
• Hypoventilation always causes increases in alveolar and arterial PCO2 (i.e. hypoventilation is a cause of hypercapnia - CO2 retention)
  • Alveolar and arterial PO2 falls with hypoventilation. However, inspiration of an enriched O2 mixture compensates for the reduced flow of inspired oxygen and reverses hypoxaemia 

The alveolar ventilation equation can show the relationship between alveolar ventilation and PCO2

  • The alveolar ventilation equation is: V̇A = V̇CO2 / PCO2 x K
  • V̇CO2 is the CO2 production; V̇A is the alveolar ventilation
  • Rearrange to: PCO2 = V̇CO2 / V̇A x K
  • Thus, answer B is correct: the alveolar and arterial PCO2 will be doubled, if V̇A is halved (assuming that CO2 production does not change)
  • The equation allows arterial PCO2 to determine alveolar ventilation

Causes of hypoventilation include:

  • Damage to the chest wall
  • Paralysis of respiratory muscles
  • Depression of the central respiratory drive (e.g. by morphine or barbiturates)
  • High resistance to breathing (e..g very dense gas at depth)
  • Morbid obesity (central respiratory drive, respiratory mechanics)

Question:
Hypoventilation causes a fall in PO2 & a rise in PCO2.

 

If alveolar ventilation is then increased in response, will alveolar PCO2 or alveolar PO2 take longer to come to equilibrium?
OptionA: Both will take the same time to come to equilibrium
OptionB: The PCO2 will take longer to come to equilibrium
OptionC: The PO2 will take longer to come to equilibrium
Explanation:
Answer B is correct.

  • There are greater CO2 stores in the body (HCO3- in the blood & interstitial fluid) than O2 stores in the body

Question: In an individual with abnormal diffusion capacity (due to lung disease), would incomplete diffusion/diffusion disequilibrium typically occur at rest causing hypoxaemia?
Explanation:
Diffusion limitation is one of the causes of hypoxaemia but answer A is likely the best answer

 

Diffusion limitation is measured by the PO2 difference between alveolar gas & end-capillary blood. In normal subjects, the PO2 difference is very small & there is nearly complete diffusion equilibrium. This is because the time needed for equilibration between alveolar and capillary oxygen is much less than the transit time of RBCs in the pulmonary capillary network. Incomplete diffusion or diffusion disequilibrium is unlikely even during exercise despite the large reduction in time available for oxygenation of the RBCs - i.e. no fall in end-capillary PO2 is observed. 

 

This typically remains so even in individuals with thickening of the blood-gas barrier/alveolar capillary block, at rest. But these patients may show evidence of changes in arterial blood gas during exercise (mechanism as above), or when the alveolar PO2 is lowered by inhaling low O2 or by high altitude. Slower oxygenation occurs with lowered alveolar O2 since a) the partial pressure difference that drives O2 across the blood-gas barrier is reduced and b) the slope of the O2 dissociation curve is much steeper with lower PO2 affecting loading of O2.

Question:
Type II pneumocytes are an important functional component of the alveolus in the lungs. They secrete surfactant which aids in gaseous exchange.

 

What type of epithelial cell are type II pneumocytes comprised of?
Explanation:
Type II pneumocytes are made of cuboidal epithelium.

 

Type I pneumocytes are made of squamous epithelium.

Question:
A patient is suspected to have hypoxaemia. The patient is given 100% O2 to inspire but the arterial PO2 does not rise as much as expected and the hypoxaemia is not abolished.

 

Of the common causes of hypoxaemia, which cause of hypoxaemia is most likely in this patient?
Explanation:
Answer C - blood shunted into the arterial system without transit through the ventilated areas of the lung - is the correct answer. 

 

Why is the hypoxaemia not abolished?

  • The shunted blood depresses the arterial O2 concentration and would not be affected by higher alveolar PO2 with the increase in the inspired O2 concentration
  • But, arterial PO2 will still rise since the blood that passes through the ventilated alveoli will be exposed to the higher alveolar PO2. The oxygen dissociation curve is nearly flat when the PO2 is high so therefore shunted blood with low O2 concentration will continue to depress arterial PO2. Thus, there may be a rise in arterial PO2 is but the rise is less than expected.

Supplementary question: would you expect the shunt to cause a rise in arterial PCO2?

  • No. PCO2 of shunted blood is high but chemoreceptors respond to increased arterial PCO2 by increasing ventilation and arterial PCO2 may even become abnormally low

Question: Regional hypoxia is beneficial as it  will divert blood to an area of the lung that is better ventilated. However generalized hypoxia can be dangerous . Which of the following is NOT a result of generalized hypoxia ?
Explanation:
D- D is correct. When there is generalized hypoxia , there is GLOBAL vasoconstriction.

 

A- Pulmonary edema occurs in very high altitudes. At these altitudes, generalized hypoxia occurs and so there is global vasoconstriction. This causes an increase in pulmonary vascular resistance. The heart will work harder to overcome this resistance , but this will lead to over-perfusion , stress failure and consequent movement of fluid from the vessels into the alveoli - Pulmonary edema 

 

B- This happens in very severe cases of COPD and PF . There is generalized hypoxia leading to global vasoconstriction, and this rise in pressure will cause pulmonary hypertension. To overcome the increase in Pulmonary resistance the right ventricle will pump harder. However, this will lead to  hypertrophy of the chamber and eventual failure- Right ventricular failure 

 

C- as mentioned above generalized hypoxia will lead to global vasoconstriction which causes the pressure to rise and so leads to pulmonary hypertension

 

E- as mentioned above Pulmonary hypertension will lead to overall increased pulmonary vascular resistnace .

Question:
You are an FY1 doctor and have just started the night shift in the ICU.

 

You take a look at the notes of the patients who have recently been admitted and you observe the following arterial blood gases (ABGs) of Mr Smith, a 69 year old male patient:

 

(Square brackets indicate normal values)

  • PH = 7.20                              [7.35 - 7.45]
  • pCO2 = 7.8 kPa                    [4.5 - 6.0]
  • pO2 = 8 kPa                          [11.0 - 13.0]
  • cHCO3- = 32 mmol/L            [22.0 - 28.0]

Using these values, what is the likely diagnosis for Mr Smith?
Explanation:
Correct answer is respiratory acidosis

Explanation:

  • pH is lower than normal, indicating acidosis
  • pCO2 is higher than normal
  • pO2 is lower than normal
  • Bicarbonate is higher than normal

 

What makes it respiratory acidosis?

  • The higher pCO2 has pushed the equilibrium to the right, meaning more H+ is produced
  • The increase in H+ causes a decrease in pH
  • The kidney which controls bicarbonate reabsorption has tried to compensate for this change by increasing bicarbonate in order to shift the equilibrium back
  • The pO2 is lower than normal which suggests the patient is suffering from respiratory failure, in this case it would be type II failure due to the patient being hypercapnic

Still confused? I found this video very helpful!
Tags: Acid base balance, Case 3, lung function, lungs

Question: If the ventilation-perfusion ratio is increased above normal in a single lung unit, what is the effect on the PO2 and PCO2 in the lung unit?
OptionA:
The alveolar PO2 rises

AND

The alveolar PCO2 rises
OptionB:
The alveolar PO2 falls 

AND
The alveolar PCO2 falls
OptionC:
The alveolar PO2 rises
AND
The alveolar PCO2 falls
OptionD:
The alveolar PO2 falls
AND
The alveolar PCO2 rises
OptionE:
The alveolar PO2 remains the same
AND
The alveolar PCO2 remains the same
Explanation:
The ventilation-perfusion ratio or the matching of ventilation to blood flow in regions of lung determines the concentration of any gas present in the lung unit & therefore the gas exchange in any lung unit.

 

Ventilation adds O2 and perfusion removes O2. Ventilation removes CO2 and perfusion adds CO2.

 

Obstructing blood flow increases the ventilation-perfusion ratio.  Alveolar PO2 rises (the PO2 of inspired air is higher than the PO2 of mixed venous blood). Alveolar PCO2 falls (the PCO2 of inspired air is essentially 0 and therefore much lower than the PCO2 of mixed venous blood). The ratio will be infinity if blood flow stops completely. If so, the alveolar PO2 and CO2, and end-capillary PO2 and CO2, will be the same as the PO2 and PCO2 of inspired gas. 

 

Obstructing ventilation decreases the ventilation-perfusion ratio in the lung unit. Alveolar PO2 falls and alveolar CO2 rises. Note that the relative changes of alveolar PO2 and alveolar CO2 will be determined by the ventilation-perfusion equation. The ratio will be 0 if ventilation is stopped completely. If so, alveolar PO2 and CO2, and end-capillary PO2 and CO2, will be the same as the PO2 and PCO2 of mixed venous blood. 

 

The question states that the ventilation-perfusion ratio increases above normal. As the ventilation-perfusion ratio is increased, alveolar PO2 rises and alveolar PCO2 falls. Answer C is correct.

Question:
Both ventilation and blood flow is greater at the bottom of the lung than at the top of the lung. 

 

The ventilation-perfusion ratio also decreases down the lung. Using this fact, state whether the differences in blood flow between top and bottom of the lung is greater or lesser than the differences in ventilation between top and bottom of the lung.
Explanation:
Answer A is correct - both ventilation and blood flow decrease from bottom to top of the lung but the blood flow decreases much more rapidly. This means that the ventilation-perfusion ratio is very high at the top of the lung due to the low amount of blood flow. 

 

Consequently, alveolar PO2 is higher at the apex of the lung than the base. Alveolar PCO2 is higher at the base of the lung than the apex, but the difference is smaller than the difference between alveolar PO2 between the apex and the base.

 

The apex contributes little to overall O2 uptake but is able to contribute more during exercise when perfusion to the apex increases.

 

The respiratory exchange ratio (CO2 output/O2 uptake) is higher at the apex as well.

Question:
The answers below list mechanisms for why uneven ventilation and blood flow in the lungs depresses the arterial PO2.

 

Select the answer which is false.
OptionA: A greater proportion of blood flow is directed at areas of the lung where the alveolar PO2 is low
OptionB: Nonlinear shape of the oxygen dissociation curve means that the oxygen added by the units with a high ventilation-perfusion ratio cannot substitute for the lower amounts of oxygen added by units with a low ventilation-perfusion ratio
OptionC: Most of the end-capillary blood is sourced from the poorly oxygenated apex
Explanation:
The two mechanisms for why uneven ventilation and blood flow depresses arterial PO2 are:

1) Answer B: The nonlinear shape of the oxygen dissociation curve means that the oxygen added by the units with a high ventilation-perfusion ratio cannot substitute for the lower amounts of oxygen added by units with a low ventilation-perfusion ratio. 

2) Answer A: Greater flow is directed at the poorly oxygenated base

 

Answer C is wrong since it is the base that is poorly oxygenated and which receives the major share of the blood.

Question:
Mismatching ventilation and blood flow impairs gas exchange and causes hypoxaemia and hypercapnia.

 

But increasing ventilation to the alveoli can eliminate one of these. Select the correct answer.
OptionC: In fact, increases in ventilation can eliminate both hypoxaemia and hypercapnia that results from ventilation-perfusion inequality
Explanation:
Hypercapnia results from VA/Q inequality since units with excessive ventilation/high ventilation-perfusion ratios are inefficient at eliminating CO2 (and make up the alveolar dead space)

 

Answer B is correct. Hypercapnia/CO2 retention can be eliminated by increased ventilation.

 

How is ventilation increased in hypercapnia?

  • Chemoreceptors sense increased CO2 retention & increase the ventilatory drive. 

How does this eliminate hypercapnia?

  • The increased ventilation typically ensures normal arterial PCO2, since, with the CO2 dissociation curve essentially linear in the working range, units with both low and high ventilation-perfusion ratios will be able to raise CO2 output with increased ventilation. 

But, the shape of the O2 dissociation curve means that hypoxaemia cannot be eliminated with increased ventilation. Units with low or high ventilation-perfusion ratios will not benefit from increased ventilation (but units with modestly low ratios will).
Tags: Ventilation-perfusion inequality, Hypercapnia, Hypoxaemia, Respiratory physiology

Question:
Dave a 50 year old patient comes into A and E following a checkup from his GP, his GP was concerned about the following symptoms below 

 

- Extreme pain in the chest when exercising and resting that radiates to his left arm 

- Pain is not eased using his Prescribed GTN spray 

- Raised troponin levels after a blood test 

- Abnormal 12 lead ECG showing st elevations 

 

What is the GP concerned about and to confirm the diagnosis what investigations would the A and E team take.
OptionA:
- unstable angina 

- caused by full occlusion of a coronary arteries 

- The doctors should take an urgent MRI
OptionB:
- Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction

- This is an example of a transmural infarct caused by a full occlusion of a coronary artery 

- The patient should undergo an urgent angiophraphy
OptionC:
- -ST segment elevation myocardial infarction

- This is an example of a subendocardial infarct 

- The patient should undergo an urgent CT Scan
OptionD:
- Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction

- This is an example of a subendocardial infarct caused by partial occlusion of a coronary artery 

- the patient should undergo an urgent MRI
OptionE:
- ST segment elevation myocardial infarction

- This is an example of a transmural infarct caused by a full occlusion of a  coronary arteries 

- The patient should undergo an urgent angiography
Explanation:
E is the correct answer, The symptoms dave is experiencing are all signs of an STEMI ( ST segment elevation myocardial infarction ) -  This rules out A B and D 

 

This is due to a full blockage (occlusion) of a major coronary artery causing there to be a mismatch of oxygen demand and oxygen supply in the the whole thickness of the cardiac tissue causing the cardiac muscle cells to die (and subsequently causing the troponin levels to be elevated) , this is known as a transmural infarct, - this rules out option C leaving you with option E

 

A Subendocardial infarct is present in an NSTEMI - Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction , this is where the only part of the thickness of cardiac tissue is affected 

 

The most appropriate method of confirming this diagnosis is for the patient to undergo an urgent Angiogram in a Cath Lab where they can identify where the occlusion is and then place a stent in place to re-vascularise the area of tissue - MRIs are not appropriate in this case 

 

GTN sprays is an example of a nitric oxide spray that aims to dilate the coronary arteries and to increase the flow of blood that supplies the cardiac tissue, it works by hyper polarising the vascular smooth muscle tissue,  decreasing the intracellular calcium levels and also increasing myosin light chain activity.

Question: A patient comes into the GP surgery complaining of a sharp, stabbing chest pain that he experiences in the night which sometimes radiates to the shoulder and back. He says that when he sits up a bit he find the pain subsides a bit and is relieved more when he leans forward too. What do you suspect this patient has?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

These are classic symptoms of pericarditis. This is where the pericardium is inflamed and the visceral and parietal layers rub together causing friction and pain. The pericardium has somatic innervation from the phrenic nerve C3-C5 and the cell bodies of this nerve mix with the cell bodies of the nerves innervating the shoulder, arm and back. This causes the referred pain felt. Sitting up and leaning forward helps to relieve symptoms as this separates the visceral and parietal layers. NSAIDs can be effective to relieve pain and if left untreated, pericarditis can lead to pericardial effusion.

Question: What cardiac pathology is this histological image showing?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

This image is showing a tear in the tunica intima creating a separation and false lumen between the tunica intima and the tunica media. This is aortic dissection. As a result, blood travels through this tear and blood builds up creating a bulge in the aorta. If this progresses without treatment, the tunica adventitia may rupture which is fatal. 

There are different classifications for aortic dissection:

Stanford:

  • Type A- before the origin of the left subclavian artery 
  • Type B- after the origin of the left subclavian artery 

DeBakey

  • Type I- ascending aorta, arch of aorta and descending aorta
  • Type II- ascending aorta only 
  • Type III- descending aorta 

Symptoms include:

  • Sudden severe chest pain
  • Sweating
  • Nausea
  • Weakness
  • Syncope
