Question: A patient comes for a health check at the GP with no symptoms and as part of this health check you perform an ECG. You notice some abnormalities in this ECG and realise that you are looking at a type of atrioventricular block. What type of AV block does this ECG show?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

This is a first degree AV block. On this ECG there is consistent prolongation of the PR interval. A normal PR interval is 0.12-0.2s which is 3-5 small squares on an ECG. PR prolongation is where the interval exceeds 0.2s. All the P waves and QRS complexes are present and QRS complexes are of a normal duration (approximately 0.08-0.12s). Patients are often asymptomatic.

 

B) 2nd Degree Heart Block Type 1-  this is the progressive lengthening of the PR interval (above 0.2s) until the QRS complex is dropped. This happens in a repeated pattern where the QRS complex is dropped around after every 3rd/4th P wave. Every P wave is present and there are more P waves than QRS complexes. The QRS durations are normal.

 

C) 2nd Degree Heart Block Type 2- this is where there are consistent PR intervals (0.12-0.2s) but intermittent dropping of the QRS complex due to conduction failure. The QRS duration may be normal or broad (above 0.12s). They are broad if the block is distal to the Bundle of His

 

D) 3rd degree heart block- P waves and QRS complexes are present but have no association with each other as there is no electrical conduction between the atria and the ventricles. There can be narrow complex escape rhythms where the block is above the Bundle of His bifurcation and the QRS duration is less than 0.12s and heart rate is less than 40bpm. Or there are broad complex escape rhythms where the block is below the bundle of his bifurcation and the QRS complex is greater than 0.12s. 

 

Geeky medics is a good website for this https://geekymedics.com/atrioventricular-block/

Question:
what antibiotic matches the following characteristics 

 

Use - broad spectrum infections caused by escherichia enterobacter and pseudomonas

ADRs - gastro intestinal disturbances achilles tendon rupture QT elongations

Question: When oestrogen binds to receptors on endothelial cells it has many effects. Which of the following is not one of these effects?
OptionA: Increased Ca2+ intracellular concentration which activates eNOS
OptionC: Increased PGHS COX activity which increases PGI2
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

When oestrogen binds to receptors on endothelial cells:

  • Intracellular Ca2+ concentration is increased due to the opening of channels which activates eNOS. eNOS increases NO which up regulates guanylate cyclase, increasing cGMP. cGMP switches on myosin light chain phosphatase and induces VSMC relaxation= vasodilation 
  • Activates AKT/MAPK which activates eNOS and stimulates the same pathway as described above 
  • Increases the activity of the COX domain on PGHS to increase prostacyclin (PGI2). This then diffuses into the tunica media where it binds to GPCR which activates adenylate cyclase. This increases the production of protein kinase A. PKA switches off myosin light chain kinase which causes VSMC relaxation= vasodilation 
  • Oestrogen has a protective effect on endothelial cells

Endothelin 1

  • Potent vasoconstrictor 
  • Stimulates proliferation of VSMC

Question: A patient comes in with a history of a blood clot and you plan to prescribe an appropriate drug to reduce their risk of another. The patient regularly takes ibuprofen to help with inflammatory pain in their knees. Which of the following drugs should this patient not be prescribed?
OptionE: None of the above- the patient would be safe to take any of these
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

The patient is on ibuprofen which is an NSAID. This is a contraindication for warfarin and therefore, the patient should not be prescribed this drug. Warfarin is a competitive inhibitor of vitamin K epoxide reductase which assists in the synthesis of factors 2, 7, 9 and 10. 

Apixaban- generally safer than warfarin and is a highly selective reversible factor Xa inhibitor. It is contraindicated if the patient has a prosthetic heart valve, excessive bleeding or coagulopathy 

Clopidogrel- an antiplatelet drug which inhibits the P2Y12 platelet receptor. When platelets bind to this receptor they are normally sensitised to collagen and degranulation, activation and aggregation are induced. Clopidogrel suppresses the collagen platelet response and is contraindicated if their is active bleeding prior to surgery.

macroglides - they work by inhibiting the translocation of events in bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 50s subunit of the bacterial ribosome

 

quinolones - they work by preventing the DNA replication specifically by inhibiting the DNA topoisomerase which is used to unwind DNA before its replicated 

 

sulphonamides - work by inhibiting bacterial dihydropterate synthesise this prevents the production of folate which is essential for the production of DNA and RNA

 

glycopeptides -   work by preventing the synthesis of peptidoglycan that's essential for the structural integrity of the bacterial cells wall, it alters the membrane permeability and inhibits RNA synthesis 

 

 

aminoglycosides - work by binding to the 30s subunit of bacterial ribosomes meaning that proteins cannot be produced

Question:
The Henderson-Hasselbach equation can be used to determine the acid-base status of the blood.

 

It states that blood pH is equal to a constant plus the log ratio of bicarbonate to CO2 concentration.

 

If the bicarbonate concentration is kept constant, what would be the effect on the pH if PCO2 is increased?
Explanation:
The equation is pH = pK + log [HCO3−] / 0.3 × PCO2.

 

Therefore, if the bicarbonate concentration is kept constant, an increase in PCO2 will decrease pH. A decrease in PCO2 will increase pH. 

 

About the equation:

  • The constant pK is normally 6.1 (related to the dissociation constant of carbonic acid)
  • The normal HCO3- concentration in arterial blood is 24 mmol.l-1 (determined by the kidneys)
  • The normal PCO2 is 40 and is determined by the lung
  • PCO2 (mm Hg) x 0.03 replaces dissolved CO2 concentration (if both bicarbonate and the dissolved CO2 concentrations are in millimole per litre) in the equation since CO2 obeys Henry's Law (the concentration of gas dissolved in a liquid is proportional to its partial pressure)
  • If the ratio of bicarbonate to (0.03 x PCO2) is kept at 20, the pH remains at 7.4
  • The ratio can be disturbed in 4 different ways by raising or lowering either the PCO2 or the bicarbonate concentration

Question: Without compensation, an increase in dead-space ventilation would cause what respiratory effect on acid-base status?
Explanation:
Answer A is correct: acute respiratory acidosis: decrease in pH secondary to an increase in PACO2

 

The HCO3-/PCO3 ratio is reduced, but the concentration of plasma bicarbonate does increase (dissociation of the extra carbonic acid)

  • Caused by a decrease in the elimination of CO2 by the lungs
  • Mechanisms of hypercapnia/hypercarbia (CO2 retention) could be increased dead-space ventilation or hypoventilation. In either case, ventilation to the alveolar is reduced affecting CO2 elimination. Alveolar ventilation will be (1-VD/VT) x respiratory minute volume. There will be changes in the ideal alveolar gas tensions. 
  • The alveolar ventilation equation shows the relationship between alveolar ventilation and PCO2. PCO2 = VCO2 / VA x K. Doubling of PCO2 occurs if alveolar ventilation is halved (if CO production is unchanged). PCO2 of arterial blood is usually the same as the PCO2 of alveolar gas.
  • There are many causes of hypoventilation
  • Increased dead-space ventilation means increase in the physiological dead space. Increased alveolar dead space refers to alveoli that are not perfused or underperfused. V/Q ratio is therefore infinite or high. Gas exchange fails due to lack of adequate perfusion of the spaces where gas distributes to at the alveoli level. Causes of increased alveolar dead space could be pulmonary embolism; pulmonary hypotension secondary to reduced cardiac output; inadequately fitted ventilatory apparatus; or air cyst communicating with the bronchus.

Answer B - respiratory alkalosis. Associated with an increase in pH. Secondary to decrease in PACO2. Cause: increase in the elimination of CO2 by the lungs - hyperventilation.

Question: How does the kidney respond to chronic respiratory acidosis?
OptionC: Excretes less H+ ions in the form of H2PO4- or NH4+
Explanation:
1. Chronic acidosis progresses slowly with the progression of gas exchange changes with chronic lung disease.
  2. Increased PCO2 in the renal tubular cells with chronic acidosis is detected.
  3. More HCO3- is conserved (answer A is therefore wrong and B is correct) so as to buffer the change in pH form the increase in PACO2
  4. More H+ ions are secreted (answer C is therefore wrong) (i.e. the urine will become more acidic) as H2PO4- or NH4+
  5. Plasma HCO3- increases which reverses the reduction in the HCO3-/PCO2 ratio which was caused by the increase in PCO2. The depression in the pH is reversed. 
  6. PCO2 is not changed as the mechanism is renal compensation for the respiratory acidosis
  7. However, renal compensation is typically not complete - the increase in the HCO3- is not sufficient to completely return the HCO3-/PCO2 ratio to normal - and therefore the pH remains moderately depressed
  8. The base excess can show the extent of the renal compensation
Tags: Acid base balance, Respiratory physiology, Renal physiology

Question: When is surfactant most effective?
Explanation: Surfactant is most effective at low alveolar volumes as the surfactant molecules are closest together. At higher alveolar volumes, surfactant molecules are further apart and become less effective at reducing surface tension.

Question:
You are taking an ECG of a patient with a history of cardiac problems, who is feeling dizzy and light-headed. You notice that as the trace is being taken, the PR interval is getting progressively longer, until a P wave is not followed by a QRS complex. The PR interval then temporarily returns to a normal length before this starts to happen again. You decide that the patient is suffering from heart block. 
Based on the ECG trace and the described symptoms, which type of heart block is the patient most likely to have?
OptionB: Second degree atrioventricular heart block (Mobitz type I).
OptionC: Second degree atrioventricular heart block (Mobitz type II).
Explanation:
A - First degree atrioventricular heart block is when each wave of depolarisation is conducted to the ventricles, but there is an abnormally long PR interval. This shows a delay in the conduction to ventricles, normally due to a problem with the AV node. 

 

B - Correct! Second degree atrioventricular heart block is intermittent failure of excitation to pass to the ventricles. There are a few subdivisions of second degree heart block, one of which being Mobitz type I heart block, caused by malfunctioning AV nodal cells which progressively fatigue until they completely fail to conduct an impulse. 

 

C - Mobitz type II heart block is a form of second degree atrioventricular heart block characterised by intermittent non-conducted P-waves without progressive elongation of the PR interval, as is seen in type I. Mobitz type II is more likely to be due to structural damage in the bundle of His/Purkinje fibre conducting system rather than problems with AV nodal cells. 

 

D -  In third degree (or complete) atrioventricular heart block the ECG will show complete AV dissociation, with independent atrial and ventricular contraction rates. Third degree heart block will happen if Mobitz type I or II are left to continue untreated for a long time, and can lead to sudden cardiac death and so is very serious. None of the impulses from the SA node are conducted to the ventricles, and so they contract independently to atria, in either junctional or ventricular escape rhythm. 

 

E - Branch bundle heart block refers to impairment of the conduction to the ventricles in the bundle of His or its branches. Left branch bundle block can be seen in the V1 ECG lead as a downwardly deflected and abnormally wide QRS complex. Right branch bundle heart block can be seen in the V1 ECG lead as an extra R wave (called the R' wave) creating an "M" shape QRS complex known as the RSR' pattern.

Mobitz type II - https://litfl.com/av-block-2nd-degree-mobitz-ii-hay-block/

Third degree AV heart block - https://litfl.com/av-block-3rd-degree-complete-heart-block/

Question:
which of the following drugs has the following Mechanism of Actions 

 

- This drug is an Muscarinic 3 antagonist

- It outcompetes  ACH for the M3 receptor found on the  bronchi smooth muscle cell wall 

-  This stops the function of the Gq coupled protein which stops the function of PLC (phospholipase C) which overall stops the movement of calcium into the cell

- The decrease in intracellular calcium leads to a decrease in the calcium calmodulin complex

-This stops the  myosin light chain kinase enzyme from turning myosin into myosin phosphatase and activates the phosphatase enzyme which converts myosin phosphatase into myosin 

- This overall prevents smooth muscle contraction and promotes smooth muscle relaxation

C - Salbutamol is a beta 2 adrenoceptor agonist it works by binding to the beta 2 adrenoceptors activating the adenylate cyclase which converts ATP into cAMP. cAMP Phosphorylates MLCK which means there is an overall decrease in the amount of myosin phosphatase and an increase of myosin (via the phosphatase enzyme) this overall leads to decrease in contraction and an increase in smooth muscle relaxation

Question: Which immunoglobulin is found on the surface of mast cells and basophils?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

IgE is found on mast cells and basophils. When a specific antigen binds to the IgE receptors, this causes degranulation of the mast cells and basophils. Histamines is released which induces an inflammatory response and therefore, IgE is allergy associated.

Question: On transitioning from the primary bronchi to the tertiary bronchi changes in the microanatomy take place . Which list below correctly describes the changes ?
OptionA:
- pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelial to ciliated tall columnar epithelial
- more goblet cells

- more smooth muscle

-  hyaline cartilage goes from being C shaped to being O shaped
OptionB:
- pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelial to squamous epithelial 
- less goblet cells

- more smooth muscle

- hyaline cartilage goes from being C shaped to being irregular
OptionC:
- pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelial to ciliated tall columnar epithelial
- less goblet cells

- more smooth muscle

- hyaline cartilage goes from being C shaped to being irregular
OptionD:
- pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelial to ciliated tall columnar epithelial
- less goblet cells

- more smooth muscle

-  hyaline cartilage remains C shaped
OptionE:
- pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelial to cuboidal epithelial 
- less goblet cells

- less smooth muscle

- Fibrous cartilage goes from being C shaped to being irregular
Explanation:
Well done ! C is correct 

 

explanation - 

-As you transition into the tertiary Bronchi , the radius will significantly decrease. As a result, resistance will increase and so It becomes harder to clear mucus. Therefore goblet cells will decrease in number, so less mucus is produced .

-Smaller airways are under greater psychical constraints then larger airways and so cannot contain as much rigid cartilage , thus cartilage becomes irregular plates 

-To control the size of the airways the amount of smooth muscle increases. This also helps to stabilize the irregular plates of cartilage 

-In the primary bronchi you will find pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelial , in the tertiary bronchi you will find ciliated tall columnar epithelial

Question: A patient comes into the GP with dyspnoea, a cough that’s lasted 3 months and sputum production which does not contain blood. They also mention they have wheezing and a tight chest sometimes. They used to smoke but quit 5 years ago. Their lips look normal when they are breathing and they are of a strong build. The patient is actually experiencing these symptoms during the consultation and you give them salbutamol. The patients symptoms do not subside. What is the most likely diagnosis of this patient?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

This patient is experiencing signs of chronic bronchitis. The three main signs of this are dyspnoea, chronic cough and sputum production. Patients may also experience wheezing and a tight chest. Their symptoms do not improve with a bronchodilator, which rules out asthma. Chronic bronchitis is where the airways irreversibly bronchoconstrict, reducing the lumen and increasing resistance. There is hypertrophy and hyperplasia of mucous glands and goblet cells. This leads to mucous hypersecretion which further decreases the lumen and increases resistance. Alveolar hypoxia leads to pulmonary vasoconstriction and pulmonary hypertension. Low oxygen and carbon dioxide result in hypoxaemia and hypercapnia. Hypercapnia can cause respiratory acidosis and hypoxaemia can cause polycthemia (increased haemoglobin). Low oxygen leads to central cyanosis and patients are described as blue bloaters. 

 

C- Emphysema patients have purse lipped breathing and muscle wasting. Chronic cough is dry rather than productive 

D- Unlikely as no weight loss, no blood in sputum and the patient has classic signs of chronic bronchitis

Question: You’re a GP and a patient comes in with progressive dyspnoea, a dry cough and finger clubbing. They have never smoked and have no family history of lung problems. Their spirometry results show an FEV1/FVC of 0.7. You send them off for a CT scan seen below. What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

This is likely to be pulmonary fibrosis and given the patient has no obvious risk factors (no family history and never smoked), this is likely to be idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. This is where the interstitium is thickened due to an increase in collagen deposition by fibroblasts. The interstitium is the space between the alveolar epithelium and the capillary endothelial basement membrane. There is an infiltration of lymphocytes and plasma cells which causes degradation of alveoli. This creates multiple filled air spaces which have a honeycomb appearance. This is what is seen on the CT scan. Due to the loss of alveoli, there is reduced lung volume and elasticity which reduces FVC and FEV1. This causes the FEV1/FVC ratio to be 0.7 or over which shows a restrictive pattern. Clinical signs include progressive dyspnoea, a dry cough and finger clubbing.

Question: Which are the three muscles of the forearm that flex the wrist?
OptionA:
flexor carpi radialis
flexor carpi ulnaris
flexor digitorum superficialis
Explanation:
remember the rule of 3s'
• 3 wrist flexors (flexor carpi radialis, flexor carpi ulnaris, palmaris longus)
• 3 finger flexors (flexor digitorum superficialis, flexor digitorum profundus, flexor pollicis longus)
• 3 wrist extensors (extensor carpi radialis longus, extensor carpi radialis brevis, extensor carpi ulnaris)
• 3 finger extensors (extensor digitorum, extensor indicis, extensor digiti minimi)
• 3 thumb extensors (abductor pollicis longus, extensor pollicis brevis, extensor pollicis longus)

Question: Which nerve innervates the flexor carpi ulnaris muscles?
Explanation: All of the flexors of the forearm are innervated by the median nerve apart from the flexor carpi ulnaris muscle, which is innervated by the ulnar nerve.

Question: Which nerve innervates the extensor carpi ulnaris muscle?
Explanation: All of the extensors of the forearm are innervated by the radial nerve apart from the extensor pollicis brevis (which is innervated by the median nerve)

Question: In which compartment of the leg is the plantaris muscle found?
Explanation:
The plantaris muscle is located in the superficial posterior compartment and is innervated by the tibial nerve. 

Superficial anterior is not a compartment found in the leg.
Tags: Musculoskeletal System, Case 1, muscles, Lower Limb

Question: Which of the following labels best describes the metaphysis?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer!

The metaphysis is the trumpet-shaped end of long bones. It has a thinner cortical area and increased trabecular bone and is wider than the corresponding diaphyseal part of the bone. It functions to transfer loads from weight-bearing joint surfaces to the diaphysis.

 

1 - epiphysis

2 - metaphysis

3 - diaphysis

5 - compact/cortical bone

8 - periosteum

Question: Which part of the structure of bones best fits label 7?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer!

 

Cortical bone - label 5. Cortical bone is also called compact bone.

Epiphysis - label 1.

Metaphysis - label 2.

Trabecular bone - label 4. Trabecular bone is also called spongy bone.

Question: Which of the following is not a risk factor for osteoporosis?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer!

 

Risk factors for osteoporosis are being female, aged over 50, having no children, being slim, alcohol consumption, smoking.

Question: Which of the following statements is not a secondary function of pulmonary circulation?
OptionE: Provide oxygenated blood and nutrients to the lung tissue
Explanation:
E is the correct answer!

 

Lung tissue receives normal systemic arterial supply via the bronchial arteries.

 

The primary function of the pulmonary circulation is to bring venous blood into contact with alveoli.

The secondary functions are: 

Act as a blood reservoir - approximately 500ml of blood that can be mobilised in shock states.

Chemical filtration - rich source of fibrinolysis, heparin and thromboplastin.

Mechanical filtration - protects the body from thrombi/emboli.

Metabolism of vasoactive substances - angiotensin I converted to angiotensin II.

 

The information used in this question if from the pulmonary circulation and lung disease lecture.

Question: Which joint directly anchors the lower limb to the axial skeleton?
Explanation:
• Answer D is correct, since the pelvic girdle (consisting of the paired hip bones and the sacrum) anchors the lower limb to the axial skeleton via the sacroiliac joint
  • Note that if you answered C (the hip joint), the bones of the lower limb also include the three fused components of the pelvic girdle (the ilium, ischium and pubis) as well as the bones of the thigh (femur, patella), leg (tibia, fibula), and foot (tarsus, metatarsus, phalanges, sesamoid bones)
  • Joint is plane synovial between the sacral and iliac auricular surfaces
  • Limited mobility with great stability; permits weight transmission from the trunk/vertebral column to the lower limb. Articulating joint surfaces have reciprocal curvatures & irregularities restricting movement
  • Strong ligaments include the anterior, interosseous and posterior sacroiliac, iliolumbar, sacrotuberous and sacrospinous ligaments. Posterior ligaments resists the sacrum being forced downwards by the trunk. Iliolumbar ligaments resists the fifth lumbar vertebra from being displaced over the sacrum
  • Foramina are created from the sciatic notches by the sacrotuberous ligament and sacrospinous ligament

Notes on other answers:

E = the lumbosacral joint is the articulation between the fifth lumbar and first sacral vertebrae. Major ligament: iliolumbar

A = the sacrococcygeal junction - symphysis between the apex of the sacrum and the base of the coccyx. Hyaline cartilage on surfaces, thin fibrocartilaginous disc in between articulating surfaces

C = the hip joint

B = the pubic symphysis is where the two pubic bones articulate anteriorly, meeting in the midline. Secondary cartilaginous joint. Articulating surfaces: medial/symphysial surfaces of the pubic bones, covered by layer of hyaline cartilage. Fibrocartilage forms the interpubic disc and connects the surfaces of hyaline cartilage. Main ligaments: superior and arcuate pubic ligaments, as well as the anterior pubic ligament

Question:
Foramina are created from the sciatic notches by the sacrotuberous and sacrospinous ligaments. 

 

Which of these two is the ligament that attaches to the ischial spine and separates the greater sciatic foramen from the lesser sciatic foramen?
Explanation:
The greater sciatic notch is a deep notch created from the posterior border of the ilium and is between the posterior inferior iliac spine and the ischial spine.

 

The lesser sciatic notch is a small notch below the ischial spine (the ischial spine is part of the posterior border of the ischium & is a thin, pointed triangular eminence that projects downwards and medially).

 

The sciatic foramina are two of the four main routes into the lower limb (with the obturator canal & the gap between the inguinal ligament and the anterosuperior margin of the pelvic bone).

 

The sacrospinous ligament attaches to the margins of the ischial spine and separates the greater and lesser sciatic foramina. Extends to the lateral margins of the sacrum & coccyx anterior to the sacrotuberous ligament. Shape: thin and triangular.

 

Sacrotuberous ligament: has a broad base (the posterior superior iliac spine, posterior sacroiliac ligaments, lateral sacral crest, lateral margins of the lower sacrum & upper coccyx). Oblique fibres descend laterally; a thick, narrow band is formed and then widens; attaches to the medial margin of the ischial tuberosity.

 

The GSF is on the posterolateral pelvic wall, & is wider in women. Function: major gateway between the pelvis and the gluteal region.

 

Boundaries of the greater sciatic foramen (clockwise):

  • Superior: anterior sacroiliac ligament
  • Posteromedial: sacrotuberous ligament
  • Inferior: sacrospinous ligament & ischial spine
  • Anterolateral: greater sciatic notch of the ilium

The piriformis partly fills the greater sciatic foramen. 7 nerves, 3 vessel sets and 1 muscles are transmitted by the GSF:

  • Above the muscle the superior gluteal vessels and nerve leave the pelvis. Superior gluteal nerve runs between gluteus medius & gluteus minimus, and supplies gluteus those 2 muscles and tensor fasciae latae. Superior gluteal vessel divides in the GSF with the superficial branch supplying gluteus maximus and the deep branch, which divides into superior and inferior divisions.
  • Below the muscle: the inferior gluteal vessels (muscular branch to gluteus maximus, cutaneous branch, articular branch to hip joint, anastomotic branches, coccygeal branch and artery to sciatic nerve) & nerve (supplies gluteus maximus), internal pudendal vessels and pudendal nerve (see below), sciatic (made up of tibial & common peroneal parts & supplies no muscle in the gluteal region & supplies muscles in the back of thigh & all compartments of leg & foot) & posterior femoral cutaneous nerves (runs downwards medial to sciatic & perineal branch enters urogenital region to supply anterior 2/3rd of scrotum or labium majus & gluteal branches supply posteroinferior quadrant of the skin of the gluteal region) & the nerves to obturator internus (see below) & quadratus femoris (runs deep to sciatic, obturator internus & gemini and supplies quadratus femoris, inferior gemellus and hip joint) leave the pelvis.

The lesser sciatic foramen is inferior to the GSF on the posterolateral pelvic wall, and inferior to the lateral attachment of the pelvic floor (levator ani & coccygeus muscle) to the pelvic wall. Function = connects the gluteal region to the perineum. 

Boundaries of the lesser sciatic foramen:

  • Anterior: lesser sciatic notch
  • Anterosuperior: ischial spine
  • Anteroinferior: ischial tuberosity
  • Superior: sacrospinous ligament
  • Posterior: sacrotuberous ligament

The lesser sciatic foramen transmits:

  • The tendon of obturator internus. Passes from the lateral pelvic wall through the LSF into the gluteal region - inserts on the femur. I.e. does not turn forwards with the other structures through the LSF into the perineum
  • The nerve to obturator internus. Supplies obturator internus & gemellus superior. 
  • The internal pudendal vessels
  • Pudendal nerve.

Course of the pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels & nerve to obturator internus:

  • The pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels (branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac) & nerve to OI leave the pelvis through the lower part of the GSF (i.e. below piriformis) into the gluteal region
  • Only a small part of the pudendal nerve seen in the gluteal region & does not supply any structure in the gluteal region
  • Pass under the apex of the sacrospinous ligament & crosses posterior surface of the ischial spine
  • From medial to lateral, arranged as PIN: pudendal nerve, internal pudendal artery, nerve to obturator internus
  • Reenters the pelvis through the LSF to enter the perineum below the pelvic floor
  • Pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels enter the pudendal canal in the ischioanal fossa & will supply external anal sphincter & structures in the perineum

Question:
The gluteal region is posterolateral to the bony pelvis and the proximal end of the femur.

 

The gluteal fold forms part of the lower boundary of the region. Which answer marks the upper boundary of the region?
Explanation:
The gluteal region is demarcated:

Inferiorly = by the gluteal fold, and the region is continuous with the posterior thigh

Laterally: a line between the greater trochanter and the anterior superior iliac spine

Superiorly: iliac crest. Answer B is correct

Medially: midline

 

Importance of the region:

  • Muscles mainly abduct, extend & laterally rotate the femur relative to the pelvic bone
  • The skeletal muscles cover vulnerable neuromuscular structures
  • Includes the sciatic foramina which create junction zones between the lower limb, pelvis and perineum. I.e. the region communicates with the pelvic cavity through the greater sciatic foramen, and communicates with the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen. 
  • The sciatic nerve, which innervates the posterior thigh and the leg and foot, descends through the gluteal region after having left the pelvic cavity through the greater sciatic foramen
  • The pudendal nerve and internal pudendal nerves briefly enter the gluteal region by passing through the greater sciatic foramen. They continue their passage from the pelvic cavity to the perineum by then passing through the lesser sciatic foramen. Similarly with the nerve to obturator internus and gemellus superior
  • The gluteal region is supplied itself by structures that pass from the pelvic cavity through the greater sciatic foramen.

Question:
Muscles in the gluteal region form two groups: the superficial group and the deep group. The plane between these muscles groups carry important nerves.

 

The main action of the one of these groups is lateral rotation of the femur at the hip joint. 

 

Identify the muscle in the answers which is included in the group described above.
Explanation:
The deep group includes small muscles. These are piriformis, obturator internus, gemellus superior, gemellus inferior and quadratus femoris. Main action: lateral/external rotators of the femur at the hip joint. Answer C is correct. 

 

The superficial group includes the larger muscles. These are gluteus minimus, gluteus medius, gluteus maximus (and tensor fasciae latae). Main action: abduct and extend the hip joint (movement of the leg in the posterior direction). TFL stabilises the knee in extension.

Question:
Identify the gluteal muscle that attaches to the medial side of the superior border of the greater trochanter of the femur. 

 

This muscle also divides the greater sciatic foramen into two regions.
Explanation:
The answers are the five muscles of the deep gluteal muscles. 

 

Many of them attach to the greater trochanter, but it is piriformis that attaches to a facet on the upper margin of the greater trochanter of the femur, and that as well forms the important landmark in the greater sciatic foramen. 

 

Piriformis:

  • Most superior of the deep gluteal muscles
  • Muscle both of the pelvic wall and of the gluteal region
  • Origin: between the anterior sacral foramina on the anterolateral surface of the sacrum
  • Passes through the greater sciatic foramen
  • Passes in the gluteal region posterior to the hip joint
  • Attaches to a facet on the superior margin of the greater trochanter
  • Innervation in the pelvic cavity by the nerve to piriformis
  • Action: externally rotates the extended femur at the hip joint and abducts the flexed femur at the hip joint

Question:
The five muscles (all of which are included in the answers) that make up the deep gluteal muscles laterally rotate and abduct the femur at the hip joint. 

 

One of these muscles passes through the lesser sciatic foramen to enter the gluteal region.

 

It attaches to the medial side of the greater trochanter of the femur.

 

Identify this muscle.
Explanation:
Answer B is correct.

 

Obturator internus:

  • Like Answer A (piriformis), is a muscle of the pelvic wall as well as the gluteal region
  • Shape: flat and fan-shaped
  • Origin: medial surface of the obturator membrane & bone of the obturator foramen
  • Forms the anterolateral wall of the pelvic cavity above the pelvic floor
  • Forms the lateral wall of the ischia-anal fossa in the perineum below the pelvic floor
  • Tendon bends around the ischium between the ischial spine and tuberosity; passes through the LSF and enters the gluteal region and then passes posteroinferiorly to the hip joint
  • Attaches to the medial surface of the superior margin of the greater trochanter of the femur (similar to the gemelli) just inferior to the attachment of piriformis
  • Action: laterally rotates the extended femur at hip joint and abducts the flexed femur at the hip joint
  • Innervation: nerve to the obturator internus

Question:
The deep gluteal muscles are formed of five muscles: piriformis, obturator internus, gemellus superior, gemellus inferior, and quadratus femoris.

 

The gemellus superior and inferior are triangular muscles that attach along the length of the obturator internus tendon.

 

One of the gemellus muscles is innervated by the nerve to the obturator internus, and the other is innervated by another nerve.

 

Which one of them is innervated by this other nerve? In your answer, also identify this nerve.
OptionA: Gemellus superior - innervated by the nerve to quadratus femoris.
OptionB: Gemellus inferior - innervated by the nerve to quadratus femoris.
OptionC: Gemellus superior - innervated by the nerve to piriformis
OptionD: Gemellus inferior - innervated by the nerve to piriformis
Explanation:
Answer B is correct: gemellus inferior is innervated by the nerve to quadratus femoris, whilst gemellus superior is innervated by the nerve obturator internus. The other muscles in the deep gluteal group (piriformis, obturator internus and quadratus femoris) meanwhile are innervated by the nerves which bear their name.

 

The gemellus muscles:

  • Origin of gemellus superior: external/gluteal surface of ischial spine
  • Origin of gemellus inferior: upper gluteal & pelvic surfaces of ischial tuberosity
  • Insertion of GS: along length of superior surface of the obturator internus tendon & into the medial side of the greater trochanter of femur with obturator internus tendon
  • Insertion of GI: along length of inferior surface of the obturator internus tendon & into the medial side of the greater trochanter of femur with obturator internus tendon
  • Action of gemellus muscles: laterally rotate the extended femur at hip joint and abduct flexed femur at hip joint. Act with obturator internus.

Question:
The deep gluteal muscles are formed of five muscles. These are shown on the diagram, along with gluteus minimus and medius muscles (two muscles of the more superficial group in the gluteal region).

 

Identify muscles A, B, C, D and E.
OptionB:
A = piriformis
B = gemellus superior

The labels also should read: 'greater sciatic foramen above piriformis' and 'greater sciatic foramen below piriformis' - i.e. it is piriformis that divides the GSF into two compartments.

Question: Which salivary gland produces serous saliva?
Explanation:
The parotid glands produce serous saliva: a watery secretion that is rich in enzymes.

The secretion from the sub-lingual glands is known as mucous saliva; a viscous secretion containing no enzymes and large amounts of mucus.

The sub-mandibular glands produce a mixed secretion, that is both serous and mucous.

Question: Raloxifene is a medication used in the treatment and management of osteoporosis. Which of the following statements best describes the mechanism of action?
OptionA: Acts on both osteoblasts and osteoclasts to increase bone deposition and reduce bone resorption.
OptionB: Binds to calcium and mimicks pyrophosphate. It inhibits bone absorption by encouraging osteoclasts to die by apoptosis, slowing bone loss.

OptionD: Mimicks the actions of estrogen to increase the density of bone.
Explanation:
D is the correct answer!

 

Raloxifene is a selective estrogen receptor modulator (SERM), mimicking the action of estrogen to increase the density of bone. It reduces the risk of vertebral fractures.

 

A - this is the mechanism of action of Strontium.

Question: Which of these neurotransmitters stimulates appetite?
Explanation:
The appetite control centre is located in the hypothalamus. Within in hypothalamus lies the arcuate nucleus, which plays a key role in the control of appetite.

The appetite centre contains both primary and secondary neurones. The primary neurones process external signals, be it neuronal, hormonal or nutritional. The secondary neurones are then responsible for co-ordinating the inputs received via the primary neurone.

These primary neurones are either excitatory or inhibitory. The neurotransmitters released by excitatory and inhibitory neurones are:

 

Excitatory: Neuropeptide Y (NPY) and Agouti-related peptide (AgRP). These promote hunger.


Inhibitory: POMC and CART. POMC can be cleaved into other neurotransmitters such as α-MSH and β-endorphin. These suppress hunger.

Question: Why does a ventilation:perfusion ratio (V/Q) decrease?
Explanation:
D is correct!

 

V/Q ratio decrease occurs when alveoli are poorly ventilated but are well perfused with blood.

This could lead to an absolute pulmonary shunt (where perfusion but no ventilation; V/Q=0)

 

  • a pathophysiology of the lungs would mean ventilation / perfusion would be affected, but different pathophysiology can occur depending on either a decrease in ventilation (pneumonia, COPD, pulmonary oedema) or perfusion (late stages of COPD, pulmonary embolism)
  • decrease in perfusion leads to an increase in the V/Q ratio.  
  • distribution of ventilation and perfusion are affected by posture change, however this occurs in health.

Question: Which of the following is not a direct metabolic effect of growth hormone?

Growth hormone is anabolic, not catabolic as it leads to anabolism.

 

Other direct metabolic effects include:

Glucose sparing w/ an anti-insulin action
Muscle = decreases glucose uptake, stimulates amino acid uptake/protein synthesis, inhibits protein breakdown -> increased muscle mass
Adipose tissue = decreases glucose uptake, increases lipolysis -> decrease in fat deposits
Liver = increases gluconeogenesis, increases protein synthesis, stimulates IGF production

Question: Which glucose transporter has a very low affinity for glucose ?
Explanation:
B is correct!

 

GLUT 2 have a Km value of 15-20mM, which is the affinity of an enzyme to substrate. Due to having a high Km, affinity for glucose is very low.

 

 

 

function of each glucose transporter;

  • GLUT 1 (Km of 1mM); basal (glucose) uptake in blood, foetus, blood brain barrier= glucose dependant
  • GLUT 2 ; rapid uptake and release of glucose in liver and a glucose sensor in beta cells (pancreas)
  • GLUT 3 (Km of 1mM); basal uptake in placenta, neurones, kidneys= also glucose dependant 
  • GLUT 4 (Km of 5mM); insulin mediated basal uptake in muscle and fat= insulin dependant
  • GLUT 5 (Km for glucose is  ; fructose transporter/ uptake in small intestine (can mediated uptake of glucose, but with low efficiency, therefore, Km of GLUT 5 for glucose is never given)

Question:
Each answer shows hormones in the same chemical class: amino acid derivatives, steroids, peptides, proteins and glycoproteins.

 

Can you identify which hormones belong to amino acid derivatives - i.e. those derived from an amino acid?
Explanation:
Answer A = steroid hormones

  • The answers shows the major classes of steroid hormone. Calcitriol (active form of vitamin D3) could also be included.
  • Synthesised from cholesterol, which takes place in the mitochondria or smooth ER. Most enzymes involved are cytochrome P450 steroid hydroxylases. Rate-limiting step is the of conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone through the delivery of cholesterol to the mitochondrion. 
  • Cholesterol is taken up via receptor-mediated endocytosis of lipoproteins or synthesised from acetate
  • Cells do not store the final hormonal product but store cholesterol, in an esterified form in lipid droplets
  • Steroid hormones are lipophilic; don't readily dissolve in the blood; rely on steroid-binding globulins; half-life in plasma of an hour or longer; metabolised by the liver into less active compounds; also conjugated by the liver to produce glucuronides & sulphates (increasing solubility & permitting excretion)
  • But peripheral metabolism of testosterone produces dihydrogetesterone (the more potent androgen) & oestradiol; liver and kidney metabolic vitamin D3
  • Readily cross the plasma membrane (small and lipophilic); normal mode of action is > to bind to intracellular receptors acting as transcription factors > which bind to response elements in the gene promoter regions > thereby modifying gene transcription

 

Answer B = modified amino acids

  • The adrenal catecholamines (adrenaline & noradrenaline) & the thyroid hormones are derived from the amino acid tyrosine
  • Synthesis of catecholamines: step-wise modification of free tyrosine residues. Storage: in secretory vessels & released in response to an action potential. Mode of action: bind to cell surface receptors, which generate second messengers. Very short half-lives: degraded by monoamine oxidase
  • Synthesis of T3 & T4: iodination of pairs of tyrosine residues in thyroglobulin. Mode of action: bind to intracellular receptors, but require specific mechanism for crossing the plasma membrane (unlike the steroid hormones). Very long half-lives; de-iodinated & then conjugated in the liver.

 

Answer C = peptide hormones

 

  • Most are the product of a larger protein (pre-prohormone) which is processed leaving the prohormone; hormone is produced by proteolytic enzymes
  • Storage: in secretory granules. Secretion: non-constitutive exocytosis - intracellular calcium acts as the second messenger
  • Water soluble & readily transported in blood, no specific carrier proteins. Short half-life; inactivated & degraded by proteolysis
  • Mode of action: bind to plasma membrane receptors of target cells > direct activation of protein kinases or generate second messenger (indirect activation of protein kinase) > phosphorylation of target proteins in the cell

 

Answer D = proteins

 

Answer E = glycoproteins

Question:
Hormones have different patterns of secretion.

 

Which of the following hormones is subject to diurnal variation in secretion?
Explanation:
Insulin = an example of episodic secretion. Here insulins is secreted episodically in response to high blood glucose.

 

T4 = an example of set point regulation - secretion maintains a constant plasma concentration

 

Adrenal corticosteroid cortisol = example of diurnal variation (daily variation / predictable pattern of hormone secretion over 24 hours). Diurnal variation in controlled by the suprachiasmatic nucleus in the hypothalamus. (Note hormones with diurnal variation secretion often also have superimposed episodic secretion).

Question:
The lumbar plexus is formed by the anterior rami of nerves L1 to L3 and most of the anterior ramus of L4. It also receives a contribution from the T12 (subcostal) nerve. There are a number of branches of the lumbar plexus, including the femoral nerve.

 

The nerves from the lumbar plexus carry general sensory information from patches of skin. 

 

The femoral nerve gives rise to what cutaneous nerve in the lower limb listed in the answers?
OptionA: Lateral femoral cutaneous nerve (AKA lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh)
Explanation:
Answer A = lateral cutaneous nerve of the thigh - cutaneous nerve that innervates the skin on the anterior and lateral thigh to the level of the knee. Answer is not correct since it does not derive from the femoral nerve - although it does arise from the lumbar plexus (anterior rami L2 and L3 - the femoral nerve is anterior rami L2-L4)

 

Answer B = saphenous nerve is a cutaneous nerve of the femoral nerve - supplies the skin on the medial surface of the leg. Other cutaneous branches of the femoral nerve include the medial and intermediate cutaneous nerves which supply the skin on the anterior surface of the thigh

 

Answer C = cutaneous branch of the obturator nerve (L2-L4) supplies the medial aspect of the thigh

 

Answer D = femoral branch of the genitofemoral nerve (L1-L2). Supplies the skin of the upper anterior thigh

 

Answer E = superficial fibular (peroneal) nerve is a branch from the common fibular (peroneal) nerve. The common fibular part of the sciatic nerve. The common fibular innervates skin on the anterolateral surface of the leg (lateral cutaneous of calf & superficial branch of common fibular), and over the dorsal aspect of the foot and toes (deep branch of common fibular). The sciatic nerve originates from the sacral plexus. 

 

Also not listed is the tibial nerve whose cutaneous branches innervate much of the foot.

Question:

The consultant requests Jasper walk towards the corner of the room and back. It is clear that Jasper is showing the Trendelenburg gait.

 

 

Suddenly, the consultant asks you which muscle could be affected to cause this gait. Out of the following muscles, which could be causing this presentation?
Explanation:
The Trendelenburg gait is usually due to weak or paralysed gluteus medius and minimus muscles.

 

Normally, these muscles abduct the hip and when walking they would contract on the stance side during the swing phase of the gait to prevent the hip dropping.

Question: Mrs Jones, a 75 year old female, has come in to A and E after falling over whilst walking. X-rays show she has broken her humerus. She is very shocked as this is her first fracture. Mrs Jones has a history of smoking and enjoys a glass of wine or 2 each night. A DEXA scan is used to assess her bone density and the results show a T score of -1.8. What is the likely diagnosis of Mrs Jones?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

Mrs Jones has osteopenia. This is where the bone density is reduced but not critical yet and is shown by a T score of -1 to -2.5. 

Below -2.5 is osteoporosis and this is where frequent fractures are likely to be seen due to significant bone loss. 

Risk factors for osteoporosis and osteopenia include:

  • Smoking 
  • Alcohol consumption
  • Underweight
  • Never had children 
  • Post menopause- low oestrogen increases osteoclast:osteoblasts ratio, more bone resorption
  • Family history 
  • Females
  • Over 50 

Primary osteoporosis is age related and often seen in females over 50 who are post menopause

Secondary osteoporosis is due to an underlying pathological cause which is lowering bone density

Question:
Systemic and pulmonary circulatory systems differ in their response to exercise. How are the following factors effected in the pulmonary system during exercise?

  • Blood pressure
  • Cardiac Output 
  • Vascular resistance
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

During exercise the pulmonary blood pressure increases, the cardiac output increases and the pulmonary vascular resistance decreases. The vascular resistance decreases due to the recruitment and distension of pulmonary blood vessels. This increases the surface area of the blood vessels which decreases pulmonary vascular resistance. Decreased pulmonary vascular resistance allows time for gas exchange and protects against pulmonary oedema.

During exercise, the blood pressure in the systemic circulatory system increases, cardiac output increases and the vascular resistance also increases. This is due to the release of adrenaline which causes vasoconstriction.

Question:
Classes of hormones have similar mechanisms of hormone action.

 

Out of the following hormones, which one binds to membrane receptors to initiate an intracellular signalling cascade?
Explanation:
SUMMARY OF MECHANISMS OF HORMONE ACTION

Τhe lipophilic proteins are: the steroid hormones (E.g. answers C, D), thyroid hormone (answer A) and active vitamin D (answer B = calcitriol). Therefore able to enter the target cell and initiate gene transcription by binding to nuclear receptors

 

Growth hormone binds to a membrane receptor associated with a monomeric G protein which activates tyrosine kinase activity or transcription factors

 

Most peptides and catecholamines (e.g. Answer E) meanwhile bind to membrane receptors linked to heterotrimeric G proteins. Second messengers are generated or inhibited (intracellular signalling cascade) activating/inducing transcription factors or directly acting on existing enzymes/proteins.

Question:
The hypothalamus and the pituitary gland are key to the regulation of the endocrine system.

 

Identify the answer which best describes their location.
OptionC:
Hypothalamus: limbic system
Pituitary gland: body of sphenoid bone
Explanation:
Answer B is correct. The hypothalamus is located in the ventral diencephalon (a group of structures in the diencephalon). The diencephalon is an anatomical division of the forebrain - includes the epithalamus, thalamus (dorsal thalamus), hypothalamus, and ventral thalamus (subthalamus). The pituitary gland is located in the inferior portion of the sella turcica known as the hypophyseal fossa - the sella turcica is a cavity or depression in the body of the sphenoid bone.

 

 

WRONG ANSWERS EXPLAINED:

 

Answer A. The hypothalamic fissure is the superior border of the ventral diencephalon, dividing it from the thalamus. The dorsum sellae is part of the sphenoid bone that forms the posterior boundary of the sella turcica

 

Answer C. The hypothalamus is associated with the limbic system. Answer B is a better answer since the sella turcica is the saddle-shaped depression in the body of the sphenoid bone. 

 

Answer D. The telencephalon is the top part of the forebrain or prosencephalon, comprising the cerebral hemispheres together with the olfactory lobes and olfactory bulbs. It is the diencephalon which is the bottom part of the forebrain or prosencephalon, linking the cerebral hemispheres with the midbrain. Meanwhile, the

tuberculum sellae is in front of the hypophyseal fossa (forms its anterior boundary) as the tubercle of the sella turcica. 

 

Answer E. The prosencephalon is the forebrain, one of the three sections of the brain of the embryo. Subsequently enlarges and divides into two regions: the central diencephalon, which comprises an upper thalamus and lower hypothalamus; and the surrounding telencephalon, or cerebrum. The chiasmatic groove is a ridge on the superior surface of the body of the sphenoid bone.

Question:
What connects the hypothalamus to the pituitary gland?

 

Select the best answer to the question.
Explanation:
Answer B is correct. The pituitary stalk or the pituitary stalk (AKA the infundibulum or infundibular stalk) connects the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland. It is the posterior pituitary that is directly continuous with the hypothalamus via the stalk. The stalk contains axons from the hypothalamic nuclei. Meanwhile, the hypophyseal portal circulation (Answer E) connects the anterior pituitary with the hypothalamus. 

 

The pituitary gland is also known as the hypophysis.

 

The posterior pituitary is also known as the neurohypophysis (Answer A).

 

The anterior pituitary is also known as the adenohypophysis (Answer C). The pars tuberalis (Answer D) is part of the anterior lobe and wraps the pituitary stalk.

Question: How are the hormones ADH/vasopressin and oxytocin, which are both synthesised in the hypothalamus, carried to the posterior pituitary?
Explanation:
Answer A is correct.

 

The posterior pituitary stores secretes ADH and oxytocin. These are produced in the hypothalamus (by the supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei). Axonal transport carries them to nerve endings in the posterior pituitary. Then the hormones are directly released into the general circulation.

 

Answer B and C:

 

Releasing and inhibitory hormones secreted into the hypophyseal portal circulation (axons from hypothalamic nuclei extend to the median eminence where the neurosecretions are released into the primary plexus of the hypophyseal portal circulation), not the general circulation, control the secretion of tropic hormones from the anterior pituitary into the systemic circulation. This ensures the hypothalamic hormones are not diluted before acting on the anterior pituitary.

Question: Which one of the following is not a tropic hormone released by the anterior pituitary gland?
Explanation:
The anterior pituitary gland secretes tropic hormones which stimulate secretion of hormones by the target glands. 

 

These are:

  • TSH = thyroid-stimulating hormone. Stimulates thyroid hormone synthesis/release by thyroid gland
  • ACTH = adrenocorticotropic hormone. Stimulates synthesis of adrenocortical steroids.
  • Gonadotropins are LH and FSH. Promote steroidogenesis & gametogenesis in testes/ovaries. 
  • Prolactin. Promotes breast milk production.
  • GH = growth hormone. Promote liver or tissue synthesis of IGFs (insulin-like growth factors). Liver IGFs are released into the circulation; tissues IGFs act in an autocrine manner. Therefore answer A is the correct answer.

histamine release ;

  • smooth muscle contraction, leading to bronchoconstriction 

cytotoxic proteins that are released from activated eosinophils lead to damage to epithelium which;

  • increase goblet cells
  • tissue remodelling
  • increase infection and increasing sensitivity to pollutants

 

there's a nice schematic diagram given to us in the lecture; inflammation and lung disease

Question: Which of the following hormones stimulates the production of androgen-binding protein?

C is correct! Androgen binding protein is produced in Sertoli cells of the testes in response to follicle stimulating hormone.

 

Luteinising hormone stimulates the production and secretion of testosterone from Leydig cells of the testes.

Question:
There are two pathways involving apoptosis, intrinsic and extrinsic.

 

Of the following molecules and receptors, which would you expect to find in a cell undergoing apoptosis as part of the extrinsic pathway?
Explanation:
Intrinsic pathway:

  • Involves biochemical stress, DNA damage (p53 activation) or lack of growth factors
  • Modulated by Bax and Bcl-2 - balance between these usually which regulates apoptosis susceptibility

Extrinsic pathway:

  • External stimuli
  • Ligands bind to death receptors on the surface of the cell
  • These receptors are normally part of the TNFR group

 

Both pathways lead to an activation of the caspase cascade which causes degradation of the cell in different ways.

Question: A 65-year-old male patient is carrying the shopping up the stairs of his apartment block when he suddenly gets an attack of chest pain with dyspnoea. He sits down immediately on one of the steps and within a few minutes the chest pain has subsided and passed. When he gets back to his apartment he takes some medication. What condition has the patient got?
Explanation: The patient is experiences the attack of chest pain whilst exercising (carrying the shopping) but it is relieved when he rests - the medications the patient could be taking are Beta-blockers (bisoprolol, metoprolol), Calcium channel blockers, long-acting nitrates, ACE inhibitor (if they are diabetic)

Question: During common cardiac conditions chest pain sometimes radiates to other parts of the body like the left arm/shoulder and the jaw, these dermatomes all share the same nerve segments- what are these nerve segments?
Explanation: it is T1-T4 dermatomes as the pain pathways from the coronary artery nerve plexuses carry nerve impulses in sympathetic nerves to the thoracic sympathetic nerve ganglia from spinal segments T1-T4.

Question: Which of the following is NOT a risk factor for ischaemic heart disease?
Explanation: Fat intake is not a risk factor, although some fats are converted into LDLs and VLDLs, large proportions of fat are converted into HDLs as well.

Question: A 74 YO female patient presents to her local GP and complains of chest pain and SOB. She says that she has been stressed due to her divorce proceedings and moving to a new house. Upon further questioning she says that she doesn't experience symptoms as much when inside the house but when she goes outside and its cold it exacerbates the symptoms. When resting there are no symptoms experienced. She doesn't complain of any other symptoms. What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
here there were some important clues: 

She mentioned physical stress due to her divorce proceedings which can stimulate angina 

She mentioned that it gets worse going outside when its cold- there will be peripheral vasoconstriction- so increased myocardial oxygen demand as BP will rise slightly therefore extra demand means more likely to experience angina as they are more likely to develop cardiac ischaemia. 

Unstable angina, pericarditis and STEMI are ruled out due to no pain when resting. 

Hypertension is possible however due to no/little symptoms indoors, stable angina is more likely.

Question:
The process of atherosclerosis is explained below: 

 

1) Damage to the endothelial lining of the blood vessels due to hypertension or toxins 

2) Cholesterol accumulates 

3) plaques cause the lumen of the artery to become narrower so blood pressure rises 

4) This causes an inflammatory response + macrophages enter the artery wall

5) Build-up of fibrous tissue reduces the distensibility of the artery wall 

6) calcium salts and fibrous tissue build-up at the site and form a fibrous cap 

7) an atheroma forms 

8) macrophages phagocytose the fatty deposits and become foam cells as they cannot break down engulfed fat 

9) This hardens the atheroma to form a plaque 

 

This is not the correct order for this process which order is correct below?
Explanation: It is what it is :)

Question:
Mrs Fitzgerald is a morbidly obese 24 year old woman with many ailments. You are a year 3 student shadowing the GP when Mrs Fitzgerald enters the consulting room.

 

Most recent patient notes indicate:

  • Weight = 308 lbs
  • Little to no exercise each week
  • Height = 160 cm

(1kg = 2.2 lbs)

 

A discussion follows and the doctor asks about her health habits. Mrs Fitzgerald discloses that she has been "thinking about trying to lose weight very soon". The doctor then gives her some advice about healthy eating and meanwhile asks you to calculate her basal metabolic rate (BMR) and daily calorie needs.

 

Women: BMR = 655 + (9.6 x weight (kg)) + (1.8 x height (cm)) - (4.7 x age)
Men: BMR = 66 + (13.7 x weight (kg)) + (5 x height (cm)) - (6.8 x age)

 

Little to no exercise = Category A (BMR x 1.2 = calories)

 

Using the given equations and data, calculate the BMR and daily calorie requirements of Mrs Fitzgerald (to nearest whole number), and state which stage of the health behaviour model she is currently on.
Explanation:
Correct answer is B! Well done if you managed to get to the end of this very long question :)

 

Explanations:

 

For the health behaviour model, see this website which explains it very well (pardon the pun): https://www.verywellmind.com/the-stages-of-change-2794868

 

Mathematics:

 

308 lbs / 2.2 = 140 kg

As she is female we must use the female equation: BMR = 655 + (9.6 x 140kg) + (1.8 x 160cm) - (4.7 x 24) = 2174

 

2174 x 1.2 = 2609 calories

 

I constructed this question from the "Energy use during exercise" tutorial from PCS1. It is important to note that BMR and calorie intake calculations are not very accurate at the extremes of muscle:fat ratios - therefore the answers for this question would probably not be very accurate in real life seeing as Mrs Fitzgerald is obese.

Question: Which of the following antibiotics exerts only bacteriostatic effects?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Tetracyclines are used to treat a broad spectrum of infections such as Malaria, Staphylococcus aureus infections and chlamydia. An example is doxycycline. They work by outcompeting bacterial tRNA for the A binding site on a bacterial ribosome. This inhibits bacterial protein synthesis and therefore, has a bacteriostatic effect

Sulfonamides also have a bacteriostatic effect. They are used to treat infections caused by toxoplasma but are seldom used due to resistance. They work by inhibiting dihydrojpterate sythetase which synthesises folate needed for DNA/RNA synthesis. This inhibits bacterial DNA replication and has a bacteriostatic effect. 

Macrolides have a bacteriostatic and bactericidal effect

Glycopeptides, quinolones, beta-lactams and aminoglycosides are all bactericidal

Gonorrhoea is a resistant infection and requires the action of dual antibiotics which are usually ceftriaxon and azithromycin. 

Penicillin is used in a large dose to treat syphilis 

Doxycycline and Azithromycin are used in conjunction to treat chlamydia but azithromycin can be used on its own

Question: The image below shows the conducting zone and the respiratory zone. What would V/Q equal in the conducting zone?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E!

In the conducting zone there is ventilation but no perfusion- it is the dead space. If there is no perfusion, then Q= 0. Anything divided by 0 is infinity therefore, V/Q = infinity. This can also occur if there is a pulmonary emboli preventing perfusion to the lungs. 

 

Right to left shunting of blood is when blood passes through the lung without participating in gas exchange- perfusion but no ventilation. If ventilation = 0 then V/Q = 0. This may occur if there was inflammation of the airway or obstruction.

 

This was in the gas exchange and breathing lecture

Question: What is the correct differentiation requirements for osteoclasts osteoblast and osteocytes
OptionA:
osteoclast :BMP - bone morphogenetic protein

osteoblast : monocyte to an macrophage to a osteoclast using M-csf and RANKL
osteocyte : entombed osteoblast with projections that communicate with other cells
OptionB:
osteoclast : monocyte to an macrophage to a osteoclast using M-csf and RANKL
osteoblast : BMP - bone morphogenetic protein
osteocyte : entombed osteoblast with projections that communicate with other cells
OptionC:
osteoclast :entombed osteoblast with projections that communicate with other cells

osteoblast : BMP - bone morphogenetic protein
osteocyte : monocyte to an macrophage to a osteoclast using M-csf and RANKL
OptionD:
osteoclast : monocyte to an macrophage to a osteoclast using M-csf and RANKL
osteoblast : entombed osteoblast with projections that communicate with other cells
osteocyte :BMP - bone morphogenetic protein
Explanation:
B  is the correct answer 

 

The synthesis of osteoclasts/osteoblast is as follows 

 

1 - Haemopeitic stem cells + M-CSF = Monocyte 

2- monocyte + M-CSF = Macrophage 

3- mesenchymal cell + BMP = osteoblast 

osteoblast produces -> RANKL

4- RANKL + Macrophage + M-CSF = osteoclast precursor 

differentiates further to the multinucleate osteoclasts 

 

osteocyte formation is as follows 

 

1. osteoclast have reabsorbed the bone the macrophages have neutralised the area 

2. osteoblast have rebuilt the bone

3. as new bone is built the osteoblast becomes entrapped 

4. the osteoblast differentiates into an osteocyte that has long finger like projection that communicates with local cells

Question: You are asked to explain to a 56 year old male as to why exercise can help to improve endothelial health and reduce hypertension. Which of these explanations would be correct?
OptionA: Exercise up regulates angiotensinogen through increased hepatic blood flow to increase the production of angiotensin 1 and then 2.
OptionB: Exercise down regulates prostaglandins through the increased cardiac output and vasodilation.
OptionC: Exercise increases the shear stress within the vessels and therefore increases the activity of Nitrous Oxide synthase and thus up regulates NO production.
OptionD: Exercise increases vasoconstriction so up regulates the markers of vasoconstriction long term which helps to improve endothelial health.
OptionE: Endothelin 1 is up regulated as the increased cardiac output that accompanies exercise allows for the increased circulation of pro-endothelin-1.
Explanation: C is correct. Nitrous Oxide is produced by the endothelium and is a short lived simple molecule. Nitrous oxide synthase converts L-Arginine and O2 into NO. NO inhibits platelet aggregation via cGMP and relaxes smooth muscle by cGMP. It also inhibits the proliferation of vascular smooth muscle.

Question: Which type of stem cell can give rise to all cell types except the placenta?
Explanation:
Totipotent (omnipotent) stem cells can give rise to any of the 220 cell types found in an embryo as well as extra-embryonic cells (placenta).

Pluripotent stem cells can give rise to all cell types of the body (but not the placenta).


Multipotent stem cells can develop into a limited number of cell types in a particular lineage.

Question: Which group of muscles are responsible for adduction of the humerus at the glenohumeral joint?
Explanation:
A is the correct answer!

 

Pectoralis major, latissimus dorsi and teres major are responsible for adduction of the humerus at the glenohumeral joint. A mnemonic that you could use to remember this is PLT or Perfect Last Time.

 

Pectoralis minor - stabilises scapula by drawing it anteroinferiorly against the thoracic wall.

Serratus anterior - rotates the scapula for abduction over 90 degrees.

Posterior deltoid - extension at the glenohumeral joint.

Teres minor - laterally rotates the humerus.

Question: Which of the following muscles is not involved in the internal rotation of the humerus at the glenohumeral join?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer!

 

Subscapularis, anterior deltoid, latissimus dorsi, teres major and pectoralis major are involved in the internal rotation of the humerus at the glenohumeral joint.

 

Pectoralis minor stabilises scapula by drawing it anteroinferiorly against thoracic wall

Question:
DHEA is an important hormone which is released from the (1)______________ of the adrenal cortex. It can be directly converted into (2)___________________ which is a precursor for testosterone and oestrogen. Adrenal androgens are

 

under the control of a hormone named (3)_______________ which is released from the (4)_______________ pituitary gland.
Explanation:
All androgens originate from cholesterol and are synthesised in the zona reticularis of the adrenal cortex which is the innermost layer of the cortex before you reach the medulla.

 

DHEA can be converted into androstenedione which can further be converted into testosterones - these testosterones can then be converted into oestrogens which is why females produce testosterone first in their ovaries as much of it is then quickly converted into oestrogens.

 

Androgen release is controlled by another hormone called ACTH which is released from the anterior pituitary (REMEMBER - the posterior pituitary only releases ADH and oxytocin)

 

See this website to find out more detail - https://teachmephysiology.com/endocrine-system/adrenal-glands/zona-reticularis/

I made this question whilst going over the Reproductive Hormone plenary from PCS3 - the diagram below is taken from the website linked above, I don't think we need to learn the diagram process, however DHEA and ACTH were mentioned in the lecture.

Question: A man's lungs have become stiff and inelastic, and are unable to increase in size as much as they used to. He can no longer take in as much oxygen. Which respiratory disease category would these symptoms fit into?
Explanation:
A- incorrect- obstructive disease is due to an ability to get air into or let air out of the lungs. It doesn't limit the volume of the lungs.

 

B- correct answer- restrictive disease limits the volume of the lungs as lungs are no longer able to expand as much. This may be due to fibrosis or a problem with the chest wall itself.

 

C- incorrect- ventilstion- doesn't restrict the volume of the lungs

 

D- incorrect doesn't restrict the volume of the lungs.

Question:
Mrs Baldwin visits the GP having fallen down the stairs which has given her double vision. She isn't able to laterally rotate her eye.

 

Which cranial nerve may be damaged?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A - the abducens nerve.


This only innervates ONE muscle which is the lateral rectus - this laterally rotates (abducts) the eye away from the midline. Damage to this nerve may cause double vision.
Tags: Cranial Nerves, Eye and vision, Eyes, muscles, nerves

Question:
Mr Jacobs is an 81 year old male who lives with his wife Maureen. He has been rushed to A&E after his wife called 999 in the middle of the night when Mr Jacobs had the following symptoms:

  • Impaired speech
  • Headache
  • Hemiplegia (paralysis on one side of the body)

You are the FY1 on the night shift and are responsible for treating Mr Jacobs. Before ordering tests and scans, you have an educated guess that it is a stroke.

 

If so, which is the most likely artery to be affected?
Explanation:
I'm not sure if we need to know about strokes in detail at this point - however the arterial supply of the brain is very important for Case 5.

 

Strokes can be ischaemic (thrombus or embolism which occludes the artery), or haemorrhagic (rupture in cerebral blood vessel).

 

The correct answer for this question was B, the middle cerebral artery.

  • ACA strokes are quite rare
  • PCA strokes usually affect vision because the PCA supplies the occipital lobe where the visual area is located
  • MCA strokes are the most common and usually cause these symptoms presented by Mr Jacobs

This website is quite helpful: https://www.ausmed.co.uk/cpd/articles/different-types-of-strokes

Explanation:
A is correct!

 

MDRD (Modification of Diet in Renal Disease) estimates glomerular filtration rate based on creatinine and patient characteristics.

 

(weight doesn't relate to GFR due to the muscle mass is the important part in the equation)

other answers given are irrelevant

Question: Clotting/blockage in which artery is most likely to trigger a stroke?
Explanation: C is correct! The angle with which the middle cerebral artery is positioned means that any emboli that find their way into the circle of Willis are likely to enter the Middle cerebral artery. Furthermore, the middle cerebral artery supplies a lot of the lateral area in the brain!
Tags: Nervous System, Neurons, Blood vessels, Brain, PCS 3

Question: Pathway of Cerebral Spinal Fluid?
OptionA: Secreted by the choroid plexus in the lateral ventricles. Travels down the cerebral aqueduct to the third ventricle and then into the fourth ventricle via the intraventricular foramen. Distributed to the rest of the CNS through the subarachnoid space and spinal canal. Reasbsorbed in the Superior Saggital villus and Arachnoid villus.
OptionB: Secreted by the choroid plexus in the third ventricles. Travels down the cerebral aqueduct to the fourth ventricles and then into the lateral ventricles via the intraventricular foramen. Distributed to the rest of the CNS through the subarachnoid space and spinal canal. Reasbsorbed in the Superior Saggital villus and Arachnoid villus.
OptionC: Secreted by the choroid plexus in the lateral ventricles. Travels down the Interventricular foramen to the third ventricle and then into the fourth ventricle via the cerebral aqueduct. Distributed to the rest of the CNS through the subarachnoid space and spinal canal. Reasbsorbed in the Superior Saggital villus and Arachnoid villus.
OptionD: Secreted by the epithelial cells in the lateral ventricles. Travels down the cerebral aqueduct to the third ventricle and then into the fourth ventricle via the intraventricular foramen. Distributed to the rest of the CNS through the subarachnoid space and spinal canal. Reasbsorbed in the Superior Saggital villus and Arachnoid villus.
OptionE: Secreted by the choroid plexus in the lateral ventricles. Travels down the Interventricular foramen to the fourth ventricle and then into the third ventricle via the cerebral aqueduct. Distributed to the rest of the CNS through the subarachnoid space and spinal canal. Reasbsorbed in the Superior Saggital villus and Arachnoid villus.
Explanation:
C is the correct order!

 

 

CSF is made in the lateral ventricles by the choroid plexus, and it is sent into the third ventricles via the intraventricular foramen. The CSF then travels through the cerebral aqueduct to the fourth ventricles, where it can then be distributed to the rest of the brain via the subarachnoid space and into the spinal cord via the spinal canal. Reabsorpttion occurs at the superior saggital sinus and arachnoid villus.
Tags: Nervous System, Neurons, Neurovasculature, Brain, Case 5

Question: Which of the following memories is stored in amygdala?
OptionD: Being able to memorise the structures of the brain
OptionE: Drawing out the other half of a triangle based on a template
Explanation:
The amygdala accounts for emotional memory which include fears.

A: episodic memory stored in hippocampus

B: procedural memory stored in other parts of the limbic system including cerebellum and basal ganglia

C: "terrified" implies emotions from past experiences

D: semantic memory is stored in either hippocampus and MTL or in the neocortex of temporal lobes

Question: In Weigert's stain what colour/ shade is the white matter?
Explanation:
A is correct!

 

 

Brain slices are usually stained to provide contrast by using Weigert's stain. The stain is used for lipids, therefore, myelin sheath will give a dark/ black shade. 

White matter (made up of myelinated axons) will be dark/black

Grey matter (containing neurone cell bodies) will be unstained/ lighter

Question: What causes Waardenburg syndrome? (hint- it's an ear problem)
OptionA: Na/K pump fails to work on the scala media
OptionC: Too little chloride ions inside the scala vestibuli and scala tympani
OptionD: Too much sodium ions inside the scala media
Explanation:
B is correct!

Waardenburg syndrome occurs as cell that control potassium ion secretion in stria vascularis fail to migrate into tissue during development leading to deafness because there is no endocochlear potential.

 

 

The scala vestibuli + tympani both contain perilymoh (which otiginate from CSF + blood plasm- high concentration of sodium ions)

The scala media contain endolymph (which originate from stria vascularis- high concentration of potassium ions)

 

Endocochlear potential is created as endolymph is +80mV compared to perilymph, meaning outside the hair cells potassium concentration is greater than inside hair cells; K+ channels open and K+ flows into cell through concentration and electrical gradient due to the driving force of the potential, which in turn depolarises the hair cell- leading to release of glutamate neurotransmitter. This leads to impulse travelling to brainstem by cranial nerve VIII.

 

Therefore, if there is no endocochlear potential, K+ cannot enter the hair to trigger neurotransmitter release to conduct impulse to brain; giving deafness.

Question:
Patient - Male 45yrs old complains of non- symmetrical sharp pain and swelling of the first metatarsophalangeal joint, you have decided to prescribe NSAIDs and further investigations.

 

Which NSAID would you prescribe and what is are the likely diagnosis

 

excuse my spelling throughout this question, typing on iPad ...
Explanation:
Correct anser - D

 

Symptoms likely points towards Gout, unlikely to be osteoarthritis / rheumatoidathritis due to the patient profile and the fact that patient doesn't present with symmetrical joint pain. However further investigation needed for confirmation eg. blood test (eg. Serum Uric acid). 

 

Gout is contraindications for the use of aspirin, because it reduces uric acid excretion and increase serum uric acid levels. Ibuprofen can reduce inflammation and have analgesic effect at the same time with lower risk of worsening gout symptoms.

Question: Vitamin K deficiency may lead to purpura on trunk, skin haemorrhage. Why ?
OptionA: Vitamin K is used for prostaglandin production and result in lack of coagulation in small injuries
OptionB: Vitamin K is used in hyperplasia of endothelial cells for repairing capillaries
OptionC: Vitamin K is used for producing coagulation factors XII, IX, VII, X and II and therefore result in lack of coagulation function

OptionE: Vitamin K deficiency inhibits the extrinsic coagulation pathway
Explanation: Vitamin K is used for making coagulation factor XII, IX, VII, X and II which leads to severe loose of coagulation function, this can be caused as a side effect of the use of warfarin which inhibits the production of Vitamin K.

Question: Which of the following is the main function carried out by the Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex ?
Explanation:
Dorsolateral prefrontal cortex is responsible for working memory and selective attention.

This means the brains ability to process memories from the past / encode short term memory for storage as long term memory.

Question:
An 82-year-old woman presents to the memory clinic hospital. She is unable to answer the question of how she would make a cup of tea. She also cannot give the questioner a response to how she would tie a shoelace.

 

Which type of memory is most likely affected?
