Question: The yearly dose of background radiation is 2.7 mSv on average. Some diagnostic imaging requires the use of radiation and increases an individuals radiation exposure. Which of the following would expose you to the most radiation?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer! 

An abdominal CT exposes the patient to approximately 12.15 mSv, the equivalent of 4.5 years of background radiation.

 

Barium enema - exposes the patient to the equivalent of 3.2 years of background radiation.

Chest XR - exposes the patient to the equivalent of 3 days of background radiation.

CT head - exposes the patient to the equivalent of 1 year of background radiation.

Isotope lung scan - exposes the patient to the equivalent of 6 months of background radiation.

Question: Which of the following imaging methods does not use ionising radiation?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer!

 

MRI scanning does not involve exposure to ionising radiation. It uses a magnet and radio waves to produce an image based off of the signal emitted by the protons in the patient's body.

 

X-rays, CT, fluoroscopy and nuclear medicine/PET scans all use ionising radiation.

Question: Surfactant reduces surface tension on the alveoli and prevents them from collapsing. What is surfactant and which cells secrete it?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

Surfactant is a phospholipoprotein complex which is secreted by simple cuboidal epithelial cells, also known as type 2 alveolar cells. The surfactant reduces surface tension on the alveoli to prevent them from collapsing. Surface tension arises due to strong cohesive forces between water molecules on the surface of an alveolus and the spherical shape of the alveoli creates the inward collapsing pressure. Smaller alveoli have a larger collapsing pressure.

Question: A patient comes to the surgery with a fever, productive cough and fatigue. The patient explains that her symptoms started 3 days ago and she's been feeling dreadful. She has never smoked and is usually fit and well. Spirometry results show a FEV1/FVC of 0.75. What is the most likely diagnosis of this patient?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E!

This patient is presenting with pneumonia. This is normally a viral infection which causes the build up of purulent fluid in the alveoli which reduces the lung volume and produces symptoms such as a productive cough, fever and fatigue. It can be hospital acquired or community acquired. Antibiotic treatment is usually a macrolide such as clarithromycin. It is a restrictive lung disease as the lung volume is reduced due to the pus build up, hence the FEV1/FVC is 0.7 or above. 

Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is less likely due to the classic symptoms for this being finger clubbing, progressive dyspnea and a dry cough. This is a restrictive lung disease where the interstitium is thickened and infiltration of lymphocytes and plasma cells leads to the degradation of alveoli. This creates multiple filled air spaces in the lungs which looks like a honeycomb on a radiograph. 

Answers A, B and C are obstructive lung disease which would show a FEV1/FVC ratio of below 0.7

Question: Poor James, a 5 year old boy, is brought to the GP by his mum who is concerned that he always seems more out of breath than the other children during sport and is often wheezy. You decide that the most likely diagnosis is asthma and prescribe Salbutamol. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of action of salbutamol?
OptionA:
Beta-2-adrenoreceptor agonist 

Binds to beta-2-adrenoreceptors which are GPCR

This up regulates adenylate cyclase

cAMP increases and activates protein kinase A

PKA switches of myosin light chain kinase 

Bronchial smooth muscle relaxes
OptionB:
M3 receptor antagonist 

Binds to M3 which is a GPCR and blocks acetylcholine from binding 

This decreases cGMP production 

cGMP usually causes bronchial smooth muscle contraction

Less cGMP causes bronchial smooth muscle relaxation
OptionC:
M3 receptor agonist 

Binds to M3 which is a GPCR and blocks acetylcholine from binding
This decreases cGMP production
cGMP usually causes bronchial smooth muscle contraction
Less cGMP causes bronchial smooth muscle relaxation
OptionD:
Beta-2-adrenoreceptor antagonist
Binds to beta-2-adrenoreceptors which are GPCR
This up regulates adenylate cyclase
cAMP increases and activates protein kinase A
PKA switches of myosin light chain kinase
Bronchial smooth muscle relaxes
OptionE:
Inhaled corticosteroid 

Binds to a glucocorticoid receptor 

Up regulates transcription anti-inflammatory mediators

Down regulates transcription of inflammatory mediators 

Reduces inflammation
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

B- Example of this would be ipratropium (short duration) or tiotropium (long duration)

D- Salbutamol is a beta-2-adrenoreceptor agonist not antagonist 

E- This is fluticasone MOA

Question: Mark is a 56 year old man who has come into A&E with severe shortness of breath and blood results show PaCO2 of 11kPa and PaO2 of 5kPa. Hypoxaemia and hypercapnia indicate type 2 respiratory failure. Which of the following is not a cause of type 2 respiratory failure?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E!

Right to left shunt is where blood passes through the lungs without coming into contact with the alveoli or participating in gas exchange. This is an example of type 1 respiratory failure which is known as oxygenation failure. Type 1 respiratory failure presents only with hyperaemia (PaO2 less than 8kPa) where as type 2 presents with both hyperaemia and hypercapnia (PaCO2 greater than 6kPa). 

The causes of type 2 are: 

  • Depression of the respiratory centre- caused by drug overdose, brainstem trauma- damage to the medulla due to location of primary respiratory centre 
  • Respiratory muscle weakness- guillan barre syndrome, motor neurone disease- weakness of the respiratory muscles prevents expansion of the thorax 
  • Chest wall deformity- kyphoscoliosis, obesity- restricts chest movement
  • Severe lung disease- COPD, pulmonary fibrosis

Question: Sarah is a 25 year old athlete who comes into the GP with numbness and pain down her right leg from the buttocks and lower back to the feet. She says the other day she was on her morning run and when she returned home the pain started and has got worse since. You diagnose Sarah with sciatica caused by muscle inflammation compressing the sciatic nerve. Which of these muscles is most likely to compress the sciatic nerve?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Piriformis arises from the anterior sacrum and exits the pelvic cavity via the greater sciatic foramen before inserting onto the greater trochanter. The sciatic nerve arises from L4-S3 and also exits via the greater sciatic foramen in close proximity to piriformis. Inflammation of piriformis can lead to irritation of the sciatic nerve leading to numbness and pain felt all the way down the leg.

Question:
Jenny is four years old. Since she was three years of age, her father has been coming home wearing a baseball cap and taking her to the park to play after work. Whenever she sees him now she becomes excited and happy as she thinks they’ll be going to the park.

What type of memory is this incident associated with?
Explanation:
Classically Conditioned memory is an implicit memory type linked with prejudices, phobias, associations etc.

in this example the baseball hat is linked with the park and playing.

 

Long term declarituve memory can be divided as semantic memory ( knowledge and facts) and episodic memory - personal experiences like graduation. Long-term nondeclaritive memory can be divided into classically conditioned memory and procedural memory.

 

from lecture on memory systems

Sarah is a 70yr-old woman who has become increasingly forgetful over that past two years. Her son brings her to the clinic as his mum forgot her way back home from the supermarket she's been to since she was 30 years. The doctor asks Sarah to complete the MMSE.

 

What domain isn't a part of this test ?
Explanation:
Five domains in the MMSE 

Attention and orientation 

Memory

Verbal fluency 

Visouspatial skills

 

From pre reading article for intro to cog assessment practical

Question: William is a 73 year old patient who is back at the GP surgery for the 5th time this month with a chest infection. He has a productive cough, dyspnoea, chest pain and wheezing. You ask him about his sputum and he tells you that it is green in colour. After taking a full history you discover this is an ongoing problem and started 7 years ago when he had pneumonia. What is the most likely diagnosis?
OptionE: Pneumonia that William never fully recovered from
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

William has symptoms of bronchiectasis. This is an obstructive lung disease caused by inflammation of the airways. Mucous secretion increases which narrows the lumen and increases resistance. Macrophages are recruited and release TNF-alpha which increases vascular permeability, and CXCL8 attracts neutrophils. Neutrophils secrete elastase and proteases which break down elastin fibres and damages the airways, including the cilia. Cilia damage prevents them from sweeping the mucous out of the airways and this results in a productive cough. The colour of the sputum is green due to the neutrophils present. Once the airway is damaged, it is more prone to infections so patients may have recurrent chest infections. Bronchiectasis can be caused by a pulmonary infection such as pneumonia. Other causes include: alpha-1 anti-trypsin deficiency, cystic fibrosis, COPD and asthma. Bronchiectasis cannot be cured but can be managed with regular antibiotics and bronchodilators.

Question: Baroreceptors are mechanoreceptors present in the walls of the common carotid artery and the arch of aorta. When blood pressure is high, they detect stretch and increase the firing of action potentials down CNIX and CNX. Which nucleus in the medulla receives the signals from these nerves?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Baroreceptors are mechanoreceptors present in the walls of the common carotid artery and the arch of aorta. When blood pressure is high, they detect stretch and increase the firing of action potentials down CNIX and CNX.These action potentials are sent to the medulla which decreases sympathetic activation and increases parasympathetic innervation to vasodilate blood vessels and restore blood pressure. This was taken from the cardiac physiology workbooks in Case 2.

Question: What is this cross section showing?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

This is the ampulla of the uterine tube which is highly convoluted with wide but thin wall. This increases the surface area and helps move the oocyte towards the uterus 

The isthmus is less convoluted and has a narrow, thick, straight wall. 

This was taken from Normal Reproductive Anatomy and Physiology in Case 4

Question: A patient comes into the GP surgery with pain in their hip and it appears to have dropped on their left side. They have presented with Trendelenburg’s gait. Which nerve is most likely to be damaged?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Hip drop occurs when there is damage to the superior gluteal nerve which innervates gluteus medius (and gluteus minimus). Gluteus medius stabilises the pelvis when a person walks and hence paralysis cause the hip to drop.

Question: Bisoprolol may be prescribed prophylactically in angina management. What is its mechanism of action?
OptionA: Competitive inhibition of beta-1 adrenoceptors in cardiac tissue, resulting in negative chronotropic and inotropic effects. Therefore there is reduced cardiac output and myocardial oxygen demand.
OptionB: Converted to NO in the circulation, leading to increased sGC and cGMP. This results in increased K+ efflux, decreased intracellular Ca2+ and increased MLC phosphatase in vascular smooth muscle, leading to vasodilation.
OptionC: Dose-dependently inhibits the mixed Na+/K+ inward 'funny' current in SAN, reducing pacemaker automaticity/impulse frequency.
OptionD: Stimulates guanylyl cyclase to increase cGMP and reduce Ca2+ entry into VSMC. Activates K+ ATP channel effluxer, hyperpolarising cells and preventing voltage-gated Ca2+ activity.
OptionE: Stops Ca2+ traffic through L-type voltage-gated channels in nodes (negative chronotrope) and in myocytes (negative inotrope). This results in less forceful contractions and relaxes vascular smooth muscle.
Explanation:
A is the correct answer!

Bisoprolol is a beta-1 adrenoceptor antagonist/blocker.

 

B: GTN spray, an organic nitrate.

C: Ivabradine, a HCN channel blocker.

D: Nicorandil, a potassium channel activator.

E: Diltiazem, a Ca2+ channel blocker.

 

For more information refer to the pharmacological treatment of stable angina and hypertension lecture or the BNF.

Question: Ivabradine is used in the management of stable angina. In which of the following cases would its use be contraindicated?
Explanation:
A is the correct answer!

Ivabradine, a HCN channel blocker, is contraindicated in acute MI, long QT syndrome, 2nd and 3rd degree heart block, severe hypotension and unstable angina. 

 

B: acute porphyrias contraindicates the use of diltiazem.

C: aortic stenosis contraindicates the use of GTN spray.

D: asthma contraindicates the use of bisoprolol.

E: left ventricular dysfunction contraindicates the use of nicorandil.

 

For more information refer to the pharmacology lecture from case 2 and the BNF.

Question: 8-year-old Sarah has been diagnosed with atopic asthma and been prescribed sodium cromoglicate to help control her asthma. What is the mechanism of action of this medication?
OptionA: Blockade of M3 ACh receptors on bronchial SM -> reduced cGMP + SM relaxation w/ subsequent dilation of bronchi.
OptionB: Inhibited cAMP production in macrophages, neutrophils and eosinophils.
OptionC: Inhibits synthesis of arachidonic acid, meaning no prostaglandins are produced. Therefore no PGI2 is produced and vasoconstriction does not occur.
OptionD: Inhibits the release of histamine from mast cells.
OptionE: Prevents the interaction between IgE and mast cells.
Explanation:
D is the correct answer. Nedocromil sodium has the same mechanism of action.

 

A: mechanism of action of ipratropium, a short-acting muscarinic antagonist. This is used in COPD management. 

B: mechanism of action of PDE4 inhibitors. This is used in severe COPD management.

C: mechanism of action of corticosteroids. This is used in the management of asthma.

E: mechanism of action of anti-IgE antibodies. These are used in patients with severe persistence allergic disease.

 

The information in this question comes from the inflammation and lung disease lecture and the case 3 pharmacology lightbulb.

Question: What layer of the meninges does the cerebral spinal fluid flow beneath?
Explanation:
A is correct.

 

The arachnoid master is an avascular layer and beneath it is the CSF. Arachnoid granulations pass into dura mater for venous drainage of CSF.

Question:
Brown-Séquard syndrome is often associated with traumatic injury. It affects the (1)_______________ pathway and the (2)__________________ pathway due to a hemisection on one side of the spinal cord. This would cause

 

(3)_______________ loss of touch, vibration and proprioception and (4)________________ loss of pain and temperature sensation.
Explanation:
The correct answer is A - well done if you managed to answer correctly!

 

Here is my explanation:

 

DCML

  • DCML (Dorsal column medial lemniscus pathway) - decussates (crosses over) in medulla oblongata
  • This pathway is responsible for touch, vibration and proprioception
  • Therefore a lesion in the spinal cord would present with IPSILATERAL loss of touch, vibration and proprioception - remember it decussates in the medulla oblongata which is above the spinal cord, so the loss of function would be on the same side as the lesion

Spinothalamic (Anterolateral)

  • The anterior spinothalamic is responsible for crude touch and pressure
  • Posterior spinothalamic is responsible for pain and temperature
  • These decussate in the spinal cord rather than the medulla
  • Therefore a lesion would cause CONTRALATERAL loss of pain and temperature sensation
  • This is because the tract has crossed over in the spinal cord and therefore the effect would be on the opposite side to the side in which the tract runs up the spinal cord

 

A hemisection would also affect the corticospinal tract, however the question was constructed so that you shouldn't get an answer with corticospinal as this involves motor effects, not the ones listed in the question - there would be an ipsilateral hemiparesis

 

See https://teachmeanatomy.info/neuroanatomy/pathways/ascending-tracts-sensory/ for more detailed information regarding the ascending tracts.
Tags: Brain, Case 5, Spinal Cord and Tracts

Question: Which of the following is not a feature of ileum?
Explanation: A: jejunum is highly vascularised, not ileum. The rest are all features of the ileum.

Question: Which of the following is not a branch of common hepatic artery?
Explanation:
C: left gastroepiploic artery is a branch of splenic artery-an alternative artery of the coeliac trunk.

Coeliac trunk gives of 3 main branches: left gastric, splenic and common hepatic arteries. 

General organisation:

Left gastric artery
- Majority travels inferiorly along the lesser curvature of stomach and supply it. Smallest of the three branches
- One small branch comes off to supply the oesophagus
Splenic artery
- It runs posterior to the stomach and then extends to enter spleen.
- Along the way: it gives off several gastric arteries to supply fundus and posterior aspect of stomach.
- At the spleen, it splits into several branches to enter the spleen
- Another branch travels downward along greater curvature of stomach to form left gastroepiploic artery
Common hepatic artery
- It extends towards live and firstly gives rise to gastroduodenal artery which travels inferiorly
- Gastroduodenal artery passes posteriorly to the right gastric artery. It then gives rise to supraduodenal artery supplying the duodenum.
- The gastroduodenal artery continues to pass inferiorly.
- When it passes inferior to the duodenum, it splits into right gastroepiploic artery and superior pancreaticalduodenal artery.
- Right gastroepiploic artery which will join the left gastroepiploic artery to form anastomosis on the great curvatures
- Superior pancreaticalduodenal artery splits into posterior and anterior part.

- Common hepatic artery continues towards the liver as (common)hepatic artery proper-found in portal triad.
- Hepatic artery proper then branches into left and right hepatic arteries as well as left and right gastric arteries
- Right gastric artery runs long the lesser curvature and joins left gastric artery to form an anastomosis.
- Right hepatic artery gives off a branch to gall bladder called cystic artery

Question: There are several types of contusions based on their location in the body. Which of the following descriptions best describes an intramuscular contusion?
OptionB: When a muscle and the surrounding connective tissue sheath tear.
OptionC: When a muscle tears within the surrounding connective tissue sheath.
OptionD: When the cartilage bends or is hit.
OptionE: When there is a small injury on the bone surface.
Explanation:
C is the correct answer.

 

A: subcutaneous contusion

B: intermuscular contusion

D: cartilage contusion

E: periosteal contusion

 

Definitions for intramuscular and intermuscular contusions can be found here: https://www.rchsd.org/health-articles/quadriceps-contusion/#:~:text=An%20intramuscular%20contusion%2C%20which%20is,sheath%20surrounding%20it%20both%20tear.

Question: Based on the colour of a bruise you can interpret the rough stage of healing, but you cannot work out when the bruise occurred from this information. What stage of healing is associated with a green bruise?
OptionA: Caused by low oxygen supply and swelling at the bruising site. Haemoglobin becomes deoxyhaemoglobin.
OptionC: Indication of DVT, which can be life-threatening.
OptionE: Sign that the haemoglobin is breaking down and healing has begun.
Explanation:
E is the correct answer.

 

A: blue/purple

B: red/pink

C: black

D: yellow (not all cases) or brown colour

Question:
Mrs McElroy is a 27 year old female who used to suffer with frequent ear infections as a child.

 

She has come into the clinic as she is worried she may be suffering with some sort of hearing loss, after a family member noticed her TV was very loud.

 

You are a year 3 medical student and the GP asks you to conduct a simple hearing test using the 512Hz tuning fork.

  • Weber test - patient reports sound to be louder in left ear
  • Rinne test - bone conduction louder in left ear compared to air conduction

 

What is the likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - well done if you answered correctly!

 

The Weber test involves placing the tuning fork on the forehead of the patient

  • If louder in one ear, may suggest asymmetrical sensorineural hearing loss or asymmetrical conductive hearing loss

Rinne test involves placing on mastoid bone on each side and then placing the fork by the ear for air conduction, then comparing which is louder.

  • In this case, the Rinne test allows us to determine whether it is conductive or sensorineural
  • Louder bone conduction compared to air conduction means the sound waves are heard louder through the bones compared to through the ear canal which suggests their is some sort of obstruction such as ear wax or a tumour (conductive hearing loss)

Question: Which of the following is not a sign or symptom of low blood oxygen levels?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer.

 

A hand flap/asterixis, in a respiratory scenario, is indicative of high blood carbon dioxide levels. Other signs and symptoms of high CO2 levels include hypersomnolence, confusion, headache, agitation, bounding pulse.

 

Signs and symptoms of low O2 levels include confusion, restlessness, cyanosis, tachypnoea.

 

(Reference: Respiratory failure and blood gases lecture)

Question: The ovaries are the site of ogenesis and contain oocytes which are arrested in their development until puberty when FSH and LH stimulate them. What stage of development are they arrested at?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

The oocytes are arrested in meiotic prophase I until puberty when they are stimulated to continue development by FSH and LH.

Question: Which of the following is involved in the regulation of eye movements and cognition?
Explanation:
Caudate nucleus - regulates eye movements & cognition
Putamen - proceeds and anticipates movement
Globus pallidus - regulate muscle tone for action
Substantia nigra - regulate subconscious activity in muscles
Lentiform nucleus = putamen & Globus pallidus
Striatum = putamen, caudate nucleus & Nucleus Accumbens
The putamen & caudate nucleus (collectively referred to as the dorsal striatum) provide input into the basal ganglia as these structures receive majority of the afferents from other brain regions. The dorsal striatum is important for associative learning.

The Nucleus Accumbens (the ventral striatum) is associated with motivation and reinforcement of behaviour. The former is due to the fact that activity of the ventral striatum, a component of the reward system of the brain, increases to cues suggestive of provision of a reward for successfully executing an action.

In Lewy body dementia, pathology affects the cortex initially before affecting the basal ganglia (hence cognitive impairment precedes movement disorder in patients), whereas in Parkinson disease dementia the pathology primarily affect the basal ganglia initially before cortical areas (hence movement disorder precede cognitive impairment in patients)

Question:
Mr Morgan is a 43 year old patient who has come to the GP worried about his weight. The GP weighs him which returns a figure of 98kg.

 

You are a year 3 student shadowing the GP and are asked to interpret this results with respect to a normal distribution.

  • Assume the mean weight of the population for males is 74kg
  • Standard deviation = 12kg

(Note these figures are made up for the purpose of the question)

 

What is the best estimate of probability that another patient in this group would have a weight greater than Mr Morgan?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D - well done for having a go at this question!

 

I used the Case 5 Statistics questions to form this question which is similar to Q4 of the statistics document in case 5.

 

Mr Morgan's weight is 2 standard deviations above the mean. Remember these rules for a normal distribution:

  • Within 1 standard deviation (68%)
  • Within 2 standard deviations (95%)
  • Within 3 standard deviations (99.7%)

It is necessary to imagine a bell shaped curve for this question. As his weight is categorised within 2 standard deviations, the probability of having another patient above this weight would enter the 3rd standard deviation. It's approximately 5% more than 95%, with 2.5% each being on the upper and lower end of the curve. Therefore the answer is P<0.025.

 

For a better explanation, see the mathematics folder for Case 5.

Question: Doris, an 83-year-old woman, presents in your GP surgery for a review of her dementia. You perform a MoCA assessment with her which reveals an impairment in her episodic memory. Which area of the brain is responsible for episodic memory?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer! 

 

A - The occipital lobe is responsible for visual processing

B - The medial temporal lobe, including the hippocampus, is responsible for declarative memory among other things

C - The parietal lobe is responsible for processing sensory information

D - The frontal lobe is responsible for short term memory and higher cognitive

E - The primary motor cortex is responsible for motor function

Question: Tracy is a 50 year old caucasian female who has recently been diagnosed with hypertension, following this she has been prescribed Ramipril. A few days after taking the Ramipril she has noticed she's getting a severely dry cough. What medication could be used as an alternative to alleviate these symptoms?
Explanation:
E is the correct answer! Guidelines state that if a patient can't tolerate the side effects of an Ace inhibitor, they should try an Angiotensin II receptor blocker. 

 

A -> Not the first line for hypertension (Remember the hypertension treatment pathway - A+C+D+ other (Alpha/Beta blocker)/Spironolactone (if low K+))

B -> Not typically used in hypertension treatment

C -> Not first line - this is an alpha receptor blocker

D -> Not first line in patients of this age or ethnicity - calcium channel blockers are first line if Afro Caribbean or aged more than 55 years old 

 

https://cks.nice.org.uk/topics/hypertension-not-diabetic/prescribing-information/angiotensin-converting-enzyme-inhibitors/

Question: Which part of the ovary is the most common site of ovarian cancer?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

The germinal epithelium is the most common site of ovarian cancers, 95% occur here. The germinal epithelium is modified visceral peritoneum which lies on the surface of the ovary. 

Cortex- site of ovarian follicles and contains dense irregular connective tissue 

Medulla- well vascularised loose connective tissue

Tunica Albuginea- tough fibrous outer coating for protection

Hilum- where the blood vessels enter and exit the ovary

This was in the Normal Reproductive Anatomy and Physiology lecture

Question: Mrs Jones has come to the GP with dysuria, blood in her urine and urinary frequency. You determine this is UTI caused by some sort of urinary pathogen. Which of the following is not a characteristic of urinary pathogens?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E.

Urinary pathogens have:

  • Pili for adhesion which stick to membranes and allow for pathogen multiplication 
  • Haemolysin to help the pathogen invade by breaking into underlying tissues
  • Biofilm- makes it hard for immune system to eliminate 
  • Flagella- for motility

Question: Mr Smith comes to the hospital after recurrent kidney infections. To determine if he has kidney disease, glomerular filtration rate is calculated. Which of the following is used to give the best estimate of GFR?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

Inulin is usually used to measure GFR as it is not reabsorbed or secreted in the kidney nephron. This means that the serum concentration of inulin is equal to the urine concentration of inulin.

The equation to calculate GFR using inulin is:

GFR = Uinulin x Ufine flow / Pinulin 

U inulin= urine inulin and P inulin= plasma inulin 

Normal GFR values are:

125ml/min/1.73m2 a female 

135ml/min/1.73m2 for a male 

Creatinine is not as accurate as a small amount is secreted in the PCT and therefore, creatinine over estimates kidney function

Question: Whilst on ward rounds as a 3rd-year medical student, your consultant presents a new patient to you. They explain the patient has suffered a fracture to one of their cranial bones. Based on this information, the consultant asks you to list which bones the patient could have fractured.
OptionB:
occipital

2 x temporal

2 x parietal

2 x nasal conchae

ethmoidal

frontal
Explanation:
A: 7 bones correctly identified. Should be occipital instead of 2 x lacrimal.

B: 7 bones correctly identified. Should be sphenoid instead of 2 x nasal conchae. 

C: 7 bones correctly identified. Should be frontal instead of vomer.

D: 6 bones correctly identified. Should be 2 x temporal instead of 2 x zygomatic.

E: correct answer.

 

The 8 cranial bones are: occipital, 2 x temporal, 2 x parietal, sphenoid, ethmoidal and frontal.

The 14 facial bones are: vomer, 2 x nasal conchae, 2 x nasal bones, 2 x maxillary, mandible, 2 x palantine, 2 x zygomatic, 2 x lacrimal.

Question: Which of the following openings, or foramina, is found within the middle cranial fossa?
Explanation:
A: found in the anterior cranial fossa.

B: found in posterior cranial fossa.

C: found in posterior cranial fossa.

D: found in posterior cranial fossa.

E: correct answer.

 

Foramina of anterior cranial fossa: anterior ethmoidal foramen, optic canal, cribriform foramina.

Foramina of middle cranial fossa: superior orbital fissure, foramen rotundum, foramen ovale, carotid canal, foramen lacerum, foramen spinosum.

Foramina of posterior cranial fossa: foramen magnum, internal acoustic meatus, jugular foramen, anterior condylar (hypoglossal) canal.

Question: The term chest infections typically refers to infections of the respiratory tract. They can be categorised into infections of the upper respiratory tract and lower respiratory tract. Which of the following types of infection is not classed as a lower respiratory tract infection?
Explanation:
D is the correct answer.

Lower respiratory tract infections affect any part of the respiratory tract below the larynx. Therefore laryngitis is an upper respiratory tract infection. 

 

Lower respiratory tract infections

  • infective bronchiolitis: in apices of lungs.
  • acute bronchitis: in bronchioles.
  • infective exacerbations.
  • pneumonia: infection of lung tissue.
  • empyema: infection of the pleural lining.

Upper respiratory tract infections

  • common cold
  • pharyngitis
  • laryngitis
  • sinusitis
  • epiglottitis
  • influenza

Question: Which pathway/stream in the brain may be damaged or dysfunctional in patients who struggle to recognise faces of friends and loved ones?
Explanation:
Ventral Stream/Pathway is correct (C)

This is the Occipitotemporal stream. Within the stream is the Fusiform gyrus which plays a role in facial recognition.

The ventral stream runs through Occipital -> Temporal -> Frontal lobes and is involved in visual object processing e.g.

- Colour

- Texture

- Pictorial detail

- shape

- Size 

 

Dorsal stream/pathway is the Occipitoparietal stream which runs through Occipital -> Parietal -> Frontal lobes and is involved in spatial processing e.g.

- Location

- Movement

- Spatial transformations

- Spatial recognition

 

Occipitoneocortical stream (B) is not a real stream and was made up. (We haven't come across it at least)

Temporoparietal stream (D) is not a real stream either (Certainly isn't involved in visuo-spatial ability, and probably doesn't exist at all)

Question: Luke has been admitted to A&E with a severe brain injury after falling off his bike without a helmet. After a few days at the hospital, Luke regains consciousness and you assess him to check for any memory loss. You ask how many months there are in a year and he says 20. Luke is able to feed himself and pick things up without difficulty. Which part of Luke’s brain is most likely to have been effected?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

Luke is struggling to remember general knowledge and facts as seen when he didn't know the number of months in a year. This shows that his semantic memory has been effected which is stored in the hippocampus and medial temporal lobe. 

Lukes procedural memory is in tact as he can feed himself and pick things up without difficulty. This means there is unlikely to be damage to the frontal lobe which contains the motor cortex or the cerebellum and striatum which are responsible for movement and coordination.

Question: A 16 year old boy comes into the GP with concerns over his appearance. He is much shorter than his friends, has a higher pitched voice, and lacks pubic hair and axillary hair. After running some tests you find he has a bone age of a 12 year old but does have elevated FSH and LH levels. There were low levels of oestrogen and progesterone detected in the blood. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

This is likely to be hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism. This is where the HPG axis has been activated but the HPA axis has not. FSH and LH levels are elevated due to low testosterone and oestrogen levels, which are not inhibiting FSH and LH release from the anterior pituitary. This is due to less negative feedback on the hypothalamus as testosterone levels are low and high testosterone normally inhibits GnRH release. It is known as primary gonadal failure which could be caused by damage to the gonads. To treat this sex steroids may be used to accelerate pubertal development 

 

A- Central precocious puberty: this is early puberty caused by the early activation of the HPG axis leading to GnRH release and FSH and LH release which activates the HPA axis. Children with this condition may appear very tall, have advance skeletal maturation, sex steroid characteristics (pubic hair, axillary hair and mood swings)

C- Hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism: this is where there is failure to switch on the HPG axis leading to failure to activate the HPA axis. In this case, GnRH, FSH, LH, testosterone and oestrogen levels would all be low. 

D- Peripheral precocious puberty- children who have early pubertal development caused by early activation of the HPA axis without activation of the HPG axis. Testosterone and oestrogen are produced but GnRH, FSH and LH may all be low. This can be caused by adrenal tumours or gonadal cysts. 

E- Isolated adrenarche- this is a benign condition causing early development of axillary hair, pubic hair, mood swings and acne 

 

This was from the Puberty lecture in case 4

Question: A 12-year-old boy has injured himself playing football and has been given some ibuprofen to help relieve some of the pain. Which domain is inhibited on the Prostaglandin H Synthase enzyme and how does this drug work?
Explanation: Ibuprofen is effective at treating mild pain, fever, and inflammation. It is a reversible competitive inhibitor which competes with Arachidonic Acid for the COX domain (cyclo-oxygenase domain) active site on the Prostaglandin H synthase enzyme.

Question: What is the effect of stimulation of the left sympathetic cardiac nerve on the heart?

The endocervix and ectocervix are formed from which type of  epithelial cell types ?

endocervix - simple columnar

The Ectocervix - made from Stratified squamous cells - multiple layers to prevent abrasion during intercourse. It is non-keratinized

Question:
A 36 year old female patient attends A&E complaining of a tight feeling in their chest, SOB and peripheral and peri-oral tingling. From the patients medical history there is nothing significant and the patient takes no regular medications and as far as they are aware have no drug allergies. You as the doctor order an ABG, FBC and U+E. The results of the ABG return as the following: 

 

PaO2: 14.6 kPa (11-13kPa) 

pH: 7.50 (7.35-7.45) 

PaCO2: 3.0 kPa (4.7 - 6.0kPa) 

HCO3- : 22(22-26 mEq/L) 

BE: +1 (-2 to +2) 

 

What does the ABG show?
OptionA: The patient is experiencing a metabolic acidosis most likely as a result of decreased reabsorption of bicarbonates ions in the kidney nephron with signs of respiratory compensation.
OptionB: The patient is experiencing a respiratory acidosis seen by the elevated pH and low CO2 most likely caused by inadequate alveolar ventilation seen in patients with COPD or asthma there are no signs of metabolic compensation.
OptionC: The patient is experiencing respiratory alkalosis seen by the elevated pH and the reduced CO2 with no signs of metabolic compensation, this is most likely due to a panic attack resulting in hyperventilation.
OptionD: The patient is experiencing mixed respiratory and metabolic alkalosis seen by the elevated pH, the reduced CO2, the patient is most likely experiencing excessive ventilation in COPD treatment.
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. Let's take it step by step: 

 

PaO2: On the upper limit of normal 

pH: elevated (suggesting alkalosis - now to decide whether its respiratory or metabolic or mixed) 

PaCO2: Low (suggesting that this is respiratory alkalosis) 

HCO3- : Normal so can't be mixed or metabolic alkalosis 

BE: within the normal range confirming the results 

 

The symptoms the patient presented with suggest that this patient is hyperventilating as a result of a panic attack - this is due to the characteristic peripheral and peri-oral tingling sensation that they are experiencing.

Question: At what stage of the Menstrual cycle do Granulosa cells start responding to LH ?
Explanation:
D- Correct. A peak in oestrogen causes the release of LH. This is picked up by Granulosa (follicular) cells with LH receptors in the Graffian follicle , inducing ovulation . At this point the Zona Pellucida is also thick and a Corona Radiata has formed .

 

A- corpus luteum - At this stage LH stimulates the coversion of Granulosa cells into the Corps luteum. Granulosa cells now produce Progesterone .Thecal cells produce oestrogen 

 

B- Primary multi-layered follicle- develops from the primary uni-layered follicle as a result of stratification of the cuboidal cells. Stroma cells form the theca layer . The zona pellucida is well established.

 

C- Secondary follicle. At this stage FSH stimulates the granulosa cells to secret oestrogen. The fluid filled antrum forms.

 

E- The primary Uni-layered follicle - Cuboidal epithelium .Production of the zona pellucida .

Question: Mrs Jones is 79yo female who, 3 years ago, was diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease. She has since been on a drug called Galantamine. This drug has lost efficacy as her Alzheimer's progresses. She has now been prescribed a drug called memantine, what is the correct MOA and the contraindications for this drug?
OptionA:
It is a reversible acetylcholine esterase inhibitor, prolonging the time ACh is in the synaptic cleft, improving cognitive function.

Contraindications: If GI pathology, asthma/COPD, arrhythmias, epileptic
OptionB:
NMDA receptor antagonist which enhances ACh-mediated neurotransmission

Contraindications: If GI pathology, asthma/COPD, arrhythmias, epileptic
OptionC:
NMDA receptor antagonist which enhances Ach-mediated neurotransmission

Contraindications: if epileptic
OptionD:
Irreversible acetylcholine esterase inhibitor, improving cognitive function

Contraindications: If epileptic
OptionE:
Reversible acetyl choline esterase inhibitor, improving cognitive function

Contraindications: If asthma/COPD or cardiac arrhythmias
Explanation:
C is the correct answer.

Memantine is used in Dementia, specifically in Alzheimer's disease, to treat moderate to severe symptoms. It is an NMDA receptor antagonist. Glutamatergic excitotoxicity causes neuronal death and this can be mediated through pathological NMDA receptor activation. Memantine suppresses the NMDA activity. Blockage of the nAChR sounds counter intuitive as it's what is happening in other drugs but the brain up-regulates nAChR in the presence of memantine to counteract its blockade. This enhances ACh-mediated neurotransmission. 

It is contraindicated in epileptics. 

 

The other drugs used to treat dementia are donepezil, galantamine and rivastigmine. These are all reversible acetylcholine esterase inhibitors. ACh is normally cleared rapidly from the synaptic cleft by acetylcholine esterases. In alzheimer's patients you want to prolong the half-life of ACh to improve cognition. 

Donepezil is contraindicated if the patient has Asthma/COPD or cardiac arrhythmias

Galantamine/Rivastigmine is contraindicated if the patient has GI pathology, asthma/COPD, arrhythmias or is epileptic

 

Option A is wrong. It describes Galantamine/rivastigmine

Option B is wrong. The contraindications don't apply to NMDA receptor antagonists

Option D is wrong. Acetylcholine esterase inhibitors are reversible

Option E is wrong. It describes donepezil.

Question: Sometimes babies can be born with an extra rib above rib 1 called the cervical rib, these babies have thoracic outlet syndrome. What is a potential consequence of having a cervical rib?

the cervical rib can compress the brachial plexus which means that patients with thoracic outlet syndrome it can also cause symptoms like 

> Muscle wasting in the fleshy base of your thumb (Gilliatt-Sumner hand)
> Numbness or tingling in your arm or fingers
> Pain or aches in your neck, shoulder or hand
> Weakening grip

Question: Which of the following is not a cause of hypoxaemia?
Explanation:
A is the correct answer.

Chest wall deformities are associated with causing type 2 respiratory failure, but are not a direct cause of hypoxaemia.

 

B: Diffusion deficit - increased thickness of the gas exchange membrane e.g. pulmonary fibrosis.

C: Hypoventilation - "under breathing" causes hypoxaemia and increased CO2 levels (results in type 2 respiratory failure).

D: Increased oxygen demand- e.g. sepsis, long operations, extreme exercise. If there is an increased demand for oxygen, then more oxygen will leave the blood and move into the tissues. If the increased demand can't be matched with an increase in the inspiration of oxygen, there will be reduced PaO2 in the blood and therefore hypoxemia occurs.

E: Low alveolar oxygen content - e.g. altitude where there is reduced PO2 in the air, resulting in reduced PaO2.

 

Other causes of hypoxaemia include a V/Q mismatch (alveoli not perfused or not well ventilated) and right to left shunting of blood. Both of these causes lead to the mixing of unoxygenated blood with oxygenated blood, lowering overall PaO2.
Tags: Case 3, Respiratory disease, Respiratory physiology, respiratory system

Question: Liam is a 75 year old gentleman suffering with dementia, when looking at a family photo he says that all the faces of the individuals in the photo look the same. What part of Liam's brain is most likely affected and causing these symptoms?
Explanation:
D is the answer! Liam is describing the symptoms of proposognosia, this is where individuals are unable to distinguish different faces and it is caused by damage to the fusiform gyrus!

 

A -> Would cause intention tremor, mask-like facial expression and shuffling gait (typically affected in Parkinson's disease)

B -> Would present with episodic and semantic memory loss

C -> Would present with hemibalisms

Question: Mr Jones arrives in A&E with a spinal cord injury. The consultant examines him and suspects he has Brown Sequard syndrome. What clinical signs must Mr Williams be presenting with for the consultant to suspect this diagnosis?
OptionA:
Ipsilateral loss of fine touch, vibration and proprioception below the lesion

Ipsilateral loss of motor movement below the lesion

Contralateral loss of pain and temperature below the lesion
OptionB:
Contralateral loss of fine touch, vibration and proprioception below the lesion
Ipsilateral loss of motor movement below the lesion
Contralateral loss of pain and temperature below the lesion
OptionC:
Ipsilateral loss of fine touch, vibration and proprioception below the lesion
Contralateral loss of motor movement below the lesion
Contralateral loss of pain and temperature below the lesion
OptionD:
Ipsilateral loss of fine touch, vibration and proprioception below the lesion
Ipsilateral loss of motor movement below the lesion
Ipsilateral loss of pain and temperature below the lesion
OptionE:
Contralateral loss of fine touch, vibration and proprioception below the lesion
Contralateral loss of motor movement below the lesion
Ipsilateral loss of pain and temperature below the lesion
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Brown Sequard syndrome is when one side (left or right) of the spinal cord is damaged and there is a lesion. 

Clinical features of this are:

  • Ipsilateral loss of fine touch, vibration and proprioception below the lesion
  • Ipsilateral loss of motor movement below the lesion
  • Contralateral loss of pain and temperature below the lesion

Question: Mrs Martin has been admitted to A&E following a stroke and you have come to check up on her. When you ask her 'How are you doing Mrs Martin?' she replies with 'Is it dog in water that I catch cold after before driving'. Which area is most likely to have been affected by Mrs Martin's stroke and where is this area found in most people?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

Mrs Martin is presenting with Wernicke's aphasia and although she can fluently produce speech, she cannot understand what you are saying and her sentences do not make sense. Wernicke's area is located in the superior temporal gyrus of the temporal lobe and is responsible for language comprehension. It is found in the left hemisphere of approximately 90% of people which explains why the majority of the population are right handed

Broca's area is in the left hemisphere in the frontal lobe and is responsible for speech production. Someone with Broca's aphasia will not physically be able to produce fluent speech. Despite Mrs Martin's speech making no sense, she could produce fluent sentences and therefore, this isn't Broca's aphasia.

Question: where in the Microanatomy of the ovaries do oocytes develop
Explanation:
Surface – formed by simple cuboidal epithelium (known as germinal epithelium). Underlying this layer is a dense connective tissue capsule.
Cortex – comprised of a connective tissue stroma and numerous ovarian follicles. Each follicle contains an oocyte, surrounded by a single layer of follicular cells.
Medulla – formed by loose connective tissue and a rich neurovascular network, which enters via the hilum of the ovary.

Hilum - where blood enters and exits

Question:

Question: Type 1 Diabetes is a relatively common condition caused by damage to the (1)______________ cells of the pancreas which release (2)_______________. This leads to a constant spike in blood sugar as (3)________________ receptors cannot be upregulated for glucose uptake into the body cells.
Explanation:
C is the correct answer. I used the notes from the PCS3 tutorial "Response to Fasting" in order to form this question.

 

Type 1 typically involves damage to the pancreatic beta cells which release insulin - normally insulin would upregulate GLUT4 transporters which would transport the glucose from meals into body cells, however due to insulin not being produced, the GLUT4 transporters cannot be upregulated and therefore glucose levels rise in an untreated diabetic patient.

 

This is sometimes described as "Starvation in a sea of plenty" - as the glucose levels rise to very high levels, it starts to be filtered into the urine

  • Glucose in urine may indicate diabetic patient - however it could also indicate a kidney function issue
  • Finger-prick testing can also show high blood sugar in diabetic patients - this is how they monitor whether they need to inject exogenous insulin

 

The way I remember the insulin and glucagon cells of the pancreas is as follows

  • DiaBetes - damage to beta cells can cause diabetes
  • GlucAgon - alpha cells release glucagon

Question: Which antibiotic(s) cannot penetrate the blood brain barrier normally but can when the meninges are inflamed (meningitis)?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Cetriaxone and penicillin are large, polar molecules that are unable to cross the blood brain barrier in health. However, when the meninges are inflamed, they are able to pass through. 

Chloramphenicol is a smaller molecule that is able to cross the blood brain barrier, with or without the inflammation of the meninges. 

This was in the antibiotic lecture in case 4.

Question:
Mr Thompson is a 58 year old male who has been blue-lighted to A&E after a consultation with his GP led to severe concerns over his productive cough.

 

He appears to have finger clubbing.

 

Which of the following conditions is this directly a sign of?
Explanation:
Bronchiectasis is the correct answer - clubbing is a common sign of bronchiectasis. Cystic fibrosis can also cause finger clubbing, as well as cor pulmonale.

 

COPD, common cold and pneumonia are unlikely to cause clubbing

 

Left ventricular hypertrophy - this would be wrong.

 

Cor Pulmonale (right sided heart failure) can however cause finger clubbing

  • Usually COPD causes cor pulmonale due to chronic hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction
  • This causes pulmonary hypertension
  • Over time the right ventricle becomes hypertrophied to compensate for the demand
  • The hypertrophy eventually leads to failure of the right ventricle
  • Therefore blood starts to build up peripherally and causes finger clubbing

The reason why COPD would be wrong in this instance is because that would not be the direct cause of the finger clubbing

Question: What type of memory is early, fast, automatic storage of visual information?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B!

Early, fast, automatic storage of visual information is a type of sensory memory called iconic memory. A good way to remember this is iconic = Eye-conic = visual. This is stored for a short period of time, about 1-2 seconds unless it is encoded into short term memory. 

Haptic memory- type of sensory memory responsible for touch and smell which is stored in the olfactory bulb

Echoic memory- type of sensory memory which is early, fast, automatic storage of auditory information. This lasts slightly longer than visual information, approximately 2-4s but still only a short period of time 

 

Semantic memory- long term memory responsible for factual information and general knowledge

Episodic memory- long term memory responsible for personal experiences

Question: You are a junior Doctor doing your ward round . You have just administered Penicillin  to an elderly female patient with renal impairment  suffering from a bacterial infection . You are aware that Penicillin has synergism ( an enhanced effect ) with two other types of drugs. In the case what drug would be most appropriate to administer with the penicillin for Synergism to occur ?
Explanation:
E - well done ! This is correct .CiproFLOxacin is part of the Fluoroquinolones group of antibiotics  (will usually end in floxacin) .It interferes with DNA/RNA synthesis by inhibiting topoisomerase II, preventing unwinding of DNA . It has Synergism with Beta-lactam antibiotics such as Penicillin's and Cephalosporins. This works as the Beta - Lactam antibiotics will weaken the cell wall , allowing entry of the fluoroquinolones to carry out their role. 

 

B- Trimethoprim is an antibiotic that inhibits folate synthesis (inhibits the enzyme that produces folate ) . It does have synergism , however this is with sulphonamides. 

 

C- Gentamycin, an aminoglycoside antibiotic ,  works by inhibiting protein synthesis . It has Synergism with Beta-lactam antibiotics.  

However : We know the patient is 1. Elderly 2. Has renal impairment . Gentamycin is contraindicated in renal dysfunction and the elderly .

This is because renal dysfunction ( which is also more likely in elderly patients ) can lead to a build up of the drug and cause toxicity . So this would not be the best option .

 

D- Metronidazole is an antibiotic that works by inhibiting DNA /RNA synthesis.

Question:
Seren is a 15 year old female who has just been diagnosed with asthma by her GP after undertaking a peak flow diary.

 

You are shadowing the GP who tests your knowledge of appropriate drugs and contraindications.

 

This patient is also a type 1 diabetic, therefore which medication should be excluded from consideration?
Explanation:
Fluticasone is the correct answer - this is because it is a steroid (more specifically a glucocorticoid).

  • Endogenous glucocorticoids such as cortisol (stress hormone - fight or flight) are usually released from the zona fasciculata (middle layer) of the adrenal cortex
  • Giving a diabetic patient an exogenous glucocorticoid such as fluticasone is contraindicated because it would promote gluconeogenesis in the liver and hence increase blood sugar

Question:
you are a first year medical student shadowing Dave a local GP based in Newport. The previous patient has recently come into the practice with gastric ulcers. this leads to you and the GP having a discussion about the cephalic phase of digestion.He begins to ask you about the stimulatory and inhibitory factors of gastric secretion in the cephalic phase. 

 

What is a correct example of an inhibitor in the cephalic phase of gastric secretion
OptionA: The sight of a massive burger from shake shack in town.
OptionB: The anxious thought of having to cook for your whole family on Christmas day
OptionC: The taste of a Sunday roast on Christmas day
OptionD: The thought of a takeaway after a busy day of lectures on digestion
OptionE: The smell of your favourite meal that your mum has made
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. 

 

- The thought smell sight and taste of food all are stimulatory factors that increase gastric secretion. This is done via the sensory inputs sending information to the appropriate centre in the cortex (e.g occipital lobe for sight) they then send this information to the hypothalamus that sends an impulses via descending axons to the dorsal nucleus of vagus.(DNV) The stimulation of the DNV leads to the impulses being run down the vagus nerve to the parietal and chief cells of the stomach this causes the release hydrochloric acid and pepsinogen 

 

- The correct answer is therefore B this is as the Anxiety or high emotions triggers the sympathetic nervous system and anything that triggers this system inhibits gastric secretion. This works by inhibiting the function of the vagus nerve. specifically by the greater splanchnic nerve. 

 

(you may not need to know about the Greater splanchnic nerve but thought that was an interesting bit of information)
Tags: Digestion, Digestion and absorption, Appetite, PCS 2

Question:
Alison, a 55 year old school teacher, consults her GP because she is experiencing episodes of severe pain affecting her upper jaw and cheek on one side of her face which occur when she brushes her teeth and swallows.

Which cranial nerve is most likely to be involved?
Explanation:
The Vth cranial nerve (trigeminal) which provides the sensory innervation to the face, the jaw and the cheek. This patient is describing a condition known as trigeminal neuralgia which is characterised by episodes of severe pain lasting a few minutes which sometimes may be precipitated by tooth brushing or other touching of the facial area. It is thought to be caused by compression of the trigeminal nerve on its course through the skull usually by a blood vessel. The condition can be very disabling and is difficult to treat.

The facial nerve (VII) is a motor rather than sensory nerve

The glossopharyngeal nerve (IX) innervates the pharynx rather than the jaw

The accessory nerve (XI) innervates the sternomastoid and the intrinsic muscles of the larynx

The hypoglossal nerve (XII) is a motor nerve of the tongue

Question:
The enzyme alpha-amylase has the code EC 3.2.1.1.

 

Using the given code, which type of enzyme is this?
Explanation:
E is the correct answer - well done if you answered correctly.

 

We must look at the first number of the enzyme code which tells us what type of enzyme it is. Then cross references with the following list:

  1. Oxidoreductase
  2. Transferase
  3. Hydrolase
  4. Lyase
  5. Isomerase
  6. Ligase

In this case, the number 3 shows us that alpha-amylase is a hydrolase enzyme.

 

A great way of remembering the order of these enzymes is "On The Himalayas, Life Is Lightened"

Question: Why  are Cephalosporins classified as a Beta-Lactam antibiotics ?
OptionA: Have a beta-lactam ring that can inhibit protein synthesis
OptionB: Have a beta-lactam ring that can bind to Penicillin binding proteins
OptionC: Have a beta-lactam ring that can inhibit the production of folate
OptionD: Have a beta-lactam ring that can inhibit the action of Topoisomerase II
Explanation:
B- This is correct. They posses a Beta-lactam ring which is able to bind to Penicillin binding protein (PBP). Normally the PBP enzyme will allow cross-linkages to form in the peptidoglycan layer of the bacteria cell wall . However the beta lactam ring will  inhibit this enzyme , so no cross-linkages can form .

(Sometimes bacteria may express Beta-lactamase , an enzyme used  to cleave the  Beta-lactam ring . However , this is overcome by the action of Clavulanic acid  , which mimics the Beta-lactam ring and in turn is able to inhibit Beta-Lactamase .

 

A- Inhibition of bacterial  protein synthesis is the role of drugs such as Macrolides and tetracyclines 

 

C- Inhibition of folate production is the role of drugs such as Trimethoprim and sulfonamaides

 

D- Inhibition of bacterial DNA/RNA synthesis via inhibition of topoisomerase II ,is the role of drugs such as Fluoroquinolones

Question: which of the following are inhibitory factors for parietal cells production of HCL
Explanation:
The correct answer is B 

 

- A is incorrect this is as ACH stimulates the production of HCL by parietal cells by binding to M3 receptors, released by the vagus nerve w

- C is incorrect this is as Gastrin is released by astral G cells which then binds to the CCK 2 receptors that causes stimulation of HCL by parietal cells 

- D is correct as somatostatin is released by astral D-cells which binds to SST receptors that causes the inhibition of HCL by parietal cells 

- E is also correct as prostaglandins synthesised from Arachidonic Acid binds to EP3 cells that cause the inhibition of HCL by parietal cells 

 

So the correct answer is both somatostatin and prostaglandin as they both inhibit the function of parietal cells
Tags: Digestion, Digestion and absorption, Appetite, PCS 2

Question: A  22 year old female has come to the sexual health clinic with dysuria, increased vaginal discharge and has noticed vaginal bleeding between periods. You prescribe Ceftriaxone to the patient . What is the likely infection ?
Explanation:
D- well done this is correct. Gonorrhoeae is a gram negative, capsulated bacteria that is treated by Ceftriaxone, a cephalosporin ,which are Cell wall inhibitors. All the symptoms presented by the patient point to likely Gonorrhoeae infection . (It is to be noted that Ceftriaxone is usually given alongside Azithromycin , to treat Gonorrhoeae . This is because 1. there is usually co-infection with chlamydia 2. co-administration may have a possible synergist effect 3. Prevents resistance of Ceftriaxone ) 

 

A- Uncomplicated UTI is usually treated by Trimethoprim , which inhibts folate synthesis. 

 

B-Syphilis is also treated by Ceftriaxone ,however symptoms would appear slightly different. Sores will initially present. Secondary symptoms will include rashes , fever and can lead to paralysis and organ failure 

 

C- Chlamydia- This is a gram negative bacteria than resides intracellularly . It is treated by  azithromycin - a macrolide that works by inhibiting bacterial protein synthesis  . This is because Beta-Lactams cannot enter the cell .

 

E- Trichomoniasis  - a protozoa infection usually treated by metronidazole - a DNA synthesis inhibitor .

Question: Mr Williams has come into the GP you are shadowing after being diagnosed with pulmonary fibrosis, a restrictive lung disease. The GP explains to him this is a thickening of the interstitium that makes breathing more difficult. Mr Williams is a builder and has no idea what the GP means by interstitium but you know exactly what it is. What is the interstitium?
OptionA: The space between the alveolar epithelium and the capillary endothelium
OptionC: The space between the alveolar epithelium and the outer wall of the capillary
OptionE: The space between the alveolar epithelium and the capillary tunica media
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

The interstitium is the space between the alveolar epithelium and the capillary endothelium. This is thickened in restrictive lung diseases such as pulmonary fibrosis due to deposition of collagen fibres by fibroblasts. The stiffened wall makes lung inflation more difficult resulting in reduced compliance. This can cause an infiltration of lymphocytes and plasma cells which destruct alveolar walls causing a reduced lung volume. 

C- wrong because its the endothelium of the capillary 

E- wrong, capillary does not have a tunica media

Question: Metabolic acidosis is defined as a decrease in pH,  base excess and bicarbonate. During metabolic acidosis , what would you expect Pco2 levels to be like if there was compensation  ?
Explanation:
B- Well done B is correct ! This is because during acidosis we have a drop in ph. However, because it is metabolic and we are focusing on Co2 levels, the will be RESPIRATORY compensation. In this case the rate of ventilation will increase or hyperventilation will take place to try and decrease the amount of Co2 in the body . Therefore we would expect levels to be low .

In contrast , during respiratory acidosis , levels of co2 will be high , but there can be metabolic compensation . As a result the kidney will reabsorb HCO3 and excrete H ions to restore the pH .Therefore we can expect levels of HC03 to be high. This form of compensation takes longer .

 

A- Levels would not be high due the compensation that is taking place that is described in the answer to B 

 

C- Levels would not stay the same if there was respiratory compensation. However ,it may be possible to have metabolic acidosis , without respiratory compensation , thus paC02 levels would remain the same .
Tags: Case 3, Regulation of pH, Respiratory physiology

Question: The Rhomboid major and minor muscles are located deep to the trapezius and are innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve. What other muscle of the upper limb is also innervated by the dorsal scapular nerve?
Explanation: The levator scapulae muscle is attached to the medial border of the scapula and the transverse processes of C1-C4 vertebra. The supraspinatus and infraspinatus are innervated by the suprascapular nerve. Latissimus dorsi is innervated by the thoracodorsal nerve from the spinal nerve roots of the 6th, 7th and 8th cervical nerves. Subscapularis is innervated by the subscapular nerve

Question: Apoptosis , can be described as a tidy death and does not lead to inflammation. It consists of an extrinsic and intrinsic pathway. Bak and Bax proteins are involved in the intrinsic pathway , what is their role in apoptosis ?
Explanation:
A- well done this is correct - .If damage is detected in the nucleus ,there will be upregulation of Bax and Bak proteins. Bak and Bax will open up pores in the mitochondria , allowing the escape of cytochrome C .This activates caspases which will release signals for phagocytes to eat the cell .

 

B- This is part of the extrinsic pathway , where ligands will bind to death receptors, activating caspases and as a result the caspases will release signals so that the cell can be eaten by phagocytes.

 

C- an indirect effect. See explanation to A 

 

D- BCl2 is actually anti-apoptosis. It will bind to Bak and Bax preventing apoptosis

Question:
Jack is a 12 year old boy who loves to play Fortnite on his Xbox but he's only allowed to do so before 9pm.

 

One evening his mum walks in and catches him playing Fortnite at 11pm.

 

She says "Jack you're only allowed to play before 9pm, you've lost your pocket money for this week"

This is an example of what consequence?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D - Negative Punishment

  • This is because his mum has taken something nice away
  • Positive punishment is more to do with an aversive consequence - for example you break the rules at work and are sent for retraining - it can also include a verbal reprimand or being given detention at school (in other words nothing is being taken away)

I formed this question based on the PCS 3 Health Psychology plenary

Question: A patient attends A&E with symptoms of an asthma attack, the doctor prescribes a nebuliser of Ipratropium. What is the mechanism of action of Ipratropium?
OptionA: Ipratropium binds to the beta-2-adrenoceptor on smooth muscle walls causing activation of GTP and Ga causing a cAMP cascade resulting in inhibition of MLCK and bronchodilation.
OptionB: Ipratropium binds to beta-2-adrenoceptor on the smooth muscle wall activating GTP + Gb causing phospholipase C to cleave PIP2 and release IP3 and DAG, activation of PKC causes inhibition of MLCK.
OptionC: Ipratropium binds to muscarinic ACh receptors blocking them, preventing the GTP + Gq cascade whereby phospholipase C isn't activated, preventing IP3 and DAG formation, and preventing an increase in intracellular calcium and calmodulin complexes hence smooth muscle relaxation
OptionD: Ipratropium binds to muscarinic ACh receptors causing a cAMP cascade where it activates PIP2 cleavage into IP3 and DAG, DAG then activates the PKC causing the increase in intracellular calcium which results in smooth muscle contraction due to more calcium-calmodulin complexes.
Explanation: Cascade outlined above - the intracellular signalling pathways

Question: Whilst waiting outside of the anatomy centre, your friend begins to quiz you on your basic anatomy knowledge. They ask you what type of bone the vertebrae are. What is your answer?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer.

 

  • Long bone: made up of shaft/diaphysis and epiphysis. They are longer than they are wide. e.g. radius, ulna, tibia.
  • Flat bones: the main source of red bone marrow (haematopoiesis) and so are a good place to sample. Also protective and point of muscle attachments. e.g. sternum, ribs, scapula.
  • Irregular bones: doesn't fit in other categories. e.g. vertebrae and bones of face
  • Short bones: strength, stability and limited movement. Are roughly equal in length and width. e.g. in ankle and foot.
  • Sesamoid bones: develop within a tendon. e.g. patella, base of thumb, base of toe.

Question:

  • Damaged structure: Dorsal radial head displacement
  • Clinical finding: Dinner fork deformity

  • Common mechanism of injury: Pronated FOOSH or direct dorsolateral wrist trauma
  • Damaged structure: Head of ulna dislocation
  • Clinical finding: Reduced pronation and supination

C: Monteggia's fracture

  • Common mechanism of injury: Posterior ulna force
  • Damaged structure: Head of radius dislocates and there is potential damage to the posterior interosseous nerve
  • Clinical finding: Extensor paralysis

D: Scaphoid fracture

  • Common mechanism of injury: FOOSH
  • Damaged structure: Avascular necrosis of the scaphoid
  • Clinical finding: Pain on telescoping the thumb, anatomical snuffbox pressure, scaphoid tubercle, ulnar deviation of the wrist

Question: Claire comes into the GP with ear pain and a bit of fluid leaking out of her ear. She tells you she recently went on holiday to Greece and spent a lot of time in the swimming pool. What do you suspect Claire has?

Perforation of the tympanic membrane- caused by sudden pressure changes (flying/scuba diving), poking a foreign object in the ear, infection or a blow to the ear/head. This presents with hearing loss, an earache, blood from the ear, tinnitus, fever and itching. 

Otosclerosis- this is abnormal bone growth around stapes which restricts its movement and causes conductive hearing loss

Serous otitis media- this is a common bacterial ear infection in children due to their Eustachian tube being short, wide and straight. Symptoms include malaise, pain and fever. Can be treated with grommets to drain the Eustachian tube

Influenza- can cause ear pain but not likely as no other flu symptoms

Question: Which of the following has the greatest effect on up-regulation of phosphofructokinase activity in the liver?
Explanation:
Full explanation:

Cycle 1:

- Release of glucagon will then activate the phosphorylation of PFKA2 by protein kinase A, this will inhibit PFKA2.
- This will subsequently switch on the active site of FBPase2. FBPase2 will convert fructose 2,6 biphosphate into fructose 6 phosphate(F6P).
- Fructose 2,6 biphosphate can increase PFK's affinity for F6P and reduce its affinity to ATP. Without it, the PFK will not be able to bind to as many F6P.
- This will reduce the rate of glycolysis and increase the rate of glyconeogenesis to convert lactate back into glucose which could be depleted quickly otherwise in the cells.
- There will then be an increase in glucose released into blood-higher blood sugar level caused by glucagon.

Cycle 2:

- Low numbers of Fru2,6 BP(corresponded with high F6P number)can lead to low rate of glycolysis but high rate of gluconeogenesis will increase the blood glucose level.
- This will trigger the release of insulin and reduction in the release of glucagon.
- PFKA2 will no longer become inhibited and instead FBPase2 will be phosphorylated by phosphoprotein phosphatase.
- This will convert F6P back into Fructose 2,6 biphosphate.
- The infinity of PFK to F6P will increase as well as reducing the inhibitory effect of ATP. This increases the rate of glycolysis.
- As a result, the rate of gluconeogenesis will be further reduced as lactate must be made from glycolysis first.
- This means the blood sugar level will decrease and this will trigger the release of glucagon.
- This marks the start of cycle 1.

Cycle 1 indicates the main cycle: as liver often have a high rate of gluconeogenesis so it needs to keep glycolysis low.

Cycle 2 will convert back to cycle 1.

 

A: ATP indicates high energy state and glycolysis is prevented to create too much energy, it is also only useful in other cells, not liver

B: Can be a correct answer, however, AMP only encourages glycolysis in other cells. The liver controls glucose concentration in blood so it can not wait until all energy has been depleted.

D: Glucagon has reverse effects on liver cells as it tells liver cells to stop glycolysis and save glucose for other cells
E: FBPase 2 is used to convert F2,6BP(which up regulates the process) into F6P

 

C: PFKA2 phosphatase remove the phosphate group from the PFKA2 which is the key enzyme in the up-regulation process, activating it

Question: Which drug increases bone deposition by osteoblasts and reduces absorption by osteoclasts?
Explanation:
Bisphosphonates - first line drugs. Alendronate reduces vertebral, wrist and hip fracture risk. Inhibits bone absorption by encouraging osteoclasts to die by apoptosis and so slows bone loss. May cause side effects such as osteonecrosis and bisphosphonate fracture.

SERM - Raloxifene - reduces vertebral fracture risk. Selective oestrogen receptor modulator. 

 

PTH - Teriparatide - recombinant parathyroid hormone. Triggers new bone formation. Risk of osteosarcoma.

Question: How does an increased PaCO2 affect ventilation?
OptionA:
CO2<-->H2CO3<-->HCO3- + H+, Hydrogen ions diffuse across the blood-brain barrier and are able to communicate with the Central Chemoreceptors. 

CCR stimulates the Dorsal Respiratory group to increase the frequency of inspiratory neurons sent to the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.

Action potentials along the Phrenic nerve increase, causing the diaphragm to contract more forcefully and frequently.
Increased Ventilation rate and depth of breathing.
OptionB:
CO2 diffuses across the blood-brain barrier to communicate with Central Chemoreceptors (CCR).

CCR stimulates the Dorsal Respiratory group to increase the frequency of inspiratory neurons sent to the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.

Action potentials along the phrenic nerve decrease so that the contraction of the diaphragm is less forceful. 

Decreased ventilation and depth of breathing
OptionC:
CO2<-->H2CO3<-->HCO3- + H+, Hydrogen ions diffuse across the blood-brain barrier and are able to communicate with the Central Chemoreceptors that the blood CO2 levels are too high. 

CCR stimulates the Dorsal Respiratory group to increase the frequency of inspiratory neurons sent to the ventral horn of the spinal cord.

Action potentials along the Phrenic nerve increase, causing the diaphragm to contract more forcefully and frequently.

Increased Ventilation rate and depth of breathing.
OptionD:
CO2 diffuses across the blood-brain barrier to communicate with Central Chemoreceptors (CCR).

CCR stimulates the Dorsal Respiratory group to increase the frequency of inspiratory neurons sent to the ventral horn of the spinal cord. 

Action potentials along the Phrenic nerve increase, causing the diaphragm to contract more forcefully and frequently. 

Increased Ventilation rate and depth of breathing.
Explanation:
H+ cannot cross the blood-brain barrier, CO2 can. 

Within the Cerebrospinal fluid CO2 + H2O--> H2CO3-->HCO3- and H+. The Central Chemoreceptors in the dorsal Medulla Oblongata will sense the decreased pH and subsequently increase their firing to the Dorsal Respiratory Group (located next to the Nucleus Tractus Solitarius).

The Dorsal Respiratory Group stimulate the Ventral Respiratory group, causing them both to increase the firing of inspiratory signals along their axons.

These axons communicate with the phenic nerve in the Ventral Root Ganglion due to the phrenic nerve being a MOTOR nerve. 

The frequency of Action potential along the phrenic nerve increases, increasing the contraction of the diaphragm.

An increase ventilation rate and the depth of breathing will cause increased expiration of Carbon Dioxide, therefore lowering the CO2 levels in the blood. 

 

This video is really helpgul in explaining this topic-    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fWBhmrrSPUk

Question:
Jasper is a farmer who likes to clay pigeon shoot at the weekend.

 

Each time he fires his shotgun it emits 155dB. He uses very old ear muffs which only reduce the sound by 35dB.

 

To the nearest second, how long is it theoretically possible to listen to this shotgun sound (with ear muffs) without causing hearing damage?
Explanation:
The correct answer is 14 seconds.

 

Explanation;

  • We can listen to 90 dB for 240 minutes (just a fact to know about)
  • For every 3 dB increase, this time (240 minutes) is halved

155 - 35 = 120

 

120 is 30 more decibels than the standard we are measuring from (90dB)

  • 30/3 = 10
  • Therefore we must half 240 ten times
  • In other words, 240/(2^10) (two hundred and forty divided by two to the power of ten)

This leaves us with 0.234375 minutes. When we multiply this by 60 we get 14 seconds

 

So we can listen to 120 dB for 14 seconds before hearing damage may occur.

Question: Diuretics are an effective way to treat hypertension and heart failure. Which diuretic works by blocking aldosterone receptors on the collecting duct and prevents sodium reabsorption and K+ excretion?

Furosemide is a loop acting diuretic which blocks Na+/K+/2Cl- pump on the loop of henle. This reduces ions being pumped out of the ascending limb into the medulla. The water concentration gradient in the medulla is reduced and less water is reabsorbed from the descending limb. This decreases blood pressure. 

Bendroflurethiazide blocks the Na+/Cl- pump on the DCT reducing water reabsorption, reducing blood pressure. 

Atenolol is a beta blocker
