Question:
An American man named Billy Ray Cyrus walks into your clinic. He's got an 'Achy Breaky Heart'. He tells you he feels like his heart 'might blow up' after exercise and even after light exercise he is breathless and nauseous.  

  1. What investigative tests would you conduct on Billy to come to a firm diagnosis?
  2. If you conclude he is suffering from stable angina due to coronary artery disease, what drugs may be prescribed?
OptionA:
Tests= ECG, coronary angiogram, PCI

Drugs= Alteplase, Bisoprolol, Ramapril
OptionB:
Tests= ECG, coronary angiogram, angioplasty

Drugs= Alteplase, Bisoprol, Ramapril, Furosemide
OptionC:
Tests= ECG, coronary angiogram, echocardiogram

Drugs= Bisoprol, Ramapril, Furosemide
OptionD:
Tests= ECG, coronary angiogram, angioplasty

Drugs= Bisoprol, Ramapril and Ibuprofen
OptionE:
Tests= ECG, coronary angiogram, echocardiogram

Drugs= Alteplase, Bisoprol, Ramapril, Midodrine
Explanation:
Investigative tests

Correct

  • ECG- ST depression is seen in a patient with myocardial ischemia. A patient presenting with stable angina will most likely have myocardial ischemia.
  • Coronary angiogram- Used to identify narrowing and occlusion of blood vessels, in this case specifically the the coronary blood vessels. X-ray using radio-opaque contrast dye.
  • Echocardiology- Ultrasound technique to identify chamber wall motion abnormalities, indicating myocardial ischemia and therefore coronary artery disease. Seen in patients with stable angina.

Incorrect

  • PCI (Percutaneous Coronary Intervention)/angioplasty- Two words for the same procedure. Performed on patients who are suffering an MI. Uses a balloon to open up a vessel which has been completely occluded by a thrombus, providing oxygenated blood to the myocardial to prevent myocardial ischemia and necrosis. Required ASAP in patients suffering from MI! Invasive procedure, could be used on this patient down the line but not usually performed on a patient presenting with stable angina. Lifestyle changes and pharmacological interventions are favoured. 

Drugs MOAs

Correct

  • Bisoprol- B1 adrenoceptor antagonist. Beta blocker which acts as a competitive inhibitor, preventing adrenaline/noradrenaline binding to B1-adrenoceptor reducing firing of SA node and heart rate. Therefore, reduced oxygen demand from myocytes, reduced myocardial ischemia, reduced symptoms (stable angina)
  • Ramapril- ACE inhibitor. Prevents conversion of angiotensin-> angiotensin 2. This results in vasodilation, reducing blood pressure and relieving pressure from the heart, reducing its oxygen demand, hypoxia and myocardial ischemia/necrosis.
  • Furosemide- Diuretic, reduction in fluid retention, more urination, reduces blood pressure and relieves pressure from heart, reducing its oxygen demand, hypoxia and myocardial ischemia/necrosis

Incorrect

  • Ibuprofen (Case 1)- Reversible competitive inhibitor of the cyclo-oxygenase domain of PGHS. NSAID that prevents AA + O2-> PGG2. Prevents production of prostaglandins which sensitise pain and inflammatory response.
  • Midodrine- Used to treat hypotension. Has a positive chronotropic effect (increases heart rate and blood pressure), the opposite of what this patient needs. Would lead to further myocardial ischemia and necrosis.
  • Alteplase- 'Clot Buster!'. A tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) which converts plasminogen to plasmin, which breaks down fibrin in a clot. This would be administered if someone was suffering from unstable angina, where a stable plaque has ruptured to form a thrombus. Alteplase would then break down a thrombus or part of a thrombus which has detached from the unstable plaque (embolism) via the MOA mentioned above. This would be ineffective in removing a stable plaque seen in stable angina. A clot hasn't formed around the atherosclerotic plaque in stable angina. A stable plaque is an accumulation of cholesterol and other lipids in the sub endothelium of a blood vessel, surrounded by a thick fibrous cap. An unstable plaque is one which has ruptured, the fibrous cap has been broken.

Question:
Carol, a 53 year old patient has been admitted to hospital after a very high fever, dizziness, nausea and vomiting. She has had dysuria and blood in her urine for the last few days. Upon examination her results were:

  • Heart rate: 115 bpm
  • Temperature: 38.2 degrees
  • Blood pressure: 95/68 mmHg

What is Carol's most likely diagnosis?
OptionA:
Carol is having an allergic reaction to something

Her mast cells have degranulated and histamine has been released

This has caused her symptoms and her examination results

She needs an anti-histamine quickly
OptionB:
Carol has a stomach bug 

Her body has tried to fight it off hence her fever and other symptoms 

She hasn't eaten or drank any water so her blood pressure is low 

She can go home with some paracetamol and wait until it passes
OptionC:
Carol has an upper UTI infection, maybe acute pyelonephritis 

The bacteria has leaked into her blood stream 

She is showing signs of sepsis due to over production of TNF-alpha

Carol needs antibiotics and fluids urgently
OptionD:
Carol is having a panic attack 

She's scared of the hospital and was worried her symptoms wouldn't go away 

You reassure her that she will be ok and discharge her
OptionE:
Carol has a UTI 

Her symptoms are just her body fighting it off 

With some antibiotics it will clear up in the next few days 

Carol can be discharged with some trimethoprim
Explanation:
The correct answer is C!

Carol is showing signs of sepsis. She is tachycardic, has a high fever and a very low blood pressure. These are caused by bacteria, from Carol's UTI, entering her blood stream. Her immune system has produced excess TNF-alpha which has increased vascular permeability too much, causing fluid to enter tissues and her blood pressure to drop. To compensate, her heart is beating faster in response to reduced blood flow in the carotid sinus and arch of aorta. Cytokines IL-1 have acted on the hypothalamus and caused a fever. Fluids need to be given urgently to restore blood pressure and a broad spectrum antibiotic is needed to fight the infection.

Question:
Which antibiotic is being described?

  • Used to treat haemophilus, legionella, chlamydia, mycoplasma and toxoplasma infections 
  • Binds to the 50S subunit on the ribosome 
  • Inhibits protein synthesis 
  • Bacteriostatic and bactericidal effects 
  • Contraindicated in those with QT elongation
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Macrolides are lipid soluble so are used to treat intracellular infections such as those caused by mycoplasma and chlamydia. They bind to the 50S subunit on the ribosome and event elongation, inhibiting protein synthesis. They have bacteriostatic and bactericidal effects. An ADR is QT elongation and therefore they are contraindicated in those with a long QT segment.

Question: Mrs Smith is a 40 year old patient with type 2 diabetes and a sustained blood pressure of 145/92. You plan to start her on some medication to lower her blood pressure. Which drug would be the most appropriate for Mrs Smith?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A!

Patients under 55 years old or with type 2 diabetes should be treated with an ACE inhibitor or angiotensin II receptor blocker as the first line of treatment for hypertension such as ramipril or losartan. If the hypertension persists, a calcium channel blocker should be added, such as diltiazem. If hypertension still persists, a diuretic may be added such as furosemide.

 

Patients over 55 or patients with an African or Caribbean origin should be started on a calcium channel blocker as the first line of treatment. If it persists, an ACE inhibitor or angiotensin II receptor blocker may be added. If there is further resistance then a diuretic may be added.

Question:
John Doe is a 15 months old male with CD4+ T cell lymphocytopenia resulting in a low CD4+ cell count. He is suffering from pneumocystic pneumonia. Laboratory findings confirm that baby is HIV negative. But DNA test confirm that he has a mutation in one of the gene which encodes for immune receptor.
Which mutation is most likely in John Doe given the information above?
OptionA: - Mutation in CIITA (MHC class II transactivator)
Explanation:
CD4+ cell is activated by antigen presentation with MHC class II receptor and since CIITA is involved in the expression of MHC class II, so A is the answer. 

MBLII is involved in the activation of the mannose lectin pathway of the complement system. 

CBR is involved in activation of the classical pathway of the complement system and act as opsonin to enhance phagocytosis. 

But both pathway does not lead to the antigen presentation and is not associated with the proliferation of the CD4+ cell, so both B and E is incorrect. 

HLA-A and HLA-C codes for MHC class I and since MHC class I interact with CD8+ cell and not with CD4+ cell and involved in the proliferation of CD8+ cell and not CD4+ cell. So mutation in HLA-A and HLA-C would not cause CD4+ cell count to be low so C & D is incorrect.
Tags: Genes, Principles of Immunity, Immunity, Immunology

Question:
The phases of bone healing involve , 1. Haematoma 2. Inflammation 3.Granulation 4.Callus 5.Considlation 6. Remodeling 

 

 Which of the following doesn't belong to the Callus stage ?
OptionB: fracture ends are united by a sleeve of vascularised granulation tissue and cartilage
OptionC:
Calcium is deposited in the cartilage and 
osteoblast start to produce a seam of osteoid across the fracture
Explanation:
E is correct - this is part of the remodeling stage .

All other points are part of The callus stage :

 

Islands of cartilage appear (especially near the periosteum)


The fracture ends are now united by a sleeve of vascularised granulation tissue and cartilage = provisional callus

 

Calcium is deposited in the cartilage


Osteoblast start to produce a seam of osteoid (organic proportion of bone matrix) across the fracture

 

Most of the new bone formation so far has been subperiosteal but now endochondral ossification is established and adds to the new bone.


The callus calcifies and the ends unite with bony callus.

Question: Will is a long distance runner and has come to the GP with pain on his proximal medial tibia. He says it gets much worse when he flexes his leg or changes direction when running. He hasn't had any trauma to his knee on either side and the pain has progressed overtime. On examination he has pain on internal rotation. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The Pes Anserine tendon is formed by gracilis, sartorius and semitendinosus muscles. These muscles all insert onto the medial proximal tibia and inflammation of the pes anserine tendon causes pain. The pain is worse when flexing the leg as this is a function of gracilis, sartorius and semitendinosus. There is also pain on internal rotation as these muscles also medially rotate. Pes Anserine tendonitis is normally caused by repeated flexion and adduction of the knee such as during running. Synovial fluid leaks out of the bursa which also increases pain. 

B- Less likely as there hasn't been any trauma to the knee and MCL damage is often caused by lateral trauma to the knee

As the femoral artery and femoral vein exit the canal they become the popliteal artery and popliteal vein

Question:
What is the correct order for the process of vomiting?

  1. Reverse peristalsis in the duodenum
  2. Relaxation of the stomach and the pyloric sphincter 
  3. Inhibition of respiration 
  4. Contraction of the anterior abdominal wall muscles and diaphragm
  5. Expulsion 
  6. Rising of the soft palate and closing of larynx to prevent entry into nasopharynx or lungs 
  7. Lower oesophageal sphincter opens and pyloric sphincter closes
Explanation:
The vomiting process is:

  1. Inhibition of respiration 
  2. Rising of the soft palate and closing of the larynx to prevent entry into nasopharynx or lungs 
  3. Relaxation of the stomach and the pyloric sphincter 
  4. Reverse peristalsis in the duodenum
  5. Contraction of the anterior abdominal wall muscles and diaphragm 
  6. Lower oesophageal sphincter opens and pyloric sphincter closes 
  7. Expulsion

Question: When saliva passes through the duct cells it is modified. Which of the following is false about this modification?
Explanation: The duct cells are impermeable to water and so when saliva passes through them, none is removed, Na+ is removed in exchange for K+ moving in and Cl- is removed in exchange for HCO3- moving in. The solution becomes more hypotonic as the saliva moves through the duct cells and osmolality increases

Question:
You are working with a radiographer who shows you an image of a MRCP (magnetic resonance cholangio-pancreatography) scan of a patient with suspected cancer. The scan confirms the presence of a tumour in the biliary tree, specifically at the bifurcation of the common hepatic duct. 
What is the correct name for this type of tumour?
Explanation:
A - This is a type of cancer that originates in mucus producing glandular cells. In the upper GI tract, this can be in cells in the oesophagus, the gall bladder or stomach (adenocarcinoma accounts for around 90% of stomach cancers).   

B - This is the name for any tumour found in the bile duct. 
C - This is a type of cancer that originates from the hepatocytes of the liver, not the cells of the hepatic duct. It is the most common form of liver cancer.
D- Correct. This is the name given to a tumour that is situated at the bifurcation of the common hepatic duct in the liver. They can cause blockage of the duct, which can be seen in the image below. 

 

This is taken from the imaging of the upper GI tract and hepatobiliary system lecture.

Question: Jake who is 3 years old has come to the GP with his Mum. When he arrived, Jake wouldn’t stop screaming and shouting in the waiting room. To try and stop his behaviour his Mum took away his favourite toy. What type of strategy is this?
Explanation:
This is an example of negative punishment. 

Negative punishment is taking away something good in response to bad behaviour 

Positive punishment is giving something unpleasant in response to bad behaviour 

Negative reinforcement is removing something unpleasant in response to good behaviour 

Positive reinforcement is giving something good in response to good behaviour

Positive is always giving

Negative is always removing

Question:
You want to assess the cortical processing of pain in a patient with a post stroke lesion . You apply a noxious stimulus to the patient . After you talk to the patient, they state they do not want the noxious stimulus applied again. However, the patient does not describe the stimulus as pain .

 

What system in the Patient may be effected?
Explanation:
Well done A  is correct 

 

- The lateral pain system consists of the lateral thalamic nuclei and the primary and secondary somatosensory cortices.  This system mediates sensory and discriminative aspects of pain . Hence in this example, if there is a lesion to any of the areas involved, the sensory discrimination of pain will be absent 

 

- The medial pain system - Consists of the Angular cingulate cortex ,insula and the medial thalamic nuclei . This system mediates the emotional and cognitive evaluation of pain . In this example , this  system was still intact so the patient still associated the pain as an unpleasant (did not wan the stimulus applied again ) 

 

Taken from the Psychology of acute pain and analgesia  - case 1

Question: Haemochromatosis can present as symptoms of tiredness, weight loss, weakness and joint pain as the result of a build up of iron levels in the body. On a physiological level, what damage does iron accumulation cause?
Explanation:
Haemochromatosis results in both oxidative stress and free radicals.

Excess iron -> increased iron deposition in tissues -> initiates free radical reactions when not protein bound -> oxidative damage to proteins, lipids and nucleic acids

Question: How does hepcadin prevent oxidative damage and free radicals?
Explanation: Hepcadin is an enzyme produced by the liver to prevent oxidative damage and free radicals by preventing iron transport and absorption

Question: Which of the following is not an indication of an inflamed airway?
OptionB: Infiltration of the lamina propria by white blood cells
OptionD: Hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the submucosal glands
Explanation:
B is due to the activation of dendritic cells and macrophages. The lamina propria consists of loose connective tissue to allow cells to be close to but not enter the airway which avoids limiting the capacity of the ciliated epithelium.

 

C is not an indication of inflammation in the airway. The mucus acts to trap pathogens and also contains defensins (secreted by epithelial cells) and lysozymes which destroy bacteria

Question:
A patient has come into Clinic complaining of a tight chest pain which occasionally  radiates to the left  arm. The pain is brought on by physical activity  and seems to be worse in the cold winter  weather. You suspect the patient has stable angina .

 

Why might their pain be worse in the cold ?
Explanation:
A- Redistribution of blood usually will occur after eating food ,  more blood flow is needed in the gut  for the process of digestion to take place . This may reduce coronary blood supply . Myocardial blood Supply wont be able to meet myocardial demand  (i,e during exercise ). Hence pain caused by stable angina may be made worse after eating 

 

B- Well done , this is correct . In the cold , blood vessels that supply the skin usually constrict to prevent any heat loss . This peripheral vasoconstriction will result in increased myocardial oxygen demand, so the heart can pump harder to overcome peripheral resistance. If supply cant meet demand , symptoms of stable angina will be brought on 

 

C- Ventricular hypertrophy ( could be due to stenosis and regurgitation etc. )  means that there is greater myocardial oxygen demand . Once again if the demand cant be meet by supply , this results in stable angina 

 

D- anemia will effect myocardial oxygen supply and the same principle of demand and supply would apply here

Question:
Terry is a keen drinker and loves to party. In a recent discussion with his GP about a non-related issue, it is discovered he has an alcohol dependence problem.

 

He mentions that he has tried to quit before but it wasn't successful and he now feels less confident about trying to quit again.

 

What type of effect has Terry experienced?
Explanation:
Correct answer is B - the abstinence violation effect occurs after a single relapse which lowers perception to self efficacy, lowers mood and the person loses belief that they can successfully quit if they try again

 

Craving is not really correct because it's to do with addiction whereas this question refers to a relapse in alcohol addiction (relapse comes after withdrawal symptoms so it results in negative reinforcement, not a craving for alcohol)

 

All of the other answers were covered in the Health Compromising Behaviours plenary in Case 6.

Question: Which of the following is not a cause of amnesia?
Explanation:
A is the correct answer.

Although forgetfulness and taking longer to recall memories is seen in ageing, significant memory loss such as that in amnesia, is not a normal part of ageing. Ageing is a risk factor for amnesia as it is a risk factor for conditions such as Alzheimer's disease.

 

Causes of amnesia:

  • Temporal lobe surgery: e.g. H.M.
  • Herpes simplex encephalitis: e.g.  Clive Wearing.
  • Anoxia/hypoxia: e.g. perinatal hypoxia as a cause of developmental amnesia.
  • Korsakoff syndrome: from chronic alcoholism.
  • AD: amnesia complicated by additional symptoms.

This is taken from the memory and memory systems lecture in case 5.

Question:
A 72 year old female has come into A&E by ambulance as she was found by a neighbour on the floor for a considerable amount of time. The patient complains of right sided hip pain and after an AP x-ray she is diagnosed with a NOF # (neck of femur fracture) that is unstable and displaced (above the intertrochanteric line). She is admitted to T&O where her treatment is to be decided promptly.

 

What is the most suitable treatment for this patient?
Explanation:
This is a little beyond what we were taught but its a bit of surgical fun and I believe there were mentions of hip fracture repairs in the case 1 lectures. Well done if you got this right!

 

A - Conservative management wouldn't be suitable as this is a displaced hip fracture in an elderly patient so needs urgent surgical intervention. (If not treated quickly there are serious risks of sepsis, DVT and mortality in elderly patients as well as poorer prognosis in getting back to normal).

B - Cannulated screws is better used in the treatment of stable minimally displaced hip fractures

C - This is the correct answer. Hemiarthroplasty are generally good as you don't need to do anything to the acetabulum so reducing the risk of dislocation and is a smaller operation compared with THR. A total hip replacement could also be carried out especially in older patients and with osteoporotic changes to the hip.

D - ORIF wouldn't be suitable as this fracture is displaced (This is basically what cannulated screws is doing)

E - Trochanteric  osteometry is used for dislocated hips

 

If you want to read more Geekymedics is good or teachmesurgery

Question: Which of the following options correctly describes the exogenous pathway of lipid metabolism?
OptionA:
1. Lipids are produced by the liver in the form of LDL from fatty acids and cholesterol which travels in the blood through the capillaries
2. LDL loses some triglycerides through lipoprotein lipase action, resulting in release of free fatty acids into the adipose tissue
3. ILD is produced and taken up into the liver
4. Liver secretes VLDL which transports cholesterol to the peripheral tissues
5. LDL receptors inn the liver itself regulates the LDL concentration in the blood
OptionB:
1. Fat is absorbed through the small intestine and chylomicrons are formed 

2. Chylomicrons travel in the blood through capillaries 

3. Lipoprotein lipase removes some of the triglyceride by hydrolysing them into fatty acids and glycerol

5. Free fatty acids are then stored in the adipose tissue and chylomicrons get smaller to form intermediate-density lipoproteins (IDL)

6. Chylomicron remnants are taken up by the liver and the liver releases fatty acids and cholesterol
OptionC:
1. Fat is absorbed through the small intestine and chylomicrons are formed
2. Chylomicrons travel in the blood through capillaries
3. Lipoprotein lipase removes some of the triglyceride by hydrolysing them into fatty acids and glycerol
5. Free fatty acids are then stored in the adipose tissue and chylomicrons get smaller to form very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL)
6. Chylomicron remnants are taken up by the liver and the liver releases fatty acids and cholesterol
OptionD:
1. Lipids are produced by the liver in the form of VLDL from fatty acids and cholesterol which travels in the blood through the capillaries 

2. VLDL loses some triglycerides through lipoprotein lipase action, resulting in release of free fatty acids into the adipose tissue 

3. IDL is produced and taken up into the liver 

4. Liver secretes LDL which transports cholesterol to the peripheral tissues 

5. LDL receptors in the liver itself regulates the LDL concentration in the blood
OptionE:
1. Fat is absorbed through the small intestine and micelles are formed
2. Chylomicrons travel in the blood through capillaries
3. Lipoprotein lipase removes some of the triglyceride by hydrolysing them into fatty acids and glycerol
5. Free fatty acids are then stored in the adipose tissue and chylomicrons get smaller to form very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL)
6. Chylomicron remnants are taken up by the liver and the liver releases fatty acids and cholesterol
Explanation:
Micelles are formed before fat absorption -> bile salts break down large globules of fat into smaller micelles-> absorbed by enterocytes where monoglycerides, free fatty acids and glycerol are recombined to produce triglycerides (which can then be packaged into chylomicrons)

 

D is the endogenous pathway of lipid metabolism

Question:
Read the following description of a type of fatty acid and then select the correct answer which matches:

 

"This fatty acid has one C=C double bond and the hydrogen atoms attached to the carbon atoms on the double bond are on the same side"
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - the fatty acid described in the question is a cis- fatty acid and it is unsaturated

 

 

Cis means the hydrogens are on the same side (commonly known as Z-isomers in chemistry - zee zame zide)

 

Trans means the hydrogens are on opposite sides (commonly known as E-isomers in chemistry - entgegen which means "opposite" in German)

 

Saturated - No C=C double bonds (saturated with hydrogen atoms)

Unsaturated - at least one double bond (polyunsaturated means more than 1 double bond)

 

I formed this question from the Biological Macromolecule Structure plenary from PCS 1

Question: Review the image of a protein below. Into which structure is this protein arranged?
Explanation:
The image shows a protein arranged in a tertiary structure. This is because disulphide bonds are present between certain molecules within the chain.

  • Primary structure is the order of amino acids within the chain
  • Secondary structure is related to alpha helices and beta pleated sheets
  • Tertiary structure is very important because it is the factor which makes enzymes specific - interaction of the secondary structure (disulphide bonds etc.)
  • Quaternary structure - monomers from tertiary structure come together - an example of this would be haemoglobin which contains 4 haem groups

Quinary doesn't exist as far as I know.

 

I wrote this question to address one of the learning outcomes for PCS 1 involving the "Biological Macromolecule Structure" plenary

Question:
Janine is currently one hour into a sponsored marathon.

 

What is the main metabolic process being used to provide her with energy to run?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer

  • From 0s to 10s creatine phosphate is used
  • From 10s to 60s anaerobic glycolysis is being used
  • From 1 minute to 3 hours, aerobic glycolysis is being used (this is the right answer because she is one hour into the run)
  • Lipolysis is undertaken at 3 hours or more during exercise

Question: During saliva formation, Acetylcholine triggers muscarinic receptors (M3) to stimulate what type of G protein?
Explanation:
D is correct!

 

Gq (stimulatory)

Gs (stimulatory)

Gi (inhibitory)

Ga= made up ?

 

During salivation parasympathetic and sympathetic NS can alter the saliva content 

 

this question was based off the parasympathtic NS (as ACh and M3 were mentioned in the stem.

1. Acetylecholine binds to muscarinic receptors on the basolateral membrane of acinar cells

2. M3 receptors stimulate G1 proteins that get rid of GDP and bind to GTP (activated form)

3. Gq stimulates phospholipase C enzyme which breaks down PIP2 into ; DAG + IP3

4. IP3 stimulate increase in Ca2+ levels inside cell that activate CAM kinases (DAG activates protein kinase C)

5. CAM kinase phosphorylate certain channels on apical membrane of acinar cell; which increases substances; H2O, Na+, Cl-, K+ and HCO3-

6. volume of substances inside acinus have increased

Question: Which of the following foramina allows for the passage of the medulla?

The foramen magnum allows for the passage of:

  • Medulla
  • Vertebral arteries 
  • Dural veins 
  • Anterior and posterior spinal arteries

Foramen ovale- CNV3 Mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve 

Foramen rotundum- CNV2 Maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve 

Foramen Lacreum- distal part of the internal carotid arteries

Question: what is the name of the condition where there's a persistent opening between two major blood vessels leading from the heart?
Explanation:
C is correct!

PDA is the condition.

 

ductus arteriosus is the opening that's a normal part of a baby's circulatory system in the womb that usually closes shortly after birth. 

When it closes, it becomes the ligamentum arteriosus, if the opening doesn't close, it becomes a condition; PDA.

A PDA allows blood to flow directly from the aorta into the pulmonary artery and to the lungs. This extra amount of blood flowing into the lungs strains the heart and increases blood pressure in the lung's arteries (giving a symptom of a heart murmur)

Question: Mr Smith has come to A&E after being hit by a cricket ball on the side of his head. The region is identified as the pterion of the skull And brain scans show an extra dural haemorrhage. Which blood vessel is most likely to be damaged?

Sven is a 63 year old male who likes to occasionally drink on the weekend. He has come to the doctor with the following symptoms:

  • Pain in upper right quadrant/epigastric region
  • Yellowing of the sclera
  • Slight yellow tinge to skin
  • Dark urine and pale stool

Before you send him for testing to confirm your suspicions, what is the most likely type of hyperbilirubinaemia based on the above factors?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D

  • E does not exist as far as I know (it wasn't on the practical anyway)
  • The answer must be conjugated because unconjugated bilirubin is bound to albumin which cannot pass into the urine
  • It either has to be hepatic or post-hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia
  • Given he hardly drinks, post hepatic is likely the cause which could be due to gallstones or a tumour blocking the biliary tree

Question: On a post-mortem brain slice which has been stained using Weigert’s Stain, what colour would the corpus callosum be?
Explanation: Weigert‘s stain stains lipids a dark colour. The corpus callosum is made up of lipid myelinated axons so this appears dark on this type of stain. This was from the Functional Anatomy of the brain lecture

Question: What sensations does the 'Dorsal Column Medial Leminscus' pathway convey?
OptionB: Fine touch, vibration, pressure, two-point discrimination and proprioception
OptionC: Fine touch, temperature, pressure, two point-discrimination and proprioception
Explanation:
A - The lateral spinothalamic tract actually carries these sensations 

B - Correct! Well done wooooo! :) 
C - I put this one in to catch you out. The DCML does not carry temperature sensations, rather the lateral spinothalamic tract does. 

D - The anterior spinothalamic tract actually carries these sensations. 

E - Carried by the spinocerebellar tracts

Question: Which layer of skin is responsible for UV protection?
Explanation:
Correct answer is E - the stratum basale is responsible for UV protection

 

A-C - responsible for waterproofing

Question:
A male 21-year-old patient attends his local GP due to nausea and a fever over the last few days, he's also complaining of having a belly ache.  Upon further questioning, the patient reveals that he was involved in a sexual encounter with two other men about 7/8 weeks ago and no condoms were used. Upon examination of the abdomen the GP notices tenderness in the right upper quadrant and believes the patient is showing signs of jaundice. The GP arranges for the patient to have an FBC, LFT, U+Es and an STD test. 

 

The results of the LFTs indicate the following: 

- elevated plasma conjugated bilirubin 

- elevated urine urobilinogen 

- elevated AST and ALT 

 

The STD test is negative.

 

What is the most likely cause for those abnormalities?
Explanation:
This question presents a lot of information. 

The patient is male having unsafe sex with other men - HIV or hepatitis B 

The patient has a belly ache - there is a clear difference in medical knowledge with this patient therefore describing the abdomen as the belly

The fact the GP notices right UQ tenderness makes it likely that there is something related to the liver and the jaundice noticed provides further suggestion for that. 

Therefore at this point GP has ordered the tests 

STD test is negative so its not HIV - the FBC may have shown if there was HIV as well if there had been alterations in the numbers of RBCs and WBCs 

The LFTs are abnormal - therefore we know its not the pancreas for definite. 

the pattern of abnormalities indicates hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia - therefore suggesting hepatitis is the most likely cause of the 5 answers available. There were other potentials but in this scenario we just used hepatitis. 

If the patient had presented with steatorrhea as well, gallstones would have been the more likely answer as it would have indicated a blockage in the biliary tree at some point - if the blockage had been at the hepatopancreatic duct then it could have also suggested pancreatitis. 

 

But today it was hepatitis - the casual unprotected sex with other men was the major hint for this scenario.

Question: what colour is stercobilin during the bilirubin pathway?
Explanation:
A is correct!

 

Stercobilin is a bile pigment and is one end-product of heme catabolism.

 

As conjugated bilirubin is water soluble, it's excreted w/ bile into small intestine through the common bile duct. Near the end of the small intestine, conjugated bilirubin is converted into urobilinogen by intestinal bacteria. Urobilinogen is lipid solube, 10 % is reabsorbed by blood bounded to albumin to liver (to where it's converted to yellow urobilin- to give urine it's yellow colour). The other 90% is oxidised by intestinal bacteria to give stercobilin it's brown colour (which is excreted by body to give faeces the brown colour).

 

to summarise;

RBC-> haem component->  biliverdin (green) -> bilirubin (yellow)-> urobilinogen (colourless)-> stercobilin (brown)-> urobilin (yellow)

Question:
Barry is a 55 year old male who has been rushed to A&E with a suspected heart attack.

 

He has chest pains and elevated cardiac troponins. The ECG shows ST elevation in leads V3 and V4.

 

Which coronary artery is likely to be occluded?
Explanation:
Correct answer is A

Question:
Jerry is an alcoholic and has come into the CDAT clinic. The addiction nurse asks him how much he drinks a day in order to establish his risk as an alcoholic.

 

He replies "I drink four half-litre cans of 5% lager, three times a day"

 

Calculate how many units of alcohol this equates to per day
Explanation:
Correct answer is 30 units. This is calculated using the equation given in the CDAT asynchronous slides.

 

%ABV x volume (ml) / 1000

 

Each lager is 5% and 500ml. Using this equation it works out to 2.5 units per can.

 

2.5 x 4 x 3 = 30 units

Stanley is a 23 year old male who has just returned from a long stay in Somalia, Africa, conducting aid work which involved helping local farmers.

 

He presents with upper right quadrant pain and yellowing of the sclera.

 

Before sending him for any tests, you make an educated guess that he has contracted hepatitis.

Explanation: Correct answer is E - as discussed in the Global Perspectives plenary, Hep. E can be contracted through working with animals.

Question:
Josephine has come to see the GP about an unrelated issue to this question. Before the doctor decides to put her on some medication, he decides to do a liver function test (LFT).

 

The blood test only shows an isolated rise in ALP whilst everything else is normal.

 

What is the most likely cause of this?
Explanation:
Correct answer is B - an isolated increase in ALP is indicative of a problem unrelated to the liver; this could be bony metastases, vitamin D deficiency, recent bone fractures

 

This is because ALP is also found in bone so it is non-specific to the liver.

 

I found Geeky Medics very useful to help interpret LFTs: https://geekymedics.com/interpretation-of-liver-function-tests-lfts/

Question:
You an F1 are assessing a patients liver test results. From the results you deduce :

 

- raised urine conjugated bilirubin 

- raised urine urobilinogen

- raised AST and ALT 

 

Suddenly from nowhere the consultant pops out and asks you what the most likely diagnosis is . What is the most likely answer ?
Explanation:
C- well done C is correct . 

  • This occurs when conjugated bilirubin begins to leak from hepatocytes into the bloodstream due to hepatocellular damage. Damage may be caused by factors such as  viral hepatitis .
  • As are result, all of the factors mentioned in the question would be observed as well as raised plasma conjugated bilirubin . 
  • (this can be distinguished from Post-Hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinemia as  urine urobilinogen IS present.)
  • (this can be distinguished from Hepatic Unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia as urine conjugated Bilirubin IS present ) 

A- Pre-Hepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia occurs when there is a high production of bilirubin , the liver will become overwhelmed and fail to conjugate bilirubin and excrete it. A good way to identify this would be a drop in hemoglobin with normal levels of plasma and urine conjugated bilirubin 

 

B- Hepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia- occurs when the liver is damaged resulting in decreased conjugation and excretion of bilirubin. May be as a result of a deficiency of the enzyme involved in conjugation (Gilberts syndrome etc.). A good way to identify this would be no urine conjugated bilirubin . 

 

D- Finally Post-Hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinemia occurs when there is an obstruction in the bile duct . This may be caused by Gall stones, cancers etc. A good way to identify this would be low or no (if a complete block ) Urobilinogen , as there is no bilirubin getting into the small intestine  .

If there is complete block you are likely to notice 

 

1. Dark urine 

2. Pale stool (no stercoblin )

 

 

Elevated ALP - suggests cholestasis (flow of bile in liver blocked )

Question: Whilst on placement you meet a 22 year old female patient complaining of pain when urinating, lower abdominal pain and increased urinary urgency and frequency. After investigation, you find that there are white blood cells and bacteria. Which of the following would be the best diagnosis?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer as the symptoms are indicative of a urinary tract infection. Females are at a greater risk of UTIs due to having a shorter urethra (around 3-4cm in length) which has a closer proximity to the anus than men. Incidence increases with increased sexual activity and also in post-menopausal women as a result of hormonal and microflora changes. 

 

Symptoms more likely associated with chlamydia:

- pain upon urination 

- unusual discharge 

- abdominal pain 

(decreased likeliness of increased urinary frequency and urgency)

 

Symptoms more likely associated with pyelonephritis:

- similar symptoms to cystitis in addition to:

- flank pain 

- high fever 

- malaise 

- confusion/ restlessness 

- nausea 

*UTIs are most commonly caused by E.coli bacteria 

 

Symptoms more likely associated with trichomoniasis:

- strawberry cervix in women 

- itching, redness, soreness of genitals 

- discharge with an unusual (fishy smell) which can be clear, white, frothy, green or yellowish 

 

In men:

- itching or irritation inside the penis 

- burning after urination or after ejaculation 

- discharge from the penis 

 

Symptoms more likely associated with gonorrhoea:
- pain when urinating 

- increased vaginal discharge 

- vaginal bleeding between periods 

 

In men:

- burning sensation when urinating 

- white/yellow/green discharge

- painful or swollen testicles

Question:
Mrs Appleby is currently experiencing severe back pain which is exacerbated at work due to having to lift heavy items. She has decided to see the GP.

 

As the GP you prescribe this patient with fentanyl, an opioid analgesic. She asks you about the method of action of this medication.

 

You explain that it acts on opioid receptors through a G coupled protein but you can't remember which one.

 

Select the correct GPCR which opioids act on:
Explanation:
Gi is the correct answer - i for inhibitory

  • Opioids interact with mu, delta or kappa receptors which are Gi coupled
  • Along with other neuronal effects, this decreases intracellular cAMP which is normally responsible for modulating release of nociceptive neurotransmitters such as substance P
  • Answers D and E do not exist

Question:
Daniel has come into the CDAT clinic with an alcohol addiction. After the doctor takes his history, Daniel asks why he has become addicted.

 

You explain that cravings involve the mesolimbic pathway in the brain which starts from the ventral tegmental area in the midbrain.

 

Which nucleus does this pathway travel to in the brain?

Question: You are a 3rd year medical student on placement in Accident and Emergency. The consultant you are shadowing has asked you to carry out an ECG on a 56-year-old male who has come in with chest pain. When you look at the ECG read you see ST elevations in leads V3 and V4. You immediately inform the consultant that this patient is having a ST elevation myocardial infarction involving which coronary blood vessel?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer.

 

A: leads V5 and V6 correspond to the diagonal branch of the left anterior descending.

C: leads V1 -> V6 corresponds to the proximal left anterior descending. 

D: leads I and aVL correspond to the proximal left circumflex.

E: leads II, III  and aVF correspond to the right coronary artery.

Question: You are revising for S1 with your friend Dominic, who is a cardiology wizard. He begins quizzing you on your knowledge of ECGs, the bit of cardiology you haven't revised yet. Explanation:

Question:
John, a 53-year-old man presents with yellow skin and appears to have dark urine and pale stool. Upon investigation, he is found to have elevated levels of conjugated bilirubin in the serum and a negative urine urobilinogen. 

 

What could be the cause of John's jaundice?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer as the findings suggest the jaundice is post-hepatic. Bile duct blockage is the only post-hepatic cause

 

A - hepatocellular cause, would present with an increase in conjugated and unconjugated bilirubin in the serum and positive urine urobilinogen.

 

B - pre-hepatic cause, would present with increase in unconjugated bilirubin in the serum and positive urine urobilinogen

 

C - CORRECT


D - hepatocellular cause, would present with an increase in conjugated and unconjugated bilirubin in the serum and positive urine urobilinogen.

 

E - pre-hepatic cause, would present with increase in unconjugated bilirubin in the serum and positive urine urobilinogen

Question: Why do Pregnant Ladies have an increased risk of contracting a UTI?
OptionA: High levels of Oestrogen causes smooth muscle relaxation -> Bladder not emptying fully
OptionB: High levels of Progesterone causes smooth muscle relaxation -> Bladder not emptying fully
OptionC: Changes in natural flora as a result of pregnancy
OptionD: Bladder alter shapes as a result of the uterus increasing in size causing vesicoureteral reflux
Explanation:
In health the bladder empties 100% preventing pooling of bacteria.

 

A - See D for explanation

 

B - When progesterone relaxes the smooth muscle (detruser muscle) of the bladder it does not fully empty this allows bacteria to replicate.

 

C - Change in natural flora occurs post menopause due to decreased oestrogen leading to altered pH of natural flora leading ladies at an increased risk of UTI's. Prior to menopause oestrogen helps keep natural flora alive and maintain a typically acidic environment which is protective.

 

D - Vesicoureteral Reflux is associated more so with Pyelonephritis as urine travels up the Ureter to the kidney, this does not happen as a result of pregnancy.
Tags: female reproductive system, Hormones, Case 4, Kidneys

Question:
You are on placement at a GP surgery. The GP has asked you to review some notes for a Miss P who has recently been discharged from the hospital and will be attending the GP surgery this morning for a medicine review and a check up on her recovery. 

You look at her ECG below and notice that there are tall tented T-waves in leads V3, V4, V5 and V6. You think about potential differentials for such an ECG finding. Which of the following is an appropriate differential for this case?
OptionE: Non-specific finding in a wide range of conditions
Explanation:
A: generalised electrolyte imbalance is associated with flattened T waves.

B: correct. Tall tented T waves are also associated with hyperacute STEMIs.

C: hypokalemia is associated with biphasic T waves.

D: ischaemia is associated with biphasic T waves and flattened T waves.

E: inverted T waves are a non-specific finding in a wide range of conditions.

 

The Geeky Medics website has some useful images of these different T waves (https://geekymedics.com/how-to-read-an-ecg/).

Question: Sarah comes to an appointment for a liver biopsy. She is worried and stressed and explains that she has also developed a continuous dry cough. After examining her you also see she has some finger clubbing. Sarah has the biopsy and a few days later receive the results. What is Sarah’s diagnosis?
Explanation: This is alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency which is an autosomal dominant condition. The lack of alpha-1-antitrypsin leads to reduced inhibition of elastases in the lungs and alveoli. This causes increased destruction of alveoli and emphysema symptoms seen in Sarah. The liver biopsy shows nodules caused by accumulation of alpha-1-anti trypsin material. This was in the Liver in Health and disease plenary

Question: A patient attends his GP as he has been experiencing severe shoulder pain over the last few months - the patient thought he was just putting too much strain on his shoulder as he's a shelf stacker at a supermarket. The doctor examines his upper back muscle bulk and concludes that there is muscle wastage between the medial border of the scapula and the thoracic spinal column, people with a cervical rib can also experience this type of muscle wastage. Which muscles are most likely wasting?
OptionB: Rhomboid major, rhomboid minor and levator scapulae
Explanation: Dorsal scapular nerve entrapment can occur for multiple reasons the hint provided with this question was the fact that people with a cervical rib can experience it - as dorsal scapular nerve entrapment is a cause of thoracic outlet syndrome. The fact that the patient is experiencing shoulder pain can be due to the dorsal scapular nerve entrapment - therefore rhomboid major, minor and levator scapulae are most likely to be affected.

Question: A patient attends the A&E department after being involved in a gangland fight. The patient claims that they were hit with a baseball around the shoulder. Upon examination there is evidence of swelling and bruising along the shoulder, the patient is asked to lift his arms from by his side to above his head (abduction), he complains of pain over the angle of 120 degrees. Which joint is most likely injured?
Explanation:

In the range of 60 - 120 degrees indicates a subacromial problem (in or around the glenohumeral joint)  

Over 120 degrees = a problem of the acromioclavicular joint

Question: Katie has returned from her gap year travelling in Asia and has started to feel unwell. She describe fever, nausea and says she’s vomited a few times. Asking more about her gap year you find out that she worked on a farm. Blood tests reveal she has acute hepatitis. Which is the most likely cause of Katie’s hepatitis?
Explanation: Hepatitis E is also found in pigs and since Katie worked on a farm, this is the most likely cause of her hepatitis. This can lead to acute hepatitis but not chronic. Hepatitis E and A are both spread by faecal oral transmission and is seen in those who have travelled internationally, are immunosuppressed, farmers and butchers (E) and MSM.

Question: Before going travelling, Mike is recommended to get a hepatitis A vaccine as he is going to a high risk country. You give him an active immunisation. Which of the following correctly describes active immunisation?
OptionA: Prepared from an active whole hepatitis A virus
OptionB: Prepared from inactivated whole hepatitis A virus
OptionE: There isn’t a vaccine for hepatitis A
Explanation:
An active immunisation is prepared from inactivated whole hepatitis A virus. It is given as an intramuscular injection and then a booster is given at 6 months for lifelong immunity. They are recommended for people: travelling to endemic areas, patients with chronic liver disease, MSM, sewage workers and staff in institutions.

Passive immunisation is used with active post exposure and is called human normal Immunoglobulin (HNIG) 

There are vaccines for hepatitis A and B (&D) but no vaccines for hepatitis C or E.

Question:
The abdominal splanchnic nerves provide sympathetic innervation to the abdominal viscera.

 

Identify the correct option:

Explanation:
A is correct

Question:
Piers has come to clinic with a large wound on his arm after taking the corners too fast on his motorbike.

 

He asks why his arm appears so inflamed, to which you explain the body's response and the different immune cells involved.

 

However, you forget which immune cell is responsible for attraction of neutrophils to the site of damage.

 

Select the correct immune cell responsible for this function:
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - below are the steps (in order) involved in inflammation

  • DAMPs or PAMPs recognised by mast cells
  • Prostaglandins and histamines are then released by mast cells
  • Histamines and prostaglandins make endothelium more leaky
  • Clotting factors and other white cells attracted to region
  • Monocytes secrete cytokines such as TNFα and CXCL8
  • TNFα causes vasodilation
  • CXCL8 attracts neutrophils to site of damage
  • Neutrophils clear up debris
  • Monocytes trigger apoptosis of activated neutrophils to end inflammation

Question: Matt comes to the GP with yellowing of the sclera, general malaise and a change in skin colour. He says he is stressed about his exams and hasn’t been eating too well. You check his notes to find he has Crigler Najjar syndrome. What is Matt’s most likely diagnosis?
Explanation: Hepatic unconjugated jaundice is seen in patients with Crigler Najjar syndrome or Gilbert‘s syndrome. These patients have a mutated or deleted UGT1A1 enzyme. This enzyme is responsible for conjugating bilirubin to glucuronic acid and therefore, a lack of this enzyme leads to a build up on unconjugated bilirubin in the blood, causing symptoms of jaundice. This happens in times of stress or starvation. Raised AST and ALT can be seen and a small raise in GGT.

Question:
Sarah is prescribed clopidogrel after experiencing a thromboembolism due to a long-haul flight from the USA.

 

As she is handed the prescription, she asks you about the mechanism of action of this medication.

 

Select the correct mechanism of action for clopidogrel:
OptionA: Stops Ca2+ ion traffic through L-type voltage gated channels in nodes - negative chronotrope and negative inotrope
OptionC: Inhibitor of the platelet P2Y12 ADP receptor
OptionD: A recombinant form of tissue plasminogen activating factor (tPA) - tPA mediates the conversion of plasminogen to plasmin which rapidly dissolves clots by causing fibrinolysis
OptionE: Modified in blood to produce NO - this is a vasodilator and stimulates cGMP signalling cascade
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - clopidogrel is an antiplatelet medication

 

A - calcium ion channel blocker

B - beta blockers

D - alteplase (fibrinolytic)

E - GTN sprays

 

See the Case 2 pharmacology light bulb for more detail :)

Question:
Jemma is a 50-year-old female who has been diagnosed as having acute coronary syndrome (ACS).

 

She has just switched GP and this is the first time you have met this patient. In the notes you can see she was prescribed Apixaban by the previous GP.

 

What is the mechanism of action of Apixaban?
OptionA: Inhibitor of the platelet P2Y12 ADP receptor
OptionB: Competitive inhibitor of vitamin K epoxide reductase which is required to mediate carboxylation of clotting factors II, VII, IX and X
OptionC: Dose-dependently inhibits the mixed Na+/K+ inward ‘funny' current in the SA node, reducing pacemaker automaticity / impulse frequency
OptionD:
(i) Stimulates guanylyl cyclase to increase cGMP and thus reduce Ca2+ entry into vascular smooth muscle cells.
(ii) Activates K+ATP channel effluxer, hyperpolarising cells thus preventing voltage-gated Ca2+ channel activity.
OptionE: Highly selective reversible inhibitor of Factor Xa which prevents the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin
Explanation:
Correct answer is E - Apixaban acts on the coagulation cascade, therefore it is an anticoagulant drug

 

A - Clopidogrel

B - Warfarin

C - Ivabradine

D - Nicorandil

Question:
Mrs Garland is an elderly patient who was admitted overnight with a suspected myocardial infarction. It turned out to be an episode of stable angina after she felt severe crushing chest pain whilst doing the gardening.

 

You are the junior doctor reviewing the notes from the previous night, which state that the patient should be given an anticoagulant but due to the "doctor's handwriting" you cannot read the name of the medication to prescribe.

 

Which of the following medications has an anticoagulant effect?
Explanation:
Correct answer is A

  • Apixaban is an anticoagulant drug - it is a highly selective reversible inhibitor of Factor Xa which prevents the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin
  • Examples of other anticoagulant drugs would be heparin and warfarin (these all have different M.O.As)

Clopidogrel (& aspirin) - antiplatelet drugs

 

Alteplase (clot buster) - fibrinolytic

 

Propranolol - beta blocker

 

Diltiazem - calcium channel blocker

Question: Mr Morris works at a supermarket stacking the shelves, he starts experiencing some pain in his elbow and notices it's swollen and red and its warm. He attends his local GP who notices the swelling around the lateral epicondyle he decides to ignore it as it believes he's just banged his elbow. However, a few hours later Mr Morris begins to feel numb in his posterior forearm and thumb. The doctor says that he has (1) condition which has lead to the compression of (2) nerve. What are the correct options for the condition and nerve?
Explanation:
Cubital tunnel syndrome is as a result of ulnar nerve entrapment however the ulnar nerve doesn't innervate the thumb so cannot be this.

 

Tennis Elbow is where there is inflammation of the tendon around the lateral epicondyle of the humerus leading swelling and therefore compression of the radial nerve which passes via the lateral epicondyle as it moves anterior to posterior forearm - it must be this as the radial nerve supplies the innervation to the thumb and posterior forearm. 

 

Carpal tunnel syndrome is not due to the elbow so isn't the answer 

 

Tendonitis is possible but as its the ulnar nerve that entrapped it cannot be the answer

Question: John comes into the GP complaining of hearing loss. You carry out the Rinne test and John says he can hear the sound louder through the air in both ears. You then place the turning fork in the centre of the forehead and John tells you the sound is louder in his right ear. What type of hearing loss is John experiencing?
OptionA: Conductive hearing loss in the right ear
OptionB: Conductive hearing loss in the left ear
OptionC: Sensorineural hearing loss in the left ear
OptionD: Sensorineural hearing loss in the right ear
OptionE: Mixed sensory and conductive hearing loss in the left ear
Explanation:
This is sensorineural loss in the left ear.

 

The Rinne test shows that John could hear the turning fork louder when it was placed next to his hear than when it was placed on the bone behind his ear- this is a positive Rinne test confirming that there is no conductive hearing loss. 

The Weber test showed that the sound was heard louder in the right ear. This could suggest conductive hearing loss in the right ear or sensorineural hearing loss in the left ear. Because Rinne’s test ruled out conductive hearing loss, it must be sensorineural loss in the left ear

Question:
Fill in the blanks: 

The superficial palmar venous arch, carries blood into the (1) vein in the lateral forearm and into the (2) vein in the medial forearm. 

Around the cubital fossa, vein (1) branches blood into vein (3), vein (3) then meets with vein (2). 

 

Vein (2) then continues up the medial arm, whilst vein (1) also continues up the lateral arm. 

 

Vein (2) then meets with the brachial vein to form vein (4). 

 

Vein (4) meets with vein (1) to form the subclavian vein.
OptionA:
1) Basilic vein 

2) Subclavian vein 

3) Ulnar vein 

4) radial vein
OptionB:
1) Cephalic vein 

2) Ulnar vein 

3) Median cubital vein 

4) Axillary vein
OptionC:
1) Cephalic vein 

2) Basilic vein 

3) Median cubital vein 

4) Axillary vein
OptionD:
1) Radial vein 

2) Ulnar vein 

3) Brachial vein 

4) Axillary vein
OptionE:
1) Brachial vein 

2) median cubital vein 

3) basilic vein

4) Subclavian vein
Explanation:
Here the hint is superficial palmar venous arch NOT deep palmar venous arch 

 

Superficial palmar venous arch involves drainage into Cephalic vein (lateral forearm) and the basilica vein (medial forearm), the cephalic vein then branches into the median cubital vein (cubital fossa) and continues as a cephalic vein (lateral arm). The Basilic vein meets the median cubital vein where the continue together as the basilic vein (medial arm). The Brachial vein drains into the basilic vein which then forms the axillary vein. The cephalic vein then drains into the axillary vein to form the subclavian vein. 

 

If it had been the deep palmar venous arch drainage then it would have been: 

Radial vein and ulnar vein drain come together forming the brachial vein. The brachial vein drains into the basilic vein (medial forearm) and then forms axillary vein and then combines with the cephalic vein to form the subclavian veins.

Question:
Petra is revising skeletal muscle contraction when she suddenly remembers that the S1 examiners like to ask about which bands/zones change length during contraction.

 

Which of the following combinations is correct?

 

You may use the image below to help you
OptionA:
A bands - length does not change during contraction

 

I bands - shorten during contraction

 

H zone - shortens during contraction
OptionB:
A bands - length does not change during contraction

 

I bands - shorten during contraction

 

H zone - stays same length
OptionC:
A bands - shortens during contraction

 

I bands - shorten during contraction

 

H zone - stays same length
OptionD:
A bands - length does not change during contraction

 

I bands - length does not change during contraction

 

H zone - shortens during contraction
OptionE:
A bands - shortens during contraction

 

I bands - length does not change during contraction

 

H zone - length does not change during contraction
Explanation:
Correct answer is A

  • A bands - thick filaments (myosin) and overlapping thin filaments (actin) - length does not change when muscle contracts (layers slide over each other but does not change length)
  • I bands - thin filaments only (this does shorten during contraction)
  • H zone - thick filaments only (no myosin heads) - this shortens during contraction
  • All of these changes bring the Z lines closer together

Question: Regarding cross-bridge cycling in smooth muscle, what is the job of the calcium-calmodulin complex (CaCM) in the series of reactions for contraction?
OptionA: Reacts with troponin to form a CaCM troponin complex, allowing muscle contraction
OptionB: Activates phospholipase C which cleaves PIP2 into IP3 and DAG - IP3 opens calcium ion channels causing Ca2+ efflux into cytoplasm
OptionE: Hydrolyses ATP to ADP + Pi and phosphorylates myosin light chain
Explanation:
Correct answer is D - some answers were made up so it's easier if I simply explain smooth muscle contraction (I have copied this from the Muscle Contraction plenary in PCS 1)

  1. Relaxed state: myosin heads are present in high-energy myosin-ADP-Pi state
  2. When Ca2+ levels rise, 4 X Ca2+ binds to calmodulin (CM) to form CaCM complex
  3. CaCM complex activates Myosin Light Chain Kinase (MLCK)
  4. Activated MLCK hydrolyses ATP to ADP + Pi and phosphorylates myosin light chain
  5. Myosin heads now bind to actin and cross-bridge cycling/muscle contraction begins
  6. Cross-bridges cycle until Ca2+ levels fall leading to myosin light chains being dephosphorylated by myosin phosphatase and muscle relaxation

https://teachmephysiology.com/histology/tissue-structure/muscle-histology/smooth-muscle/

Question: what substance stimulates the enzyme in the rate limiting step of cholesterol synthesis?
Explanation:
C is correct!

 

For this question you had to recognise that the rate-controlling enzyme of cholesterol synthesis is the HMG CoA Reductase in the liver which controls the "rate limiting step". 

HMG CoA reductase catalyse the conversion of HMG-CoA to mevalonate (a necessary step in the biosynthesis of cholesterol)

 

insulin stimulate the HMG-CoA enzyme

 

cholesterol inhibit the HMG-CoA enzyme by activating proteolytic enzymes

glucagon also inhibit the HMG-CoA enzyme (which oppose insulin)

 

important to note that cholesterol synthesis requires NADPH!

 

Also, statins are competitive inhibitors of the rate limiting enzyme

Question: What is the net production of ATP from one molecule of glucose in glycolysis?
Explanation:
Glycolysis only produces a net of 2 ATP.

 

Both the Hexokinase and PFK1 regulatory steps require 1 ATP each. Then the phosphoglycerate kinase step and the final pyruvate kinase step produce 1 ATP each. Don't forget we have 2 molecules of Glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate.

 

So before the two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are made, 2 ATP has gone into glycolysis. After G3P is made, each of the two G3P molecules produces 2 ATP which equals 4 ATP.

 

4 ATP - 2 ATP = 2 ATP (net gain)

Question: Which drug would be best for managing an asthmatic patient presenting with primary hypertension?
Explanation:
A is incorrect because bisoprolol is a beta-blocker and these are contraindicated in asthma patients.

B is almost correct - GTN is used to treat hypertension - however, patients can build up a tolerance to nitrates without a 'drug holiday,' so this is not the most ideal choice.

C is correct! Diltiazem is a calcium-channel blocker and is best in this situation, as the patient is asthmatic and therefore contraindicated for beta blockers.

D is incorrect - furosemide can be used to treat hypertension, but this is often in cases where there is kidney or heart impairment, but the patient is presenting with idiopathic hypertension.

 

An asthmatic patient could also be given ACE inhibitors such as enalapril, but some of these patients may develop an ACE-I related cough.

Question: Whilst on placement at a GP surgery you meet Mrs L who has recently had a child. Mrs L had a difficult labour and delivery, which resulted in her child suffering nerve damage. As a result, the infant has paralysis of their intrinsic hand muscles, flexors of the wrist and fingers in their left forearm. This paralysis means the infant has a "claw hand", seen below. Upon observation of the child, you also notice that they have Horner's syndrome. What nerve had been damaged in this child?
Explanation:
A is the correct answer. 

In this infant there has been damage to the inferior brachial plexus (C8, T1), resulting in Klumpke's palsy. This can be caused by a difficult breech delivery. Symptoms include:

  • Paralysis of their intrinsic hand muscles, flexors of the wrist and fingers.
  • Claw hand
  • C8/T1 dermatome numbness.
  • Horner's syndrome, which is characterised by miosis (constriction of the pupil), ptosis (drooping of the upper eyelid), and anhidrosis (absence of sweating of the face). This occurs in Klumpke's palsy due to the damage to T1.

B: Median nerve damage is associated with carpal tunnel syndrome.

C: Radial nerve damage would result in wrist drop.

D: Superior brachial plexus damage causes Erb's palsy, in which the upper limb is typically in the "waiter tip" position, with the shoulder adducted and internally rotated, the elbow extended and pronated, the wrist flexed. This damage can also occur during birth.

E: Ulnar nerve damage would result in the claw hand presentation, but it does not explain the presence of Horner's syndrome in this patient.

Question: A patient presents to the A&E department with a suspected myocardial infarction. You decide to test the troponin levels in their blood in order to inform your diagnosis. Which type(s) of troponin would be measured and high if your diagnosis is correct?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B - TnI and TnT!

 

The cardiac troponin complex is made up of TnI, TnT and TnC. However, the types most easily measured in labs by chemiluminescent immunoassay are TnI and TnT. 

 

More info: It is the cardiac damage form hypoxia from ischaemia which causes the troponin complex to be released. This is measurable in blood. Cardiac troponin is biochemically different from skeletal troponin. Troponin complex is present in everyones blood so intervals are created based on normal levels for 99% of the population in order to identify abnormal levels.

Question: You are a GP and a patient complains to you of increased shortness of breath when doing mild exercise. You ask them to do a spirometry test and find they have an FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.9. What could be a possible extra-pulmonary cause of this?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A - kyphoscoliosis. This is where the chest wall is slanted to one side, reducing the possible total volume of the lungs. 

 

The increased FEV1/FVC ratio indicates the patient has a restrictive lung disease as they can expel a large proportion of air in the first second of exhalation showing the issue is the total amount of air in the lungs (restrictive disease) as opposed to being able to get the air out of the airways (obstructive disease). 

 

B - interstitial lung disease: this is a restrictive lung disease but is a pulmonary cause, and the question asked for an extra-pulmonary cause

C - asthma: this is an obstructive lung disease. 

D - COPD: this is an obstructive lung disease. 

E - bronchiectasis: this is an obstructive lung disease (airways of the lungs become abnormally widened, leading to a build-up of excess mucus that can make the lungs more vulnerable to infection). 

 

Other possible correct answers would include cardiac issues (eg cardiomegaly/ cardiac tamponade), respiratory muscle issues (eg due to neuromuscular disease) and obesity (eg adipose tissue compresses thorax/ obesity hypoventilation syndrome/ decreased diaphragm descent).
