Question:
Kate is playing hockey, without her shinpads, a hockey ball hits her shin.

 

She is in great pain and her leg is starting to swell and bruise. She can no longer bear weight on the leg and cannot dorsiflex her ankle or extend her toes.

 

The team captain thinks she might have sustained a fracture to one of the bones in her leg.

 

What compartment in the leg is most likely to sustain compartment syndrome and what is this compartment innervated by?
Explanation:
B. This is the correct answer as anterior compartment syndrome is most common in the lower limb. Additionally, you can work out that it is anterior compartment as she cannot dorsiflex her ankle and extend her toes.

 

This is caused by:

- Fractures causing bleeding --> pressure within compartment building up --> compression of blood vessels

- Stops arterial supply to the leg which can lead to potential loss of tissue 

 

TREATMENT: Fasciotomy (the fascia is cut to relieve tension/pressure)

CAUSES: (Overuse was the example said in lecture)

Acute-

  • broken bone/crash injury 
  • plaster cast/tight bandage to limb before it has stopped swelling
  • Burns (skin become scarred + tight)
  • surgery to damaged/blocked vessel

Chronic-

  • Young people who do regular repetitive exercise (overuse)

Info from: 

- Lower Limb lecture

- https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/compartment-syndrome/#:~:text=Chronic%20compartment%20syndrome%20usually%20occurs,a%20whole%20group%20of%20muscles. 

 

A- This compartment and innervation have the action of - extension of thigh @ hip; flexion of leg @ knee.

B- 

C- This compartment and innervation have the action of - Plantarflexion of ankle; flexion of toes; inversion 

D- This compartment and innervation have the action of - Adduction of thigh @ hip.

E-This compartment and innervation have the action of -  Eversion of ankle; weak plantarflexion.

Question: Which of these is not a function of an astrocyte?
Explanation:
D is correct!

A - involved in regulating the concentrations of Ca2+, Cl- and water in the extracellular space

B - Converts glucose to lactate which is released into EC space and taken up by neurones

C - Excess glutamate can be toxic to neurones

D - CSF is made my the Ependymal cells in the choroid plexus

E - Astrocytes in the chemosensory areas of the brainstem are highly sensitive to pH. They release ATP to stimulate chemosensitive neurones that cause increases in breathing
Tags: Autonomic Nervous System, Basal ganglia, Brain, Head and neck, Case 5

Question: The botulinum toxin is produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum, which is found in soil, dust and river sediments. The toxin is associated with food poisoning and a resulting paralysis. Botulinum toxin prevents the activation of cholinergic receptors on the postsynaptic membrane, but how does it achieve this?
OptionA: Acetylcholine is released into the synaptic cleft, but Botulinum toxin terminates it before it can bind to receptors.
OptionB: Botulinum toxin deactivates receptors on the postsynaptic membrane.
OptionC: Botulinum toxin terminates acetylcholine in the presynaptic membrane.
OptionD: Cleaves SNARE proteins, meaning that the SNARE complex cannot assemble. Hence, acetylcholine release into the synaptic cleft is inhibited.
OptionE: Cleaves SNARE proteins. This doesn't prevent SNARE complex assembly, but the resulting SNARE complex is non-functional. Hence, acetylcholine release into the synaptic cleft is inhibited.
Explanation:
1. Botulinum toxin binds to the cholinergic nerve terminal by its heavy chain domains forming a toxin-receptor complex
2. Botulinum toxin is internalised into an intracellular vesicle
3. The light chain performs highly specific cleavage of SNARE proteins.

4. Cleavage of individual SNARE proteins does not prevent SNARE complex formation, but results in a non-functional complex. Cleaved SNARE proteins are competent for facilitating docking of the secretory vesicle with the synaptic membrane, but fusion of the vesicle is compromised.
5. Release of ACh is inhibited
Tags: Membranes, Nervous System, Neurons, Bacteria, Neurotransmitters

Question: There is a white matter tract connecting Wernicke’s and Broca’s areas. What is the name of this tract and what type of tract is it?
Explanation:
The Arcuate fasciculus connects Wernicke‘s and Broca’s areas which are both found in the left hemisphere of the brain. This means the Arcuate fasciculus is a association tract as it connects 2 regions in the same hemisphere

Commissural tracts- connect an area in one hemisphere to the same region in the opposite hemisphere eg anterior commissure connects the left and right temporal lobes 

The other type of tract is a projection which includes afferent or efferent fibres

Internal capsule- white matter connecting the thalamus and cerebral cortex

Question:
Arachidonic acid (AA) is cleaved from the membrane phospholipids by the action of Phospholipase A2 (PLA2). It is described as a polyunsaturated 20:4 omega-6.

 

What does this mean?
OptionA:
It contains only C-C single bonds.

It has 20 carbon atoms in total with 4 bends

Omega-6 is just a type of omega.
OptionB:
It contains C-C double bonds.

It has 20 carbon atoms in total.

The first double bond is located 4 carbons from the start of the molecule.

There are 6 C-C double bonds in total.
OptionC:
It contains only C-C single bonds.

It has 20 carbon atoms in total with 6 bends

Omega-4 is just a type of omega.
OptionD:
It contains C-C double bonds.

It has 20 carbon atoms in total.

The first double bond is located 6 carbons from the start of the molecule.

There are 4 C-C double bonds in total.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

 

Polyunsaturated = contains C-C double bonds
Omega-6 = first double bond encountered is 6 carbons from the start of the molecule

20:4 = The molecule has 20 carbons and 4 C-C double bonds

Question:
Katara brings Aang to Dr. Iroh, the best doctor in the Fire Nation. Aang has a fever of 40 degrees Celcius. He is sweating and shivering and seems to be disoriented. Katara explains to Dr. Iroh that Aang's fever has started in the morning.

Dr. Iroh thinks back to his medical school days when he learned about basic immunology and are cytokines. He knows that some cytokines cause fever, but which of those pyrexic cytokines are also produced by osteoblasts to stimulate osteoclast formation?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D

I don't know if we need to know this for S1 but I came across it when I did my reading on IL1, 6, and TNF alpha. Also if I'm wrong please do correct me.

 

All these 3 are fever producing (pyrexic), promote lethargy, secreted by macrophages and are cytokines 

 

IL 1 - secreted by macrophages and monocytes, epithelial cells, and endothelial cells

IL 6 - secreted by macrophages mainly. Also produced by osteoblasts stimulating osteoclast formation, secreted by adipocytes and SM cells in tunica media 

TNF alpha - secreted by macrophages mainly, also secreted by mast cells, endothelial cells, cardiac myocytes. TNF alpha is also called cachexin as it causes wasting (cachexia) in cancer.

Question: Whilst on placement in Accident and Emergency, you see a 25-year-old female with jaundice. The consultant shows you the patient's blood test results, from which you conclude she has hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinemia. The consultant asks you to name a potential cause of the patient's jaundice based on this minimal information. Which of the following could you give as your answer to the consultant?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer.

Other answers that you may have given the consultant are primary biliary cholangitis/cirrhosis or viral/toxic hepatitis.

How does Dubin-Johnson disease cause conjugated hyperbilirubinemia?

Causes a deficiency of MRP2 🡪 build-up of conjugated bilirubin in hepatocytes 🡪 upregulates MRP3 🡪 transports conjugated bilirubin into the blood, rather than bile canaliculi 🡪 conjugated hyperbilirubinemia

 

A: This is a cause of pre-hepatic hyperbilirubinemia. Other causes include rhesus incompatibility at birth, drug-induced haemolytic anaemia, defects in red cell membranes, defects in haemoglobin production, sickle cell, defects of red cell metabolism.

 

B: This can cause hepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia. It is when an individual lacks the conjugating enzyme.

 

D: This is a cause of post-hepatic hyperbilirubinemia. Other causes include biliary stricture (narrowing), cancer, primary biliary cholangitis, drugs, acute hepatocellular damage, e.g. infection.

 

E: This is a cause of hepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia. This syndrome causes there to be a mild deficiency of the conjugating enzyme. This is found in 5% of the population, and these individuals may become jaundiced upon stress. Other causes include a lack of the conjugating enzyme (Crigler-Najjar syndrome), drugs, 'physiological jaundice of the newborn’ (immature liver).

Question: Which of the following correctly describes type 2 respiratory failure and the appropriate treatment for it?
OptionA: Hypoxaemia with normal or low CO2 - treat with ventilation
OptionC: Hypoxaemia with normal or low CO2 - treat with oxygen therapy
OptionE: Hypoxaemia with hypercapnia - treat with oxygen therapy
Explanation:
D is the correct answer. C would be correct for type 1 respiratory failure

 

Type 2 respiratory failure involves hypoxaemia and hypercapnia, meaning PaO2 <8kPa and PaCO2 >6kPa. It is primarily caused by hypoventilation, which can be due to pulmonary causes such as obstructive sleep apnoea, or things such as reduced respiratory drive caused by CNS damage, or neuromuscular problems such as diaphragmatic paralysis. It can also be caused by chest wall deformities. It is treated with some kind of ventilation, either non-invasive or invasive

 

Type 1 respiratory failure involves hypoxaemia with normal or low CO2 levels. This is caused primarily by V/Q mismatch, or oxygenation failure. This can be caused by things such as pneumonia, pulmonary oedema, pulmonary embolism, emphysema or pulmonary fibrosis. Essentially, air is still able to enter the alveoli, but for some reason the oxygen cannot actually enter the blood. This is mainly treated with oxygen therapy
Tags: lung function, Case 3, Respiratory disease, respiratory system

Question: A 65 year old male patient presents to A&E and you notice that he has his elbows propped on the arms of the chair. He appears to be breathing quickly with an audible wheeze upon examination. You can also see that he has tar staining on his fingers and his wife tells you that she has noticed that he has lost weight over the past year. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
In this case, the symptoms listed in the stem are classic indicators of COPD. A patients may also present with progressive breathlessness and exercise intolerance, a productive cough, oedema (as a result of pulmonary hypertension due to vasoconstriction of the vessels in response to hypoxia). COPD is an umbrella term encompassing chronic bronchitis and emphysema.

 

Chronic bronchitis is characterised by a cough and sputum on most days as a result of hypertrophy of submucosal glands, mucus hypersecretion (goblet cell hyperplasia) and mucociliary dysfunction . This leads to inflammation and airway obstruction in the airways.

 

Emphysema is characterised by dilatation of the the alveoli and destruction of their walls as a result of the inactivation of proteases, allowing an increase in neutrophil elastase and proteases which degrade elastin. This leads to a reduction in gas exchange and a loss in lung elasticity.

 

Pneumonia is a radiological diagnosis of a restrictive lung disease due to consolidation in the alveoli (where fluid/pus replace the air). A patient with pneumonia would present with a productive cough, confusion, fever, chills, shortness of breath and chest pain (as examples)

 

Bronchiectasis results from widening of the airways which become inflamed with thick mucus. Patients will usually present with a persistent productive cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, haemoptysis (coughing up blood) and finger clubbing 

 

Apergillosis is an infection caused by the fungus aspergilus which causes inflammation in the lung. A patient may present with fever and chills, haemoptysis, shortness of breath, headaches or eye symptoms. 

 

Lung cancer can be caused by dysplasia (abnormal development of cells) within the lung epithelium as a result of exposure to carcinogens. A patient will usually present with a persistent cough, haemoptysis, persistent breathlessness, unexplained tiredness and weightless, and aches or pain when breathing or coughing.

Question:
Mr Jones, 46, is an alcohol dependent patient in your practice. In a recent consultation you note that he has lost weight, and is appearing confused. 

Which of the following vitamins is he likely to be deficient in?
Explanation:
Vitamin B1, thiamine, is the answer. Up to 80% of people with chronic alcoholism develop thiamine deficiency because ethanol reduces gastrointestinal absorption of thiamin, thiamin stores in the liver, and thiamin phosphorylation. As well as this alcohol dependent people frequently don't eat fully nutritious diets. 

Early B1 deficiency is often seen with anorexia and confusion as symptoms. As it develops it can cause beriberi, peripheral nerve wasting, but this is not often seen. 

Vitamin B2 deficiency: presents with skin disorders, hyperemia (excess blood) and edema of the mouth and throat, angular stomatitis (lesions at the corners of the mouth), cheilosis (swollen, cracked lips), hair loss, reproductive problems and other issues. 

Vitamin B12 deficiency: deficiency can potentially cause severe and irreversible damage, especially to the brain and nervous system. At levels only slightly lower than normal, a range of symptoms such as fatigue, lethargy, difficulty walking (staggering balance problems), depression, poor memory, breathlessness, headaches, and pale skin, among others, may be experienced.

Vitamin C: Deficiency is seen as Scurvy

Vitamin E: Can cause a form of anaemia in which red blood cells rupture (haemolytic anaemia)

Most frequently these deficiencies are caused by malabsorption.

Question: You are seeing your local GP about a bacterial infection you have recently acquired. They prescribe you an antibiotic, and explain that this class of drug blocks the enzyme usually responsible for unwinding supercoiled bacterial DNA prior to replication. What class of antibiotic have you been prescribed?
Explanation:
A - Correct, quinolones prevent bacterial replication by inhibiting the enzyme that usually unwinds supercoiled bacterial DNA. An example would be Levofloxacin. 

B - Beta- lactams prevent the production of new bacterial walls by binding to penicillin-binding-proteins (PMPs), preventing cross linkages being formed between peptides in the wall. These are only effective for gram positive infections, such as staphylococcus. An example of this class would be Penicillin, but remember some bacteria contain beta-lactamase enzymes and so are resistant to beta-lactams. 

C - Tetracyclines are effective for a wide range of bacterial infections, and prevent bacterial protein synthesis by acting on the 30S ribosome subunit and outcompeting tRNA for the "A" binding site. An example would be Doxyclycline. 

D - Macrolides, such as Azithromycin, inhibit translocation in the 50S ribosome, thus preventing protein synthesis. They can have both bacteriostatic and bactericidal effects. 

E - Aminoglycosides act on gram negative bacteria and block protein synthesis by acting on the 30S ribosome subunit. An example would be Gentamicin. 

 

Bactericidal = kills bacteria 

Bacteriostatic = prevents growth/replication of bacteria but does not necessarily kill bacteria  

 

This information is from the Case 4 pharmacology lightbulb.

Question:
Skeletal Muscle contraction is caused by the binding of calcium ions to Troponin molecules, which in turn, exposes the actin binding sites to form cross bridges with the myosin heads.

 

What causes the 'power stroke' that pushed the myosin heads back and bring the two Z lines closer together?
OptionA: The binding of ATP to myosin heads.
OptionB: The binding of ADP and Pi to myosin heads.
OptionC: The dissociation of ATP from the myosin heads.
OptionD: The dissociation of ADP and Pi from the myosin heads.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

 

The binding of ATP to myosin heads causes a detachment of the myosin to the thin filaments (actin).

Myosin itself has 'ATP-ase' activity. The splitting of ATP into ADP and Pi 'recocks' the myosin head, so it is able to bind to actin and pull the z lines even closer.

Question:

Question: When would atherosclerosis become clinically overt?
Explanation:
stages of atherosclerosis: 

1. LDL infiltration into sub endothelial layer and phagocytosis and oxidation by macrophages - only a few ISOLATED foam cells present

2. more LDL accumulation, the fat is still intracellular, but instead of having ISOLATED foam cells, there is now a conglomerate, forming a fatty streak

3. intermediate lesion: this is the stage where some of the earlier macrophages have undergone apoptosis and the fat is now extracellular as well as intracellular in the still living macrophages

4. atheroma: fibroblasts have moved in and are beginning to border off the fatty core to prevent its spread in the sub endothelial layer. The plaque may now be clinically overt as it has grown to a stage where it could cause occlusion of the arteries or is liable to rupture if this fibrous cap breaks down

5. fibroatheroma. Fibrous cap has been established around the extracellular necrotic core, there is also migration of VSMC into the subendothelial space within the tunica intimal, these are now known as myointimal cells. At this stage calcium may also begin to be deposited on it

6. complicated lesion: the cap may break down, vasa vasorum may rupture, or cholesterol crystals may pop through and erode the plaque leading to thrombus formation on the top.

A: incorrect, ischemia refers to inadequate O2 supply for demand. therefore it does not indicate cardiomyocytes death, note: myocardial infarction would though (MI)
B: stable angina doesnt lead to myocardial infarction therefore no troponin is released

D: correct

E: unstable angina is not associated with myocardial infarction. There can be changes to the ECG, but there is not cardiomyocyte death. Unstable angina leads to myocardial ischemia not infarction.

Question: Becca is a 20-year-old student. She presents at the sexual health clinic wanting a prescription for the contraceptive pill. Before doing so, the nurse takes her blood pressure which is 115/85. What is her mean arterial blood pressure?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C.

MAP = 1/3(systolic pressure) + 2/3(diastolic pressure)

MAP = 1/3(115) + 2/3(85)

MAP = 95 mmHg

 

 

2/3rds of the cardiac cycle is spent in diastole with the remaining 1/3rd spent in systole therefore the equation is made to be more heavily weighted towards diastole.

Question:
You are on placement when asked to carry out a cranial nerve examination on Mr Smith. 

 

The examination is going well until you come to the eyes. You notice that Mr Smith's right eye is resting in a down and out position. He is unable to track your finger comprehensively with his right eye when you trace out an H in the air in front of him. You suspect he may have a lesion to a cranial nerve.

 

Which cranial nerve do you suspect?
Explanation:
The correct answer is C! Well done if you got it right!

 

There are six muscles in the orbit. 4 receive motor innervation from CN-III (Oculomotor). These four muscles are superior rectus, medial rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique. If there is a lesion to this nerve, then superior oblique (innervated by CN-IV) and lateral rectus (innervated by CN-VI) will be unopposed. This creates a net vector in the direction of down and out. Because these muscles are immobile in Mr Smith's right eye from the lesion, he cannot comprehensively track an H shape when you are examining the cranial nerves supplying the optic muscles.

 

The Olfactory nerve (CN I) is involved in the sensory innervation of our smell, so has no control over the movement of the eye.

 

The Optic nerve (CN II) is involved in the sensory innervation of our sight, and has no motor function.

 

The Trochlear nerve (CN IV) gives motor innervation to the superior oblique muscle. A lesion to this nerve would present with the eye not being able to look down when turned medially. 

 

The Abducens nerve (CN VI) gives motor innervation to the lateral rectus muscle. A lesion to this nerve would present with the eye not being able to turn laterally and abduct.

 

A good way to remember the cranial nerves is by using the mnemonic Oh Oh Oh To Touch And Feel Very Good Velvet Ah Heaven.

Olfactory, Optic, Oculomotor, Trochlear, Trigeminal, Abducens, Facial, Vestibulocochlear, Glossopharyngeal, Vagus, Accessory, Hypoglossal. 

 

Another mnemonic to remember whether a cranial nerve is providing sensory, motor, or both types of innervation is Some Say Marry Money But My Brother Says Big Brains Matter More.

Sensory, Sensory, Motor, Motor, Both, Motor, Both, Sensory, Both, Both, Motor, Motor.
Tags: Eye and vision, Orbit, Case 5, Cranial Nerves

Question:
In a clinical trial of 1200 patients, 575 are given a placebo and 625 patients are given cyclizine to prevent nausea post operatively. Of those given the placebo, 450 patients experience nausea. Of those given cyclizine, 425 patients do not experience nausea.
What is the best estimate for the number needed to treat in order to prevent the nausea of 1 patient?
Explanation:
C is the correct answer.

 

First, calculate the occurrence of nausea for both groups.

Placebo risk: 450/575 = 0.78

Cyclizine risk: 200/625 = 0.32

 

Secondly, calculate the absolute risk ratio.

ARR: 0.78 - 0.32 = 0.46

 

Then calculate the number needed to treat.

NNT: 1/0.46 = 2.17

 

Finally round it up to the nearest whole number as you always treat a whole person. This is done so that, for the value calculated, you will help at least 1 additional person. 

Therefore = 3

 

The tutorial for the number needed to treat is in the case 4 statistics folder.

Question:
A clinical trial studied the effects of a new sleeping pill on medical students right before their S1 exam.

 

A total of 1500 students took part - 800 were given the medication and 700 were given a placebo. Of those that took the medication, 375 said that it didn't work, and of those that took the placebo, 255 claimed it worked for them.

 

Calculate the number needed to treat (NNT):
Explanation:
Correct answer is D - more information on number needed to treat can be found in the Case 4 statistics folder

 

Explanation:

  • So to work this out we must calculate for both the placebo and the medication, the percentage (in decimal form) that it didn't work for
  • For the medication, it is 375/800 = 0.47 and for the placebo we must remember to do 700-255 first, and then 445/700 = 0.64
  • We must then work out the Absolute Risk Difference which would be 0.64-0.47 (just remember to do the larger number - smaller number) which gives us 0.17
  • Then to work out NNT we must do 1/0.17 and that gives us 5.88, rounded up to 6.

Question: You are stressed and your sympathetic nervous system starts to influence your blood pressure. Which molecules may be secreted?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B - angiotensin II and endothelin! 

As the question indicates sympathetic nervous system control, you were looking for agents that cause vasoconstriction. 

Endothelin I and angiotensin II and vasoconstrictors, and prostaglandins and NO are vasodilators. 

 

NO - binds to sGC enzyme causing cyclic GMP production which binds to smooth muscle cells causing relaxation and inhibits smooth muscle proliferation. 

Prostaglandins - produced from AA in endothelial cells, bind to smooth muscle releasing cAMP which again causes relaxation and inhibits smooth muscle proliferation. 

Angiotensin II - angiotensin is converted to angiotensin I by renin, and then to angiotensin II by ACE. This causes vasoconstriction and smooth muscle proliferation. 

Endothelin I - this binds to smooth muscle cell receptors to cause vasoconstriction and smooth muscle proliferation.

Question: Will on placement you meet a 17-year-old female who is concerned as she has not been showing any signs of puberty. The consultant sends her for some blood tests and an assessment of bone age to confirm delayed skeletal maturation and which type of delayed puberty the patient has. He then asks Will what could cause hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism, a type of delayed puberty. What answer should Will give?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer.

 

Hypergonadotrophic hypogonadism is where puberty is delayed due to primary gonadal failure, which means there is a structural abnormality in the HPG axis. Causes include gonadal dysgenesis and testicular or ovarian damage.

 

A, C and D are causes of hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism, which is where puberty is delayed due to a defect in or no switching on of the HPG axis. This could also be caused by a constitutional delay in growth and puberty.

 

E: ovarian tumours are a gonadal cause of peripheral precocious puberty, which is early puberty caused by sex steroids being secreted without HPG axis activation. Ovarian cysts can also cause this. Congenital adrenal hyperplasia and adrenal tumours are adrenal causes of peripheral precocious puberty.

 

Central precocious puberty is caused by the early activation of the HPG axis. This is typically idiopathic in females, but likely to be pathological in males. Causes include tumours affecting the CNS, post head injury, post meningitis, hydrocephalus, post-cranial surgery and post radiotherapy.

Question: Ischaemic myocardium sends out vasodilation triggers. Which one of the options below is the incorrect trigger?
OptionA: Tissue hypoxia - reduced smooth muscle ATP synthesis opens KATP channels causing hyperpolarisation which leads to decreased calcium entry and then vasodilation
OptionB: Local adenosine - activates endothelial KATP channels causing hyperpolarisation which causes NO release and so vasodilation
OptionC: Increased CO2 + H+ - hydrogen ions block calcium channels leading to reduced influx and so vasodilation
OptionD: Increased K+ - initial depolarisation closes outward Kv channels causing hyperpolarisation which leads to decreased calcium entry and then vasodilation
OptionE: Increased prostacyclin - binds to smooth muscle cell receptors releasing cAMP which causes vasodilation
Explanation:
The right answer is E: Increased prostacyclin - binds to smooth muscle cell receptors releasing cAMP which causes vasodilation. (meaning this is the incorrect option)

 

Prostacyclin is a prostaglandin so it does cause vasodilation by binding to smooth muscle cell receptors, releasing cAMP which triggers vasodilation. However, it is not a vasodilation trigger used by ischaemic myocardium. 

 

I wrote this question more to draw attention to the 4 correct triggers used and their mechanisms.

Question:
You are working in an sexual health clinic and are seeing a patient who has come for STI screening. Her results come back positive for HPV, and as you explain this to her she starts to become very worried and upset. She tells you that she never had her HPV vaccine in school, and is concerned that she may develop cervical cancer as a result of this infection. 

You explain that only some forms of the HPV virus are associated with increased cervical cancer risk, and luckily se does not have one of these. 

Which forms of this virus could lead to an increased chance of cervical cancer?
Explanation:
HPV (or genital warts) is a non-enveloped dsDNA virus with over 100 different forms. 

90% of infections in the UK are caused by HPV types 6 and 11, and so this patient has likely contracted one of these. 

70% of cervical cancers are associated with HPV forms 16 and 18, and so an infection with one of these could greatly increase cancer risk. 

However, the HPV vaccine targets HPV forms 6, 11, 16 and 18, and so genital warts rates are declining (has been given to 12-13 yr-old girls since 2008, and boys since 2019).  

 

This information is from the case 4 "Microbiology of UTIs and STIs" lecture.

Question: Which sensory modality is local anaesthetic least likely to block?
Explanation:
Local anaesthetics preferentially block small fibres therefore block C-fibres and A-delta-fibres first. C-fibres transmit only pain. A-delta-fibres transmit pain, temperature and some fine touch. Crude touch is transmitted by A-beta-fibres but proprioception is transmitter by A-alpha fibres, which are larger still and therefore least likely to be blocked by a local anaesthetic.

 

(One2One revision)

Question:
Aang is a 60-year-old man, currently retired and stuck at home due to the pandemic. He smokes daily but doesn’t drink alcohol. He was diagnosed with familial hypercholesterolemia when he went to the cardiologist after his GP referral regarding his weight gain and central arcus.

 

What sign is most diagnostic of familial hypercholesterolemia?
Explanation:
This was from the case 2 plenary by Dr McDowell about lipids and cardiac disorders. 
Familial hyper cholesterolaemia is an autosomal dominant condition

if the condition is heterozygous you will have some LDL receptors present

however if the condition is homozygous you have no LDL receptors present

 

in the plenary Dr McDowell mentioned

1. central Arcus which is a ring of fat and cholesterol around the cornea. Its not diagnostic of familial hypercholesterolaemia

 

2. the second symptom he mentioned was tendon xanthoma- which is  depositions of cholesterol on your extensor tendons or on Achilles tendon. this is the most diagnostic of familial hypercholesterolaemia but it is less commonly seen in patients

 

3.he also mention xanthelasma - lipid pockets on the corners of your eyes. once again this is not completely diagnostic as its due to high Cholesterol or LDL levels not necessarily FH

 

4.Central obesity as well could be due to any other cause so it’s not diagnostic

Question:
Ellie, a 50-year-old woman presents to her GP with SOB, wheezing, chest tightness, a chronic cough, and frequent respiratory infections. Upon taking her social history you discover that she used to smoke 20 a day and suspect she may be presenting with early signs of COPD. You decide to perform some spirometry tests to determine her FVC and FEV1.

 

1. What is the correct method for practically obtaining her FVC and FEV1 with spirometry?

2. What would you expect her FEV1/FVC ratio to be?
OptionA:
1. For FVC and FEV1, the patient takes a exhales deeply and then inhales onto the spirometer. They are lying flat.

 

2. FEV1/FVC = 0.5
OptionB:
1. To measure FVC and FEV1, the patient takes a deep breath in, as large as possible, and blows out as hard and as fast as possible into the spirometer, and keeps going until there is no air left. The patient must be lying down flat on the bed.

 

2. FEV1/FVC > 0.7
OptionC:
1. To measure FVC and FEV1, the patient takes a deep breath in, as large as possible, and blows out as hard and as fast as possible into the spirometer, and keeps going until there is no air left. The patient is sat upright.

 

2. FEV1/FVC < 0.7
OptionD:
1. 1. For FVC and FEV1, the patient takes a exhales deeply and then inhales onto the spirometer. They are sat upright.

 

2. FEV1/FVC < 0.7
OptionE: I don't know, why you asking me!
Explanation:
The correct answer is C. To obtain values for FEV1 (forced expiratory volume in one second) and FEVC (forced expiratory vital capacity), the patient takes a deep breath in, as large as possible, and blows out as hard and as fast as possible into the spirometer, and keeps going until there is no air left. They should be sat upright.

 

COPD is an obstructive lung disease, therefore FEV1/FVC is likely to be < 0.7.

 

Patient positioning: correct measurement posture is as follows...

 

1. Sit upright: there should be no difference in the amount of air the patient can exhale from a sitting position compared to a standing position as long as they are sitting up straight and there are no restrictions

2. Feet flat on the floor with legs uncrossed: no use of abdominal muscles for the leg position

3. Loosen tight-fitting clothing

4. Dentures normally left in: it is best to have some structure to the mouth area unless dentures are very loose

5. Use a chair with arms: when exhaling maximally, patients can become light-headed and possibly sway or faint
Tags: Case 3, Respiratory disease, Respiratory physiology, Spirometry

Question:
Jane comes to the GP after falling in a thorn bush and cutting her arm a month ago. She is a bit worried about her scar and she shows you this. 

 

What type of scar does Jane have?
Explanation:
This is a hypertrophic scar. Features of hypertrophic scars include:

  • Rapid growth 
  • Vertical blood vessels
  • Thick collagen bundles with fibres in parallel 
  • Spontaneous regression in less than 6 months 

A keloid scar:

  • No spontaneous regression
  • Haphazardly arranged collagen fibres
  • firm, purple and raised 
  • Genetic predisposition 
  • Extended beyond sight of injury

Question:
Katara is approaching her wedding to Aang and has started to become increasing fuzzy headed, her complexion is pale and has fainted on several occasions but not injured herself. She has fainting spells when she teaches water bending and stays standing for long periods. She visits Dr Iroh as she is concerned about her condition. Her ECG’s are normal. He performs a tilt test which is positive and comes to a diagnosis.

 

what is the diagnosis made by Dr Iroh?
Explanation:
This was from Dr Allen’s lecture on cardiac physiology - the case about the fainting girl.

Anxiety can lead to fainting (syncope)

orthostatic syncope (postural hypotension) occurs when you suddenly change your position - when you stand suddenly blood shifts from cardiopulmonary regions to legs causing lightheadedness.

 

 

low blood pressure (hypotension) is recognised  by baroreceptors and volume receptors which send signals to the hypothalamus and medulla.  

 

when in a prolonged upright position, blood pools in lower extremities resulting in lower inter cardiac volume. This causes arterial hypotension and is sensed by carotid sinus baroreceptors. This stimulates afferent nerves to increase heart rate and LV contraction. But C fibres are activated in pressure rectors in the under filled LV and this triggers paradoxic slowing of heart rate and contractility (mediated by CNS) which causes sudden arterial hypotension.

 

As a result less blood goes to the brain and you faint to protect yourself (vasovagal syncope) 

 

explained simply on https://www.amboss.com/us/knowledge/Syncope
Tags: coronary vessels, Cardiac, Cardiac rhythms, Case 2, Clinical Skills

Question:
Uh oh. Jane didnt revise histology. For her placement she was put in the respiratory histology lab. 

There is no wifi in the lab. She has to try and remember from her lectures the features of the respiratory tract. The doctor asks her what section of the airways is this based off the epithelia type? 

- some Clara cells

- simple ciliated columnar epithelia 

- simple non ciliated columnar epithelia 

- no goblet cells
Explanation:
The nasopharynx is pseudostratefied ciliated columnar epithelia + goblet cells 

The trachea is pseudostratefied ciliated columnar epithelia + goblet cells + no Clara cells 

 

The bronchus is where the epithelia changes from pseudostratefied to tall columnar. Remember the bronchi are the regions of the lungs distal to the carina. They sit behind your heart and you dont want any 'pseudo' (fake) epithelia here, you only want true simple lovers (i.e., simple columnar) and its nice when they have long hair too (ciliated). They have a few sparse goblet cells but no Clara cells. 

 

The bronchioles contain no goblet cells, you dont want mucus in your lungs that far down, and a mixture of ciliated and non ciliated. At this point the macrophages are gonna help you out so you dont need as much wafting up. 

 

Alveoli cells are squamous simple epithelia.

Question: Jake is a 19 year old male who attends his local GP due to constant itching inside his penis and yellow discharge from the penis, he has found that he experiences a burning sensation when masturbating and ejaculating. The doctor takes a urethral swab of the penis and also takes a urine sample. The results come back positive for trichomoniasis. What antibiotics will you prescribe Jake?
Explanation:
Trichomoniasis is a protozoan infection - which commonly causes ejaculation to be painful in males and makes sex unpleasant. Jake can't have been using condoms or the condoms split. Either way Jake will take an oral dose of metronidazole - after doing so he mustn't drink for 72 hours as it can cause nausea and vomiting hence causing oral medication to be brought back up. 

 

Also the medication takes about 7-10 days to clear up the infection so Jake mustn't have sex until this period is over.

Question: A 15 year old male patient attends his GP practise complaining of discharge from the tip of the penis and dysuria - upon examination the testicles appear tender. The doctor takes a urine swab and an anal swab. The tests results come back positive for Chlamydia trachomatis, what antibiotics will you prescribe?
Explanation:
As the patient has been diagnosed with chlamydia you would prescribe them doxycycline (tetracyclines inhibit the tRNA from binding to the A binding site of the bacterial 50s ribosomes - inhibiting protein synthesis). 

Ceftriaxone is a cephalosporin given for gonorrhoea - it can be used in synergism with Azithromycin if there is co-infection with chlamydia 

Doxycycline is shown to be 100% effective however azithromycin isn't 100% effective as a treatment for chlamydia hence doxycycline is the preference. 

 

Metronidazole is used for trichomoniasis 

 

Penicillins are beta-lactams and target the peptidoglycan cell walls in the gram positive bacteria therefore wouldn't be used in this instance as chlamydia is a gram-negative bacteria.

Question: A 64 year old woman is having difficulty with speech. On further assessment you conclude that she is unable to understand the questions and while she can answer her responses are not coherent and do not make sense. Which area of the brain is most likely damaged ?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D! 

Unable to understand questions shows difficulty with comprehension.
Wernicke’s area in temporal lobe has role in language comprehension & understanding.
Damage to Wernicke’s = receptive aphasia/ Wernicke’s aphasia. (Wernickes's = weird) 
See that patients will be able to talk fluently but what they’re saying won’t make any sense.

 

 

A – Arcuate fasciculus white matter tract (bundle of axons) connecting Brocas and Wernicke’s area so damage would cause conductive aphasia, see patients have difficulty repeating things back to you.

 

B – Broca’s area, located in dominant hemisphere of frontal lobe (normally the left). Has important role in the production of speech. Damage to Broca’s area = Broca’s/ expressive aphasia where patients have a problem with the production of speech.
Good way to remember is damage to BROCa’s = BROKen speech

 

C – cerebellum, does have some role in speech (not really understood well) however would not really present like this.

 

D – Heschl’s gyrus. Primary auditory cortex (located in temporal lobe)

Question:
You are on placement, shadowing a consultant cardiologist who loves to test and quiz his students.

 

He asks you, at what point in a ventricular action potential would you see L-type Ca2+ channels opening, causing an influx of calcium ions?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - phase 2

 

Phase 4 - Baseline: K+ channels are open, resting membrane potential

 

Phase 0 - Fast depolarisation: Voltage-gated Na+ channels open in response to depolarisation that spreads into the cell through gap junctions. The influx of Na+ ions depolarizes the cell further causing the opening of more Na+ channels. These channels then close almost immediately after

 

Phase 1 - Notch: These transient opening K+ channels rapidly repolarise the cell before the plateau phase. Therefore they set the membrane potential of the plateau phase. Greater K+ currents during this notch phase allow more repolarisation so that the plateau occurs at lower voltages. Fewer K+ currents means that less repolarisation occurs and the plateau phase occurs at higher voltages.

 

Phase 2 - Plateau: L-type Ca2+ channels are located in the T-tubules that penetrate the cell. These channels are in close proximity to the sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR). Therefore the Ca2+ that enters through them binds to ryanodine receptors located on the SR.This triggers massive Ca2+ release from the SR through a channel in the ryanodine receptor. This phenomenon is called calcium-induced calcium release (CICR). The majority (75%) of Ca2+ that enters the cell comes from the SR. CICR is essential for excitation-contraction coupling within the cell. Calcium ions bind to troponin C and initiate the movement of tropomyosin away from the myosin head binding site on the actin molecule – permitting contraction.

 

Phase 3 - Repolarisation: As Ca2+ channels close, K+ currents succeed in repolarising the cell, driving the membrane potential toward EK. During this phase, Na+ channels will begin to recover from inactivation as the membrane potential becomes more negative. This permits the cycle to restart.

 

Information above was taken from here: https://teachmephysiology.com/cardiovascular-system/cardiac-cycle-2/action-potential-ventricular-cells/

Question:
Consider the following:

  • Changes in blood flow
  • Changes in the vascular wall
  • Changes in components of the blood

What does this refer to?
Explanation:
The answer is B!

A is incorrect because Beck's triad refers to three medical signs associated with cardiac tamponade, which are:

  • Low arterial blood pressure or hypotension
  • Distended neck veins
  • Distant, muffled heart sounds.

 

B is correct - Virchow's triad refers to three concepts that may contribute to thrombosis, and these are stated in the question stem.

  • Changes in bloodflow may refer to the development of turbulent bloodflow.
  • Changes in components of the blood could be thrombocythaemia/elevated platelets.
  • Changes in the vascular wall may come about from collagen exposure or damage to the endothelium.

C is incorrect. Glagov's phenomenon has two aspects: a positive and negative remodelling aspect. Positive remodelling is where the plaque can grow up to 40% of the internal elastic lamina area, but the lumen area remains preserved because the affected coronary artery simply grows in response. Negative remodelling refers to when >40% of the area is affected by stenosis - here, the plaque begins to grow inwards and the area of the lumen begins to shrink.

 

D is incorrect. The Frank-Starling mechanism refers to the ability of the heart to change its force of contraction and therefore stroke volume in response to changes in venous return. The basic principle of this mechanism is that the more the heart chambers fill, the stronger the ventricular contraction is.

Question:
Denise has had COPD for around 10 years and has been coming to your clinic monthly. Recently she has started to gain weight and developed swelling around her ankles. She struggles to breathe and her alveolar ventilation is impaired.
What does this ventilation directly depend on?
OptionA: Airway elasticity, compliance, resistance to air flow, tidal volume
OptionB: Airway radius, inspiratory reserve volume, resistance to air flow, respiratory rate
OptionC: Compliance, resistance to air flow, respiratory rate, tidal volume
OptionD: Distension of air ways, smooth muscle relaxation, resistance to air flow
OptionE: Distension of air ways, respiratory rate, respiratory rhythm, resistance to airflow
Explanation:
This is from dr Katie pink’s lecture in case 3 on resp failure and blood gas

alveolar ventilation - process of gas exchange in the alveoli. Oxygenation failure can cause type 1 respiratory failure which is low hypoxemia. Ventilation failure can cause type 2 resp failure as CO2 levels are high (hyper capnia) while O2 levels are low/normal
ventialtion and oxygenation don’t mean the same thing as they’re 2 different processes- ventilation is gas exchange, oxygenation is receiving oxygen 

alveolar ventilation depends on 4 things - tidal volume, respiratory rate, resistance of airways to airflow and compliance 

tidal volume - size of each breath 

resp rate - how many breaths per min

resistance of airways to airflow - would affect speed of air flow

compliance - distensibilty of lungs

 

compliance = change in volume / change in pressure

 

elasticity isn’t the same as compliance - it means that if something is pulled it will return to its original shape 

compliance is how something changes in volume when the pressure changes. Surfactant increases compliance by protecting alveoli from bursting due to Hugh pressure exerted by water droplets in alveolar surface

 

respiratory rhythmn wouldn’t affect ventilation directly - but can have indirect effects eg when exercising
Tags: Breathing, CBL, Case 3, Hypoventilation, Respiratory physiology

Question: You are a junior doctor doing a block on a paediatrics ward. A young child, 8 months old, presents to the ED with sepsis. After taking a history from the child's parent, you discover that the child has a history of recurrent infections as well as a general failure to thrive. You come to a differential diagnosis of SCID (Severe Combined Immune Deficiency). SCID is a group of primary immunodeficiencies caused by defective/deficient T and B-cell production and/or function. With this in mind, what would be the best treatment for the child?
OptionC: Ensure that all appropriate vaccines have been given
Explanation:
B is the correct answer. As both B and T lymphocytes are deficient/defective, there must be an issue with their production. Both B and T lymphocytes are produced in the bone marrow, arising from common lymphoid progenitor cells, although T cell maturation occurs in the thymus. Therefore a bone marrow transplant will be the most effective option here, and it's most effective at treating SCID if the transplant occurs in the first 3 months of life (although we most likely don't need to know that!)

 

A - Antiretroviral drugs are used to treat HIV/AIDS patients, not SCID - this is a different cause of immunodeficiency!

C - vaccines won't be much help at all if there aren't any T or B lymphocytes to develop immunity!

D and E - these treatments may indeed be necessary to help treat an SCID patient and the effects of the disease, but they won't address the root cause of the condition and so they are not the best option here

 

For more information I'd recommend reading this webpage on Teach Me Physiology - https://teachmephysiology.com/immune-system/cells-immune-system/t-cells/

Question:
It's Summer 2021, and you're volunteering at your local care home. A resident who you've grown close to has been diagnosed with Parkinson's disease. Word gets round that you're a medical student and a care worker asks you what is happening to Jim's brain.

 

You're on the spot, thinking back on Y1 all you see are blurred pictures of Hannah Shaw, Shibby. Now it's Dr Watson, his Scottish accent is ringing in your ears....

 

Suddenly, you have an epiphany.  You explain to the care worker that Parkinson's disease is an idiopathic disorder which affects the dopaminergic neurons of the basal ganglia.

 

Which part of the basal ganglia does Parkinson's disease affect?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

 

Well done, Dr Watson would be proud.

 

Parkinson's disease is a idiopathic disorder affecting the dopaminergic neurons of the substantia nigra. In late stage disease it will affect the mesocortex (area between the limbic system and the cerebral cortex) as well as the neocortex. This is in contrast to Dementia to Lewy bodies which first affects the cerebral cortex, limbic system and brain stem before moving to the basal ganglia. Dementia with Lewy bodies and Parkinson's disease are associated with an abnormal build up of the same protein. Therefore, the difference between Parkinson's and Dementia with Lewy bodies is what part of the brain they initially affect. This provides an explanation for their different presentations in early stage disease; motor impairment vs memory impairment.

 

 

Below is all very complex. Don't worry though, just try to get your head around the constituents of the basal ganglia and their function. Let me know if anyone has a pneumonic to remember them...

 

Basal ganglia-

  • Putamen- Anticipates movement
  • Nucleus accumbens- Reinforcement
  • Substantia nigra- Subconscious muscle activity
  • Caudate nucleus- Eye movement
  • Globus pallidus- Muscle tone regulation of voluntary movements
  • Subthalamic nucleus- Processor of basal ganglia
  • Ventral pallidum- regulation of motivation, behaviour, and emotions (Limbic loop)
  • Olfactory tubercle- reward cognition.
  • Ventral Striatum- Olfactory tubercle + nucleus accumbens (reward processing)
  • Dorsal Striatum- Putamen + Caudate nucleus (decision-making)

This was covered for sure in PCS Unit 3- Motor lecture, although it might have cropped up in Case 5.

Question: Which of the following types of cytokines are most likely to prevent viral replication?
Explanation:
Correct Answer - B!

Interleukins (e.g. IL-8) - Signaling molecules that are expressed by leukocytes and are mostly pro-inflammatory.

Interferons (e.g. IFN-8) Involved with the prevention and interference with viral replication, hence the name 'interferons'.

Colony Stimulating Factors (e.g. CSF1, 2 and 3) - Involved with the stimulation of haematopoietic progenitor cell proliferation and differentiation.

Chemokines - Controls chemotaxis and recruits leukocytes to the site of infection; has proinflammatory effects. 

Tumour Necrosis Factor (e.g. TNF-alpha) - Proinflammatory cytokines which are secreted by inflammatory cells and activate cytotoxic T cells.

Question:
A study investigates several variables that may affect cognitive performance in older age. The study recruits 1000 community dwelling volunteers aged 50 years or more. One variable is found to be normally distributed and for this variable the researchers calculate the approximate proportion of volunteers that lie between the mean ± 2 standard deviations.

 

What proportion (%) is most likely obtained?
Explanation:
This question is asking about normal distributions and the 68:95:99.7 rule. 

 

What this means is that 

 

1. 68% of the values will lie within ±1 SD of the mean

2. 95% of the values will lie within ±2 SD of the mean 

3. 99.7% of the values will lie within ±3SD of the mean

Question:
Angelo is a young lad who suffers with heart palpitations and has been prescribed 40mg propranolol per day by his GP

 

What type of medication is this?
Explanation:
Correct answer is E - propranolol is an example of a beta blocker - also known as a beta-1 adrenoceptor antagonist.

  • The sympathetic innervation of the heart relies upon beta-1 adrenoceptors which involve noradrenaline binding to a Gs protein
  • This medication antagonises this innervation and hence has a negative inotropic and negative chronotropic effect

A - an example of a beta-1 adrenoceptor agonist would be epinephrine (adrenaline), this is sometimes given in an epipen and as well as increasing heart rate it also has many peripheral effects such as bronchodilation (as well as exogenous adrenaline it is also known as the "fight or flight" hormone and can be released from the medulla of the adrenal glands

 

B - example of M2 muscarinic antagonist would be atropine - this is an important medication we learnt about in PCS which can treat bradycardia but it is also found in some poisonous berry plants

 

C - an alpha 1 agonist which we learnt about would be phenylephrine (this was taught in the virtual eye drugs practical) which can bring about pupil dilation...tropicamide also brings about dilation but works on the parasympathetic system (M3 antagonist)

 

D - I don't think we learnt about a specific M2 agonist but we learnt about pilocarpine which is an M3 muscarinic agonist and brings about pupil constriction

Question:
Denise has a silent MI which goes unnoticed. A few months later, she finds it hard to walk up the hill to her house without feeling tired. She can no longer bend to tie her shoelaces as she’s in pain and short of breath. Her husband takes her to see the GP despite her protests that she’s doing fine. At the clinic, the doctor explains to her how part of her myocardium has died.

 

What junctions connect the cells in this structure?
Explanation:
This was from PCS 2 cardiac cycle plenary by Dr Allen. 

The myocardium is composed of cardiac muscle cells. They’re shorter and narrower than skeletal muscle. They’re striated, branched and end to end forming a synctium (That is the cells are connected to each other via desmosomes and gap junctions and are found in the intercalated discs).

explained really well here https://courses.lumenlearning.com/ap1/chapter/cardiac-muscle-tissue/

 

Regarding types of cell junctions 

1. Tight junctions (occluding junctions) - act as barriers, separate apical and base lateral membrane, determine if epithelium is tight or leaky 

2. Anchoring junctions - cell to cell, ECM matrix, have cytoskeleton components and proteins - 3 types - desmosomes, hemidesmosomes and adherens

3. Gap junctions - seen in myocardium, myometrium, enteric SM -> electrical synapses, functional connections between cytosol of 2 adjacent cells, permits selective transport of ions across membranes of adjacent cells. They are formed by connexones (formed by 6x connexin monomer proteins) - a bunch of connexins form a gap junction. 

I think cell junctions were mentioned in PCS 1

Question:
Demeter comes to your clinic complaining of breathlessness, fatigue and headaches. She says when she lies in bed she can feel her pulse pounding. When you do auscultations on her you hear a ventricular gallop.

What best describes this phenomenon?
OptionA: Atrial contraction forces blood into a noncompliant left ventricle
OptionB: Fast paced beating of the ventricles due to positive inotropy
OptionC: Large amount of blood strikes a compliant left ventricle during rapid filling
OptionE: Whooshing sound created by blood flowing fast to compensate for increased myocardial demand
Explanation:
A - atrial gallop (s4)

B - made up

D and E - murmurs

 

From PCS 2, Case 2 and clinical skills sessions 

There are 4 main heart sounds - S1, S2, S3 and S4

S1 and S2 are normal and caused by closure of valves 

S1 is heard when the mitral valve closes 

S2 is heard when the aortic valve closes 

S3 is heard right after S2 and can be normal in children, pregnant women and athletes. It is due to large amounts of blood hitting a compliant LV during passive ventricular filling. Its called ventricular gallop

S4 is atrial gallop and almost always pathological. It is heard due to blood hitting a non compliant LV and before S1 - when atria contract to force blood into LV 

 

Whooshing sound due to turbulent flow - heart murmur definition

 

I dont know how much detail we need to know, but as murmurs were mentioned in the 2nd case scenario it may be important. You could answer this by eliminating answers ig.

 

explained simply on https://www.healio.com/cardiology/learn-the-heart/cardiology-review/topic-reviews/heart-sounds

Question: Michael is a 68-year-old male who attends his GP after experiencing headaches, nausea and swollen lymph nodes. When asked about his sexual activities he says that he has had multiple sexual partners in the last few years. He also says that he used to experience rashes on the palms of his hands which he believed was eczema. What would you say is the most likely diagnosis based on this information?
Explanation:
Trichomoniasis causes discharge from the penis as well as dysuria and pain on ejaculation - its unlikely the patient has this as the symptoms aren't right. 

Flu - the swollen lymph nodes could indicate this as well as some of the nausea but there would be chest pains and coughing associated as well. 

Syphilis - these symptoms are those of secondary stage syphilis, so at an earlier stage he would have experienced sores on his penis or around his penis and maybe sores on his hands - the rashes on the palms are commonly seen in secondary syphilis - he would be treated with penicillin 

Pompholyx is a dermal eczema common in the fingers and palms and sometimes the arms which would just be treated with a steroid cream. 

HSV-1 infection would involves sores around the mouth - as that's what the virus causes however there are no sores hence no indication of herpes.

Question: You are a doctor and Sian is a 27-year-old lady who's currently being treated for Helicobacter Pylori, she's been given a combined antibiotics of omeprazole magnesium, amoxicillin and rifabutin. She has recently started a relationship with a guy from work and asks about contraception that she could use, which of the following methods of contraception would be contraindicated in Sian?
Explanation: Rifabutin and ramipril are contraindications of the progesterone only pill and the COCP as well as the implant and progesterone injection. As she is taking them for helicobacter pylori she will need to use a mechanical barrier such as condoms or femidoms until she finishes her treatment or have an intrauterine device fitted instead or the copper coil.

Question:
Nathaniel is a 15 year-old boy who attends the doctors, they perform an examination of Nathaniel due to concerns he has expressed over his physical development into a man. Upon examination they notice that there is no signs of pubic hair growth or enlargement of the testicles or penis. They send off some tests for testosterone, LH, FSH, GnRH etc. 

 

These are the test results: 

Testosterone: Low 

FSH:              Low 

LH:                 Low 

GnRH:           Normal 

 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Here Nathaniel's results are showing that with the low levels of testosterone, FSH and LH but normal levels of GnRH that he has hypogonadotropic hypogonadism because the hypothalamus is functioning fine, however there must be an issue with the pituitary gland as everything else is low following that, the pituitary gland isn't releasing the FSH or LH which caused by pituitary tumours or other causes. 

 

The difference between hypergonadotropic hypogonadism and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is that in Hyper - there is problem of the testes as the GnRH is produced normally as is the LH or FSH levels. In hypogonadotropic hypogonadism there is a problem with either the hypothalamus or the pituitary gland, in this case the hypothalamus is not the issue, it is the pituitary gland that is the problem, which is why the GnRH is fine. 

 

Primary hypogonadism is caused by a testicular problem whereby testosterone is not being produced hence preventing testicular enlargement and penis enlargement but it will also prevent the development of secondary sex characteristics, however the FSH and LH are being produced hence the testicles have problem producing the testosterone in the leydig cells. 

Primary hypogonadism and hypergonadotropic hypogonadism are the same thing 

 

Precocious puberty is early puberty and that would not be a reason for delayed puberty

Question: You are prescribing your patient a drug for their angina which works by disturbing the Na+ / K+ funny current in the SA node to decrease impulse frequency and so decrease heart rate. Which drug would you prescribe?
Explanation:
The correct answer is D - ivabradine!

  • Bisoprolol - a beta blocker which works by blocking B1 adrenoreceptors to block sympathetic innervation to the heart. Sympathetic innervation increases heart rate and force of contraction and so increases myocardial oxygen demand. By preventing these changes, beta blockers decrease myocardial oxygen demand and are also hypertensive.
  • Diltiazem - a calcium chandler blocker which works by stopping calcium influx to cardiac myocytes having a negative chonotropic and inotropic effect (to decrease myocardial oxygen demand), it is also a vasodilator. 
  • Nitrates - release NO which triggers a cyclic GMP mediated pathway to cause vasodilation to increase blood flow to the heart
  • Nicorandil - this has multiple MOA including a cyclic GMP component to act as a vasodilator.

Question: Why is pulmonary vascular pressure decreased when systemic pressure is increased?
OptionC: Slow down blood velocity to allow more time for gas exchange
Explanation:
The correct answer is E - all of the above. 

 

Pulmonary pressure is decreased when systemic pressure is increased in order to:

  • Minimise load on right ventricle
  • Increase surface area for gas exchange
  • Slow down blood velocity to allow more time for gas exchange
  • Protect against pulmonary oedema

Question:
Amanda has come to the clinic with a wound she sustained whilst cycling. It appears to be very inflamed.

Whilst we don't need to fully understand complement at this stage because it's very complicated, below is what I think we are supposed to know:

  • Classical pathway (IgM, IgG bind to pathogen or antigen-antibody complex), Mannose binding lectin (produced in liver and detects mannose on pathogens), Alternative pathway (bacterial endotoxin)
  • All of these pathways lead to production of C3 convertase which is important for producing downstream effects

  • From both of these enzymatic reactions, C5a and C3a are chemotaxins
  • C3a, C4a, C5a can cause inflammation by binding to mast cells and basophils, increasing vascular permeability through release of serotonin and histamine

Question: Which of the following is NOT a function of angiotensin 2?
OptionA: Increases GFR by constricting the efferent arteriole
OptionB: Causes the release of ADH from the posterior pituitary gland to increase water reabsorption in the DCT and collecting ducts
OptionC: Up-regulates production of PGI2 to cause widespread vasoconstriction
OptionE: Stimulates the zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex in the adrenal glands to secrete aldosterone
Explanation:
Well done if you said C! Angiotensin II causes vasoconstriction, increased body water, increased Na+ content and finally, increased blood pressure. The easiest way to answer this question was probably to remember that PGI2 causes VASODILATION, so this would be the opposite of the intended effect of angiotensin II.

 

I remember this by thinking that angiotensin II has 4 targets:

 

1. Efferent arteriole - constricting the efferent arteriole increases the GFR which increases sodium concentration of the filtrate

2. Adrenal cortex - specifically the zona glomerulosa, which responds to angiotensin 2 by releasing aldosterone to increase sodium reabsorption which subsequently causes more water to be reabsorbed into the bloodstream, increasing blood volume and pressure.

3. Posterior pituitary gland - releases ADH to increase water reabsorption in the DCT and collecting ducts via insertion of aquaporins

4. Heart  - increases intrinsic heart rate by binding to cardiac Ang-II receptors and increasing contractility, cell-cell communication and impulse propagation

 

 

The negative feedback loop stops the release of renin from the juxtaglomerular granula cells when blood pressure is increased, causing a return to normal perfusion of the juxtaglomerular apparatus

A is a function of Interferon-γ

Question: How is melanin made in skin?
OptionA:
In melanocytes, thyamine is converted into dihydroxyphenylalanine 

 

this is polymerised to melanin 

 

melanin binds to protein and is transferred in melanosomes which are then taken up by keratinocytes
OptionB:
in melanocytes tyrosine is converted into dihydroxyphenylalanine

 

this is polymerised to melanin

 

melanin binds to protein and is transferred in melanosomes which are phagocytosed by keratinocytes, releasing melanin
OptionC:
In melanocytes, tyrosine is converted into dihydroxyphenylalanine

 

this is polymerised to melanin

 

melanin binds to receptors which initiate melanosomes which are then phagocytosed by keratinocytes, releasing melanin
OptionD:
In keratinocytes, thyamine is converted into dihydroxyphenylalanine

 

this is polymerised to melanin

 

melanin binds to receptors which initiate melanosomes which are then phagocytosed by keratinocytes, releasing melanin
OptionE:
In keratinocytes, thyamine is converted into dihydroxyphenylalanine

 

this is polymerised to melanin

 

melanin binds to receptors which initiate melanosomes which are then phagocytosed by melanocytes, releasing melanin
Explanation:
B is correct!

 

Melanocytes make the pigment called melanin.
Tyrosine is converted into dihydroxyphenylalanine (DOPA) which is then polymerised into melanin. The melanin pigment binds to protein, and the melanoprotein is transferred along the long dendritic processes of the melanocyte in vesicles (called melanosomes). The tips of these processes are then phagocytosed by the surrounding keratinocytes, which then take up the melanin.

Melanin protects cells from damage by UV, by producing a 'veil' over the nucleus.
Melanocytes are found in the stratum basale layer. About 1 in every 5 to 10 cells in this layer is a melanocyte.

Question:
Your name... Tom Hanks

 

But no, life isn't like a box of chocolates at the moment. Actually it's gone quite tits up for you. You're Cast Away, stranded on an island!

 

Within a day you start to become dehydrated, causing a drop in your blood pressure. Having spare time on your hands, you wonder what mechanisms work to oppose this. You remember that Tubuloglomerular feedback counteracts a reduced hydrostatic glomeruli pressure caused by a blood pressure drop in the nephron, which would otherwise reduce GFR.

 

What cells are involved in Tubuloglomerular feedback?
OptionA:
Juxtaglomerular apparatus:

Principle cells (P cells)- Regulate Na+ balance

Intercalated cells (I cells)- Regulate acid-base balance
OptionB:
Juxtaglomerular apparatus:

Intercalated cells (I cells)- Regulate acid-base balance

Granular cells- Secretes renin to increase tone of efferent arteriole
OptionC:
Juxtaglomerular apparatus:

Granular cells- Secretes renin to increase tone of efferent arteriole

Principle cells (P cells)- Regulate Na+ balance
OptionD:
Juxtaglomerular apparatus:

Granular cells- Secretes renin to increase tone of efferent arteriole

Macula dense- Responsible for NaCl reabsorption and sodium signalling
OptionE:
Juxtaglomerular apparatus:

Intercalated cells (I cells)- Regulate acid-base balance

Macula dense- Responsible for NaCl reabsorption and sodium signalling
Explanation:
D is the correct answer... WELL DONE! Not that it'll help you get off the island. Maybe you could do a Johnny Depp and build a raft of turtles?

 

Juxtaglomerular apparatus:

Granular cells- Secretes renin to increase tone of efferent arteriole. Stimulated by macula dense NaCl reabsorption, granular cells secrete renin which increases efferent tone, increasing hydrostatic glomerular pressure  and GFR. 

Macula dense- Responsible for NaCl reabsorption and sodium signalling. A closely packed group of specialised cells in glomeruli. Reduced NaCl due to reabsorption by macula dense will decrease afferent arteriole tone, increasing hydrostatic glomerular pressure, increasing the GFR.

 

Intercalated cells (I cells)- Regulate acid-base balance

Principle cells (P cells)- Regulate Na+ balance

Both I and P cells are found in the loop of Henle

Question: What are two syndromes related to abnormalities in chromosome 15?
OptionA: Cri du chat syndrome and Turner syndrome
Explanation:
Cri du Chat syndrome = results from missing a piece of chromosome 5. Symptoms include a high-pitched cry that sounds like a cat, downward slant of the eyes, partial webbing or fusing of fingers or toes, and slow or incomplete development of motor skills. (I like to remember this by remembering that five = cinq in french which begins with a C like cri du chat )

 


Turner syndrome = Turner syndrome (TS) occurs when one of the two X chromosomes in females is either missing or incomplete. The most common symptoms are short stature and gonadal dysgenesis, which can cause incomplete sexual development and ovarian failure and infertility. The karyotype would be 45,X - a single X chromosome 

 

Edward's syndrome

Trisomy 18, or Edwards syndrome, occurs when a person has a third copy of material from chromosome 18 instead of the usual two copies. Some symptoms include clenched hands, feet with a rounded bottom, mental deficiency, underdeveloped fingernails, and an unusual shaped chest.

Memory tip = I know this isn't completely true but 18 is the age where you can start working on hospital 'wards'. 

 


Patau's syndrome 

Trisomy 13, also called Patau syndrome, is a disorder in which an individual has three copies of genetic material from chromosome 13, rather than two.

(Memory tip - Patau = Thirteen)

 

Prader Wili syndrome 

Prada-Willi Syndrome is associated with a mutation in Chromosome 15. This causes people to produce large amounts of Ghrelin leading to constant hunger sensation.

 

Gilbert's syndrome

This is a mild liver disorder in which the liver does not properly process bilirubin. Gilbert's syndrome is due to a mutation in the UGT1A1 gene which results in decreased activity of the bilirubin uridine diphosphate glucuronosyltransferase enzyme.

 

Marfan's syndrome

Marfan syndrome is an autosomal dominant disorder that has been linked to the FBN1 gene on chromosome 15. FBN1 encodes a protein called fibrillin, which is essential for the formation of elastic fibres found in connective tissue.

 

I know this is a really silly memory tip but its the only one I could think of. '15' is a film rating in the UK. Willy wonka is a film. There are lot's of fan's of willy wonka. Or you could even think of 'mar'shmallow chocolate bars 

 

So Prader Willi syndrome and Marfan's = chromosome 15!

 

Also, all these syndromes have definitely been mentioned at least once in the course. Marfan's syndrome I believe in PCS 2/CASE 2. Prader Willi and Gilbert's in CASE 6. Then the rest in the chromosomes lecture.

Question:
Fill in the gaps: 

 

The theca cells of the follicle produce (1), which then passively diffuses to the granulosa cells where the enzyme (2) converts it into estrone where it is then secreted from the granulosa cells as (3).
Explanation: During the menstrual cycle, the hypothalamus releases GnRH which causes the release of LH and FSH from the anterior pituitary gland. LH stimulates the theca cells to convert cholesterol into androstenedione. This then passively diffuses into the granulosa cells of the developing follicle, granulosa cells then use aromatase to convert androstenedione into estrone, which then gets converted into estradiol and released hence there is an increase in estradiol before ovulation which causes the LH surge as high estradiol concentrations lead to LH secretion (surge)

Question:
Mike and Donny are setting up the sound systems for the Nottingham Festival, 2095, 5 years after the eradication of Covid-19.

Donny goes to test the speakers. He switches them on and speaks through the mic.

The sound that comes out is so loud that he falls to the ground.

With a 140dB rise, what does this increase the sound energy (in kHz) by?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E!

 

An increase of 20dB means there is an increase in energy by a tenfold (times 10).

That means an increase of 140dB = 10,000,000 kHz increase. 

 

100 + 140 = 240dB! (That's even louder than a space shuttle! Technology for sound systems must have advanced quite a bit by 2095...)

Question:
9-year-old Bella comes across a red bench one day.

She likes the look of it and sits down.

As they pass a random bench, Bella states, " I really wish I had a big bag of candy right now".

 

What type of memory is this?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E! Priming is where one unconsciously associates one object with another. A better example would be when thinking cutlery, you would automatically think "spoon, knife and fork".

 

A and B - both are declarative memories where you actively recall information. The above scenario does not represent this.

C and D - both are associative learning. This is similar to priming, however, an action takes place for the memory to be recalled subconsciously (think of Pavlov's dog) and it is usually for a more specific response. With priming, this can be done without an action taking place with a more broad response.

Question: You are prescribing a patient at your GP practice a short acting bronchodilator for their asthma. You give them a salbutamol inhaler. How does this drug work?
OptionA: Acts as a glucocorticoid receptor agonist to be a transcriptional regulator to reduce inflammation
OptionB: Acts as an antagonist on muscarinic ACh receptors to decrease cGMP production which then reduces muscle contraction
OptionC: Acts as an agonist on muscarinic ACh receptors to increases cGMP production which then reduces muscle contraction
OptionD: Acts as a beta2-adrenoreceptor agonist to increase the G-protein coupled receptor cyclic AMP activated muscle relaxation pathway
OptionE: Acts as a beta2-adrenoreceptor antagonist to decrease the G-protein coupled receptor cyclic AMP activated muscle contraction pathway
Explanation:
The correct answer is D - acts as a beta2-adrenoreceptor agonist to increase the G-protein coupled receptor cAMP activated smooth muscle relaxation pathway. 


^This is also the MOA of salmeterol (a long duration bronchodilator for moderate/ severe asthma management).

The other pathways which were correct for other drugs were A + B.

  • Fluticasone - acts as a glucocorticoid receptor agonist to be a transcriptional regulator and decrease inflammation
  • Tiotropium + Ipratropium - act as muscarinic (mainly M3) ACh receptor antagonists to decrease cGMP production to decrease smooth muscle contraction

Question:
John is a 80 year old man who comes to the clinic as he is starting to lose his hearing. The doctor explains how this is normal in ageing and is called presbycusis. John wants to know more detail about hearing and hair cells. He says his grand daughter is a medical student and she was trying to explain to him that there are 4 rows of hair cells, 3 outer and 1 inner layer.

 

Can you help the doctor by giving their correct functions? Select the most suitable answer.
OptionA:
Inner hair cells - one row - impedance matching 

Outer hair cells - 3 rows - cochlear amplifier
OptionB:
Inner hair cells - 1 row - pitch determination 

Outer hair cells - 3 rows - impedance matching
OptionC:
Inner hair cells - 1 row - pitch determination 

Outer hair cells - 3 rows - cochlear amplifier
OptionD:
Inner hair cells - 1 row - cochlear amplification

Outer hair cells - neurotransmitter release
OptionE:
Inner hair cells - 1 row - cochlear amplification 

Outer hair cells - 3 rows - pitch determination
Explanation:
Dr Watson's case 5 hearing plenary 1 

 

Hair cells are the sensory receptors of both the auditory system and the vestibular system. They detect movement in their environment and transmit these movements as sound.

 

In the cochlea of the inner ear - Auditory hair cells are located within the spiral organ of Corti on the thin basilar membrane 

The hair cells are of 2 anatomically and functionally distinct types - outer and inner hair cells

Inner hair cells CANNOT regenerate and damage is permanent. At birth you had 3500 inner hair cells and 12000 outer hair cells.

 

Outer hair cells mechanically amplify low-level sound that enters the cochlea. Inner hair cells transform sound vibrations into electrical signals. These signals are related via the auditory nerve to the auditory brain stem and the auditory cortex  

 

 

Inner hair cells - pitch determination, neurotransmitter release, converting mechanical sound to electrical signals

 

This next bit is for understanding, I can't remember if it was in the plenary so there might be too much detail.

- deflection of hair cell stereocilia open mechanically gated ion channels. This allows small positively charged ions to enter the cell. The hair cell itself doesn't fire an action potential. But its the influx of positive ions from endolymph in the scala media (Na+ and K+) that depolarize the cell creating a receptor potential which opens voltage gated Ca channels. Calcium ions enter the cell and trigger release of neurotransmitter.

Neurotransmitter diffuses across the narrow space between hair cell and nerve terminal where they bind to receptors and trigger an action potential in the nerve. 

 

Hair cells are repolarised due to the electrochemical gradient between perilymph and endo lymph
