Question:
John is an 80-year-old man with Lewy body dementia. He is beginning to develop some signs of Parkinson’s disease. His daughter, Kaya brings him to the clinic as he's started to become aggressive and develop some personality changes. The doctor schedules an appointment with a psychologist in the afternoon. While at the consultation later on, the doctor and psychologist discuss how her father's reduced cognitive abilities are dye to his reduced processing speed. They say the rate at which he performs tasks has decreased due to his ageing nervous system. They give this hypothesis a name.

 

Can you help Kaya remember what it is?
OptionA: Atkinson and Shifrin’s three-stage model of memory
OptionB: Common cause hypothesis by Baltes and Lindenberger
OptionE: Inhibition deficit hypothesis by Hasher and Zacks
Explanation:
From case 5 ageing and cognition lecture

3 hypothesis mentioned

1. General mental slowing by Salthouse - most cognitive effects of ageing are due to reduced processing speed. The rate a which tasks at performed decreases due to an ageing nervous system. Age related sensory limitation (visual defects) and slowing of neural transmission thought to be responsible. 

 

2. Common cause hypothesis by Baltes and Lindenburg - sensory and cognitive functions are correlated in older people. Handgrip strength declines. As processing speed is slowing this is reflected by body processes.  

 

3. Inhibition deficit hypothesis by Hasher and Zacks - cognitive deficits in ageing are linked with the reduced capacity to inhibit irrelevant stimuli. Linked with central executive function of working memory.

 

Multiple factors contribute to cognitive deficits seen in ageing

 

Atkinson's and Shifrin's 3 stage memory model explains how sensory memory becomes short term memory but only becomes long term if repeated. There's a diagram in the memory systems plenary.

 

Generalised adaptation syndrome by Selye was from PCs 3 - stress lecture 

No matter what the stressor you have a none specific response 

Alarm - resistance - exhaustion

Question: John suffers from a stroke. He then develops the inability to recognise familiar faces, including his own face. What part of the brain is damaged in his stroke?
OptionD: Fusiform gyrus in the temporal lobe and occipital lobe
Explanation:
John is suffering from prosopagnosia, which is the inability to recognise faces. Prosopagnosia is thought to be the result of abnormalities, damage, or impairment in the right fusiform gyrus, a fold in the brain that appears to coordinate the neural systems that control facial perception and memory.

 

The fusiform gyrus, also known as the lateral occipitotemporal gyrus, is part of the temporal lobe andoccipital lobe in Brodmann area 37.

Question: Matthew suffers from epilepsy and has regular seizures. What neurotransmitter is altered in this psychiatric disorder?
Explanation: Gamma-Aminobutyric acid (GABA), the principal inhibitory neurotransmitter in the cerebral cortex, maintains the inhibitory tone that counterbalances neuronal excitation. When this balance is perturbed, seizures may ensue.

Question: Mr jones is an 65 year old man who was involved in a helicopter crash. He presents to A and E with severe bleeding. He is given intravenous noradrenaline. Which of the following cellular changes is most likely to occur in response to noradrenaline?
OptionA: cAMP decreases in bronchial smooth muscle cells
OptionC: cAMP increases in vascular smooth muscle cells
OptionD: DAG decreases in vascular smooth muscle cells
Explanation:
This question is asking us about adrenergic receptors as noradrenaline is the key focus. 

 

We have 5 classes of adrenergic receptors 

 

We would see, 

1. An increase of cAMP in bronchial smooth muscle cells - Gs linked 

2. An increase of cAMP in cardiac muscle cells - Gs linked

3. A decrease of cAMP in vascular smooth muscle cells - Gi linked 

4. An increase of DAG in vascular smooth muscle cells - Gq linked

5. Alpha 1 receptors are the only adrenergic receptors linked to IP3. These aren't found in heart. So you wouldn't see a rise in IP3 in cardiac muscle cells - Gq linked

 

 

 

α1

  • Gq linked so lead to increased IP3 and DAG due to PLC - so a rise in Ca2+.
  • These receptors are found in vascular smooth muscle
  • Activation of these receptors is normally involved in smooth muscle contraction, causing vasoconstriction in many blood vessels

So noradrenaline would increase DAG in VSMC, not decrease so we can rule out D

 

 

α2

 

  • Gi linked - inactivate adenylate cyclase and decrease cAMP
  • Activation of these receptors causes negative feedback on noradrenaline and decrease transmitter release.

 

 

 

B1

 

  • Gs linked so activate adenylate cyclase and increase cAMP
  • This receptors are primarily found in the heart, in cardiac muscle cells 
  • Activation of this receptor would increase cardiac output by increasing heart rate (positive chronotropic effect), conduction velocity (positive dromotropic effect), stroke volume (by enhancing contractility – positive inotropic effect), and rate of relaxation of the myocardium, by increasing calcium ion sequestration rate (positive lusitropic effect), which aids in increasing heart rate

So we would see an increase in cAMP in cardiac muscle cells!

B2

  • Gs linked so activate adenylate cyclase and increase cAMP
  • These receptors are found in airway smooth muscle
  • Remember cAMP has different effects in cardiac muscle and smooth muscle. Unlike cardiac muscle, increased cAMP in smooth muscle causes relaxation.

So noradrenaline would actually increase cAMP in bronchial smooth muscle. So we can rule out A. 

 

B3

 

  • Gs linked so activate adenylate cyclase and increase cAMP
  • Found in adipose tissue and increase lipolysis

Question: You are a medical student doing a placement in a neurology unit. One day you are shadowing a clinic with a consultant, and a regular patient presents who has been suffering with enhanced sensitivity to pain - pressure and temperatures that do not hurt for most people are causing this patient severe pain. The consultant informs you that this patient suffers from hyperalgesia. Hyperalgesia is thought to occur as a result of sensitisation of nerves in the nociceptive pathway. What mechanism best describes central pain sensitisation?
OptionA: An increase in the number of opioid mu receptors, as well as increased sensitivity of opioid mu receptors to B-endorphins
OptionC: An increase in the number of NMDA receptors, as well as increased sensitivity of the NMDA receptors to glutamate
OptionD: Release of substance P by the free nerve endings which stimulates surrounding cells to release molecules, potentiating pain.
Explanation:
C is the correct answer here. Central sensitisation to pain occurs within the spinal cord, and is thought to occur as a result of an increase in the number of NMDA receptors, as well as increased sensitivity of NMDA receptors to glutamate. This change occurs on the dendrites of second-order neurones, resulting from prolonged glutamate because of persistent nociceptor activation

 

A - this change would actually lead to desensitisation to pain, as B-endorphins are endogenous opioids that hyperpolarise the second order neurones and block nociceptive transmission

B - this might well cause increased pain sensitivity but is not the mechanism at play here

D - this is the mechanism by which peripheral sensitisation to pain occurs

E - release of these factors is as a result of tissue damage, causing activation of nociceptive fibres. In hyperalgesia, tissue damage doesn't need to occur for pain to be felt 

 

I made this question using Teach Me Physiology's page on Pain Pathways, which I found very useful :) https://teachmephysiology.com/nervous-system/sensory-system/pain-pathways/

(Also this question may be slightly beyond the scope of what we need to know for year 1 but it helped me understand the descending pain pathways a lot better)

Question: At what concentration of CD4 cells (cells/microlitre) would one be considered to have 'AIDS'
Explanation:
4 stages of HIV (cd4 cells/microlitre)

 

1) no symptoms, CD4 500-600

2) minor symptoms, CD4 350-500

3) opportunistic disease, CD4 200-350

4) full on AIDS, CD4 <200

Question:
A 30-year-old man comes into your GP.

He complains of pain in the medial side of his right elbow.

He tells you it gets worst whenever he grips an object with the affected arm or bends his right elbow.

When you take his history, you find out he is an avid golf player.

 

Which of the below options is a close diagnosis for this individual?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B! 

 

This is a type of epicondylitis that comes from the overuse action of the elbow. For this specific one, the repeated motion when playing golf.

 

This may be a condition we do not need to know but hopefully by the way the question was structured it was easy to understand (for those questions in S1 where unfamiliar conditions will come up)!

 

A - the symptoms are always identical for Tennis elbow except that the pain would be localised to the lateral side of the elbow.

C - Golfer's elbow is an example of epicondylitis.

D - this is where the rotatory cuff tendons are compressed in the area they run through (the subacromial space).

E - this is where the bones of the joint would be separated. A dislocation here is quite rare - would happen when there is greater trauma to the elbow.

Question:
You meet a girl named Sarah at a local bake sale in Cardiff Centre.

You and her start talking and you find out that Sarah is a carrier for the genetic translocation for Down Syndrome.

You think back to the lectures on genetics and you cannot remember if this is due to a Reciprocal Translocation or Robertsonian Translocation.


What is the difference between the 2 of them and which translocation is due to the genetic mutation that Sarah is carrying?
OptionA:
Reciprocal Translocation: fusion of two different acrocentric chromosomes at their long arms, with the loss of their short arms.

Robertsonian Translocation: an exchange of genetic material between non-homologous chromosomes.

 

Sarah is a carrier for the genetic translocation for Down Syndrome due to Robertsonian Translocation.
OptionB:
Reciprocal Translocation: an exchange of genetic material between non-homologous chromosomes.

Robertsonian Translocation: fusion of two different acrocentric chromosomes at their long arms, with the loss of their short arms.

 

Sarah is a carrier for the genetic translocation for Down Syndrome due to Reciprocal Translocation.
OptionC:
Reciprocal Translocation: fusion of two different acrocentric chromosomes at their long arms, with the loss of their short arms.
Robertsonian Translocation: an exchange of genetic material between non-homologous chromosomes.

 

Sarah is a carrier for the genetic translocation for Down Syndrome due to Reciprocal Translocation.
OptionD:
Reciprocal Translocation: an exchange of genetic material between non-homologous chromosomes.

Robertsonian Translocation: fusion of two different acrocentric chromosomes at their long arms, with the loss of their short arms.

 

Sarah is a carrier for the genetic translocation for Down Syndrome due to Robertsonian Translocation.
Explanation:
The correct answer is D!

 

Reciprocal Translocation: an exchange of genetic material between non-homologous chromosomes.

There is usually no harmful effects to the individual, however, divisions in meiosis may produce unbalanced gametes with net/loss gain of genetic material.

An example is below:

 

 

Robertsonian Translocation: fusion of two different acrocentric chromosomes at their long arms, with the loss of their short arms.

Again, there are no harmful effects to the individual but meiosis may give net/loss gain of genetic material in the gametes.

 

Here is an example with chromosome 14 and 21:

(The "balanced carrier" is why Sarah is asymptomatic and a carrier.)

Question:
Sarah is revising the TCA cycle and has forgotten which enzyme is necessary for the rate limiting step.

 

Select which of the following enzymes is crucial for regulating the rate limiting step:
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - if you're going to remember anything about the TCA cycle then this is the enzyme to know :)

 

Isocitrate is oxidised to alpha-ketoglutarate (a five carbon molecule) by this enzyme which results in the release of carbon dioxide. One NADH molecule is formed.

 

This is rate limiting because the enzyme can be allosterically controlled.

Question:
A patient named Sarah has been admitted to A&E. You take over the shift from your colleague who's handwriting is terrible in the notes so you take an ABG as a precautionary measure.

 

pH = 7.55                [7.35-7.45]

PCO2 = 7                [3-5 kPa]

What is the likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C

 

The Base Excess (BE) is severely deranged to +5 - this tells us that it is a metabolic alkalosis along with the pH because the BE is out of the normal range so it's metabolic

 

A cause of metabolic alkalosis may be emesis, hypokalaemia, excess use of antacids etc.

Question: Which of the following bones does NOT contribute to the pterion?
Explanation:
At the pterion, the frontal, parietal, temporal and greater wing of the sphenoid bones come together.

Clinically, it is important because the middle meningeal artery runs deep to it. Therefore damage to the pterion is likely to cause a severe extradural hematoma which can be fatal.

Question: Which of the following is NOT a function of thrombin?
OptionE: Activation of factors V, VII, X, XIII
Explanation:
Thrombin activates factors V, VIII, XI, XIII as well as fibrinogen (factor I), it doesn't activate VII and X

 

So E is the wrong answer, others are functions of thrombin:

A - P selectin mobilisation - endothelial adhesion molecule expression (helps neutrophils migrate)

B - Chemokine production - gets immune cells into site of damage

C - COX induction - makes prostaglandins 

D - Thrombin initiates aggregation of platelets

Question: Macrophages release cytokines that control collagen deposition in wound healing. What are these cytokines?
Explanation:
Collagen deposition is controlled by the cytokines TNF and IL-1 which are released by macrophages

These cytokines stimulate the proliferation of fibroblasts which undergo collagen synthesis + deposition

 

This was taken from the cutaneous wound healing lecture from Case 1

Question: How does wound contraction work?
OptionA: Fibroblasts deposit collagen which pulls the edges of the wound together
OptionB: Fibroblasts differentiate into myofibroblasts and possess skeletal muscle actin and myosin which work to pull the edges of the wound closer together
OptionC: Myofibroblasts adhere to the ECM and the actin present in the myofibroblasts contracts against the collagen, pulling the edges of the laceration together
Explanation:
Healing by secondary intention involves wound contraction:

This occurs when fibroblasts differentiate into myofibroblasts in the granulation tissue and these possess smooth muscle actin.

They adhere to the ECM and the actin present in the myofibroblasts contracts against the collagen, pulling the edges of the wound together.

 

This was taken from the cutaneous wound healing lecture from Case 1

Question:
Josie’s mother brings her to the clinic. She says Josie has started looking pale and has fainted a few times. The doctor asks Josie some questions and asks about he menstrual cycle. Josie says she has very heavy periods and feels tired during menstruation. She says she feels nauseous during those times and doesn’t eat as well because she gets abdominal cramps. The doctor explains a certain absorption pathway isn’t working properly due to low intrinsic factor and explains the normal pathway to Josie and her mother. She says “This vitamin needs to bind to haptocorrin at low pH as well as intrinsic factor for its proper absorption”. 

 

What type of anaemia is Josie most likely to have?
Explanation:
The most likely answer is D, since she has low intrinsic factor being produced.

 

micorcytic anemia - due to iron deficiency mostly, RBCs are smaller in size 

 

Both vitamin B12 (cobalamin) and B9 (folate) can cause macrocytic anemia where the RBC’s are large (MCV is higher than normal). With these types of anemia, the red blood cells don’t develop normally. They are very large and they are shaped like an oval, not round like healthy RBC. This causes the bone marrow to make fewer red blood cells. In some cases the red blood cells die sooner than normal.

 

as she is forming less intrinsic factor its pernicious anemia, a type of macrocytic anemia. Intrinsic factor is needed for the body to absorb vitamin B12. Macrocytic anemia occurs if you have deficiency in B12. Macrocytic anemia can be further divided as megalobalstic or nonmegaloblastic to further clarify the cause of anemia.

 

Megaloblasts are large nucleated red blood cell (RBC) precursors with noncondensed chromatin due to impaired DNA synthesis. Macrocytes are enlarged RBCs (ie, mean corpuscular volume [MCV] > 100 fL/cell). they are not the same.

 

In Jeff’s PCS 2 lecture on digestion he explains b12 absorption really well. Anemia was spoken about in case 6 and digestion plenaries as well

Question:
James comes to the clinic complaining of difficulty walking, hallucinations, and other cognitive defects. He says the problems started a few months ago when he went on a trip and ate contaminated meat at a street market. You believe his condition is due to transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs). 

 

What microbe has caused this?
Explanation:
From Dr Tonk’s microbiology PCS 2 lecture 

Prions are also called transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs). They’re a rare family of progressive neurodegenerative disorders.

Prion diseases occur when normal prion protein, found on the surface of many cells, becomes abnormal and clump in the brain, causing brain damage. This abnormal accumulation of protein in the brain can cause memory impairment, personality changes, and difficulties with movement.

 

The slide in the lecture shows a brain section of spongiform pathology characteristic of Creutzfeldt Jakob disease - the most common prion disease to affect humans

Question:
Margaret, an 85 year old female, has been admitted to hospital following a stroke. During your assessment, you ask if she could draw a clock and she draws it like this:

 

Based on this, which lobe is most likely to have been effected?
Explanation: This clock shows constructional apraxia. This is usually caused by damage to the parietal lobe. Damage to the right parietal lobe leads to the patient neglecting the left side as seen in this drawing. If the left side was effected then the right side would be neglected and the numbers would be on the left hand side of the clock.

Question: A 70 year old male with COPD presents with shortness of breath. He is receiving 40% supplementary oxygen. What should the PaO2 be?
Explanation:
D is the best answer in this instance!

 

PaO2 (arterial) always LOWER than PAO2 (alveolar)

  • on air (meaning patient is breathing on their own) PaO2 should be >10kPa
  • if patient is using inspired concentration (-supplementary oxygen, like in this question) PaO2 should be 10kPa less than the % of the inspired concentration 

 

40% - 10kPa= 30kPa 

 

(this question was made from using a revision presentation on interpreting ABG)

Question: Anna was out for a run when she tripped and landed awkwardly on her leg. She went to A and E where they performed an X-ray and discovered a fracture of her fibular head. A nerve wraps around the fibular head, what sensory deficits in the leg may be a result of this injury?
OptionA: Loss of sensation on the sole of her foot and lateral aspect of leg
OptionB: Loss of sensation isolated to her knee
OptionC: Loss of sensation between the first and second digits and anterolateral thigh
OptionD: Loss of sensation to posterior calf area, heel and lateral 3 digits
OptionE: Loss of sensation to the anterolateral leg, dorsum of her foot and space between first and second digits
Explanation:
E is the correct answer

 

- the nerve which is most likely to have been damaged is the common fibular nerve as it wraps around the head of the fibula

- this nerve splits into the superficial and the deep fibular nerve

- superficial fibular nerve provides sensory innervation to the dorsum of the foot and anterolateral aspect of the leg, whilst the deep fibular nerve provides sensory innervation to the space between the first and second toes

 

- it also gives off the sural communicating nerve which combines with part of the tibial nerve to form the sural nerve

- the sural nerve provides sensation to the posterolateral aspect of the distal third of the leg and the lateral aspect of the foot, heel, and ankle- however because it has input from the tibial nerve, damage to the common fibular nerve would not result in complete loss of sensation in these areas

Question:
Fill in the gaps...

 

A gentleman named Boris Johnson enters your clinic. He's Prime Minister, he's got god knows how many children and now the Castellan of Barnard Castle has outed him to the public.

 

To alleviate a stressful day life he smokes and has done long term. He presents with tightness of the chest, clubbed fingers and a persistent dry cough. You think a likely diagnosis is 1, which you explain to him is where there is the hyperactivation of 2 which leads to 3 of the intersititium of the lungs as it is laid with collagen. 

 

You conduct spirometry and a peak flow test on him in the GP practise, and some radiological imaging is conducted on him. Below are the results. Using these results you confirm he has a 4 lung disease.

 

 

White= Normal results

Red= Patient's results
OptionC:
1- Idiopathic Pulmonary fibrosis

2- Fibroblasts

3- Fibrosis

4- Restrictive
Explanation:
Correct answer is C!

 

Boris's likely diagnosis is IPF, Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis. His finger clubbing and dry cough are suggestive of this, however the key to differentiating IPF from pneumonia in this question is the radiological imaging.

 

His IPF is likely a result of his long term smoking, although there could be a genetic component.

 

IPF is where fibroblasts are chronically hyperactivated, leading to the secretion of collagen and fibrosis of the intersititium of the lungs. It presents on an x-ray, and radiological imaging is used to diagnose IPF.

Pneumonia is a bacterial infection of the lungs, where air in the alveoli is slowly replaced by pus. This is known as consolidation. It is a restrictive lung disease, and presents with similar symptoms to IPF: breathlessness. However, the cough would be productive (with phlegm), there would be no finger clubbing. Also, the x-ray would present with opacity with no volume loss, see below image.

 

Two types of pneumonia infection:

  • Community acquired- S.pneumonia, Hib Moraxella
  • Hospital acquired- S.Aureus, P. Aeruginosa

 

Intersititium =The space in the lungs between the alveolar epithelial basement membrane and the capillary endothelium basement membrane. Known as the skeleton of the lungs.

Question: Julie has come in with glaucoma which needs urgent treatment. Which of the following drugs would you use for glaucoma?
Explanation:
Pilocarpine is used for glaucoma. It is a Muscarinic receptor agonist and allows drainage of aqueous humour in the eye via the Canal of Schlemm. This decreases the intraocular pressure. Glaucoma is often seen in diabetic patients. 

This was in the eye practical in PCS3

Question:
You are shadowing a doctor on placement where a patient attends surgery complaining of hearing problems. The doctor performs Weber's and Rinne's tests on both ears. The results are as follows;

Weber's test: Sound heard loudest in the left ear

Rinne's test: Positive (in both ears)

What type of hearing loss is the patient likely to be experiencing?
OptionA: Sensorineural hearing loss in the right ear
OptionB: Conductive hearing loss in the right ear
OptionC: Sensorineural hearing loss in the left ear
OptionD: Conductive hearing loss in the left ear
Explanation:
Rinne's test was positive, this means that the patient heard the sound loudest when the tuning fork was held outside the ear rather than on the mastoid process. This means air conduction > bone conduction. As a result, this isn't conductive hearing loss and answers B and D can be ruled out. 

 

Weber's test showed unilateral hearing loss since the sound wasn't heard loudest equally in each ear - this means E is incorrect. 

 

By deduction, we can see it must be sensorineural hearing loss.

 

In sensorineural hearing loss, weber's test will produce a louder sound in the unaffected ear.  The patient heard the sound better in the left ear, this suggests the hearing loss must be in the right ear. 

 

Therefore, the answer is sensorineural hearing loss in the right ear
Tags: Ear, PCS 3, Head and neck, Case 5

Question: Growth hormone releasing hormone (GHRH) is released in a pulsatile fashion from the hypothalamus. This stimulates the release of growth hormone (GH) form the anterior pituitary gland. Which of the following is part of a negative feedback loop, inhibiting the release of GH?
OptionA: Puberty causing increased testosterone and oestrogen levels inhibits the release from the hypothalamus
OptionB: Low blood sugar levels (hypoglycaemia) act on the hypothalamus inhibiting the release from the hypothalamus
OptionC: Growth hormone and somatomedins form somatostatin in the hypothalamus which inhibits GH release
OptionD: Increased GH in the liver and muscles stimulates the release of somatotropin which inhibits release of GH in the anterior pituitary
OptionE: Exercise induces the adrenal glands to release adrenaline which inhibits GHRH release
Explanation:
Correct answer = C, Growth hormone and somatomedins form somatostatin in the hypothalamus which inhibits GH release

 

Options A,B and E are all factors that have a positive feedback on growth hormone release. 

Option D is incorrect because increased GH in the liver and muscles stimulates the release of somatomedins (NOT somatotropin) inhibiting GH.

Somatotropin is just another word for Growth hormone. 

 

To summarise:

 

GHRH release is triggered by:

1. Hypoglycemia inhibits GHRH

2. Exercise causing release of adrenaline from the adrenal glands inhibiting GHRH

3. Puberty, high levels of oestrogen and testosterone inhibit GHRH

 

GH and GHRH are inhibited by (negative feedback loop):

1. Increase in GHRH in blood inhibits release from hypothalamus

2. In liver and muscle somatomedins are formed which inhibits release from anterior pituitary

3. GH and somatomedins form somatostatin which inhibits release of GHRH

Question: What is Mifepristone used for and why?
OptionA: Abortion during pregnancy because it is a PGE1 analogue
OptionB: Abortion during pregnancy because it is a progesterone receptor antagonist
OptionC: Treatment of angina because it stimulates guanylyl cyclase to make cGMP and stimulates ATP dependent K+ channel (negative chronotropic and inotropic effects)
OptionD: Treatment of angina because it inhibits the inward movement of K+ and Na+ funny current (therefore negative chronotropic)
OptionE: Lowering blood cholesterol by binding on LDL receptors and stimulating LDL breakdown and metabolism
Explanation:
Mifepristone is an antiprogestogen. It works by blocking the effects of progesterone, making the cervix easier to open. It also sensitises the uterus to prostaglandins making the myometrium contract.

 

A - Gemeprost

C - Nicorandil

D - Ivabradine 

E - PCSK9 inhibitors

Question: During a pacemaker action potential, which phase would you expect to see the sodium funny current occuring?
Explanation:
Correct answer is B - slightly tricky question because there are actually only three phases to a pacemaker action potential

 

I remember the order 403 in the most random way - you know when you get ERROR 403 when trying to open a web page? ;)

 

 

  • Anyways, phase 4 is the first phase and it is responsible for the sodium funny current which occurs through HCN channels.
  • At the threshold point, around -40mv, phase 0 (depolarisation) occurs where Ca2+ influx depolarises the cell - at the peak, Ca2+ channels close and K+ channels open.
  • Phase 3 is initiated and K+ efflux occurs, repolarising the cell.

Question: A patient comes to visit your clinic because they think they have damaged a nerve in their leg. Upon examination, the patient cannot dorsiflex their left foot and have lost sensation over their first (most medial) interdigital cleft. Based on these findings, which nerve do you suspect this patient has damaged?
Explanation:
B is the correct answer. 

This patient has foot drop, so must have damage to the common fibular or deep fibular nerve. As the sensory impairment is only the first interdigital cleft, it must be the deep fibular nerve as the remaining sensation of the dorsum is from the superficial fibular nerve.

 

Common fibular nerve damage – footdrop
 Motor loss: dorsiflexion + eversion.
 Sensory impairment: dorsum of foot + lateral leg.

 

Deep fibular nerve damage – footdrop
 Motor loss: dorsiflexion.
 Sensory impairment: 1st interdigital cleft (dorsum).

 

Superficial fibular nerve damage
 Entrapment: causes pain + paraesthesia over lower leg + dorsum of foot. Result of ankle sprains, twisting of ankle, compression by deep fascia where it exits the deep fascia.
 Motor loss: eversion.
 Sensory impairment: dorsum (except for 1st interdigital cleft) + anterolateral aspect of leg.

 

Sural nerve damage
 Sensory impairment: loss of sensation of posterolateral lower leg, lateral border of foot + small area under heel.

 

Tibial nerve damage
 Tarsal tunnel syndrome: entrapment + compression of tibial nerve. May have altered sensation to sole of foot + can be weakness + wasting of intrinsic foot muscles.
 Motor loss: plantarflexion, flexion of toes + weakened inversion (tibialis anterior can still invert foot).

Question: Growth hormone has varying effects through out the body. Which of the following is an example of an indirect effect?
OptionA: IGF-1 decreases amino acid uptake in muscles
OptionB: Acts on adipose tissue to increase lipolysis
OptionC: Increases gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis in the liver
OptionD: Increased insulin resistance in tissues meaning an increase in blood glucose
OptionE: IGF-1 stimulates increased bone length by increased function of osteoblasts and epiphyseal cartilage (growth plates) remaining open increasing size and proliferation of chondrocytes
Explanation:
Correct answer = E, IGF-1 stimulates increased bone length by increased function of osteoblasts and epiphyseal cartilage (growth plates) remaining open increasing size and proliferation of chondrocytes. 

This is an Indirect effect of growth hormone.

Answers B,C, and D are all direct effects of growth hormone. 

A is incorrect because IGF-1 increases amino acid uptake in muscles

 

Summary:

Direct effects of growth hormone:

1. Increased gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis in the liver - increasing blood glucose

2. Increased lipolysis in adipose tissue

3. Increased insulin resistance in tissues, increasing blood glucose - diabetogenic

 

Indirect effects of growth hormone are stimulated by the production of IGF-1 (insulin-like growth factors) in the liver:

1. Increased amino acid uptake in the muscle for protein synthesis - anabolic effect

2. Increase osteoblasts activity and  chondrocytes for epiphyseal cartilage and bone growth

3. Stimulates cell growth, division and differentiation. Reduces apoptosis.

Question:
A piece of DNA is undergoing replication each piece has its own part to play,

DNA topoismerases unwinds the dna 

DNA helicase breaks the hydrogen bonds 

DNA ligase joins the breaks in the phosphodiester backbone 

DNA polymerase... adds nucleotides to the growing strand in the X prime to the Y prime direction 

 

solve for X and Y

Question: Kaya is feeling stressed due to academic responsibilities. As a result of this stress she has started binge drinking on semi-regular basis. What behaviour is this an example of?
Explanation:
Negative reinforcement is the answer. This is because she is removing an unwanted stimulus (stress) by her behaviour (drinking alcohol). This increases the probability of her continuing to drink as it is removing the negative stimulus from her life, reinforcing her reliance on the substance. 

Positive reinforcement would be adding a positive stimulus when a positive behaviour is shown to reinforce it. For example giving a dog a treat when it sits. 

Positive Punishment is the addition of a negative stimulus in the presence of negative behaviour e.g. spraying a misbehaving dog with a water bottle. 

Negative punishment is the removal of a positive stimulus in the presence of a negative behaviour e.g. removing a misbehaving boys playstation. 

Classical conditioning (also known as Pavlovian or respondent conditioning) refers to a learning procedure in which a biologically potent stimulus (e.g. food) is paired with a previously neutral stimulus (e.g. a bell). It also refers to the learning process that results from this pairing, through which the neutral stimulus comes to elicit a response (e.g. salivation) that is usually similar to the one elicited by the potent stimulus.

carcinoma 5%

other causes - neoplasia, stress, ZE syndrome, and Crohn's - 5%

the 3 2 1 method is used to treat H pylori - 3 drugs (PPI and 2 antibiotics), twice a day for 1 week

Question:
Sharon moved to the UK recently and has developed Hepatitis B after getting a tattoo at KatDemon. She calls her GP and they arrange a test as she can't remember if she was vaccinated. She also forgot to send the GP her vaccination records.

These are her serology results.

What is the most likely diagnosis?

 

HBsAg   +

HBeAg   -

Anti-HbcAg IgM   -

Anti-HBsAg IgG    -

Anti-HBeAg IgG   +

Anti-HBcAg IgG   +
Explanation:
Antigens

Hep B surface antigen (HBsAg) if positive - currently infected, acute/chronic

Hep B envelope antigen (HBeAg) if positive - currently infected, the virus is replicating, high infectivity, high risk of liver damage 

Hep B core antigen (HBcAg) if positive - generally not measured but the antibody against it is measured 

 

Antibodies 

Hep B coreIgM antibody (anti-HBcAg IgM) - acute infection

Hep B core IgG antibody (anti-HBcAg IgG) - chronic infection

 

Hep B envelope IgG antibody (anti-HBeAg IgG) - decreasing replication and infectivity (low risk)

 

Surface antibody (anti-HBsAg IgG) - viral clearnace, post vaccination (>100 IU/ml is protective)

 

If you've developed immunity after vaccination ONLY anti-HBsAg is positive 

 

This was all from the plenary^

 

The 2 below were from medsoc revision sessions

If vaccinated against Hep B recently (2 weeks) HBsAg and anti-HBsAg IgG would be +

If there's Hep B DNA in your blood, the viral load is very high

Question:
Llewellyn is a 30-year-old who eats Maccie's every other day, he also drinks 2 cans of coke daily and a Monster. He does minimal exercise and eats very few vegetables. On some days he feels pain in his upper abdomen and bloated. He has acid reflux regularly but he reckons it's just due to his unhealthy lifestyle and ignores it. Llewellyn's girlfriend, however, becomes worried and persuades him to go to the GP. Llewellyn is on no other medications and has no allergies. The GP prescribes a drug for his reflux and says it's also a cytochrome P450 inhibitor which impairs the metabolism of warfarin and phenytoin. 

What drug has the GP prescribed to Llewellyn?
Explanation:
Well done if you got this right!

This is from the case 6 plenary on therapeutics of the Upper GI tract 

 

Cimetidine and Ranitidine are H2 receptor antagonists.

Cimetidine is a cytochrome P450 inhibitor that impairs the metabolism of warfarin, phenytoin, etc. Side effects - impotence, gynecomastia (man boobs)

Ranitdine has been discontinued as it has carcinogenic compounds.

 

Lansoprazole is a proton pump inhibitor (PPI), more effective than H2RA's and antacids. It inhibits the K+ ATPase pump on parietal cells and therefore reduces HCl acid formation. Has side effects of diarrhea, nausea and headaches 

 

GORD has 3 stages 

1. Stage 1 - occasional heartburn fewer than 2-3 times a week. Treated with lifestyle modifications, nonprescription antacids and H2RAs as needed 

2. Stage 2 - frequent heartburn and symptoms (more than 2-3 times a week). Treated with H2RA but PPI may be more effective 

3. Stage 3 - Persistent symptoms, esophageal complications (stricture, barret's), chest pain etc. Treatment PPI therapy daily or twice a day

 

You could also do antireflux surgery and this is called a Nissen fundoplication

 

This is all from the plenary, irdk how much detail we need to know. Also good luck for S1, we got this. :)

Question: You are shadowing an eye surgeon and he suddenly turns to you and asks, 'WHAT TYPE OF COLLAGEN IS FOUND IN THE CORNEA!!!!'. You are caught off-guard and can't quite remember what type. What type of collagen is found in the cornea?
Explanation:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GcG6ojwGWqw - This video is brilliant. Just skip over the stuff that is too in cdepth. 

 

  1. Type I collagen is found in Bone, Tendone, Co(r)nea, and Skin (tone). It is the strongest and most abundant form of collagen. 
  2. Type II collagen - the spongy type. It absorbs shock from compressive forces. This is found in cartilage - hyaline and fibrocartilage 
  3. Type III collagen - the 'webby type'. This is found in tissues where pulling forces occur. Eg. blood vessels, granulation tissue, uterine tissues 
  4. Type IV collagen - this is located in the basement membrane to provide stabilisation to the cell. Tissues found in = kidney, ear, eye and skin

Fibrocartilage = type I and type II 

Hyaline = type II 

Elastic = type II

Question:
Sophie is 65 years, post menopausal and has a family history of athritis. She was diagnosed with osteopenia a few years ago, and since then been increasingly careful when walking and being physical. Despite this, she trips over her youngest child’s lego set and twists her ankle. Her ankle is swollen and there is an open wound. TNF alpha is expressed in the liver, spleen and other organs due to systemic infection. It can cause shock in sepsis by increasing vascular permeability and decreasing BP

TNF alpha also plays a role in athritis by increasing metalloproteinase synthesis by synoviocyts leading to loss of connective tissue in joints. Hoewever joint inflammation is athritis is driven by autoimmune events.

IL 1  produces fever and IL6. It activates vascular endothelium, lymphocytes etc. 

 

Physiotherapy wouldn’t be suitable as she has a fracture so it would need time to heal. It may be useful later on.

HRT could give some protective effects of estrogen but it would’t be the most appropriate in terms of septic shock.

Question:
Christopher has been sent for a liver function test (LFT) by his GP after it was noticed he had slight yellowing of the sclera when undergoing a fundoscopy for an unrelated issue.

Gilbert's syndrome involves a decreased activity in the UGT enzyme which conjugates bilirubin in the liver, hence why this would be pre-hepatic.

Question: Jane has fallen over and she is in a lot of pain. How does the PAG (periqueductal grey) work to inhibit the feeling of pain?
OptionA: Distraction leading to change from lateral to medial pain pathway increases activity in S1 and S2 somatosensory cortexes. Therefore you get the uncomfortable feeling assosicated with pain but not a localised sensation of pain.
OptionB: Distraction leading to change from medial to lateral pathways of pain leading to increased activity in the PFC (pre frontal cortex) and ACC (anterior cingulate cortex). Therefore you uncomfortable feeling assosicated with pain but not a localised sensation of pain.
OptionC: Stimulating PAG activates enkephalin releasing neurones that lead to release of serotonin from raphe nuclei. This activates interneurons in the substantia gelatinosa of the dorsal horn and they release opiod neurotransmitters that bind to mu recrptors and inhibit substance P release.
OptionD: Stimulating PAG activates oxytocin which blocks the ”gate“ of pain by binding to interneurones and this inhibits the spinothalamic pain pathway by promoting A beta fibres that respond to light touch to open and the C and A delta fibres that carry pain to close
OptionE: Stimulating PAG activates substance P which is an inhibitory neurotransmitter, that inhibits A beta fibres and promotes activity of A delta and C fibres which carry pain in the spinothalamic tract.
Explanation:
From case 1 pain lecture

2 

 

distraction - involves changing from lateral pain pathway to medial pathway 

lateral pathway is involved with sensory discrimination of pain - s1 and s2 somatosensory cortexes and the lateral thalamic nuclei

medial pathway is involved with the uncomfortable emotion assosciated with pain - PFC, ACC and medial thalamic nuclei

 

Gate theory of pain - inhibits C and A delta pain fibres by opening A beta fibres that respond to light touch, which is why rubbing a wound reduces pain slightly 

 

substance P is an excitatory neurotransmitter. endogenous opiods (encephalin and endorphins) prevent release of excitatory neurotransmitters 

substances like serotonin, GABA, noradrenaline and endogenous opioids (encephalin and endorphins) are inhibitory neurotransmitters involved in pain modulation

Question:
Ramipril is an ACE inhibitor used to treat hypertension. It works by stopping the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II and so lowers blood pressure. A retrospective study was used to investigate the efficacy of ACE inhibitors in treating hypertension. 4600 patients were included in the study and 2200 received ACE inhibitors. The remaining participants in the study received a placebo drug and were untreated. From this study, hypertension persisted in 60 treated patients and 700 untreated patients. 

From this data, the number needed to treat (NNT) is calculated.

 

What value is most likely obtained?
Explanation:
NNT = 1/ARD

ARD = absolute risk difference. This is worked out by the risk is 'untreated' group minus the risk in 'ACE inhibitor' group.

 

Answer = E, 4. 

There were 4600 patients in the study. 

You are told 2200 received ACE inhibitors and the remainder did not. Therefore, the number who received the placebo drug and were untreated is: 4600-2200 = 2400.

 

Risk in untreated group:

2400 did not receive it, 700 still had hypertension at the end of the study. Therefore risk = 700/2400 = 0.29167 

 

Risk in treated group:

2200 did receive ACE inhibitors, 60 still had hypertension at the end of the study. Therefore risk = 60/2200 = 0.02727

 

ARD = 0.29167 - 0.0272

        =  0.26447

 

NNT = 1/0.26447

        = 3.78 (2.dp)

For NNT you always round up so the answer = 4.

Question:
A patient presents with foul smelling, frothy discharge and upon examination 'strawberry cervix' was observed. A swab was taken and this patient was subsequently diagnosed with Trichomoniasis. The doctor prescribed metronidazole. The patient is concerned about the the test for trichomoniasis and asks the doctor 'How sensitive is the test for trichomoniasis?'

 

The doctors thinks back to a study that they recently read:

240 participants were swabbed and tested for Trichomoniasis. 145 participants were known to have Trichomoniasis and the the remaining participants did not have the infection. 110 test Negative for Trichomoniasis, 25 of these had known Trichomoniasis. 

 

What is the best estimate for the sensitivity (%) of the test? (1.d.p)
Explanation:
Sensitivity is the chance of obtaining a positive result for individuals who have the disease. By using the table format, you can fill in the missing gaps and the divide the number of true positives by the total who had the disease. To work out the percentage you then X100.

 

Answer = D, 82.8% (1.dp)

Question: Where does B12 bind to haptocorrin?
Explanation:
The low pH of the stomach causes the release of B12

B12 binds to haptocorrin (from the saliva) to create a protective complex. Haptocorrin is found in saliva but doesn’t bind to B12 until it is released from food in the stomach 

This complex travels to the proximal ileum where B12 is released from haptocorrin and binds to intrinsic factor 

This B12-IF complex travels to the terminal ileum where it enters an enterocyte - transport is calcium dependent 

In the enterocytes the B12 is released from IF and it binds to transcobalamin II

This is then transported into the blood

Question: What are beta blockers?
Explanation:
Correct answer is A!

Beta blockers are Beta 1 and 2 antagonists. They bind to beta 1 receptors to prevent the effects of noradrenaline on heart. They have an overall effect of reduced heart rate and reduced heart contractility. 
Beta 1 receptors are found in the heart- to remember this, you have 1 heart, B1 receptors

Beta 2 receptors are found in the lungs- 2 lungs, B2 receptors 

Beta 3 receptors are found in adipose tissue

Question: Joe has had trouble hearing the tv recently. He thinks its due to clogged earwax in his ears. He tries to scrap it out with a cotton bud but he accidentally puts it too far and ruptures his eardrum! Oopsy...The next day he finds that he has reduced saliva secretion on the affected side. What nerve has he damaged?
OptionB: The mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve
Explanation:
Joe has ruptured his eardrum aka his tympanic membrane. The nerve associated is the chorda tympani, a branch of the facial nerve. So C is technically correct but D is more specific. 

 

The chorda tympani runs along the posterior surface of the tympanic membrane. In tympanic membrane rupture, the chorda tympani can be damaged, resulting in loss of taste to the anterior 2/3 of the tongue as well as secretory dysfunction of the submandibular and sublingual glands. However, taste from the posterior 1/3 of tongue (supplied by the glossopharyngeal nerve) remains intact.

Question:
Duncan is trying to remember the arterial supply to the GI tract.

 

Where would the arterial supply for the inferior part of the duodenum derive from?
Explanation:
Correct answer is C - the inferior part of the duodenum is supplied by the superior mesenteric.

 

This is very important to remember:

  • Coeliac trunk supplies the foregut - the foregut ends at the ampulla of Vater (major duodenal papilla to be more precise)
  • Therefore the inferior duodenum is part of the midgut which is supplied by the superior mesenteric
  • The hindgut starts at the distal 1/3 of the transverse colon and is supplied by the inferior mesenteric

Question: Which of the following is an example of an insoluable dietery fibre?
Explanation:
B is correct

 

Fiber is commonly classified as soluble, which dissolves in water, or insoluble, which doesn't dissolve.

 

Soluble fibre. This type of fiber dissolves in water to form a gel-like material. It can help lower blood cholesterol and glucose levels. Soluble fiber is found in oats, peas, beans, apples, citrus fruits, carrots, barley and psyllium. Examples: Plant pectin, gums, beta-glucan

 

Insoluable fibre. This type of fiber promotes the movement of material through your digestive system and increases stool bulk, so it can be of benefit to those who struggle with constipation or irregular stools. Whole-wheat flour, wheat bran, nuts, beans and vegetables, such as cauliflower, green beans and potatoes, are good sources of insoluble fiber. Examples: Cellulose, hemicellulose

 

Microfilaments, also called actin filaments, are protein filaments in the cytoplasm of eukaryotic cells that form part of the cytoskeleton.

Question: A patient has a blood pressure of 125/83, what is their pulse pressure?
Explanation:
Pulse pressure is systolic pressure minus diastolic pressure. So in this case:

125-83 = 42

 

Therefore answer = D, 42mmHg

Question:
A patient has a blood pressure of 132/91, what is their mean arterial pressure? 

Round to 1.d.p
Explanation:
Answer = B, 104.7 mmHg

 

Mean arterial pressure = diastolic + 1/3PP

PP = pulse pressure, which is systolic pressure - diastolic pressure

 

Therefore: 91 + 1/3(132-91)

               = 91 + 1/3(41)

Question:
Use the relevant values to work out the ejection fraction of this patient: 

 

End diastolic volume: 140ml

End systolic volume: 60ml

Heart rate: 78 bpm

 

Round your answer to 1.d.p
Explanation:
Answer = E, 57.1%

 

Ejection fraction = SV/EDV X 100

SV (stroke volume) = EDV - ESV

The value given for heart rate is irrelevant in working out the ejection fraction.

 

Therefore:

stroke volume = 140 - 60 = 80

ejection fraction = 80/140 X 100

                         = 57.1%

Question:
Use the relevant values to calculate cardiac output for this patient:

 

End diastolic volume = 160ml

End systolic volume = 50ml

Heart rate = 72 bpm

 

Give your answer to 2.d.p and in L/min
Explanation:
Answer = B, 7.92 L/min

 

Cardiac output = SV X heart rate

SV (stroke volume) = EDV - ESV

 

Therefore:

SV = 160-50 = 110ml

CO = 110 X 72

      = 7920 ml/min

Answer is asking for L/min

To convert from ml to L you divide by 1000

        = 7.92 L/min

Question:
Using relevant values calculate the stroke volume for this patient:

 

End diastolic volume: 142 ml

End systolic volume: 45 ml

Heart rate: 65 bpm

 

Give answer as a whole number, in ml.
Explanation:
Answer = D, 97 ml

 

Stroke volume = end diastolic volume - end systolic volume

Therefore SV = 142 - 45 

                      = 97 ml

 

Value given for heart rate is irrelevant

Question:
A clinical trial was assessing a new genetic test for Cystic fibrosis. An autosomal recessive condition affecting the function of the CFTR chloride channel. 721 individuals were screened using the new test, 311 of which had known cystic fibrosis. 

From the data provided (see table), calculate the postive predictive value for the test. 

 

Give your value to 2.d.p in a %.
Explanation:
The positive predictive value is the probability that individuals with a positive result truly have the disease. It is the proportion of positive results that are positives. 

 

Therefore answer = C, 65.03%

 

From the table the number of positive results for the test is 429. Of these, 279 are true positives. 

Therefore the PPV is 279/429 = 0.6503...

Expressed as a percentage this is: 65.03% (2.d.p)

 

This type of question is from Case 4 statistics question booklet

Question: Drug metabolism can happen in two phases (I and II). Which of the following options best describes what happens in phase II of drug metabolism?
OptionB: A portion of the intermediate compound can exert a highly toxic effect
OptionC: Breakdown of the drug causes the formation of an intermediate compound which is 'switched on'
OptionD: The intermediate compound made in phase I is deactivated and made water soluble by phase II enzymes
Explanation:
Answer = D, The intermediate compound made in phase I is deactivated and made water soluble by phase II enzymes.

 

A,B,C,D all explain processes happening in phase I of drug metabolism

 

Phase I metabolism may create (transiently) reactive intermediate compounds.

Phase II: The drug (or intermediate metabolite from Phase I) can be (a) de-activated and (b) made water-soluble by Phase II enzymes.

 

This is from Dr Coffey's case 6 lecture on drug metabolism

Question: What is the origin of the Sartorius muscle?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A: The origin of Sartorius is the Anterior Superior Iliac Spine

 

This is one of the 7 muscles of the lower limb that attachments need to be learned for- this explanation is being reused to consolidate understanding.

 

Sartorius:

  • Origin: Anterior Superior Iliac Spine
  • Insertion: Pes Anserine Tendon
  • Action: Hip and knee flexion, abduction and lateral rotation of the hip
  • Innervation: Femoral Nerve

Gracilis:

  • Origin: Inferior Rami and Body of Pubis
  • Insertion: Pes Anserine Tendon
  • Action: Adduction of the thigh at the hip and flexion of the leg at the knee
  • Innervation: Obturator Nerve

Biceps femoris:

  • Long head origin: Ischial Tuberosity
  • Short head origin: Linea Aspera
  • Insertion: Head of Fibula
  • Action: Flex knee, extend thigh, lateral rotation at hip and knee
  • Innervation: Sciatic Nerve (Long head tibial part, short head common fibula part)

Semitendinosis:

  • Origin: Ischial Tuberosity
  • Insertion: Pes Anserine Tendon
  • Action: Flex knee, extend thigh, medial rotation of hip and knee
  • Innervation: Sciatic Nerve

Semimembranosus

  • Origin: Ischial Tuberosity
  • Insertion: Medial Tibial Condyle
  • Action: Flexion of knee, extension of thigh, medial rotation at hip and knee
  • Innervation: Sciatic Nerve

Gastrocnemius:

  • Long Head Origin: Lateral Femoral Condyle
  • Short Head Origin: Medial Femoral Condyle
  • Insertion: Calcaneal Tendon and Bone
  • Action: Plantar flexion, support of lateral foot arches
  • Innervation: Tibial Nerve (Superficial posterior compartment)

Rectus Femoris:

  • Origin: Anterior Inferior Iliac Spine and Ilium superior to the Acetabulum
  • Insertion: Quadriceps tendon on the Patella
  • Action: Flexes the thigh at the hip and extends to the leg at the knee
  • Innervation: Femoral Nerve

Question: A young man visits his GP as he is not developing secondary sex characteristics as his peers are, he is found to have low levels of FSH and LH in his blood resulting in lowered androgen production in the peripheral tissues. What type of vision loss could he be experiencing as well?
Explanation:
The correct answer is A: 

 

The patient is displaying Secondary Hypogonadism, or Hyponadotrophic hypogonadism. This can be caused by a pituitary tumour. The pituitary gland lies just below the optic chiasm so tumours can compress this structure, and result in bitemporal hemianopia- or loss of vision on the lateral half of the visual field in both eyes.
Tags: Eye and vision, PCS 3, Reproductive Hormones

Question: What enzyme is responsible for converting PIP3 into PIP2?
Explanation:
The correct answer is E: PTEN

 

MAPK is Mitogen Activated protein kinase which is involved in a a protein kinase cascade, which has an amplification effect on the number of protein kinases activated. As this mechanism generally triggers growth and proliferation via growth factors, a mitogen activated protein kinases (cyclin dependant for example) to trigger cell cycle events.

 

PIP3 is the kinase which phosphorylates PIP2 into PIP3

 

PKA and PKC are both protein kinases which behave as second messengers and are associated with different intracellular cascades, commonly associated with Gs and Gq coupled receptors respectively.

 

Wouldn't worry too much about intracellular signalling on it's own as there will be very few isolated questions, however in contexts such as muscle contraction, hormones, and pharmacology it may come up.

Question: Your heart is racing with anxiety about the S1, you really need a correct answer. Which division of the autonomic nervous system results in the stress responses you're feeling right now?
Explanation:
The correct answer is B: It's sympathetic innervation that triggers the fight or flight response, as opposed to parasympathetic innervation which triggers rest and digest.

 

To consider the function of each system, consider what you would need to happen if there was a lion trying to hunt you (such as pupil dilation to take in more light, bronchodilation to increase respiration, less blood for digestion and more for heart muscle). These will be effects of sympathetic innervation- the reverse is parasympathetic.

 

Both divisions of the ANS have a preganglionic section, and a post ganglionic section, with a two neuron pathway. In all the preganglionic neurons, acetylcholine is used. The ganglia (synapses) for the sympathetic nervous system are close to the spinal cord, while the parasympathetic ganglia are more peripheral. 

 

The sympathetic nervous system primarily using noradrenaline as its post ganglionic neurotransmitter, while the parasympathetic division still uses Acetylecholine. There are a few exceptions:

 

 

The receptors that sympathetic fibres usually work on are adrenergic receptors of which there are 5 kinds: 

𝞪1- found in vascular, genitourinary, intestinal smooth muscle, iris radial, liver, and heart tissues and so is responsible for the sympathetic effects on these such as smooth muscle contraction, mydriasis, and vasoconstriction. Coupled with Gq.
𝞪2- pancreatic islets, platelets, and nerve terminals, responsible for inhibition of insulin release, induction of glucagon release, and negative feedback in nerve synapses. Couples with Gi.
𝞫1-Heart, juxtaglomerular cells of the kidney, increases cardiac output by increasing heart rate, stroke volume, and conduction velocity and increases juxtaglomerular cell renin secretion to lower blood pressure.
𝞫2-Vascular, bronchial, genitourinary, gastrointestinal smooth muscle, skeletal muscle, liver, smooth muscle relaxation, vasodilation (particularly in skeletal muscle opposite to dominant vasoconstriction by 𝞪1 & 𝞪2 ) lipolysis in adipose tissue, glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis.
𝞫3- adipose tissue, enhances lipolysis of adipose tissue. All beta receptors are coupled with Gs

 

Parasympathetic fibres usually exert their effects on muscarinic receptors, of which there are also 5:

M1- Found in the salivary glands and enteric nerves
M2- found in the heart and smooth muscle
M3- also found in smooth muscle, as well as salivary glands and muscles of the iris
M4- found in the brain and lung
M5- found in the brain (specifically substantia nigra) and in the eye

Question:
You are waiting in the queue anxiously to go in for the dreaded S1 exam. It’s your turn to go in. Your sympathetic nervous system is in overdrive, your adrenaline levels are through the roof as you haven’t slept in two days and are twelve red bulls deep since last night. You walk through the door and hear a thunderous “WAIT”. This startles you so you look around and out pops Jeff. Your heart starts to race even faster because you know that he expects you to be a competent cardiologist by now. Dr Allen gives you a cheeky smile and says “You must answer one question before you can enter“. This is too much for you to handle, you consider turning and sprinting away from this dastardly place. You decide to be strong and face Jeff, gladly accepting his challenge of a question.

 

He asks “How many chambers are there in the human heart”
OptionE: Boot Jeff in the nuts and proceed to your exam
Explanation:
PHEWWW that was actually easy.... 

 

Well I hope that I don’t need to explain the answers to this question, if anyone does ask in the comments then all I say is good luck.

 

Just so this wasn’t completely useless here’s a quick reminder of the common ecg patterns.

 

Conduction blocks are simply when conduction of the impulse innervating the heart is partially slowed or blocked

 

A first degree block is when the PR interval is greater than 200ms, therefore is only slowing the conduction down


A type 1 Second degree block is progressive prolongation of the PR interval over a few action potentials until the QRS complex is dropped.

A type 2 Second degree block is when there is no progressive prolongation of the PR interval before a QRS complex is dropped.

 

A third degree block is when there is an absence of any relationship between the P waves and the QRS complex, they simply occur without being connected to each other.

 

And I’m sure you have all seen this before but it’s nice to remind ourselves for the 500th time as to which leads show which views of the heart.

 

 

Thats all from me, good luck with the exam everyone!
